text: i do not like coffee i love the smell but the taste is lost on me , but this should not be feared by non coffee lovers .  on tap at rogue in portland , or . appearance : black , opaque , thin cover of dark tan leaves heavy lace in the heavy rogue goblet .  the only thing slightly disappointing about this beer for me was the mouthfeel seemed a bit watery .

a- pours chocolate milk color into black with the creamiest of tan heads . s- aroma is soft and roasted , not much going on . perfect amount of malt .  pours black with virtually no light around the edges . towering cap of light brown foam that grew on the pour like one of those ash-growing snake things from a fireworks stand . retention is great , as is the lacing .  it had a light feel on the palate with mild carbonation .

s- corn ... a little bit of lemon in there as well . not much . nothing outstanding here d- good , easy drinking beer .  huge head , somewhat lasting , good lacing , smallish bubbles .  thin mouthfeel , this is the achilles heel of the beer .

smell- notes of citrus and rice , what one would expect .  a - very very dark . very fluffy head and lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is ok. fairly light body , more than i 'd think it should be at this abv .

the smell was really subtle for me and i could n't detect anything more than a slight sweetness like burnt caramel .  a : the perfect clear orange color . great retention .  a- blackness with a espresso colored head s- coffee beans ground soaked in licorice coffee and dark chocolate really bold t- straight up coffee and espresso with bitter chocolate and a slight tang finish m- medium carbonation and a bit watery for the style d- i drink 3 cup of coffee a day who am i to judge ?

the aroma is composed of citrus and yeast . i detect the slight prenence of hops in the aroma . the flavor is slight on the front of the tongue , but the hops are prevelent on the back of the tongue .  a- the pour yields an opaque black body with a small khaki colored head composed of tightly knit bubbles . the head is long lasting and leaves complete rings on the sides of my glass .  this is almost as good a stout as they come . i like guinness extra stout better because it has more bitterness . but this stout is smooth and easy to drink with a nice bitterness . if you are looking for a stout to bring to a party this is a good one because it is not too bitter . almost everyone i have served this to has liked it .

the nose had some malt , and a light note of candy .  pours a clear amber , nice thick white head forms , as it drops leaves some pretty epic lacing , settles to a nice layer , great retention . looks great , smells good , but the alcohol takes too much of it .  tastefully good as well.with the same taste of chocolate milk with a hint of hops and lots of malt.i could have this one for breakfast lunch , and dinner.what ya mean i 'm a raging alcholic.i beg your pardon.this is one tasty beverage , one that will put a smile on your face all day long .

lacking a little bit on the smell but the taste has all the usual fall spices in these seasonals . very drinkable and balanced with a nice body to it . along with the lack of smell , there 's also a lack of carbonation i thought , which would have improved the score .  spectacular retention and thick , chunky lace .  smell is of old corn/rice and skunk . pew . taste was horrendous . a skunky malt liquor flavor mixed with sweet rice/corn adjunct . maybe it went bad on it 's journey from the carib-bean ? looks like i should have gone for the sam light that was also in the fridge ...

the aroma is quite faint , i pick up some buttery caramel malt .  pours a two finger white head that fades slowly , leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  the mouthfeel is just average . also , carbonation is lacking enough to make this feel sticky .

the smell has a tangy fruit character , some caramel nut , and alcohol . super cloying sweetness , rotten fruit , sickly sweet caramel .  bottle says bottled on 4/16/09 a - pours cloudy orange with huge 3 fingers of pillowy foam that takes forever to die down - lacing is all over the glass . this is one fine looking beer s - very hoppy with a strong grassy aroma - there are so many other aromas also - reminds me of a wine t - bitterness is subdued , bready yeast flavor is present , solid malt backbone m - great creamy mouthfeel - but i wish there was a little more lingering bitterness to this brew d - this is a very sneaky 9 % abv - deceptively drinkable .  the rye is evident , as is a tangy almost sour note along with the bread . a little over-carbonated ... i found it slightly distracting and that it may have affected my enjoyment of the beer 's complexity . light-bodied and very refreshing . while i have little to no experience with beers of this style , i enjoyed this one and i believe that its a great refresher during the summer months .

s : not the best aspect of this beer -- smells a lot like balsamic vinegar without much of the underlying fruit coming through . t : quite tart with a bit of barnyard horse blanket .  golden yellow with a full white head that melts to a quarter inch covering of sticky lacing .  m : slick mouthfeel with a medium amount of carbonation that can be prickly at times . body is medium and has a bit of resiny stickiness to it .

smell is fairly muted with a noticeable amount of citrusy hops . the hops in the smell are much more present in the taste . a light body and pleasant flavor make this very drinkable . all around a very well executed ipa .  tasted june 22nd 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - a clear blood red , one finger tan head and some lacing s - alcohol , wine barrels , sweet dried fruits , earth , oak , french vanilla and more sweet and alcohol t - alcohol , lots of sugar , sweet malts , tons of sweet dried fruit , black cherries , wine barrels , raisins , charred oak , molasses , carmelised brown sugar and vanilla .  mouthfeel is perhaps a bit thin for the style but not bad .

s - light roasted malts with little pecan , not impressed with the aroma . o - this is a solid brew , i would n't drink more than one personally but a great night cap , prime time would be cool evenings with a maduro .  it has the perfect color for a lager , dark but not to dark .  m : the feel is slightly creamy but on the lighter side of medium bodied . could be a bit thicker here ... d : if you like coffee beers i could see someone drinking good amount of these .

served in a goblet at armsby abby in worcester 8/24 . the nose in this beer is all alcohol with sight sweet malt .  excellent head duration to boot , with the dollop of foam in the middle arranged like a hurricane taking shape ; stellar looking beer .  this is a great beer . the aromas are sweet and malty , with hints of caramel and vanilla . this beer has a nice , smoky flavor with hints of toffee and vanilla . this will definitely be going on my `` favorite beers '' list .

the nose is doughy soapy water and yeast . spicy hops hit first chased by metallic sweetness with a soft-baked quality .  pours a very nice looking dark ruby with a thick tan head which remains forever and leaves sticky lacing in my delirium glass . a beautiful beer , i wish they all looked like this .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . flavor is a hospital antiseptic . said to be an ipa , i understand pigs fly too . looks bad , smells bad , tastes worse , higher abv is hidden . waaay overpriced at $ 10.45 for a 330ml bottle from colonial spirits acton , ma .

the smell is hops , almost bitter , and faint malt .  gorgeous . big , beautiful , creamy head over a glowing murky golden body .  carbonation a little higher than i expect in the style but still manages to be exceptionally drinkable .

s - an overall dry aroma of pine , juniper , and dried yeast . not too strong , but there . t - pretty yeasty for an ipa , but not bad .  appearance : extremely voluptuous head , almost overflowing , with lots of carbonation and bubbles . color is pitch black , no nuances there .  drinkability : mouthfeel is a little thin , but this is a very solidly crafted stout , up there with the tops in style .

the nose has some sweetness and faint hops , but seems a bit muted . i do n't think i have a cold or anything ... hrm . smooth citrusy american hops flow into the big , boozy backbone . in all , this was a very enjoyable beer and i might have to pick up another bottle when i head back for groceries tomorrow night .  drank on-tap at atwood 's tavern , cambridge , ma served in a stemmed glass gorgeous appearance . thick , lasting rings of lacing coated the glass .  not too complicated , but a pleasant experience overall . goes down quite easily ( in part because of the low carbonation ) .

really quite pale - barely gold . mild grainy aroma with a mild yeast quality . drinking while cold i think kept off any excessive taste from adjuncts .  pours a luscious peach/dark gold color with a substantial , fluffy , two-finger head that exhibits excellent retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel is less crisp then i had hoped .
smells of smoke and burnt coffee .  the beer arrived at the table black with a tan head .  medium bodied , highly carbonated .

the slightly hoppy floral aroma is pleasant , and the flavor is a classic pale ale with a lovely hop-bitter finish .  a - classic dark bronze doppelbock color .  m-medium bodied with slightly more carbonation than i prefer in a porter .

aroma : slight grainy aroma . i was surprised i did n't pick up on those traits in the aroma . grapefruit notes . i really liked the way this beer came together .  best by date of 5/3/11 a : standard pour yields a billowy 2.5 finger light creamsicle colored head with very good retention . lacing is patchy and spotty with nice cling .  medium bodied , it seems a little flat at the beginning , but there 's sharp carbonation at the finish , which is a little watery and silty .

s - roasted grain . bit of coffee , that 's about it .  poured into my big family guy mug and was greeted with one of the best looking heads i 've ever seen in that mug . perfect ruddy brown with a hint of mbver red , just like a bock should . nice and opaque too , hard to see any bubbles in there .  slightly sour , a bit thin , highly carbonated . quite drinkable .

deep black in color-nice slight tan head that lingers down the glass.subtle aroma of malt.slight chocolate smell.roasted flavor dominates.hints of licorice.very subtle sourness in the backround.full bodied mouthfeel.a very drinkable beer-comes off more as a stout then old ale to me.very enjoyable none the less .  caged and corked 75cl bottle ; poured with an immense head of tight foam and a beautiful tornadic swirl of yeast-inspired carbonation .  m -- light carbonation . good body with a lightly soft mouthfeel .

s : honestly , not too much aroma . it definitely tastes better than it smells . pleasing bitterness that is n't ever overbearing , and it sticks on the palate well into the aftertaste . at first the appearance and especially smell were nothing special at all , but it makes up for it with the great taste .  incredible looking esb . pours with the cascading effect and settles to a bright amber color .  it seems to light and over carbonated for a stout .

adeep , dark , rich brown ; about a 1 inch thick foamy head that disappeared quickly , light lacing on the glass sspicy with a strong plum scent ; a little banana and clove aroma as well . i liked the taste very much but the smell was a little strong and foul for me .  two fingers of light tan head forms and recedes slowly . the color of this beer is truly gorgeous ... smell is sweet and sugary upfront .  thin on mouthfeel medium orangish-amber with a 1 finger offwhite head that leaves a respectable amount of lacing . taste : broad caramel maltiness with a warming alcohol changes over to a restrained english hop bitterness . notes : a nice esb , although the abv is much higher than say , honker 's ale . drinkability ranks fairly high but the alcohol content is above that of a session beer .

superoir lacing & very good head retention s : nothing up front , but then earthy hoppyness & whisper of fruit . this was the only area this beer let me down t : huge grapefruitty hops & then a little fruittyness up front .  glassware - imperial pint appearance - dark amber/red in color , which makes sense . nice two finger white head that leaves a lot of really great lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel was slightly thin with a very tasty caramel taste on the tongue . the finish was semi-sweet , slightly dry , very nice for the style .

ah ... sierra nevada pale ale ... . smell is mild and not tons of identity here . a bit of a metallic smell . nothing overpowering .  beautiful amber color . medium just-barely-off-white head that is nice and dense . very lasting lace .  a little thin , flavors do n't linger or expand much .

the smell is hardly there , but i do get the twist of saaz hops and some nice wheaty bready and certainly grainy malts , a clean overall smell just not very strong .  light-sucking black with a monumental 2.5 finger head of a nice deep tan . great retention and lacing . ca n't ask for a better appearance than this .  light bodied though , almost watery . in a way this is an ipa-light - some similar desirable flavors and aromas , but less bitterness , less alcohol , and lighter bodied .

on tap at de molen in bodegraven after the waitress walked the tap list board over to us after asking what was on tap . lovely . s - dark fruit malts obvious . bready with dark rye coming to mind . more mild than exprected . weak aroma but flavour is what counts for me , so this was good .  very attractive beer . massive sticky foamy eggshell colored head rises to 2 fingers and holds there forever .  mouf & gt ; meh . okay . average .

the aroma is of muted hops and barley . there is n't really much going on in the nose . after smelling this beer i thought it would be rather bland but the flavors pop off the tongue . i would n't call any 8.7 % alcohol beer extremely drinkable , but this is exceptional .  2011 batch 1 - 750ml bottle poured into a cbs snifter a : black as night . gorgeous finger-and-a-half dark brown head that leaves a nice full cap throughout consumption .  mouthfeel is light and carbonation fades to almost flat .

the smell was a disappointment , as it was hardly even there . i only got a whiff of a little alcohol , malt , and a faint lager-like aroma . the taste , however , makes up for this . a little more complexity would have driven this beer into the upper echelon of great tasting brews , but i thoroughly enjoyed it nonetheless .  bottle from the lcbo the 2008 vintage has held its own agaist the 2007. black with a lovely tan head .  body was very light and thin .

has an awesome color too it , good all the way around ... not very scented though but that to me is by far the least important qualty of a beer .  great retention , light lace . gorgeous .  i found the body to be a bit thin carbonation medium to low .

s - malt aroma accented by hops .  pours a bright , clear , light orange color with a nice looking head .  it 's light on body , and not especially interesting - but as fruit beers go , this was excellent .

slight fruity aroma but nothing stands out here .  makes an impressive appearance , a nice red amber color with a large foamy pale head that lingers in the chalice with some sticking .  the body was medium to medium light .

s : hints of breadyness mf : medium bodied , slick & very well balanced great drinkability , such a well crafted dubbel ! although the lack of nose is a let down .  lighter and brighter looking than i expected , nelson poured without any `` redness '' i typically , and erroneously , associate with rye beers . a clear hay golden hue , with a beautiful cream white head ; excellent retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel was the only thing that detracted from the beer in my opinion , as i found it to be a little to watery for my personal preference .

from tap into a pitcher , then into a frosty 16 ounce mug at brick house pizza in west richland , wa . s- dark malts . t- nice rollercoaster in the mouth : started only slightly sweet , built to a robust dark malts , maybe a hint of charring , then dissolved with a touch of hop bitters . finished nice and clean with the alcohol completely concealed .  a -- beautiful dark amber color with two fingers of head using a standard pour . very dark for an ipa . great lacing as well .  m - a little watery for the style , but not objectionable .

not a ton of aroma , some carmel notes there though .  pours very dark , almost black with dense head that does not dissipate till the end of pint , leaving thick and dense lacing . amazing .  the only thing i felt was it could use a little more carbonation to balance the tart flavor and make it more perky .

smell- very light smell . a bit of grain and that 's about it . taste- very flavorful . very impressed with this one .  great looking beer .  not too complex- makes for easy drinking , as does its texture . carbonation level seems low , though as an earlier commenter noted , it is actually just very fine .

smell - some nobles are faint but mostly a faint skunky smell taste - a pleasant combination of barnyard flavors ( straw , earthiness ) with nicely balanced noble hop flavoring and slight crisp in the finsih mouthfeel - full bodied for a pilsner . overall - this a very decent german pilsner in my book .  appearance : black in color sporting a two finger creamy head that lasted a long time .  though this is a red ale of stormy garnet and the menu states it is `` brewed with 20 % honey malts for a touch of sourness '' ( honey = sourness ? it is not merely that this red ale tastes bad ; it is absolutely offensive . of the lowest evolutionary order . the entire beer is corrupted by spoilage and should n't be served publicly .

s : typical grain and bready aroma . t : surprisingly less bitter than i expected .  this brew pours a very large head of creamy fine light brown bubbles and opaque black brown body .  this beer was skunky ... skunky like a becks . and i couldnt find any other component of this beer redeeming enough to get over that skunkyness . my encounter with this beer started out ok ... it has a pale yellow appearance with a medium amount of head . taste exhibited becks ( or maybe even becks light ) levels of skunkitude , again with a bit of clove chasing after it to apologize . definitely not recommended .

-- slight smell of caramel , even slighter smell of fruit . i had no expectations whatsoever and will definetally try more of this style .  poured from a liter swingtop bottle into a snifter a= pours a thick black color with a nice one finger brown head that lasts suprisingly long with amazing lacing . s= huge hop notes which is amazing as well as a prominent coffee smell .  m : medium to light body with medium to low carbonation . would have preferred a bigger body by far .

i couldnt detect much aroma , but the flavor was a tasty mix of vanilla with a hint of malty chocolate .  into a tulip . pours the closest to motor oil i 've ever seen in a beer , dark crimson/brown head , dense retention and heavy legs .  average feel for the genre i 'd say . it 's pleasant in sips and gulps and a few of em would be just as enjoyable as one .

aroma is faint , but of roasted malts and some nutty and fruitiness . for such a mild beer , this is very impressive . full of flavour .  poured into a pint glass , this radiant beer had a crisp , clear orange body and a thick white head .  m - the mouthfeel is a little light , with little carbonation .

this was a wonderful helles , with the crisp maltiness one would expect from german lager . sparingly hopped , but enought to balance well . show this to a lover of the macros and they might convernt yet ! i wish however , that they were in brown bottles , because i got that slight skunkyness from uv reaction .  exquisite in appearance !  m- thin and smooth with almost not carbonation feel . kind of has the texture of a flat soda .

s - a very light nose , almost imperceptible . the yeast spice does start to come through . some alcohol warmth . t - starts very smooth , grainy and sweet - seems like loads of pilsner malts are present .  thick dense white head with great retention .  m - a little on the thin side .

the smell dropped off a bit , being dominated by a biscuit smell with bit of roastiness under it . nice , but nothing special .  tasted in mid-may 2009. nearly opaque , black/brown , with reddish brown on the edges under the light . great lacing , forming curtains in the latter half of the glass .  m- light in body and light to medium in carbonation .

excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with rings , streaks and splotches of soapy lacing . earthy hop aroma with hints of soil and pine needle as well as some faint fruit character and a prominent malt backbone . there 's some faint pineapple and grapefruit in the nose but the hop profile mostly gives off an earthy scent .  cloudy pale copper color and of hazy reddish tone nearer to the top which is adorned by a rich creamy head of froth about an inch high and colored of dark ivory . head retains its thick body to settle a bit with a lumpy top and lots of lace in big blotches , looks scrumptious !  medium bodied and a bit sticky in the mouth .

lots of lacing that only adds to the beauty . smell - hoppy with a nice malt backbone taste & mouthfeel - let me just say that this one is highly biscuity , and i love it .  this is a stunning looking ale : dark-brown with a ruby glaze , bubbles dancing toward the top like a light snowfall in reverse , crowned with a creamy mocha head .  mouthfeel : thin body and medium carbonation overall : a nice geuze , a bit too watery for my liking though .

aroma - a light roasty grain and smoked peat . pleasant but fragile levels .  brown to copper towards the edges with a huge off white head that falls slow and never completely goes away while clinging to the glass . as the edges fall away , thick ringed sheets of foam . this is one damn good lookin ' beer .  mouthfeel is a bit light , to me , for the style , though it seems appropriate for the flavors that this beer brings to the palate .

rich malt lacing . drawback : only subtle hints of malt in the aroma , but with the quaff came a load of malts and an earthy , spicy finish .  a - pours with one finger of white foam on top of a perfectly clear , copper colored body . the head settles slowly and leaves nice , thick lace .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

the aroma is slightly malty , but nothing to write home about .  this beer sure looks good , but it sure aint of me . stone ris pours an oily thick pitch black witha huge brown head . as the head disapates , it leave so great lacing .  thin bodied , and just sufficient carbonation , but i suspect the growler is at fault much more than the beer .

aroma was well restrained , with dark malt notes and roastiness coming forth . 3.9 look : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | feel : 4 | drink : 4 1267  pours a chocolate brown color with a massive invincible head that lasts to the bitter end and gobs and gobs of lace .  m honestly its way too light of a mouthfeel .

smell is very moderate , a bit malty .  has a lovely appearance . produces about two and a have fingers thick of light tan head that has perfect retention . the body of the brew is cleanly filtered and is dark copper/ruby red in color .  a little too thick on the tongue , but nice .

smell here is n't of really much . perhaps a bit of creaminess . it 's just kind of `` beery '' . an easy drinker ... at this low abv , you could drink these seemingly all day .  deep golden to light amber colored with a big head that settles into a nice thin layer of foam with moderate lacing as you get through the pint .  the mouthfeel has average carbonation and ismedium bodied yet feels a bit thin at the same time , as it falls off the toungue quite quickly .

draft beer in a bottle is as good as it gets with mgd . nothing fancy , this is a great bbq beer . throw some burgers on the grill , crack open an mgd and have a great day out in the sun . not the best beer made by miller , but a great cold filtered brew .  quite surprising ... not because it 's a great beer from dogfish head ( that 's certainly not surprising ) , but because i have never actually enjoyed a pumpkin ale . seriously ever . appearance & gt ; what a beauty . colour reads from dark honey to a pumpkin orange glow . extremely lively .  mouthfeel is sticky-sweet and dense .

the smell is average , its not bad or obtrusive , but there is very little of anything that i could smell , neutral to the most . its fairly simple , but sometimes excellence is in simplicity . very clean finish .  great looking beer .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with likely carbonation . that , and the over carbonated pour make this beer a something i would not recommend .

the smell was n't nothing spectacular -- very malty and that 's about it . i could n't smell the fruit at all . it was just a hint of cherry , nothing overbearing , and very delicious .  poured into a large wine glass , very dark , giant creamy brown head ( very enticing ) .  a fairly light bodied beer with near champagne carbonation ... a bit too much for me , although i know many like this in their wild ales .

had on-tap at the red lobster in hickory , nc . nose was a bit sweet but there really was n't much there .  this brew produces mounds of bright white head , which peaks easily over the top of my stein . it has a very nice golden and hazy body .  mouthfeel is pretty average , as is the smell ... i ca n't think of anything distinctive about these characteristics .

the aroma is pleasant but muted , with a nondescript sweet and somewhat tart character .  poured with some mild carbonation that settled into a thick yellowish head . absolute best porter i have ever seen .  lighter body than i thought it would be with with very low carbonation..the weakest point of the brew . easy drinker for the abv and ignoring the mouth feel , a nice brew .

nice grapefruit citrus taste . a nice malty front with the citrus and slight sweetness undertones .  the beer itself pulls a pitch black into the glass and lets no light through . darkness is right . head retention is decent , leaves a perfect lacing behind .  the body is thin and slightly anemic . a little more carbonation and body would carry this really unique beer into the stratosphere .

the aroma is pretty unremarkable with the typical malt smell .  put it under bright light and it looks magnificent in my flute !  a bit thin , but a very good stout flavor develops in the mouth . i 'd have preferred a bit fuller body .

smells solid . a nice malty backbone , a touch of caramel and some slightly toasted wheat .  pours with a beautiful amber body topped by a thick lasting head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  the mouthfeel was thin with a slightly dry aftertaste .

this irish stout surprised me in all regards . the color is pitch black , with only a thin amount of head on top holding in a slight coffee/nutty scent . the taste is of toasted barley and coffee , and is balanced extremely well .  a : this pours pitch black . a large tan head ( over two fingers forms ) with great retention .  body is a little thin .

s : not much in the nose at all . a hint of roasted malts is about it , and that 's faint . not completely unexpected for the style , however . m : creamy , as you 'd expect from a nitro pour , body is on the light side , also about what you 'd expect for this style . easily quaffed . worth checking out .  nice retention and very good lacing . clear amber color makes this an all around great looking brew .  mouthfeel : pretty thick and a little syrupy . i 'd actually like a little more carbonation .

s : sweet malty caramel upfront followed by earthy citrus banana with hoppy bitterness on the backend . decent .  a : clear copper , fluffy white head , good retention and lace .  the taste is fantastic , but the beer is a little thin and a bit hot ; not a good session beer , but great type of brew to have after a long day .

aroma seems a little incomplete , with yeast smells and a touch of leather .  this beer looks absolutely perfect .  this beer was purchased at cyclone liquors , in ames , iowa . the beer was very dark in color and tasted very well . i drank the beer warm and i think it was a good beer . i would try this beer again if it was presented to me . it had a very nice sweet taste for a german dunkel , which i am not a huge fan of .

a hazy copper pour with a sustaining head , the beer smells sort of indistinct for the hops and malt you 'd expect .  a perfect pour into an oversized wine glass with rich deep amber body a tightly formed thick white head , i could not find any reason to not give a perfect score.tropical fruity hops in the nose with a little boozy and caramel sweetness , overripe mango and pineapple on the palate with again some sweetish booze , the malt base is quite dry underneath the hops and sweet booze.a nice dipa , one of the best pours for me ... ever .  mouthfeel is rather thin and average .
aroma of mild citrus . it was hard to smell . had to stick my nose right down over the glass .  beautiful looking beer .  too carbonated , the mouthful of liquid seems to almost crumble right away .
s : sweet malts , pine , not that aromatic .  pours almost black , with tan 2 finger head .  m : i feel that this could have used a little more body and less carbonation , but overall ... not bad .
smell is almost non-existant to me .  great retention and lacing !  mouthfeel - a bit too carbonated which overrides the wonderful taste at first .

subtle . t/m : great malt flavor .  a - golden and slightly hazed with coppery highlights and a foamy , cushiony head that jets to the surface and clings to the glass like glue as it subsides . head retention is fantastic , and would be even without the aid of the etching at the bottom of the glass . fantastic .  mouthfeel is grainy and oily , body is medium to thin , carbonation is sharp .

foam didnt leave lace it left a coating of thick shaving cream , very nic ! s-dominated by sweet caramel malts with low floral/ citruy hops .  pours with a rich , rocky head over a cloudy orange body , with lots of lacing . one of the best presentations i 've seen .  m light body for the style , but not unpleasant .

s : mildly sweet but kind of faint .  a- pretty beautiful . a reddish amber color , just glowing .  being from the adirondacks i quickly likened this to adirondack brewery 's bear naked ale , yet a lager version , and a bit more wheat-filled . the mouth-feel is nice , but nothing special ( not flat , not too bubbly ) . in short , its a dandy brew- we all enjoyed it and thought it was pretty cool to have something that is only currently available in growlers from the brewery ( spring seasonal ) , drink up !
aroma is some spice , toffee .  this beer looks perfect . theres not as much smell to this one as others like it .  this one was surprisingly thin in body .

not much smell what was there was slight maltiness . great kolsch flavor , really nice for the style .  the best looking beer in the world , & one of the tastiest .  the mouthfeel was medium with a syrupy sweetness on the palate .

smell is a very subdued smoky chocolate , a bit earthy and a faint whiff of bbq sauce .  poured from 12oz bottle into trusty milwaukee brewers pint glass a- deep lushous brown with nice 1/2 '' head that sticks around a while to keep me company s- some faint malts , all in all not much going on in the smell department t- a lot of different but very faint flavors . it looks amazing and feels great but the taste is kind of lame and i detect little to no smell .  the mouthfeel i found oddly watery ... but still fairly full bodied at the same time . carbonation was fairly mild - maybe that lended to the `` watery '' sensation .

this rauchmalt is combined with modest amounts of crystal malt and two types of chocolate malt that add sweet and chocolaty notes to balance the assertive smoke qualities . hops really take a backseat in this style , so as not to interfere with the complex smoky aromatics '' -- free state this pours a very dark brown almost black . unfortunately , the aroma is weak . some very small tinges of smoke come out , but not much else .  great lacing that lined the entire glass . cloudy .  m : full bodied and creamy , the slightest touch of carbonation and a smooth , somewhat watery finish .

so-so lacing and at least for me no real aroma detected . however this beer tasted great and i am at a loss on how to describe the taste .  simply beautiful cascading action that lasts for over a minute ! superb tan head retention that is not going away at all !  good carbonation , which i appreciate . minimal complexity to this beer .

the aroma was subtle and i tried to pick up the smokiness but really could n't . mostly it smelled like a pale ale just not as hoppy and citrusy.the beer has a nice velvety mouthfeel but was a lot crisper than i thought it would be .  reddish copper in color , impressive head with incredible retention and massive lacing down the sides of my pub glass .  m. thin to medium body with a somewhat biting carbonation . ends fairly dry .

s - plenty of malt , not much else .  served cold , poured into a pint glass , it has a great amber red color with excellent clarity . the creamy head sticks around a good long time but slowly settles leaving a sheet of lacing on the glass .  hate to say it , but the bottle/case i have is absolutely awful . other than a hint of coriander spice all i got was an overwelming sourness that made this one of the few i had to pour down the drain . they obviously put wayyy too much orange peel in their mix . if you can get past the sourness it is par for a wit bier course . i 'm hoping this was a bad/expired batch because ... .as far as mill street goes imo , stick to the coffee porter ...

s - nothing particularly special here , but what is most noticible is that there is no overpowering smell of alcohol ; just a bit of hops or some sort of plant material , let 's say it has a slight 'grassiness ' to it . aside from that there is a distinct fruitiness to the aroma which is most enticing , though mostly through its lissome appearance . nothing really jumps out at me for this beer ; though i must say the frutiness stays with me with an added dimension of spice .  a toasted head has great retention and lace .  it was pretty smooth for stout and for for the alcohol content . i tried it with a few other beers .

aroma is some light malt , some caramel , raisin . quite subdued though .  the body of hop head poured an absolutly beautiful copper-orange color , with a sizable custard head . retention and lacing were both excellent , thanks to a constant supply of carbonation from below .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with thankfully a burst of carbonation near the end , making it a little less watery than it initially presents itself to be .

the aroma is somewhat faint , i pick up some raisins and grains , pretty disappointing for a bsda .  pours a mouthwatering dark , rusty , brown color . head is substantial in size and settles to about 1cm thick . light tan in color with a dense foam consistency .  the mouthfeel is thinner when compared with other stouts , merely decent .

s - not very scented , it has almost a dull metallic smell , but this does n't detract from the experience .  beautiful dark color , with good mapping down the sides .  low carbonation . a bit coating , but not to syrupy/thick .

a : nice clear golden with a white head that fades quickly s : light lemony malty with grass t : lemon flavor stays throughout , finishes very smooth , very slight hop flavor d : very drinkable beer , nice lemon flavor that makes it very refreshing .  a : pale straw , great carbonation , crystal clear , and a lovely full head .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp , with a high carbonation level .

s : apple skin , musty dried fruit , creamed corn , slightly metallic . t : sweet and fruity up front - apples , a bit of raisons , prunes , figs .  poured from a 750ml bottle into my troubadour tulip glass . a dense and enormous mattress of foam tops the ale almost like a merengue . a sudsy lattice-work of lace remains in the glass even after it is empty .  perhaps a bit thin for the style , which i suppose makes it a good pale ale for summertime quaffing .

appearance this had a nice , dark , cloudy orange body with a decent head that laced a bit on my glass . smell this one is wrapped kind of tight , but the rind hops came out after a while and a touch of sweetness . yep , thats an ipa .  pours very dark brown color with a 2.5 finger dense tan head with incredible retention , with some very nice lacing on the glass .  slinky and a little thin , but ok .

s- smells of grain , faint hops . relatively clean .  a : pours a wonderfully bright golden/orange color .  it pains me to trash a beer , but this brewery needs a swift kick in the pants . i ordered this to give the brewery a second chance , since the white cloud ale i had the day before was patently awful . after a couple sips , i took it back to the bar and told the bartender , saying i wanted to try the local beer , but could n't drink it . no lager is intended to be a sour beer . he added that it 's sort of an acquired taste , but happily replaced it with a real beer . i could n't finish either of these sour beers ( and not like it 's brewed intentionally with brett ) . whoever the new guy is , he needs to clean up the brewery and get back to basics with brewing .

s- wheat , citrus , some grass . reminds me a little bit of some freshly baled hay -- sweet . t- very crisp , assertive hop notes that slide easily into citrus .  poured - beautiful dark color .  mouthfeel : i 've always thought this was a little off ... not quite enough spine to offset the sweetness .

s - a little bit faint for me , would have like to smell the aroma a little more to get a better idea of what ingredients were used to brew it . but i did get a hint of belgian yeast with a slight funk to it , sweet malts , a small whiff of raisins and oranges . did n't get much hop aroma on this one at all . t - definitely an improvement over the smell ... flavors come out a lot more to define this beer . overall a good belgian ipa , was expecting a little bit more with the a- overall rating but a solid beer from flying dog no doubt !  a - amazing grey color s - yeast , very slight citrus , wheat t - plain in a good way , kinda thick and sweet bready coriander turns to a dry slightly bitter finish .  i could drink this one all night long . just the right amount of sweetness with a little more than expected carbonation . pale yellow in color , lemony aroma.very clean with little aftertaste . easy to drink and very enjoyable . will definately drink again .

smooth , creamy taste , easy to drink with mild to medium body . cloudy , yellow-amber color . compatible with multiple foods . the first i have had of this style .  poured into a tulip a nice dark brown color , nice carbonation , awesome fuckn ' head , never seen a head like this from a bw , two-finger creamy tannish head , tons of sticky lacing and islands through out the drink .  m & # 8211 ; thin , refreshing , light , plentiful , smooth carbonation .

a translucent orange body , sorta lie copper or a slightly lighter orange blossom honey . a solid malty body , chewy and a bit hoppy , hell of a lot better than the nose . this is a solid english pale ale , solid body of hops and malts , nothing to let you down initial taste is a bit bitter with mostly malts .  i absolutely loved this bottle .  the beer feels just a bit thin on the tongue .

s : malty , bready , yeasty and a bit hoppy . t : caramel sweet malt with toffee flavors , great malt/hop balance .  it lasts forever and settles to a nice pillow . usually old ales have no head at all . i 'm amazed this looks so good .  mouthfeel : a little slick , thinner on the palate than i expected drinkability : a fine porter , would definitely drink again .

the smell was pretty vague for me ... can pick up on some floral and citrus hops and sweet caramel malts .  anyways , into the erdinger glass ... a - really impressed with this head .  body is on the thin side of medium and the finish is both mildly astringent and slightly bitter .

nothing particular made it stand out from the crowd , but it was definately good and strong and hoppy .  biggish , crusty , light tan head leaves lots of hard , sticky lacing . very pretty .  mouthfeel is a little thin and alcoholic with low carbonation . overall this beer has a nice balance of flavours but i feel the barrel presence is a little bit too subtle and the mouthfeel a bit too thin to prevent a higher score .

a bit light on the nose . pleasant and fresh , but not ultra complex .  a : pours a light golden with a couple fingers of dense white head that reduced very slowly into a thick frothy head . beautiful rings/sheets of lacing left with every sip .  mf : the carbonation is n't quite as spritzy as i would hope to go along with the huge sourness , the body is light d : this is a great lambic .

i definitely smell some sweet notes . t- tons of stuff in this one .  a - pours a beautiful golden/amber with a puffy head which quickly dissolves with lots of lacing s - wow .  m- low carbonation , medium-body .

another head scratcher ... .a wheat beer made with oven roasted beets ? a-gorgeous , brilliant red copper with a medium white head that hangs on and leaves nice lace .  light amber beer was topped by a thick head that left some of the thickest lacing i have seen in my career .  the beer is somewhat oxidized , but still highly drinkable very light bodied bitter , true to the the style . this is a prime candidate for a session beer . at 3.8 % abv , it 's alcohol content makes this a clear choice for something that could literally be consumed all day long , starting with your pancakes !

smell : there is some notable hops ( not overwhelming ) and not much else . taste : the taste is quite curious , as i sipped away it at first tasted like a mild ale and about halfway through the bitterness asserted itself like a pale ale .  pours garnet with 4 fingers of off white/sand colored head . insane lacing & healthy head retention s : sour , vinergary notes up front that dissipates to not much of anything & then comes back t : sweetness & sourness do battle up front , along with serious dryness .  mouthfeel - this seems a bit watery for my liking , and a bit light too , it does n't take away from the beer too much though luckily , still great . the carbonation seems pretty good , maybe a bit overcarbonated .

s : nothing to out of the ordinary for a hefeweizen . t : slightly thick and creamy .  poured into a fluted pilsner glass , this czech pils showed an exceptional ability to form a stiff , meringue-like , rocky head of foam . retention was great , lasting for the duration of the glass , leaving irregular clumps of foam on the way down .  m - not as thick as i 'd like it to taste considering how rich the smell is . d - very drinkable , with the lighter mouthfeel it 's easier to forget how much you 've had .

bitterness is very balanced and in the background . very drinkable lager ! clean tasting and pretty smooth .  12 oz bottle poured into a dfh tulip . a- literally my favorite color of beer- deep reddish-copper . solid 1+ inch head that laces well .  m- seems a little thin , but nicely carbonated .

the aroma is lightly fruity and deeply roasty with some mild bittersweet chocolate , some soft dry tobacco , and stale wet coffee grounds .  poured into my duvel tulip a - pours a dark reddish-brown color with a huge pillowy tan head . this is absolutely beautiful , and took a good 3 minutes to recede enough for me to drink it !  the carbonation is unfortunately at a distracting level , but the feel is strong enough otherwise to not hurt too much overall .

smell : not too much on the nose , i get a little toffee .  the beer looks really good with a thick brown creamy head , tons of lacing , and a very nice head that lasts and lasts .  pretty average mouthfeel overall .

the first versions were too heavy on the holiday spices and every year it seems to become more and more balanced . the smell is average , relative to a xmas style beer , which are usually loaded with spice and citrus . only the slightest hint of orange comes off the beer . the taste is excellent though . the spices and fruit are at a perfect balance with the malts and hops .  this beer pours exceptionally well for a three finger thick cranium in a light tan color .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is light , as is the body .

smell is roasted grain , coffee , caramelized sugar .  on tap tonight at fountainhead in chicago ... poured into a tulip ... pours dark brown with nice dark ruby red highlights , good clarity . capped with three fingers of cool whip-esque white head that leaves a bit of lacing ... sweet and sour cherries dominate the nose with bits of oak and vanilla .  very light bodied , but carbonation seems too low to me .

very sweet sour nose and gives a consistent very thickish foamy head leaving lots of delicate complex lacing all over the glass .  appearance/pour : nice dark amber with a surprising stream of carbonation rising from the glass bottom etch . head which dissapates to a nice ring with small foamy clusters . thick lacing and a dense sound while pouring- sounds thick .  the carbonation is moderate high . i think it is a bit high for the style but the carbonation does not take anything away from the beer .

the aroma is peaty smoky malts , leather and tobacco and maybe some vegetables . sweet toffee comes out as it warms . it 's unusual and odd and i 'm not sure if i like it .  bottle provided by mike , drank into my hill farmstead glass ... looks great , a dark clear peach with a big bright white head . looks awesome ! ! ! ... boring aroma of light toffee and hops , generic .  in my opinion , flying dog brewery has created a great seasonal , smooth-tasting beer with very little bite or after taste . i would definitely recommend it to any self-respecting beer drinker who might be having an end-of-summer party this or any october .

smell : malt scent with some clear citrus and spice also . taste : malty taste with a slight hop bite .  pours a gorgeous dark caramel in the glass , with a nice thick tan head .  good carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is spicy , yeasty , hints of sweetness that gets buried by the yeast . lingering yeasty aftertaste .

smell is subtle and surprisingly fruity . overall an outstanding example of the style .  ruby and brown shades with decent clarity , a beautiful 1/2 inch head of white foam sits atop with solid retention .  m : flat , slick , and that 's it . not quite watery , but pretty close .

s : mainly a malty scent . some light floral honey , but smell is almost non-existent , the only disappointing thing about the beer .  look : bright golden color , white head of creamy foam with 2 fingers thick , very good lacing , has a sticker that say it was the best beer in the world in 2002 , let see if it 's true ; smell : biscuity malts and fruit essences ; taste : pine and spicy hops , molasses , some biscuity malts , alcohol and sugars at the finish ; mouthfeel : dry and very bitter , bittersweet and spicy finish , the body is creamy and thick ; drinkability : the first time i try the `` tripel '' style , very spicy .  it was a little thin .

smell was milder than i expected ( also could be due to the allergies/cold i have ) . malts and alcohol primarily . coffee aroma appeared much later , as it warmed .  great amber apperance with thick ass head that will not stop clinging to the glass .  3.0 m : medium body . smooth , but not creamy .

light tan head sits upon this almost purple/amber colored beer . not much in the way of aroma . this concerned me and i was not hopeful .  appearance is near perfect for this style .  mouthfeel : both the carbonation and body are on the higher end of the light range .

s- not getting much smell . brew is a little too cold as it was in my basement . very nice . d- this is a very drinkable beer .  abv 5 % pours a brilliant , perfectly clear , golden color with a fluffy three finger white head . picture perfect of a pils .  mouthfeel is quite viscous , with not a lot of texture . feels full and a bit flat . could use more carbonation to cut through the smokey flavour more .

no faults here ... s : citrus , roasted malt , cocoa , and chocolate malt . all very light aromas . t : acidic darker and roasted malt , the same cocoa as detected in the smell is present here as well .  appearance : slightly hazy , ruby-amber pour with a voluminous ( and tenacious ) , light-tan whipped-cream head . recedes to floating dollops ... lace everywhere !  m : feels alright . average .

surprisingly malty aroma from the fresh pour . hop aromas are very muted , particularly for the style . while appealing , this does n't produce the tradition ipa smell . like the smell , more malty than the style suggests , but it is still delicious .  appearance : pitch black . very dark head .  my first tripel style beer , i spit it on my counter . the flavors of fruit combined with a bitter aftertaste left one bottle down the drain , and three still sitting in their case . anyone near me is welcome to the other three . while i am confident in the quality of this product , this style is definitely not for me .

aroma , while nice , is on the more subtle side .  got a single of this the other day , and poured it into my mug and the appearance is beautiful . hazy straw color , best looking ive seen in a hefe .  the drawback on this beer is the carbonation - it 's too heavy . sparkly but with a nice dryness in the finish .

faint clean scent the malty base swiftly gives way to a spicy resin that lingers so long you can get lost in its subtle piney suggestions of cinnamon and nutmeg .  one beautiful looking barleywine here . it almost glows a nice dark amber color .  the nose is caramely and very malty . a little too carbinated for a traditional barleywine but lines ones gut like the best of the bunch ! being a sucker for barleywines i have to give this beer high remarks .

the aroma is very weak . actually , i ca n't get any aroma , even with a big swirl .  this brew pours into the glass with a black body topped by a thick creamy , light brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  body is light and the carbonation is lively , a bit too much for my preferences .

the aroma was clean , woody , spicey , and fruity .  slightly opaque with a chilled haze , this brew looks damn inviting .  but there are hints of dark fruits that seem to disintegrate on your tongue , slight astringent alcohol tate/smelll this is defiantly a very drinkable brew .

smell : just a simple beer smell hops barley a bit floral . a little floral like th smell .  dark chocolate brown with a nice , thick , creamy , khaki head atop .  while the champagne-like extreme dryness may put off some , i think it makes the beer truly unique and tasty as opposed to unblanced .

nice straw gold , big rolicking white head . nothing special . grainy at first , gives way pretty quickly to caramel . finish could use some work , it just sort of ... ends . needs some hopping to bulk up the backend . very drinkable , nice for a hot summer day .  a : yellow , straw hues , slightly hazy , enormous whipped meringue head , long lasting retention , nice lacing .  and this is a surprisingly warming , earthy-tasting beverage for a `` summer ale '' -- i would n't mind opening up one of these in midwinter either , except in that it lacks body . it 's in the mouthfeel that the summeriness stands out .

the aroma is not very strong for a double ipa , but pleasant . tastes good .  a gorgeous beer , this pours a rich , hazed , honey amber with a killer head of eggshell puff that forms stiff rocky peaks and deposits thick clumps of lace .  medium bodied with carbonation that was a little too high and too coarse for my liking , but it did n't turn me off completely . my only issue was the carbonation .

not too much in the way of the aroma department , kind of dissapointing .  appearance - you can immediately tell from pouring that this beer has exceptional carbonation . it also has phenomenal lacing capabilities that do n't want to let go of the glass .  the mouthfeel was a little on the watery side but i did n't feel like it ruined the experience .

nice job by a new ( to me ) bartender . amber shade to the brew , with a slight aroma of sweet malts and hops . nice representative of the style .  poured into duvel tulip glass , half beer half very thick foamy head . very solid beer .  m - a little thin-bodied and watery and a little low on the carbonation .

the smell is that of a traditional lager with a little roasted malt to it .  this beer poured slow , and was pitch black in color . the head was medium sized , but brown , with small bubbles . looked beautiful !  ran into the maui brewing company while killing time until our dinner reservations were ready . there was a very slight bitterness in the aftertaste but was well hidden in the passion fruit sweetness . found the beer to start like any average golden ale but the aftertaste was what i really liked about it sorta like an ice tea aftertaste .

a great summer ale . taste is citrusy . all in all , this is not a complex beer or anything really special .  blood red color with a thick pink foamy head the color of blush wine .  the beer seems to thin a bit in the mouthfeel . very clean beer for a triple , slightly thin in the mouthfeel , but that helps give this beer a nice clean dry finish .

s- there really is n't much of a smell , but there is a slight metallic smell , with a bit of a slight acid smell . as this warms up its more of a sour cabernet sovereign .  a : clear , pale golden color with two fingers of fluffy white foam that diminishes to a quarter-sized berg . extensive speckled lacing remains on the glass and tiny bubbles rise in many steady streams through the column .  lowish carbonation and a slightly thin mouthfeel .

s - very fresh but light aroma .  but not rahr and son 's w.w. from the get go the pour was great a beautiful reddish brown with a head that stuck around for awhile . and lacing that covered the glass throughout the few minutes it took for me to gobble this one down and lots of sediment in the bottle .  toward the end of the drink , the beer felt almost flat .

very dark with a light tan head . smell is not too impressive and kind of fruity .  pours black with a long lasting brown head that leaves plenty of lacing .  smooth and to the point , bit of a sweet aftertaste in the sweet sticky beer way .

s : a bit oc chocolate but not much to the nose here t : malty chocolateness , along with a bit of bready malt .  a : poured a dark clear ( filtered ) chocolatey amber color with a rich white foamy head .  light , decently carbonated , and quenching for the desert dweller .

tried to hold it up to some light , and managed to spill ( experimental error , or general incompetance ) i 'm finding it a little weak in the nose , generally unexpressive . solid dark roast , a little espresso , perhaps a little sarsaparilla . tastes deep , heavy , and satisfying .  dark copper with a 2 finger off-white head from a 22 into a pint glass . i drink slower , so i poured the remainder almost 30 minutes later and it still formed a 2 finger head . this is much lighter in the smoke than any rauch that most people have had .  it also takes a hit because while it looks thick , it feels a bit thinner than it should be .

aroma is quite subdued . subtle citrus and toasted malt about sums it up . taste follows suit , but offers a bit more .  glass : chimay goblet temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees bottling date : 04-23-08 pours an exceptional clear golden amber color . minimal head that retains a light lacing all the way down .  m : thinner and crisper .

this beer is n't bad , but it does n't stand out in any way to me . the color is good , but the taste is a bit carbonated and weak for a porter . not as rich as i like , but not too pungent either . i prefer the cream stout . not sam 's best .  a- gorgeous . deep gold with hints of orange .  m - this is the weakest part of the beer . medium body with a little too much carbonation .

s : not a real pungent smell ... .a little dank . not bad but nothing special . t : nice well balanced hop beer .  incredible retention , eventually falling to a quarter-inch layer of froth . impressive start .  the carbonation is nice throughout . thinner than expected also .

s - herbal hops , sweet fruit and graininess ; feels a little light in the nose t & m - hop bitterness nicely balanced with malts .  pours a nice deep and shiny orange/amber , with a beautiful white , fluffy head that stays a good while . nice creamy lacing on the glass .  the overall feel is dry , like it should be , but unfortunately , it 's also a touch chaulky , which is pretty unfortunate .

sexy stuff . smells of roast malt and cocoa . very faint , should be stronger .  on tap o'brien 's pub san diego , ca black with a lot of visible carbonation and a thin brown head . regular , lined lacing down the glass . very attractive and perfect for a black ipa . roasted malts and pine aromas combine , though i would suggest that the roast is fairly dominant .  m-a bit watery for my tastes but the taste makes you forget about it being slightly thin .

( s ) - a dry , yet floral-like citrus . a damp wood-like pine . ( t ) - a fresh & crisp floral citrus of lemon , pineapple , grapefruit , and lime . has everything you would expect from the style .  a deep golden pour teams with a fluffy cream head . good head retention and great lacing . very sexy served in a tulip .  mouthfeel : the body is oddly thin , and crisp .
smells of ambient pines and a touch of birch bark with a pale , white toast base . rather bland .  this beer looks perfect . pretty gold color , with a nice big fluffy head .  nothing special here .

real nice looking here . very dirty and manure like smelling . this is kind of unexpected . overall nose seems slightly off putting , but the taste more than makes up for it .  pours a clear dark brown with superior side lacing and a copious tan head with very good retention . appearance is exceptional .  m- thin to medium in body . highly attenuated with a soft carbonation .

the nose is very mild , with just a hint of malt .  pours a light , burnt orange , very clear . the beautiful amber-orange gives it an amazing radiant quality , looks delicious and refreshing . also great for the beach , on a deck or patio watching the sun set to match the color of this gorgeous beer , especially since it will go great with chips and salsa .  medium bodied and dry .

the smell is hoppy and a little of for some reason .  appearance : i 'm a huge fan of this beer 's appearance . it is mildly dark in colour with a deep rich , ruby read colour that really glows when held up to light . it pours with a nice dense , slightly rocky head .  4.5/5 m : crisp , medium body .
not much in the nose . coffee and maybe a hint of lactose .  the carbonation gives rise to an absolutely stunning off white , creamy head with excellent retention .  carbonation seems spot on .

poured from bottle into chimay goblet . smell - all i can really smell is the alcohol , maybe a bit of oak , not sure . taste - exceptional for its abv .  1,000 review a- awesome copper red appearance , great foam and nice head when poured from a bottle .  a malty mouthful without much carbonation . resiny flavors fill the mouth but do n't obscure the big malt . this one is quite drinkable with an interesting mix of flavors that rise out of the basic malty sweetness .

s - light citrus hop aroma . not much else .  1 pint 6 oz tall dark brown bottle with a racer checkered flag on the label with red and yellow print , pewter cap . great retention and clumpy lace .  nice floral hops and malt starchiness in the finish . it 's a drinkable beer . heavy in the stomach .

light aromas of sweet fruit and a hint of chocolate ... but it is very faint !  thanks to mistakebythelake for this growl pour apperance- golden orange with a good amount of white head . a gorgeous beer !  mouthfeel was week and its not complex at all .

appearance : straw color , effervenscence , good head , awesome lacing smell : this is blasphemy but it smelled sorta like mgd .  growler the bruery placentia , ca a clear light golden with a big and thick foaming white head . the head sticks around for quite a while and eventually leaves thick and sticky lacing all down the glass .  mouf & gt ; nice , nothing special drinkability & gt ; sure thing

my sense of smell is not the greatest so do n't want to bash it on this but the smell is not strong enough for me to really pick out much , just a pleasant grassy aroma . mouthfeel is very good with quite a lot of carbonation [ or so i thought ] followed by quite a solid hops kick and lingerng bitter aftertaste . is actually very hoppy for what is meant to be a english style pale ale , which i have often found quite subdued . this really is a nice enjoyable beer , admitedly it cost about as a imported english pale ale & i do think they have played with the style a little to make it this bitter but very nice indeed .  a : an outstanding looking beer . dark plum color with a pinch of tannish head and amazing coating lacing . stunning .  if you aerate the beer in your mouth , it really releases the co2 . it would do well as a beer to server with medium to strong cheese .

original rating date : august 30 , 2008 pours an enticing dark gold , smells of a bit of hops but not as much as i expected , relatively weak on the nose which surprises me as most iipas i 've tried have a great nose . looking down the ratings already here , it seems like i 'm the only one who will score this weak on aroma- maybe my nose is too stuffed ? i want to give this a higher rating but the nose just was n't there for me . either way , excellent iipa , a far better effort than lagunitas ' regular ipa .  it poured with a huge , frothy , clumpy , and sticky head that was the darkest brown i 've ever seen .  a little lighter and less sweet than many `` real '' belgian beers , and a little thinner in the mouthfeel department .

there was a faint earth and citrus aroma but nothing really pronounced .  i had this on tap and have to say was extremely impressed by its beautiful golden color , and fine head .  mouthfeel was fine but that doesnt make up for much .

the smell is malty , very mild . mouthfeel is thick , rich , almost creamy .  this one pours a beautiful orange copper color with 3/4 '' off-white head .  m - crisp and bitey , high carbonation - the bottle overflowed when i opened it .

appearance- it has a nice straw golden yellow body . smell- pretty plain and not much aroma to speak of which i thought was odd for bavarian beer . taste- it has a very nice but even hoppy taste for a beer of this style .  a - a very light straw color with great clarity and a large , thick white head . perfect . this looks tame like a corona but has loads of complexity .  parching on the tongue . almost no flavor : slight sweetness up front , trace of bitterness on finish . really .

aroma : sweet , grainy wheat accompanied with apple , citrus , and a slight hint of floral hops taste : sharp lemon and apple over a tasty and grainy wheat backbone . drinkability : excellent , as you 'd expect from any wheat beer worth a damn . verdict : saint arnold has created a solid wheat beer , perfect for a summer 's day here in texas .  the beer pours a jet black liquid ; impenetrable by light . the head is a nice coffee color , about an inch right up to the edge of my pint glass . the head retention is excellent and the lacing on the side of the glass leads down to a creamy top of the beer even when almost gone .  light bodied .

i do n't usually like fruity beers especially one 's involving raspberries , in fact only apricots are a fruit that i liked in my beer . the smell is not overwhelming but the taste is perfectly mixed with a beer and raspberries .  pours an effervescent honey color with3+ fingers of cream colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : grapefruit & lemon , fades a bit as this warms t : follows the nose , plus pineyness , slight breadyness & a touch of leafy hops & dryness hiding behind a ton of grapefruit up front .  on tap this poured as a golden straw colored ale , clear and bright with less than an inch of head . there is an apparent hoppy aroma that followed with a similarly dominant slight-hoppy taste followed by the expected bitters - very tasty . i stopped with one . not to discount its drink-ability , there are just several others i wish to try .

i like a good pale ale and this one was just right . is paired very well with japanese food .  pours hazy gold with a massive , fluffy white head . very promising appearance , but way overcarbonated if you 're shooting for anything lambic-esque .  m_on the lighter side with a bit too much carbonation . the carbonation is along the lines of a tripel which is a bit too much for the style . d_the light body while a flaw style wise make this fairly easy to drink .

s - not bad , vinous with a touch of vinegar . some fruitiness there as well . t - fruit vinegar and a touch of funk there .  this is more like it ... pitch black . pours a thick brown head that quickly swells to 2 inches and then recedes to 1/4 inch .  m - a little thin , sickly-sweet finish .

it do n't smell all that strong or sweet , even for the style this seems little tame . light nodes of dark roasted barley . that 's it . tastes a god sight better .  pours into a nonic the darkest shade of brown , almost black . huge frothy tan head that leaves gobs of lacing around the glass with good head retention .  fairly thin and smooth , mild to medium bodied . breckenridge definitely delivers a vanilla porter as i would expect a vanilla flavored porter to be . i suggest toning down the roasted barley and focusing more on bittering hops .

good , solid , workaday porter . no off characteristics . clean and balanced . really good beer .  pours a very nice black color with some ruby hues and a thick white head . i love to watch this beer settle .  mouthfeel can be too fizzy if you do n't make sure to pour high for tall head . when i 'm drinking more than one beer , this is my favorite second or third , as it 's got enough hops to satisfy , is not highly alcoholic , and sells for a real good price where i live .

s : sweet malts and yeast on the nose for the most part . slight breadiness as well as a smidgen of hops , but not much .  very nice looking beer in a great setting .  m : not too bad , there was a little bit of body .

smell : really expected a bit more from this . chocolate and coffee aromas at the fore . also roasted malt .  pours a two finger cream head that fades slowly , leaving a good lace . nice deep amber color .  the only thing that could be improved on this beer is the mouthfeel . a bit light for my tastes , but like i said it has incredible drinkability without making you get too full too quick .

the aroma is slight but hoppy , with some pine to it . the flavor is surprisingly light , with piny hops and a tinge of bready malt .  a rich gold hue with white one-finger head , laces astonishingly well . looks like a good beer .  actually thought it might be bad but when i drank it there was plenty of carbonation . smell : a toasted malty smell with an almost cardboard smell . taste : very strong toasted smell but more of a bitterness then a sweetness . note : no date on the bottle but wondering if this beer had gone bad . will try another attempt at it but not really looking forward to it .

aroma is non descript ... maybe a hint of chocolate .  got this one in trade , thanks eric ... a : perfect look . thick 1 and 1/2 inch off-white head that slowly fades leaving nice lacing around the glass .  lighter mouthfeel than expected . d - full flavor and light mouthfeel .

smells mostly of sweet malt , with some fruit and wine-like oak . very nice complexity where the malt sweetness starts off , followed by fruit and some spices , then it has a crisp finish that 's malty and tails off with some more malt that 's roasted , delicious and dry . an overall great beer that is belgian in style and complexity , even though it 's a french beer ; clearly the belgian influence has dominated the taste of this beer , which i am thankful for .  impressive retention , plenty of lacing .  m - moderate carbonation , medium bodied .

smell is a bit muted , whiff of malt .  a clear copper ruby when held up to the light with brilliant head retention and honeycomb lacing .  mouthfeel works just fine , but is a little watery . highly drinkable .

the nose let 's you know this has a good bit of hops . the taste starts off smooth and malty , then the hops kick in and then more creamy goodness finishes this refreshing beer .  a - incredible crimson-amber color with a lasting two-finger off-white head .  the huge head tipped me off and my first taste confirmed that this beer was infected . as a homebrewer , i 'm sure to sample every beer i brew before i give it to a friend . a little qc goes a long way .

it has a nice colour and can easily be consumed on mass while watching either the maple leafs of the blue jays . i find that creemore does not have the best aroma and infact it greatly detracts from the flavour .  a : awesome when poured from a nitro bottle , cream to brown to almost black right before your eyes . nice caramel colored head and lacing that hung around throughout .  mouthfeel is smooth , crisp and almost watery , with medium carbonation and a medium body .

the beer tastes like a dark , think stout , except that it is very carbonated in comparison . so the beer is very smooth , but with a prickle that reminds me of a hard cider . a friend of mine has an inexpensive , yet tasty scotch that she says is her `` every day '' scotch .  poured from a 12 oz bottle , 2008 version a : pours a clear mahogany brown , with ruby hues , under a big slightly off white head . excellent retention and lace .  the mouthfeel was quite thin with a very fine and mild carbonation .

smells mild . pine and clean alcohol .  incredible whipped retention and lacing everywhere . this is an awesome looking beer !  m - light bodied , not overly carbonated , clean finish , mild fruity aftertaste fades quickly .

citric , fruity aroma . flavor is dominating by a surpsingly nice fresh , leafy hop flavor throughout the sip , undergirded by amaltiness which starts off sweet and develops a toasty , biscuity character toward the finish .  this beer had a beautiful pour into a tulip glass . very dark and rich , with a dark roasted tan head that was very thick and continually rebuilt itself every time i swirled the glass .  nice chewy mouthfeel , but significantly under-carbonated . the only thing it lacks is carbonation and a decent head .

the was not my favorite part of the experience , it has a strong urea scent to it which i did n't care for , but that was more than compensated by the taste . the taste is very rich and deep , with different hops tones throughout .  ( bottle into pint glass - sampled 4/5/10 ) picture perfect pour with a dark brown color and creamy off white head .  m : standard mouthfeel for a low alcohol ale .

the smell has some peach aromas to it , but it 's much lighter than i expected .  thanks for the opportunity ... poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1/4 '' dark brown ( almost purply black ) head above the opaque black brew . head hangs on , with average lace , which actually is pretty good for the style .  mouthfeel : medium and semi-smooth . bottom line : this is one of the most bland beers i 've ever had .

i did n't think it smelled much like a pilsener but then again i did notice the malt used ... .the hops were a little muted for the style i thought .  330ml bottle poured into tulip dec9 2010 a super hazy golden orange with tiny suspended particles being move around by a shitload of bubbles . a gentle pour leaves a massive 3 finger head that forms a dome over the top of the glass and just sits there for a while ever so slowly falling to a thick film with a island in the middle that looks like a little brain s a little yeast and pineapple with some other fruits i ca n't quite place and some booze t what i smell but with a little more booze , some cereals and a nice little blast of hops .  it states `` the deep coffee flavors are created naturally during the brewing process by dark roasted malts . '' then later it notes `` stout brewed with coffee . anyway , i 'll refer to this as a steady drinking stout because of its thinness , otherwise it 's pretty enjoyable . not particulary complex but enjoyable taste of roasted malt with coffee . abv seems pretty low as i had two with no noticable effects .

smell : faint aroma with some piney hops , a little bit of malt , and a hint of iced tea . taste : rich biscuit malty taste with a fair bit of caramel as well . drinkability : easily drinkable and very sessionable . final notes : a very good amber ale - lots of biscuity , caramelly goodness but the hoppy back end is also a pleasant surprise .  hazy light golden with a nice , moussy white head ; excellent head retention , and great lacing . perfect looks . no contest here .  the mouthfeel was medium bodied with adequate carbonation .

a very faint smell , hard to put a nose on it but there 's some sweetness there .  a : amazing head on top of a dark yellow body launches up to the top of the glass and hangs out forever , ending its long life in a spiderweb of beauty . glass is soapy all the way down . this beer could not look any more inviting .  it is light bodied and enjoyable . it has a light hops aroma and a light bodied feel to it .

smelled very malty with a little pinch of hops . tasted malty and sweet , with caramel and toffee undertones and a roasty finish .  pours a clear golden color with a thick , fluffy , off-white head .  a watery texture and lighter body than i expected from the nose , with a moderate amount of carbonation .

muddled malts are rather roasted and somewhat sweet . some coffee , perhaps . not the best . t : this more than makes up for the subpar flavour . the flavour is full of smoked chocolate , soft roasted malts , and nutty notes . d : quite drinkable , warming , filling , and satisfying . i 'm impressed .  pours a cloudy yellow/gold color , with a huge thick fluffy white head . a good deal of carbonation helped this head hold for what seemed like an eternity .  this is about my only complaint of this beer-too much carbonation ! carbonation gives a foamy/frothy mouthfeel .

the smell was very faint , hints of breads and malts . great taste ; earthy , bready , and lightly hoppy .  stamp directly on top of the white , generic cap announces : bottl 2008* a dark caramel body with a significant amount of sediment floating around that were actually dark in appearance . topping all of that is a nice , creamy white head that sticks around for several minutes . very cool look .  overall , i quite enjoyed this beer . it 's got a fresh and interesting taste that makes it a decent drinking beer . deliciously fruity hops , nice malt sweetness , comes across as quite fresh . noticeable taste of apricots which i quite like makes this distinctive and something i look forward to drinking . disappointing finish however . lots of interesting things happening up front and then nada . nothing really lingers which is a darn shame , 'cause overall this beer is well worth a try . still tasty after each bottle . mmmm .

smell is pretty average - sweet maltiness and slight citrusy hop aroma .  had a gorgeous impenetrable chestnut coloration , massive amounts of creeping carbonation , and a thick , creamy off-white head that displayed amazing retention .  mouthfeel is just a tad watery .

this hefe comes from a brewery whose name can be easily pronounced by an american speaker and as such , is approached with disdain and apprehension . if this were pfaffleschlutzelbraenhiemer brothers hefeweizen , i suspect this beer would be more favorably received . its all wheat and the faintest essence of fruitiness . some are hoppier , but the existence of superior beers dont make widmer hefeweizen a bad beer .  a - two fingers of off-white head slowly fade on top of a gorgeous translucent amber beer with bubbles rising steadily through it s - smell is a juicy blend of citrus and apricot , grapefruit is most prominent but plenty of orange zest comes through , apricot is muted and there 's a little bit of mint and pine in there too , do n't get too much aroma from the malts , a touch of toffee maybe t - flavor is far too muted considering that the beer is so appealing to the eyes and the nose , a touch of sweetness , a lot of hop bitterness , some grapefruit and orange , some apricot , but so subdued m - nice tongue coating from the hops but the carbonation is a little prickly , not as smooth as it could be o - not a bad ipa , not a great ipa .  long , super bitter piney bitterness , aftertaste almost of pine-sol but i love the hop attack . problem is that it 's too sweet and slightly syrupy , especially evident in the middle . a little harsh and unbalanced overall , big beer and it shows .

even though this beer tasted great , the smell left much to be desired . to some up in one word , bland in comparison to the complex smells of other beers .  a : fantastic clarity , golden , and a relentless head , a 3 millimeter head is still visible after 20 minutes , leaving rings of lace in its wake .  m - medium body , with moderate to high carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my liking . slightly thin , would like a bigger body from a stout . the mouthfeel is lacking , and sweet flavors of vanilla and chocolate make it too much like a dessert beer , one is all you need .

aroma of caramel , sweet malt , some alcohol , mild nuttiness and not much of a hop component . wow , flavor is suprising given a fairly unassuming aroma . a pretty decent to heavy hop bitterness gives way to a fabulous hop backbone and a floral hop flavor , with slight spiciness and maybe a hint of pepper .  the beer poured a nice black with a tan lacing .  mouthfeel : body is light to medium and slightly watery .

not a lot of aroma . crisp mouthfeel with a very nice bready , wheat flavor .  this brew pours with a deep amber body topped by a medium thick head with lots of lacing .  the mouthfeel is just a little light and watery .

the aroma is a bit lighter than i 'd expect for a dipa , picking up a grapefruit hop aroma with a strong sweet malt backing , hint of pine .  a-amber with sediment and good frothy head . the color an intense head gives this one high scores .  the mouthfeel is a bit weird ; kind of a harshness on the tongue .
