smell was alcohol and burnt malt .  pour revelaed an extremely thick and long lasting creamy white head.as it reduced it left rings of lace in the glass.the color presented was orange and somewhat cloudy.mouthfeel wasnt very crisp and seemed a bit watery.the finish left a sharp sweet or tart twist that dissapeared real quick.a bit bitter in the back of the throat with a wheaty grain taste.a spicy aroma thats not too strong but is there.tastes of oranges , lemon , cloves , corriander , and honey are noted.overall good with a medium body .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin and watery side though .

amber brown , with a thin light tan head and a scant malty aroma . full mouth , light chocolate start progressing to caramel with some spice .  a big fluffy ice cream scoop of a head , eventually smooths out to about a quarter inch . for a lager this is a very good looking beer .  even with the earthy malt flavor , the overall feel stays on the thin side .

very easy drinking ale with nice dark copper color and good lacing . makes a good session ale or good beer to introduce to non craft beer drinkers who will occasionally drink guiness stout .  a : damn near perfect in my book . nicely hazy , radiant golden orange color . it 's got a big , soapy head that settles into a cap and leaves big sheets of lacing . so far so good .  5/5 m : medium body and smooth . the lighter body makes it sit not-too-heavy , and it would be easy to partake of a few of these on a cold night .

s : a funky , doughy yeast aroma .  1-fingered extremely light tan head with very impressive retention , leaves rings of lace all the way down the glass .  m : crisp and a very smooth , medium body , medium carbonation , finish is slightly sticky . tad too thin for my liking , but not too bad .

smell : musty , minerally , grassy . taste : great malt sweetness tempered with spicy citrus hops .  pours an opaque thick looking black , with a fat beige head . very attractive .  lightly bodied , perhaps overly so , with a passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

s ; has a mild roasted malt aroma with a good bit of sweetness mixed in .  a : pours a beautiful bronze with ruby highlights . this beer looks fantastic . s : smell is of juicy citrusy hops , with an abundant dose of pale and caramel malt .  m : hmmm . it may be a tad too aggressive with the carbonation .

nice light smell of roasted nuts and dark caramel .  appearance : pours with a massive amount of head , ca n't even pour the bottle in one try . awesome lacing . the beer itself is black as black can be , without even a hint of any other color around the edges . drinkability : this beer is a beautiful thing to behold , with amazing lacing .  m : medium-bodied , creamy , resiny , thin finish .

smell is a little flat ... some burnt caramel and a little bit of orange citrus . taste is off the rocker , though ... this is basically dogfish head 90 minute without the bitterness .  pours out almost pitch black but some light shines through around the edges . a nice fluffy , off-white two finger head has nice retention and leaves heavy lace behind . a huge pillow stays on top of the beer .  m- the mouthfeel is a little lighter than expected , almost watered down .

bit of smoke in the nose , but overall subdued .  poured from a 11.6oz brown bottle with a white cap marked `` bottl 2006* 12 % '' into a tulip glass . easily one of the longest lasting , largest frothy heads of foam i have ever seen on any beer . appearance is a rusty yellowish orange color , cloudy and semi-translucent .  solid mouthfeel , nothing noteworthy , but nothing wrong with it .
body is not heavy , smell is no special event . try it .  in the original struise glass it looks really great .  m- just average .

slight malty nose . starts mellow with some sweetness , finish is more malt than hop with no aftertaste .  pours up a beautiful grapefruit color with a very thin white head .  m : smooth on the palate .

very clean aroma and taste , classic sammy smith . the complex grain profile makes it so delicious .  the beer poured a hazy golden color with a massive white head .  mouthfeel is a bit lacking . this is not a full-bodied beer , as i would prefer , but the carbonation level is to my liking for a barley wine drinkability is very good for a big beer .

surprisingly little spice aroma . relatively dry malt with very light hop . frankly , small in the nose .  a - caramel-butterscotch gold with a thick off-white head , very nice looking .  body is very thin for a dipa , medium carbonation .

i perceive an overall sanitizer/cleanser aroma overall though , pretty much hides the aroma of the brew .  brett poured a beautiful slightly hazed golden-orange color producing a massive white head of assorted bubble sizes which was a bit hard to tame .  m : surprisingly on the more carbonated side with a slight fizzy mouthfeel .

aroma of coffee though initially strong fades to subtle . the taste is superior to the smell . good mouthfeel with pleasant carbonation .  chocolate head over a pitch black pit , some sweet lacing ... some mild anise and roasted malts tingle the nose , also a hint of acetone in there .  i first had this beer a year ago and fell in love . so i was excited to see it appear once again this fall . i find it a very easy beer to drink even for the inexperienced beer drinker . flavorful and rich with malts , a slight hint of hops towards the end . the aroma is sweet but not overpowering , you can definitely smell the sweet malt that went into this brew . i highly recommend this beer . unfortunately its not around year round but it definitely will give you something to look forward to come fall .

the aroma is a bit of wheat and sweetness but not much .  pours with a fluffy , light tan head that sticks over a deep , hazy , amber brown body . great lace .  m : decent mouthfell , it has to have this considering how light it is .

aroma - not much of aroma . taste - cola and lightly fruity flavors . nothing amazing , but nothing to be shy about .  summit horizon red : a : appearance is exceptional , great amber-red color to it with exceptional clarity ! nice 1 '' head that develops yet depletes half-way through .  quite watery for the big flavor this one tastes and smells different from the main stream craft ipas , which is a pretty new category i 'll give it that .

s - muted floral notes , a certain meaty quality , and some of the malt is coming out in the nose - hints of nut and bread .  still a bit of haze but not anything like a hefe . the beer looks great in this glass !  a light- to moderate mouthfeel , hints of sour flavor linger at the back of the tongue after the swallow . i do n't pick up much of a hint of carbonation in the mouthfeel .

s - very little nose . vague impression of american hops ; lightly sweet and citrusy .  pours a cloudy golden/orange color with a two finger frothy head that has really good retention and leaves lots of sticky lacing .  m : light body , watery touch , smooth with low carbonated in the mouth .

when smell is present , it is pleasant . taste=good taste .  it poured black as a tuxedo in a dark closet . it came topped with a dense , dark-brown head that had a lot of staying power .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too syrupy , though it does n't detract much at all from the enjoyment of the beer .

s- dull smelling dry hops , wheat malt . well balanced with bitter dry hop nose , complex wheat malt finish . the nose lacks however .  probably the prettiest lacing you will ever see on a glass . effing beautiful .  first sip reveals a much thinner body than i expected and average carbonation .

s - not much going on smell wise , reserved , yet some hints of dark roast , fresh mulled grains .  appearance : gorgeous beer with strong lacing throughout the entire glass . it looked sooo good , but there is almost no aroma .  m : the honey seems to add a little body to this , but other than that , just average .

s : light on any nose , what i could smell was a bit malty , but otherwise the entire scent was nearly non-existent . t : fantastic ! powerful , full malt with slight yet perfectly blended hops . i was a bit turned off by the smell , but as soon as i had a swig , i was totally impressed .  two fingers of thick billowing collapse into a thin cap that left sticky lacing on my glass .  this beer pours with a very pale yellow body topped by a medium thick head with some lacing left behind . not much flavor or aroma but more than you get from most light beers . the aroma was sour and bitter and the flavor was malty with a hint of bitter hoppiness .

mild bakers ' chocolate with a roasted toffee smell . nothing exciting ; expected .  this keller bier produces vast amounts of bright white head and has a hazy orangish and silver color .  mouthfeel : a bit thin and watery .

mickey 's is the malt liquor that makes the name worth it . granted the whole idea that you play the brown paper bag hiding game , not right way to enjoy this delicious beverage . if you 're going to `` roll '' with a malt liquor , this is the selection for that night .  a - black , inch and half of tawny head . leaves amazing lacing that should be in a museum as art .  mouthfeel - smooth , yet a litle effervescent .

smell : not much smell , the small amount i am getting has nice coffee and mocha notes . taste : this really shines in this category , like the smell suggests this has strong coffee flavor with a nice mocha after taste that really becomes apparent several seconds after tasting . the light mouthfeel and the carbonation make this very drinkable ; almost scary drinkable for an oatmeal stout !  head retention was excellent , melting down to a slightly less huge frothy , rocky head . lacing was thick and plentiful ... .a beautiful looking beer .  not too much that i can to the other reviews here . this beer was nothing but dissapointing . the label does say ipa right ? where are the hops ? i know that it does n't have to be a hop bomb but the flavor just is n't very good at all . i 've got 5 bottles left from this 6-pack . now i have to decide if i struggle though them or i just pour them out .

perfect for drinking on the patio on a summer evening or with a light lunch ! been looking for a good summer beer since the demise of petes rally cap ! this has hints of citrus in a bright light beer that goes down all too easily !  my bottle looks different than the picture ; guess they changed the label . appearance : clear light amber with a big frothy head of light tan .  my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin .

the smell is not all that appealing . it is way earthy and at first it reminded me of an ashtray . the mouthfeel is excellent very `` wet '' and good finish . overall , a very nice beer .  appearance - gold honeyed color in a belgian glass . extremely high effervescence yields 3 fingers of foam instantly . the soft bubbled head recedes unevenly to a thin solid cover .  start is lightly sweet , the top skeletal in feel , the finish lightly carbonated , hops shy in their spiciness , a bit medicinal , dry aftertaste , quite drinkable but a touch different than my normal american over the top beers , and frankly scarlet i dont give a damn , im ready for a change .

huh . ok , big punch in the mouth for flavor . lovely beer .  this is the only barley wine i have every tried , and chances are it will be the last . some people love this stuff , not me , not my taste buds .  it has a medium body and a fair amount of carbonation , but again feels a bit weak .

smelled of sweet malt and tart fruits .  the color of this beer i find just amazing . it 's so dark as it sits in a guinness glass , with it 's beautiful smooth head . are there bubbles finer than these ? in contrast to how heavy it looks , it 's goes down incredibly smooth and fast .  smoky , malty and mildy coffee-like . deep black with a thumb thick mocha head . fore is hoppy bitter then roasted barley malt follows . very much in the fullers vein as opposed to the more roasty and coffee/chocolate flavored american porters . very nice brew .

my first instinct was that the aroma was very faint ; but as i adjusted , the roasted malts smell followed by a yeasty , brown bread and caramel odors .  this pours out the same deep orange color as the last one with the same solid fluffy head , lacing , etc . as appearance goes , there is nothing left to improve upon .  t - great pilsner , very slight hops , clean finish m - light body d - very smooth and very drinkable .

the smell was very modest and faintly malty .  a- pitch black with a nice tan head s- roasted malt hits the nose right away , some undertones of black coffee and dark chocolate t- the nose gave the preview roasted malts , coffee and dark chocolate , very nice m- balanced , but i do like my stouts a bit thicker d- an easy dinking stout that i could have often .  a bit thin , for i think i like them a bit more bodiful , but smooth and flavorful i do think this one , yes .

smells of a typica quad , a bit spicey and harsh .  bottle : poured a deep pitch-black stout with a motor oil consistency and a small foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  m - the bitterness and acidic notes can be a bit of a turnoff , and its a bit prickly going down , thus not the smoothest dubbel i 've had . o - a tasty dubbel , but not my favourite .

lacing got more impressive as the glass emptied . i quite enjoyed this beer and found it more interesting than the leffe blonde ; my only criticism might be that it 's a bit too rich at times , but that 's a minor distraction . my preferred leffe right now .  pours a dark brown with nice ruby highlights and a very frothy cappuccino head that lasts and leaves abundant lacing .  my first new pumpkin beer of the year . i love october ( because of pumpkin flavored beers ) . this is definitely not the best pumpkin beer i 've tried , but it 's still a very good beer . if you like shock top 's wheat , you want to try this . i ca n't promise i 'll buy another 6 pack , mostly due to price and wanting to try new things .

this is the first time i 've bought leinenkugel 's on my own and i 'm very delighted in the results . smell is bland and much less present than any other aspect .  appearance there 's pretty much no flaw to how this beer looks . its a deep , thick black , capped with a super rich , creamy tan head . great retention and solid lacing .  a bit too foamy actually . last swigs : overall enjoyable . that 's cheap !

smell is lightly malted and a bit sweet ... not unpleasant at all .  330 ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance - the beer pours a hazy golden orange with three fingers of pillowy off-white head .  m : medium-light in body .

aromas of hops , alcohol , and yeast .  this beer pours a hazy honey golden orange with a huge fluffy white head , that leaves some seriously sticky lacing . i could only think to myself that this is an absolutely beautiful beer .  smooth , mellow finish , and a thin watery mouthfeel .

however , the nose is pretty muted overall .  a - this beer pours black in color . this is a beautiful looking beer .  ( m ) smooth , oily , and flat . it 's a solid beer , or a solid base of a beer that could be improved only with a better mouthfeel .

s : surprisingly little nose on this beer . it has some maltiness and caramel notes , but again not a ton there .  head holds well making this an incredibly good looking beer .  mouthfeel : a little thin , medium body , low carbonation , medium flavor . underwhelming mouth .

the aroma is oddly sweet . the floral nature of the jasmine really comes out in the nose . i really do n't know if the sweetness comes from the jasmine or the malt .  terrific retention and lots of lace . stunning .  m - this one finished a little dry , too much so for my liking , but the carbonation was nicely balanced , making it very smooth .

strong malty smell , along with some dark fruits soaked in alcohol ... cherries or plums .  the beer was poured into a champagne flute . appearance : this may be the singularly best looking beer i have ever seen in a glass . the head was very tall and proud with an off white coloration . the retention was perfect throughout the consumption of the beer . the carbonation was explosive rolling boiling bubbles .  m - pretty watery and thin .

this is a good beer . it poured a nice light amber with a small head . the taste was surprising and full flavored for the style with a good balance between hops and it 's great sweet malt backbone . the mouthfeel was exceptionally creamy .  pours a huge head with crazy retention that wo n't leave the glass .  m : somewhat thick , bread-y . but smooth .

aroma of burnt toffee - more like a brown ale to me . very tasty , hop flavor mixes well with the roasty , chewy grains . no yeast trub in this bottle .  dark brown head over a black body . there were tons of good stouts opened at the tasting , but this rose to the top of the heap . lovely stuff  on my first stop on my michigan beer tour . the grand cru on tap was a very nice start to my tour . the first taste was wonderful , but , the flavor of the beer left my mouth looking for just alittle more .

smell is hops and very very little floral notes .  a : beautiful two inch creamy head . incredible creamy yellowy orange color with micro rising carbonation .  m -- slightly too watery , does n't really coat the mouth like i would hope but it washes down clean with no bad lingering tastes d -- this is it here , i think this is the beer i would use to introduce someone new to ipa 's .

smells kind of like homemade bread .  it was presented in a room-temperature glass with a thin , bone-white head with moderate retention . the color was spot on - a beautiful , deep-golden yellow with ne-quality clarity .  could use both more body and carbonation .

08-09 winter bottle out of a 6pack . smell has a bit of alcohol in there which i would expect , but i did n't pick up the alcohol in the taste . very powerful and tastey . i may have to get another 6er to age .  bottle slightly hazy golden orange and yellow . quickly forming , large , persistent near-white head . lots of lacing left down the glass .  the mouth is a tiny bit like flat soda which was the only off-putting part of this beer .

s - there is n't much of a very strong aroma with this beer , but what is there is hints of caramel , lemon , and pine . d - flirts with being sessionable , but is more of a `` couple pints is good '' deal imho . overall - a very solid pnw ipa . pretty tough to beat for $ 4 a bomber . if you 're in the mood for a decent ipa , this one will deliver .  hazy blond in color with a steady stream of bubbles rising from the bottom of the glass to form a huge , thick , rocky white head that lasts for the entire glass .  malts help to round it out a little , but that bitterness hangs around for quite a bit m : medium body with typical sa carbonation , slightly oily d/o : well , apparently zeus is known for that intense piney flavor , so it is highlighted well here .

an excellent golden yellow body with semi haze . smell is prety light , just a hint of the american hefewizen light crispness , zest . this hefe has tons of flover it just dosent need to blast your palate with them .  poured into a standard snifter at about 55 degrees f , 1-inch head , light lacing , deep beautiful cloudy magenta .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is quite sharp ; a bit fizzier than i 'd like .

it 's very drinkable and has a pleasant , subtle mix of grain , hops , and english yeast . the aroma is very muted , even for this style , i just get a little grain dust , but the taste holds lightly caramel barely and gentle , spicy hops that finish the beer out . overall , a great session beer and a rare locally-brewed example of the style .  poured into a chimay goblet and it looks beautiful . nice size head with a nice golden clear look to it .  taste : a bit thin for a porter , almost to the point of being slightly watery .

aroma is basic , clean and crisp .  pours a murky brown/dark copper with brighter highlights when held to the light . a three-finger sticky and frothy tan head crests the top of my tulip glass , but stays together . the head lasts a long time and leaves thick sheets behind .  the mouthfeel is slightly buttery but leans more towars a syrup-like feel . carbonation would be greatly appreciated and add a very unique feel for this beer .

the aroma was mostly a bready malt smell with just a hint of hops and a bit of a clove scent . i would prefer more interesting citrus flavors , but it is still very good .  poured into a snifter , revealing rich black body and one of the thickest and darkest heads i 've ever seen on an ris , one which bubbles down nicely into a turgid foamy mess of a surface .  i wish the mouthfeel had a bit more viscosity ... .but i say that about every stout .

aroma is surprisingly mild with light roasted malt and espresso scents a hit of grassy hops mixed in too .  pours a beautiful dark orange/copper color with a good head retention and lacing . i love the color of this beer .  t - again , bicuit and nut . nice and malty , virtually no hop bite , but tasty none the less . d - i have had this a ton in the past , but i only just got around to getting another one for the purposes of reviewing .

s : very mild malty , grainy scents . some background hop aroma present .  bottle into a pils glass pours a clear , deep copper orange with a one and a half inch off-white head which holds up well throughout from lots of carbonation release . it also leaves some nice looking sheets of lacing down the sides of the glass . ca n't ask for a better looking beer .  m : somewhat thin body , slightly watery ; could do with more carbonation also .

smells mostly of citrus and light malt . floral notes . nothing too prominent .  let 's start with first impressions : this big beer makes a big impression on appearance . dark and sinister looking , the rough-textured mocha-colored head sits atop the black body like a russian fur cap . lacing is full and sticky .  smell is cocoa , touch of coffee , licorice , slight vanilla , a whiff of smoke . taste is thick creamy , dark and bakers chocolate , touch of espresso , end is dry and slightly bitter , a woody aftertaste .

s- not so much here , unfortunately . some citrus hops with some sweet malt . slightly floral as well . t- good stuff , not too much bite not too much sweetness . this is a fine ipa .  jet black ... amazing tan head .  from the perfume river in vietnam ( no really , that 's what the label says ) , on to the beer : poured into a mug , it 's a clear yellow color with a soda-like head . this flavors in the beer do n't meld together well for me . there 's more cooked corn , a mild astingency , and a straightforward bitterness that battle each other for supremecy . even at ice cold , it took some work for me to stomach this beer . round off the edges and we might have something more tolerable .
smell : yeasty . maybe some very mellow goldings or fuggles .  its pale golden liquid is filled with lively bubbles cascading to the the bright long lasting white head .  m - felt a bit thin to me .

smell : not much here , smelled like your average porter . weak coffee scents were all i got . taste : like guinness draught with some balls .  dark brown pour with a solid tan head .  a - black on the pour with no head whatsoever s - big burnt malt and bittersweet chocolate aroma along with some bourbon , some oak and vanilla in there as well , slight alcohol , as the beer warms up , smells almost like straight bourbon , maybe more like a bourbon and cola t - big bourbon flavor right up front , lots of oak as well , some bittersweet chocolate in the body , finish is more bourbon and oak along with some vanilla , alcohol notes , long finish m - a bit too flat for my taste , full-bodied but totally devoid of any carbonation action in the mouth d - i 'm glad port put this in a 375ml bottle , because this is a sipper , treated this almost like fine bourbon sipping for quite awhile , but i could sip on this all night very interesting beer .

the scent is a malty mix of grains and corn . very wheaty smell with a very slight hint of hops .  poured into a weizen glass . beautiful colors here - shades of deep amber , gold , and a bone white head that leaves all kinds of lacing . decent amount of carbonation bubbles are present as well .  heavy bodied but also heavily carbonated . less carbonation would have been preferred as experiencing more of the beginning flavors would make for a more enjoyable tasting .

she loves scotch ales/scottish ales and when i ca n't turn up something new/local for her to enjoy i fall back on the classic imports . the nose is mildly malty .  there is something hypnotic about watching the beer cascade into a jet black liquid with a wonderful tan thick creamy head . to me , the head on this is the best of almost any beer , and has a unique look .  little fruityness . light to medium body , oily , light carbonation . could be a little more carbonated .

a 1.5in foamy head builds as i pour-swish-pour-swish-pour my way through the last 4 ozs . lots of cloves and bread in the nose , but just as dominant is the smell of bier . perhaps a bit of citrus as well . the first few pulls are sublime , with big mouthfeel and a wonderful orange citrus mid palate .  frickin ' a beautiful . deep and black , medium head of nice and tight dark tan bubbles . no effort required to get it and even going vigorously on the pour it seems like there 's not a crazy amount of head . beautiful .  the carbonation is ok ; small fresh bubbles at a decent strength .

it smells sweet , with pine and citrus coming through .  it 's one of the prettiest beers i 've ever seen ! deep , dark brown with a hint of ruby when held up to strong light . a tan frothy and foamy lasts and lasts , leaving waves of sticky lace on the side of the glass ( artful ) .  medium thin body manages a bit of creaminess .

hay and some sweetness give this beer a fairly simple aroma . grainy flavored beer with some faint pale malt sweetness .  a : ca n't really take anything away from this one , perfect tan head on top of a pitch black body .  m : finish stays around for quite a while , almost too long , really coats the mouth .

aroma is admittedly pretty normal for the style , spicy hops and a cool malt sweetness . nice , if a little faint , and certainly typical .  poured a beautifully clear , clean amber golden color , with a huge 3 finger , frothy , white head . lacing was incredible on this one , totally covered from the top to the bottom of the glass when finished .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with a high level of biting carbonation ( the carbonation is the only part of this beer that i 'm not too fond of ) . quite dry due to the high level of carbonation .

i 'm not up on my tasting formalities , so i 'll forgo the usual format and say this : + extremely malty . not necessarily a bad thing on its own , but in this case it was overwhelmingly , sickly sweet .  pours a very clear copper color with a fluffy white head . leaves lots of lacing on the glass as it slowly recedes .  this brew is 5.2 % abv and my bottle looks exactly the same apart from the two silver australian international beer awards one from 2007 & the other from 2008 in the top left of the label anyways it pours a dark cola hue with a fast vanishing two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is fresh chocolate icecream and vanilla expresso , it has an average mouthfeel with tastes of fresh chocolate icecream , vanilla expresso , macadamia and it finishes with a light bitter mouthfeel , overall a nice brew that is just lacking that full mouthfeel of a stout in my mind but in saying that its very sessionable and ill definately buy this again .

feeling inside the neck , it is totally smooth so i have no reservation about the safety of the beer , but the carbonation is another thing ... aroma - roasted grain , kind of woody , a touch of coffee beans .  it basically looks very impressive ... fantastic .  had this during o'briens wet hop festival . pours clear orange with a white ring of bubbles . lots of caramel with some tropical hops in the nose . kind of like a fruitcake . earthy , yet citrusy in the taste . bit sweeter than your normal ipa . grapefruit and blood orange . good stuff .

really nice looking brew . s : apricot faint apparent , hops overwhelm the fruitiness making for a very odd nose .  poured out a beautiful and dark midnight black color with a cascading and creamy rich head of tan foam .  mouth feel is reasonably rich .

a little bit of fruit gone bad on the nose , this might be due to the aging , it is n't too strong but still noticeable . rich malts and still some hops in the bg .  poured from a 750ml bottle into a champagne flute : appearance : pours a beautiful strawberry red/ lavander purple color . huge pink head that has great retention .  the body is sufficient to carry the 10 percent alcohol which is impressive by itself . some spicy notes and an effervescent type of feel to it .

s : surprisingly light smell ; holds heavily roasted dark malts a bit smoked . strong black coffee . t : taste is stronger than smell ; sweet marzipan-like malt , heavy roast and smoked .  appearance - black with murky auburn brown edges . nice semi tan head with great retention and lacing . super sticky on the sides , just beautiful .  t - tastes like a combination of pine-sol and a basic light lager m - who cares ?

smell is all malt and little hops ... i do n't detect a hint of citrus or hops smell at all .  a beautiful looking beer with at least a two-finger head that lasts for a while before fading to a nice cap that remains to the end .  first pull provided a mouthfeel that was a little more smooth than i would have expected , just short of creamy .

smell : i ca n't pick up much here . some yeast and maybe hints of vanilla ?  pours nicely for a two finger thick tan head , and has a copper colored well filtered body .  carbonation is n't bad , with fairly good activity after each drink . mouth-feel is a bit dry .

surprising aroma of the euro skunk , not heavy , but noticeable - along with some spicey malts .  lovely looking beer , and very similar in appearance to the classic guinness look , with a large creamy tan head on top of a dark body .  it has a medium-light body and it 's pretty smooth .

not much of an aroma on this but picked up some slight floral hints and a bit of caramel .  first of all this is an amazing looking beer . a nice pale orange , hazy , with a huge rocky white head . great retention and that belgian lace that i love .  m - this is where the beer ranks fairly average for me . under carbonated and a little bit flat , would have liked it to be heavier , stickier , and have more of a bite .

nose is not what i expected . quite lacking especially in the hop department . but everything else is great . nice spicy and earthy rye notes with mild fruit and a touch of citrus . overall it 's a nice very drinkable beer . lacking in hop notes and characteristics for an ipa , but good . i do recommend this for the nice rye spiciness and earthiness that is really nice .  black boss porter , poland the bottle is very bold and to the point , solid block cap , impressive . poured into pint glass : this beer is rich black color with a creamy brownish head , the head is small but retains well and long . the nicest red/mahogany color come thought when hit by light .  it has little to no head on it with a soft pour . this beer has a good balance of spices that is not overpowering . the aftertaste is mellow . this is one of the darker ales that i have drank but all in all i would give it another try . especially on a snowy winter day .

despite my usual preference for ales , i really enjoy this lager . if the macros produced lagers like this one ( and i 'm sure they could do so ) , american beers would be looked at quite differently by the world of beer experts .  this ipa is perfect specimen as far as appearance . it is a cloudy gold in color with a nice foamy long lasting head that sticks perfectly to the glass .  m - a little water , but it goes down smoothly d - this is a really good beer .

the initial pour sends a wafting of grapefruity hop notes into the nose , though sadly the aroma fades away , becoming very subdued .  appearance : hazy golden orange . effervescent body with a thick pillowy , white head that just wo n't quite .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low yet sharp carbonation .

aroma is very soft a little bready malt , and pumpkiny but hard to bring forth . the flavor is nice definately my favorite sam seasonal .  on initial pour this is one of the finest looking brews i 've ever laid eyes on .  m good medium body , with a lot of carbonation , either takes away from this beer .
the beer was thin , watery , with a touch of bitter hops .  a : excellent dark red color . very bright and enticing .  mouthfeel : it 's a bit heavy for the style .

s : some malt characters , bread and toffee mostly . after that not to much going on in the nose . very subtle hints of hops but that 's reaching for it . d : very drinkable beer !  this was poured from the bottle into a consendonk tulip glass . a - clear light golden straw color with a thick foamy , ice cream-like head that is very well retained s - sweet malt and fruity yeast aroma with a slight hop spiciness t - like aroma , sweet malt up front with fruit-like notes and a very slight amount of hops on the finish m - medium body with high carbonation d - this is a decent , well-made beer .  muted roastiness and chocolate malt notes . deep black body with a decently firm and lasting thumb thick head . roasted coffee beans int he fore followed by toasted and burnt bread and some mild chocolate notes int he finish . finish is dry and coffee tinged great classic porter .

the smell was earthy and of tart fruits .  pours a beautiful golden color with thick , frothy guinness-like white head .  always looking for a great session beer and this one fits the bill for me . great bitter citrus aromas with just enough malt balance on the taste to keep the acidity in check . great piney hop character with a nice citrusy finish . my only complaint on this one is the price , for $ 11.99 a six i would prefer stone keep the etched bottles and give me a 4 % abv beer at a more reasonable price .

i smell sour wheat , lemon zest , cilantro , clean cotton , and sea salt . very fresh , but not as complex as i expected from such a revered brewer of belgian style brews . not very assertive or complex . t - ok here we go . a damn near flawless witbier , it just needs to smell a bit more assertive and it would be awesome .  pours a oil dark black with a big brown head .  mouthfeel - rather bubbly , fairly thin .

aroma is mild but some chocolate and roasted malt but surprisingly no raspberry really shows up here .  pours a three fingered cream head that slowly fades to a thin layer , leaving a good lace .  thanks to ncvbc for this great extra best by 12/31/08 bottle poured into my sniffer produced a good fingers worth of tan head that turns into a ring of lace around the glass on top of a jet black body aromas of toasted malts , coffee and chocolate with a slight funk ( i 'm glad i am not the only one to pick it up i though my nose was going ) earthiness , sweat malts , light chocolate , molasses good balance of flavors the only real complaint is it is a little thin for a stout good drinkability i could drink a few of these a night easy .

very little aroma . some roasted/molasses type scents .  this brew pours out a deep , hazy red amber color crested with a massive head that retains very well and leaves huge , sticky lacing .  mouthfeel- medium body with very little carbonation .

the appearance is dark and deep with small pillow of foam on top ( died off on the way over to my table ) . the taste begins very sweet - a blend of chocolates , malts and sweet nuts . the finish is a bit delayed and it arrives with soft notes of bitters and alcohol . i 'd drink this one again ... and again .  very nice 3 finger head that was creamy with a great deal of structure . deep orange/amber in color and quite translucent . great lacing and a touch of visible carbonation . this short description is not an indication that it was n't great .  light feel with lots of carbonation .

a little one-dimensional but still pleasant . very light malt , coriander ( again ) , and a faint orange flavor on the palate .  plenty of head that lingers all the way down the glass .  spicy and yeasty on the finish , this beer is medium-light on the palate with a high level of carbonation , much higher than i care for , really foaming up in my mouth .

not much in the nose -- just some faint grassy notes . the taste was outstanding for a pilsner , which is not my favorite style -- especially for an american pils . tremendously drinkable -- the ultimate lawnmower beer . interesting and well-crafted enough to please my beer geek friends , even the ones who crave a cellar-temperature russian imperial stout on an 85-degree day , but accessible enough to please those who usually shy away from anything more complex than bud or mgd .  appearance : as poured the beer is a nice lightly hazed golden apricot color with a 1 fluffy off white head that leaves rings , legs and small patches of lacing as it recedes .  the mouthfeel is medium but i think the beer would be better if it was properly carbonated .

the nose is slightly floral , but to be honest , i failed to detect much .  a gorgeous midnight pitch-black , with luscious creamy , light-tan head , almost a finger thick . impressive sticky lacing .  a chore to swallow . lingers on the palate like a bad cigarette . overall : not something i 'll ever subject myself to again . there are way better means of getting trashed than this , and though it 's cheap , it 's not at all worth the gagging and self loathing .

s : quite vegetal , has a hint of agave syrup , fairly hoppy , not what you 'd expect .  a : beautiful , clear , dark ruby body under a majestic two-finger head of creamy , sticky tan foam . tons of lace . truly spectacular . s : a little underpowered - light acetic sting , some sweet fruit , and a bit of husky malt .  it looks like a pale ale should , there 's some yeast on the bottom of the bottle and the head stays for a bit . i 'd rather have a bit more malt presence , it 's just too hoppy and bitter for me . drinkability , if i had to choose between this and a macro , i 'd take this . edit on 10-3-04 i 've raised my review score , since i 've either started loving the hop , my tastes have changed or the fact that this is one of the few decent beers you can get around here on a night out and i 've become more accoustomed to it .

s- not the strongest of aromas , hard to pick up . i get some pine/citrus hops and belgian yeast spice .  it poured cleanly into a glass with a large-bubbled head which stayed steady , and a very yeasty smell opened up in the room . the color , particularly , is astonishing ; a yellow-amber cloudiness that draws the eye , with the contrasting white head giving it some depth . the wildness of the yeasts gave this particular bottle a vinegary quality , though traces of an apricot flavor could be found underneath .  i can see why the word peat was used before in a review the mouthfeel was medium to light i will agree it needs some more body to it this is a good brew and with a little tweaking it could become world class .
aroma was surprisingly weak , notes of smoky roasted malt and hints of coffee .  a - huge head , really fluffy . beautiful amber color with appealing haziness .  come and drink this corn syrup !

s : the nose generally lacks aroma . some grainy bread notes emerge but the hops offer nary a scent . t : a sip makes up for the lackluster nose , lots of flavor jumps out from the get-go .  pours an intense orange/cherry with a full finger of fluffy off-white head .  mouthfeel - a little gritty , though a light body to it .

smell : it 's kind of a let-down smell wise actually . some slightly sour hops and some nutty malts . does n't really smell that great to be honest .  this bock pours perfectly with a tight forming bright white head that stays around for a good duration .  decent head , minimal lacing , crisp smell with just a hint of hops . the hops are more noticeable in the taste . really nice american lager . makes bud look like the crap it is . my only macro beer ( maybe amber bock , too )

s : here 's my one complaint : light citric hops , light caramel malt . good , but way too light . my nose was wet before i picked up anything .  a : attractive drink on the pour , looks like a lighter , creamier guinness pint from a good tap . huge head and flowing bubbles .  i think i 'm a bit parial to this beer for 2 reasons . it 's not by any means a `` specialty '' beer , it 's your typical lager and since it 's been around since before any of us were born it 's got a nostalgic feel . excellent beer in my books , average for most .

very malty smell . sugary , raisin and malty flavor that mix very smooth .  a : jet black with some garnet around the edges when held to ( candle ) light ; about the most enjoyable thing about guinness is watching the bubbles work their way up the glass , creating a nice and tight , light almond head , leaving nothing but an opaque blackness below ... s : hmmm , not much here ... maybe some roasted malts , but faint .  i think if the mouthfeel was better it would have made a world of difference imo .

i had mixed feelings about the noble pils before it even came out , as i had always enjoyed the white ale that sam adams had previously marketed as its spring seasonal . basically , i feel like the white ale should have remained the spring beer offering , whilst this beer should have become a full time staple of the sam adams line-up . great taste , and easy as hell to drink !  pours a two finger , cream head that slowly fades to a thin layer leaving a good lace . clear deep amber color .  mouthfeel : hoppy and rough , but a bit fuzzy .

very simply , appearance-wise , this beer is not markedly impressive - with its stillness and particular redness it could easily be mistaken for a glass of pinot or cabernet . accordingly , the nose ( what little manages to announce itself ) is wholly dominated by obvious wine-like grape notes and supple/elegant tannins ; there might be a spicy undertone ( nutmeg ? however , once we have moved beyond these categories , this beer is radiant . the feel is gently carbonated , extremely dense and somewhat ideal .  pours into a pint glass a translucent straw yellow with a billowing white head and and amazing lacing that last throughout the drink .  high carbonation detracts slightly .

s : citrius hops , not the strongest aroma . t : bitter finish .  looks very impressive ... just like i expect beer to .  mouthfeel : it feels like an astringent hop bitterness , but i sure as heck ca n't taste any hops .

the first thing i noticed was the head , which was average.it had an average amber color , but the taste was quite different than others i have tasted so far.i tasted chocolate.i understand this to be from the malt flavor being intensified.i have read that the kolsch style of beer should have a stronger hops taste , so maybe this is put in the wrong catagory.i liked this beer , probably due to my chocolate affinity.it has a pleasant disposition and is unoffending to the palatte.it has a sticky taste , like chocolate.i liked it.i would buy again , probably with a piece of chocolate .  towards the end of the night it settles down to a thin concentric ring but a nice swirl brings you back to viewing what i consider one of the most beautiful looking barleywines i 've ever seen .  m - medium/light body with little carbonation good with spicy food .

s : nose rather faint , tones that i picked up mostly chocolate . t & m : creamy textures throughout with some smokiness mixed in .  poured into my duvel tulip glass , poured a rich thick borwn that cant be seen through , a rich creamy five finger head rises to the top and stays awhile , the smell is rich grain and alchoal with a sweet fig overtone , the flavor is figs , hazelnuts , molasses , honney , sweet malt , a hint of folaral hops then malt for days .  the motuhfeel is moderately carbonated and slightly watery .

s - very grape . almost smells like lighter fluid .  a - translucent , super vibrant golden straw color that could illuminate a room . finger eggshell ( always wanted to work that color into a review ! ) head with a nice bubbly ring and a thin white film of bubbles remains on the surface .  the hops however tastes amazing but it needs more malt m - very light mouthfeel d - probably the most drinkable 7.2 % beer ive ever had

has a strong fruity citrus smell , i do n't really smell hops ... maybe slightly ... but not as much as other people say .  poured a hazy straw colored hue with a fluffy three finger head . the retention was beyond excellent as was the very stick lacing . by the time i got to the bottom of my hefe glass , there was still nearly a finger of fluffy head remaining .  medium bodied with medium carbonation . i only wish this average mouthfeel was supporting an average taste .

s : a roasted nose with hop undertones . not a big nose on this beer .  pours dark amber with a large honeycomb coloured head and lots of lacing .  for the mouthfeel , i found this stout almost watery in consistency .

think of a nice malt being toasted . keep toasting it until it is black and almost burnt or charcoal and make guinness . when you make this beer do everything exactly the same just change how much you toast the malt . to me i like the dark toast flavor and color of kilkenny the best . the taps for kilkenny say it is brewed by guinness .  dissipates slowly and exhibits great retention with beautiful lacing .  slight astringent twinge . d- very good `` sessionable '' strong ale .

smell was odd ... something seemed off ... unbelievable the difference between smell and taste ... the taste was great..sweet on the front , rounding into a tartness and a very nice overtone of alcohol . drinkability is very good for the high abv ... very easy to drink .  some of shakespeare 's stuff is pretty dark , but shakespeare stout a nihilistic black , with a big head the color of creamy coffee . the little black bubbles peppering the head make it look alluringly like a chocolate chip cookie .  it was also a little to carbonated for me in the mouth feel category .

light chocolate , clean aroma . one finger dark beige head . big chocolate flavor . reminds me of the hershey 's cocoa powder form .  maredsous 8 on tap in a tulip glass . black cherry color with a nice creamy head . excellent lacing , thick on the glass .  mouthfeel - very enjoyable borderline complex character .

aroma is malty and estery , nothing to write home about .  a big frothy white head that sticks around forever , and then leaves some pretty sticky lace on the glass . a very pretty beer , love head .  crisp taste - not heavy as expected ... hints of smokey , woody flavors - has the appeal of a coffee porter ... mouthfeel is average .

s : a bit fruity and pretty spicy , with some nice hops in the background . not strong smelling at all .  sediment floats about in a strange vapor-like form . just the head by itself is more complex than most beers , sits on top the whole time , slowly getting all awesome and chunky looking and leaving good lacing .  smooth , nice , a little thin maybe . not a ton of carbonation at the end which leaves it a little watery .

limited aroma with just a slight fruitiness and some citrus . assertive . crisp .  pours beautiful dark brown with red edges , almost black with a huge tan head that sticks around and leaves walls of creamy lace .  way too thin in the mouthfeel category , however .

the aroma was very strange and not at all appetising for me . the aroma was disappointing but that is one of the nicest beers i have ever tasted .  it has a gold cloudy body with a beautiful head and just the right amount of carbonation from an aesthetic point of view . it is a simply picture perfect beer .  taste is dominating by anis with some candi sugar . body was above average and alcohol was well hidden .

smell is of molasses , toasted oat , and french roast coffee . for some reason i detect some alcohol in the nose too , and for a 5.5 % abv i 'm not liking it a whole lot . after the initial appearance and smell , i fell in love with this beer .  beautiful nitro thick creamy tan head over a black body . has a lovely way of settling to a creamy solid chunk that wo n't spill out of the glass if you tilt it .  m : a touch thin .

first it poured a very clear medium amber , just beautiful and it 's clarity reminded me of many cask beers i have enjoyed in england . aroma was a bit of a surprise , i was expecting , or hoping maybe , for the citrusy hop character of bear republic racer 5 or el toro 's agressive interpretation . i found it very restrained and almost tea like .  this beer pours a semi-cloudy pale orange color . the head is an impressive two and a half inches in height , and recedes very slowly into thick , chunky lacing .  ) my only qualm was the the body seemed a little thin .

i was actually pleasantly surprised by this beer . i acquired it in the winter variety case and finally got to it . very nice red hue to the beer . very carbonated , of course , and more than a hint of cranberry .  hazy/cloudy straw yellow coloe . great lacing .  a medium to full body . possibly a little too thick ( syrupy was mentioned earlier by easyr which sums it up well ) as it took me a while to make headway down the glass ( unusual for me ) .

nothing exceptional here .  very bright , very glowing red body . cream-colored head is boisterous and rocky .  the feel is smooth , suprisingly light for a beer that seems so heavy . while i feel that this is one of north coast 's better efforts ... though none are really bad , i do wish that it had a bit more body .

s- mostly chocolate aroma with oats , not very strong aroma though t- lots of bitter chocolate , oats , roasted malts , and strong bittersweet vinegar aftertaste m- very creamy , lighter bodied for the style o- good flavor , very creamy , and highly drinkable .  the beer looks great ! s : i get some notes of honey , grass , caramel , and light seasonal summer fruit .  thin , oily body ... definitely needs some more heft .

s : chocolate , yeasts , and some sweetness . t : belgian yeasts up front with a nice mellow back drop of chocolate , this beer is balanced complex and awesome .  tall , nearly white head with good retention and great lacing .  smooth , medium body with a palate almost entirely made up of bitter , herbal hops ; perhaps trace notes of biscuity malt can be detected , but they are virtually non-existent . finish is long , dry , and bitter , and leaves you wanting more , which leads to a great level of drinkability , especially for a hophead .

the aromas are relatively straight forward with caramelized sugars and a raisin smell in the background .  11.2 oz bottle poured into duvel tulip a : perfect . billowing tan head barely contained in this glass . settles to leave full layer of fine tan lacing . as you sip the soft foam coats the side of the glass in sheets not patches .  the only real flaw for me with this beer is that it 's a bit thin , but that 's a bit nit-picky and did n't detract at all for me from this wonderful beer .

the aroma does n't seem so bad ; perhaps even pleasant - prairie grass , damp pollen , clean grains and hints of mild spice . there 's a lemon grass element as well , but i 'm concerned the lemon smells too ... pungent . yuck .  poured this puppy into a duvel tulip , which helped to bring about an ample 4 finger thick fluffy and off white head . the body is very murky and peach in color . head retention is great , as well as the lacing .  color and mouthfeel are average for the style and fine .

s- very sour and thick . smells nothing like it tastes . d- incredible summer beer . this beer is the best witbier i have had .  pours to a very dark brown , only slightly ruby colored liquid with a massive fluffy white head that coats the entire circumference of the glass in a perfect frilly victoria 's secret crotchless panty-style lacing . she really is quite sexy looking .  so we have another german pilsner . i 'm still amazed that there are so many of these . i 'm still unable to get passed the grassy flavor of these . i just which they 'd add something else to mute that flavor down a bit . then again that would change the style and it would n't be a pils anymore . anyhow this brew is clear yellow with an earthy natural aroma and taste . the style just is n't for me .

s-very faint . citrusy hops , malt notes , and some sweetness .  has my favorite froth for this style , thick and sticky , goes nowhere fast and the color looks bread .  now i understand the meaning of the word `` swill '' . i have an enormous amount of respect for european beers . avoid . trust me .

foam looks like insulation foam.. smells okay , not a whole lot going on , mostly dark malts .  like nocturnum , my favorite of the delirium family , this beer has nice white fluffy head . the beer pours orange/gold , and the head lasted through the entire glass .  m - average mouthfeel . carbonation on par , but a very thin feeling brew .
strong roasted malt smell , but with some odd background notes .  pours a jet black wth a huuge , really tight brown head that retains really well , beautiful !  a tad thin .

the aroma was the typical malty smell of a brown ale .  the beer poured into the glass a brilliant clear gold with a thick , dense white head , te head retained well , and when it did recede it left a chunky lace on the side of the glass . a stream of champagne bubbles rise from the bottom , a testament to the carbonation of the bottle conditioned beer .  decent palate , a little thin like the others in the series , but fairly smooth .

i live in north carolina and love to get my hands on beer from my area back home . the smell is just fairly subtile but hinted of almost friuty . overall a very decent beer .  pours a motor oil black with some brown edges and two fingers of mocha tan head . threads of lacing line the tulip . however , for some reason the beer is extremely green - perhaps it 's the victim of oxidization ?  mouthfeel i kind of like the mouthfeel to this one . the carbonation isnt bad , and it goes down smoother than most .

i really enjoyed this beer . it really did not have an aroma .  this one pours a hazy yellowish orange with a white head that just will not go away . looks great overall .  feel is also a bit thin and fizzy .

some dms , malt , toffee and something nutty on the nose . flavour - intriguing mix of caramel , toffee , chocolate , nut and something hard to pin down .  appearance is beautiful . pours an oaky golden light brown . leaving a dense one finger head on top of the beer .  m : lightly carbed , thin , slightly oily , tannic finish .

it had a faint grassy , hoppy smell . the initial taste was some bitterness with a touch of citrus .  a - pretty , near black pour with quite a sold 1+ inch head that stays around for awhile .  m - medium body , not a lot of carbonation .

s : very little other than a light , roasted aroma . t : more taste than the nose was led to believe .  a -- this one pours with as much head as you want , and probably more . i must have had a little too much force behind mine because there was a fluffy white head up 3/4 of the glass . golden yellow with carbonation bubbles racing quickly to the top . tons of lacing .  mouthfeel was a bit thick , and it was not quite as carbonated as i would have liked .

the aroma is a variety of differnet malts with a very slight spicy scent that i could n't identufy .  the way the carbonation and creamy foam mixes with the super dark body of the beer is gorgeous . through the glass , it looked like the bubbles were cascading like a waterfall , only upwards . anyway , the body is opaque and the head is super creamy and tan in apprearance . the head stuck around for a long time and left decent lacing .  hmmm . drank this because a chick bought a pitcher and the service was terrable . it 's like club soda with a twist of beer . not much color , not much flavor . not bite of hop . not really much to say about this stuff . it 's pretty popular with girls ...

s - smell is mostly malts with nothing much else detected . t - taste is sweet roasted malts with smoked sausage .  a : gentle pour creates a 3 finger powdery white head with incredible retention . a beautiful beer to behold .  m : the body is light but sugary and grainy with a moderate carbonation .

s - mostly pine , citrus smell coming from hops . not as strong most ipa 's go .  it has a great thick fluffy dark mocha colored head perched upon a jet black body . the head was still present a good 5 minutes after pouring .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and resinous , this is really the only fault i can find .

- smell is almost absent . very light sweet brown sugar , very light malt ... all which traps a huge piney hop bitterness ... that just ca n't really be smelled . - fantastic light sweet malts ... .  a - murky apple juice with and incredible pillow head ... slow to leave , chunky lace left .  mouthfeel : bubbly and light body . the mouthfeel is a little peculiar and affects my experience .

the head really has some large pillows in it and it just sits high the whole way down ... one of the more impressive looking pale ales ive experienced . the nose is very very subtle ; biscuity malt , pine and citrus , but very subdued , i had to stick my nose down in it for a minute to really draw everything out .  a : pours a hazy golden with a thick bubbly white head that slowly faded into a thick film that lasted the whole beer through and left an incredible fuzzy sheet of solid lacing down the glass . beautiful .  the only fault is that its a little thin bodied but that 's what makes this brew dangerous .

the aroma is a pretty subtle combination of lemony and herbal notes .  12 oz bottle poured into a snifter - best before oct. 19th 2007 appearance : harsh pouring reveals a generous 2 '' head that lasts quite a long time . the head is tan with tiny bubbles that leaves a bit of lace behind .  the mouthfeel is a bit astringent .

s : i smelled hops and some sweetness maybe from cinnamon , that 's about it . d : it is a great christmas ale .  a - only a sliver of red around the edge . tall very tight light brown head leaving considerable lacing .  a : pours a dark brown with a two finger head ; burnt orange around the edges of the glass when held to light ; lacing is excellent s : smells of caramel and coffee ; very earthy aroma t : tastes like a bitter coffee initially , but the sweetness of caramel and honey slowly creeps in m : i think its a bit too watery and the carbonation does not seem right d : two in a sitting is nice ; i 'm generally not a porter fan , but i enjoyed this beer

it 's a bit subdued though . overall , a very nice iipa .  what a shame ... pours a pretty golden-amber color topped by a huge , thick , creamy white head .  mouthfeel is on the thin side for a stout .
smell is weak , thankfully the taste is not .  honestly one of the most impressive looking ipa 's i 've encountered .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

very faint smell . medium body , medium carbonation . easy to drink for such a dark and strong ale .  pours with a deep red-brown body topped by a medium thick lasting head with good lace .  the mouthfeel was about what i expected going in , but i thought it might a little over-carbonated . the aggressiveness of the carbonation was a little distracting .

s : weaker aroma than i expected but i might have hyped the wet hops in my mind . floral hops and citrus `` dominate '' but the nose is still weak .  looks perfect . mounds of off white maybe pretty much light tan head , and has a clear dark copper colored body .  the body is medium with decent carbonation .

for such a strong tasting beer the aromas are difficult to pick up . mostly what i get for a smell is a malty sweetness .  i rarely describe a beer 's color as `` black '' , since most are actually a deep brown , but this poured like motor oil ! i got just over a finger of deep-tan head with decent retention off of my pour .  m- low carbonation and very low mouthfeel .

hobgoblin is a very easy going down brown ale that is a perfect session beer .  the chocolate yeti has perfect color in both the body of the beer and the frothy dark brown head .  the mouthfeel is a bit overcarbonated for the stle but not bad .

light malt and grainy presence upfront with nice floral hop notes and undertones of grassy hops . overall , quite flavorful and easy drinking , tasted fresh despite the freshness date being about 3 weeks past .  snow-white head was thick and pillowy , and lingered through the entire drink , and reduced to excellent lacing up and down the glass .  m. a bit acidic d. overall a nice iipa .

the nose is entirely too one dimensional though . it smells almost like straight up cold coffee , with just barely a appreciable hint of dark chocolate .  impressive looking beer .  pretty thin mouthfeel i guess , but overall its a great balance of flavor and drinkability , something i would definitely buy again .

nose is very faint , almost no odor , hints of roasted malt . taste - a lot of flavor , and complete opposite of the nose . dark semi-sweet candy-like , mild bitterness and dry maltiness , with the sweetness fading leaving the dry malty taste into the finish .  pours a slightly hazy , deep copper with a 3-finger thick , frothy light yellow head . lots of lacing .  carbonated but not overly so . on the lighter side of medium bodied , i 'd say .

s : i could detect coffee bean t : very good !  poured a dark mahogany with a big light brown head that left some lacing .  this is a man 's beer . none of this flowery wine swilling critique lingo . light color , smell and mouth feel , who really cares . outstanding dry & hoppy flavor without sweetness . when bought in the 30 pack , cost is about 50 cents each . the best macro being produced !

some thick lacing towards the top s : nose is probably the weakest part of this beer . not much too it ; some roasted oat and malt t : ah yes , the beer i remember . very flavorful and easy drinking .  two fingers of thick , creamy baige head with great retention and tons of lacing .  this feels thin for some reason . carbonation is good and proper .

smell was a little light but developed after taste was introduced . if agitated there is a burst of floral smell tasted good .  16.9oz bottle - 2006 vintage - served at 45 degrees into a large snifter appearance : charcoal black and completely opaque . vigorous pour yieds a 3 inch head that is thick and creamy . caramel colored head with great retention .  mouthfeel too prickly and astringent but medium body is appropriate for style .

now , i 'm an ale lover , so to be greeted by a lager was less than exciting . it goes down smoothly with a light aftertaste . i hope they are n't disappointed when i leave town .  great divide brewing rumble oak aged ipa : as you pour this beer in a glass you will notice a burnished copper color , a luxurious off-white head that laces and lasts to the end , and a subtle but complex aroma .  the only knock here is that it was a little thin . m = is it possible to be creamy and watery at the same time ?

the aromas are a bit bland , mainly dominated by wheat with a hint of citrus .  pours a dark black color with no light being able to penetrate in the glass , large tan head that fades slowly to leave some patchy lacing on the glass .  feel seems to be about medium in body , but slightly watery , with a lingering semi-bitter dark unsweetened chocolate/coffee bean aftertaste .

the aroma is coffeeish , bitter . this beer is a pretty masterful beer of the style , but it 's not quite exceptional ( for a stout ) . considering the fact there was as much flavor left as there was , this would probably be a beautiful beer if drawn from a cask with a handpump .  a freind brought this brew over ... a : perfect look for a belgian ale . deep dark ruby color like an iced tea .  mouthfeel is on the light end .

the smell is a little odd to me , very tinny , almost like it was in a can .  out of a bomber this beer was a true , opaque black color . the retention was very good ; it soon became a fluffy cap that also left very good , consistent lacing .  tart and dry feel , but not overly so . lower carbonation detracts a little , really the only flaw in my mind .

very raisiny and sweet smelling , yeasty , but not all that inspiring , really ... but the taste - where to begin ?  4 finger frothy white head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : this was my one issue with this beer . it loses carbonation quickly , and with not that much to start with , it is kind of a bummer . a little sticky as well but the taste makes up for a bit of this .

the smell was n't all it should be , but average . the taste above average , in fact , very good , but no top shelf kind of beer taste .  a very appealing looking brew .  mouthfeel : this is the one downside of this beer ; it 's just a bit thin .

smell is caramel malts and a subtle lager yeast , really hope it does n't taste like it smells .  poured a nice orange/golden color with a very large bubbly head which remained for a long time and left average lacing . an excellent looking beer .  i thought the mouthfeel was a touch watery but the whole packaged seem very much an alluring strong-lawnmower , early evening session beer .

the aroma is more dull , but the flavor has a nice mix of sweet wheat grains ( bready ) with creamy ringwood and spice .  a- clear dark reddish copper hue with a billowy tan head that last forever and leaves tons of sticky lacing on the glass . edit : holy shit , this beer is so hoppy it turns your tongue yellow !  tingly in the nose which is common with sour ales but this is n't sour at all t. sweet with dried fruit , malty m. has a biting quality , a bit to carbonated .

nice lacing developed . the aroma was of some barely noticeable malt .  makes a nice , thick head with staying power . deep , dark brown color with a lighter ( and nicely creamy ) brown head .  an e-mail from the brewery indicated that twins lager is not the same beer as hauenstein , just with a different label . schells tells me that the twins lager uses a different recipe and yeast than the hauenstein , but a side by side comparison leaves me wondering why they would go through the trouble . i have always liked `` cheap '' beers . the beer drinkers of olden days wanted it cold , crisp , and cheap . but for afternoon lazing back and swigging , there is certainly nothing wrong with a cold bottle of twins lager . twins lager might be `` twice as refreshing '' as the label purports , but , boy would it be a treat to drink an original recipe fitgers again !

* the smell is feint , but boy does that thick and milky head stick around ! * it 's lke a scottish ale but without the bite ; not harsh . * smooth and milky * major big swath of milky lace * taste is sweet actually ; some chocolate * the scotch ale taste is there , but very mild ; not as pungent as usual * has a alcohol presence , but it is subtle * it 's a balanced scotch ale , not brutal .  beautiful pour . bits of sediment floating around . nice creamy tan head that remained throughout with gorgeous lacing .  boosting the carbonation would help .

s - it has a firm soap scent but a hint of caramel can be picked up .  appearance - perfect ! black with brown 2 finger head tiny bubbles smell - very pleasant as one would expect..malty , chocolatey , caramel and a very slight smokeness taste - very balanced as usual from a uk brewer .  light-medium carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is sour apple cider without the expected hops from a bitter , one has to question if this bottle has gone bad but after reading other reviews apparently it has n't , even though it has n't been brewed since 2006 .

malt scent with a feint fruitiness to it .  this beer black and entirely opaque with a thick and persistant off-white head with flecks of tan in it - very nice looking beer .  m - sort of dry but hops represented well in this brew .

not much of an aroma , a slight nutty sweet smell . great sweet nutty , caramel , hint of toffee flavor .  color is an absolutely gorgeous golden amber that promises an excellent brew .  there is little ( hardly any ) carbonation here , and the mouthfeel really does n't pack a punch at all .

i have to disagree with the other reviews of this beer : working as a beertender here in florida , i have never once recommended this beer and had someone not like it . it is a great replication of an english mild or amber ale by wild goose , probably the best beer they make ( that we can get here in fl ) .  pours a three finger cream head that fades slowly to a thin layer leaving a good lace .  m/d - mouthfeel is nothing special , the steely hop bite takes a bit away .

s - roasted malts faint grassy hop and dark fruit smell . t - nice balance .  great head , expected cascading upon serving .  shockingly light carbonation feel . i think the mouthfeel is off from what it should be .

the smell was fruity , sweet and slightly hoppy .  a : red-brown , fluffy off-white head , awesome retention and lace !  mouthfeel : low carbonation , light-medium body , slick texture . a bit flat all in all .

light aroma of malt and some hops , nothing earth-shattering . hurry , get some at the brewery before it 's all gone !  brilliant gold with enthusiastic bubbles streaming up to meet the huge fluffy white head .  m : medium body but the finish is not as crisp nor as clean as it could be .

it is pretty boring .  pours thick and pitch black , no light can penetrate this . has a nice sized brown head that fades to medium ring that leaves an awesome lace .  mouthfeel was a little thin , that 's my only complaint .

the smell is very mild with a bit of toasted bready malt coming through . while the smell was a bit small the flavor is the opposite , very big . huge fruity malts up front with a bit of sweet apricots and a touch of raisins , toasted malt and bread qualities linger as a strong juniper and grapefruit bitterness take over and linger on the tongue .  two fingers of frothy light yellow head with great retention and lacing . truly exceptional .  seems a bit thin , with very soft carbonation .

nice crisp pils aroma . smells nice and bready but not very complex . tastes great . very crisp and refreshing .  pours a amber ale color with a super looking coffee colored head with tight tiny bubbles that also remits some great lacing .  thanks jpm30 . clearly sour taste that sweetens as you drink it . vineous and slightly rich , wood only detactable before the taste buds are overpowered.. great after salty fish . a slightly milder alternative to a cantillon , overpowering the mouth but not for the entire day .

the smell of th ebeer is of subtle hops , again , nothing to over-powering .  reviewed 1/12/2010 ( bottle ) : pours a dark reddish brown color body , big fluffy head , off-white , lasting .  m : light but slightly creamy body .

aroma : grassy and a bit metallic , also spritzy . taste : heavy toasted undertones slapped with a veneer of molten dark chocolate .  very dark ruby red colored body with tightly knit khaki colored head .  feel left me a bit disappointed , however , as it was thin -- too thin for this big of flavor .

the beer 's predominant smell is malts , with some citrus in the form of lemons and orange coming through , too , kind of like the first hint of spring .  pours a rich golden orange , excellent clarity , good carbonation , topped by a level one finger slab of snow white foam .  the mouthfeel was light but a bit chewy .

nothing to exceptional about the aroma . taste is very nice .  has a really nice fluffy one finger tan head that sticks around . lacing covers a huge portion of the glass .  this beer has a flavor i really like m- pretty thin and bubbly , almost reminds me of a bmc feel o- one of my favorite tasting pale ales .

s : aroma is reserved , with hints of dried fruit and spice . t : dried fruit , bananas , cloves , and ginger are well balanced .  pours a deep murky brown with a nice frothy light-tan head that lasts and leaves great lacing .  m : a bit thin , i was kind of expecting it to be a bit more viscous .
color and smell is nothing to get excited about .  a : pours opaque jet black with a formidable tan head -- nice retention .  nicely carbonated .

smell : boozey , toasty malts . uh oh.. `` dirty nickels '' .. but not that much.. lets hope we dont taste them .  pours with a short , brown head with melted caramel edges . really nice lacing .  mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . if we 're talking about banana bread here , then it should be thicker , like bread .

smell : a surprisingly faint aroma , which was somewhat of a turnoff since i love the big malty aroma of doppelbocks .  11.2oz bottle poured into a chalice pours a murky , deep brown with a thick , one-finger head that has awesome staying power and leaves rings of lacing down my glass .  m/t : light to medium body , watery and a good amount of carbonation . however with the light body , low bitterness and virtually zero aftertaste , i could session this beer .

s - light crisp malt aroma with bitter hop flavors coming through well .  one and a half fingers of super creamy off-white head . excellent retention and lots of lacing . awesome !  medium bodied fairly low carbonation .

smell : rather light on the nose despite the big head , just a hint of citrus and maybe a bit of fresh cut grass taste : very light malt that reminds me of cereal and almonds ( just a hint ) and a nice solid refreshing lemon zest hop finish . kick ass lawnmower beer . very good stuff , it 's superb drinkability and the genuinely good ( not superb ) flavor .  pours a lighty hazed burnt orange , huge cap of frothy and sticky white head , great retention and lacing .  tastes like , yeah , tart blueberries ( probably artificial blueberries ) . just sweet & weird & sweet ... really tough to finish one . much like a cheap , too-tart wine cooler .

this is one of the five winter beers offered at cambridge brewing , an irish dry stout . it 's drinkable like all the other dry stout , and quite tasty to boot .  well there is no way i can fault the look of this ale..its perfect for style darkest of black with a huge frothy light brown head..beeee-u-tiful .  i did notice after a while that it has been pulled from tap that it acquires a lack of a better word , a buttery taste that really dos n't go good with anything . i do like this beer and i 'm not bashing it . the buttery taste in my opinion did not take effect until thirty or so minutes after pour . i do keep some in my fridge . i have shiner before to make burgers with , which turned out great . good beer for beer lovers .

s : smells like oranges and has a slight malty scent , like sweet smelling syrup . the sent is very light though .  huge 3 to 4-finger tan/beige head , slowly recedes to thin but relatively constant layer . great webby lace .  slightly under carbonated for my taste but not really a flaw .

the smell is funky lemon and a hint of the pepper corns .  the two versions are enough alike that any impression of 15th anniversary will translate to 16th ; therefore , my review of 15th anniversary follows : [ `` great divide 15th anniversary wood aged double ipa poured a beautiful copper with red hints when held to light . there was a massive creamy head and huge amounts of lace clung to the glass .  m : relatively light though not particularly carbonated .

moderate yeasts and slightly sweet on the nose , with a mix of fresh and dried fruit . rather light for the style yet obviously restrained by a copious surface cap , holding the volatile smells at bay . this beer looks better than it smells . all is good again in the flavor of this beer .  it settles slowly in a dramatically lumpy fashion leaving a tremendous amount of chunky and webby lace .  drink this on tap at city beverage in durham . i like the color and mouthfeel , though a bit thin for a heavy beer aroma is slightly sweet and complex spices taste is toasted barley , spices , and slight caramel with little head . drinks easy for a heavy beer

smell is fairly muted , some lemon , some belgian yeast . wish the smell was more pronounced .  great sustain and massive lacing . as good as it gets .  i think that the long trip from greece to williamsburg , va did n't treat this beer too kindly . pours and looks like the standard heine-clone . taste was rather flat .

nose is mild malt with a hint of floral hops and maybe some citrus .  pours a very hazy orange-amber with a massive , pillowy , long-lasting head and great lacing .  not as sweet as oscura , but the mouthfeel reminded me of it . it is a little light in the feel for an imperial but ample carbonation maybe to much .

it smells of yeast .  on tap at strange brew in manchester , nh 2/2/11 a : light yellow , almost hay colored , hazy . 1 1/2 inch fluffy white head , leaves tons of lacing , almost completely covering the glass .  as a swallow i think the first thing i notice is that this is a tad light , but still serviceable in mouthfeel . a nicely balanced apa if not a little thin . im still pleasantly surprised !

i smell chocolate and coffee and malt and even some hops . very nice and somewhat unique representation of the style .  it pours a beautiful clear coppery-brown with just a little head .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with no carbonation .

nice beer . not a great saison , but a very good one . not the funkiest saison , but i kind of like that . almost a saison/belgian pale ale cross .  beautiful 3 finger head , caramel , frothy and persistent , reddish mahogany nice stream of bubbles , good lacing ; if this did n't look so inviting i would put it on a shelf and leave it there forever !  the mouthfeel is light with a decent amount of carbonation .

lots of yeast sediment . s- a little citrus but mostly smelling lots of big hops ! d - very smooth highly drinkable . reviewed 5-25-10 1st review !  insanely sticky , a spectacular pour .  m : the feel is creamy and medium bodied . rather light for a ris and that really detracts from the beer in my opinion . the mouthfeel is lighter than what i come to think of when i thik of a ris .

i am a big ipa fan and had never heard of this beer , but when i saw it on tap at a local restaurant decided to give it a try . nice traditional amber color , slight citrus nose , decent malt to hop balance , very drinkable , and went great with my pizza .  appearance : pours a beautiful hazy dark amber color with a finger of foamy off white head that leaves a little bit of lacing and good retention .  m_slightly below medium bodied and very effervescent .
