not much on the nose here , just an openness that has some light roasty tones and dryness to it . some small phenol and sweet notes sneak in as it warms . easy , clean feel , medium bodied , nice mild little sweetness and roasty tone . not much for the nose but it makes up for it with a nice , easy going pace with flavors and body .  appearance & gt ; yellow , lively . lovely .  s : candied pineapple , yeast , and hops well balanced t : a typical ipa taste with accents of pineapple ; yeasts and hops , well balanced m/d a bit thin , carbonation too small and too much , abv on the high side and quite noticeable good beer

s : the combination of hops and funk is a little weird . nothing about the smell is jumping out and telling me that i want to drink the beer , but it 's not off-putting , really . it 's quite sharp , and big kind of like a double ipa . it 'd be nice to slip in a saison dupont or hennepin between servings .  a - pours a gorgeous pure orange color with a nice white dense head . it recedes slowly and it is sticky and very attractive .  m : very smooth , but seems pretty thin in terms of the body of the beer .

he posted a note in the midwest forum that a hudson store rec 'd a case or two & i promptyly left home for the 25 minute drive that netted me my first kentucky breafast stout . and as is proper for an imperial stout , it 's a very dark version of black . the smell 's a little disappointing . coffee , it screams . as it warms it gets a little more subtle , but there 's still nothing else .  as for the head , it stood about an inch in height when it first came out . the consistency is foamy and the color khaki . amazing retention and cobweb-like rings of lacing .  mouthfeel is lightly carbonated , a little thick ( like a dark lager ... blech ) , and generally mediocre .

s : a little sour and yeasty , followed by fruit . pears , figs and banana . i can just see a abbey full of monks enjoying this out of chalices , and having a great time .  appearance : a massive white head sits atop a slightly hazy golden body . classic looks and perfect presentation for a tripel .  not sure what they used for malt , but very sugary at first . the hops comes in and stays with you . almost like an ipa with the first snoot full of hops . i suppose they have to keep winning people over cause of the whole inbev deal . king of beers , so i am not surprised .
aroma of malted grains , hops , very nutty and sort of citrusy .  pours near black with tan head .  m - slightly thin and sweet .

s : yeast hops and some sweetness from the malt . not really that great a nose on this . definitely it 's weak point . t : sweetness from the malt , citrus from the hops , the yeast adds a slight spiciness .  pours hazy light brown with some orange tints . great head and great lacing .  it 's viciously acidic , but tasty . i like acidic ... i 'll drink straight malt vinegar . this is fizzy alcoholic pomegranate juice with nothing to resemble beer to my palate . i would n't hold `` not tasting like beer '' against a legitimate ale beverage , which i 'm sure this is , except that i like beer , and i do n't like this .

s : smells like roast and acetone ... yup , that 's nail polish . ok , i 'm not very impressed with this beer so far . t : aaaahhh ! d : as long as you hold your nose , this has great drinkability .  a brilliant tan head rose quickly to three-fingers and lowered very slowly leaving brilliantly thick patchy lace on the glass .  very light mouthfeel .

s - roasted malt and faint molasses and hot chocolate notes . t - roasted malts , bakers chocolate , coffee and a faint sour note that i ca n't place , but it 's not unpleasant .  perfect appearance . really smooth 2 finger ashy cocobutter brown head . dark black balled body that looks beautiful in my snifter .  the mouthfeel is fairly overcarbonated and dry .

truly great drinkability , malty and full-bodied . in what concerns oktoberfest beer , i found this to be a very good one : smooth taste , good looks and very , very drinkable . definetely worth a try .  appearance - jet black in color with a very nice one finger light tan head that lingers while drinking . perfect for keeping in the flavor and smell of the beer smell - very light on the malt smell , but somewhat heavy on the bitter hops .  mouthfeel is medium with a thick body but too much carbonation for a barleywine .

decent german pils a- clear golden color with a nice fluffly head that leaves great lacing s- floral , medicinal , and metallic smells coming from this .  the color was near black to black with light tan head . the lacing was exceptional , straight rings from the top to the bottem .  m - heavy , with little carbonation .

either is the rye . i sought out rye as i chose it to pair with an herbed chicken . the smoke is light as well so i suppose i could call it a bock . the hops , as expected , were n't pronounced .  the head fades very slowly , leaving a massive lacing .  m- thinner than i would like and overly fizzy from too much carbonation .

the smell is really light but i get some sweet carmel and pine and citrus with no hint of the oak .  a-pours a pitch black color with a finger and a half tan head .  m- a little light and watery , but not awful . makes for easy drinking .

the aroma was a simple citrus hints and some malts .  pours out a beautiful amber color with a wonderful fluffy white head .  mouthfeel is surprisingly tingly and sharp from the tiny carbonation and i suspect a hop i ca n't discern in either the aroma or taste . mouthfeel is unfortunately a little weak and thin for style to my mind .

some sweetish caramel malt . not much else in the nose but what 's there is tasty . overall it is very good .  pours a very dark and opaque brown , almost black , very thick brown head forms , settles to a big thick ring around the glass , lots of sticky lacing , about as perfect as a stout can look .  average body and carbonation .

s : not much of a smell , some malt and some burnt notes . t : tastes like guinness extra stout up front but finishes with a sweeter chocolate taste .  the old version of this beer brewed at devils canyon was pretty mediocre , but this is actually very good . appearance is excellent . clear golden with a soapy-looking white head that lasts and leaves great rings of lacing .  mouth : such a light and watery mouthfeel that it becomes distracting pondering the feel when you should be appreciating the tastes . drink : the nearly too-light mouthfeel is redeemed by the drinkability of this brew .

s - not what i anticipated . lots and lots of booze along with some sweet malt characteristics . the hops i do smell are only a tad floral . t - as much as i wanted to throw this one away after smelling it , i took one drink and it was amazing . a huge beer , malty and bready and hoppy and piney and fruity at the same time .  pours pale gold with a massive crown of stiff white foam .  m - ok and average .

mild hoppy smell , and malt .  black with reddish tints if you look hard enough . looks really good . fluffy foam settles to a thick , dense mass .  this is n't the fault of the brewer so maby it had great head . the main problem with this beer was infection . i 'm sure it was an infection because when i sniffed it i thought for a second maybe i was at the movies about to dig into a 12 dollar medium popcorn . past the buttery flavor i could taste blueberry almost which i 'm sure was n't intended either . it 'd be interesting to taste one from a different batch .

s : not much of a smell t : sweet , very sweet with light vanilla . m : creamy medium body d : dispite the alcohol this is very enjoyable and drinkable .  pours a deep chestnut brown , with a layer of foamy white goodness on top . laces amazingly . the more beers i try from this brewery the more i realize they sure know how to make a beer look good .  palate : medium body and higher end carbonation .

aroma is pretty subdued .  a : pours a clear golden color with two fingers of creamy white head that fades slowly , leaving countless strips of lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel : this beer has adequate body , but i would like a bit more texture .

s : had no conception this was a strong ale . i found the smell to be mild with some fairly noticeable hop notes . t : hoppy but not overpowering . d : another reviewer noted a `` double pilsner '' and i think this is dead on . good thing i only had one .  a deep , but crystal clear cherry wood red/brown with some creamy tan head . just perfect !  m= a little thin . boring mouth on it .

s : bouquet is faint , but notes of smoke , bananas , and butter make it through nicely . t : smokey upfront with a hefty dose of walnuts .  appearance : darkest , thickest brown head i 've seen , even a notch above rogue 's shakespeare stout . pitch black even when directly on top of a 60w lamp . tall head , intense lacing .  the mouthfeel was lowly carbonated .

the aroma is hoppy more than anything else . i pick up earth tones with a roasty malt background .  head leaves a serious amount of lace on the glass . really a great looking pint of beer .  definitely a little too carbonated for my taste - the mouthfeel was a little too creamy , masking the flavor .

smell is minimal ( beer could have been too cold at first ) taste is nice and malty that grows as it gets a bit warmer .  poured into an ommegang chalice a reddish/purplish brown color with a solid half-inch of head.. perfect for the style .  had a typical pilsner mouthfeel .

the smell is faint spices , notably cinnamon .  not sure if i need a spoon for this one . pours thick as anything i have ever seen .  m- average medium bodied beer o- great take on a saison style beer .
smell is small , hints of fruit .  appearance - crystal clear gold body with a huge white head ( took three goblets to pour this ) . gorgeous .  mouf & gt ; sudsy .

s : faint toasted grains and earthy heath . t : toasted malts much more pronounced that aroma ; chocolate , lightly burnt toffee and bitter coffee . disappointed in the nose , but a good stout past that .  pours a dark brown with a healthy sandy light tan head that lingers at a fairly thick level and laces the glass heavily .  mouthfeel is a bit watery not much body to it , but on a hot day like today , i could take plenty of these guys down .

as my first experience with a lambic , i was not sure what to expect from the beer . of course , i knew the facts : brewed in belgium , fermentation occurs when openly exposed to wild bacterium . my first thoughts were as follows : sweet , tangy , yet lacking in the strength of a full-bodied flavor . luke-warm , i discovered the very lack of flavor i had been missing !  poured from the bottle into a sam adams sensory glass . a : a beautiful pillowy head sits atop a clear , deep brownish copper , with great carbonation . perfect and appetizing .  m : a light-medium feel to it and kind of syrupy .

aroma is tart and a bit earthy .  pours a deep brown with ruby highlights into a tulip . creamy off-white/light khaki head leaves excellent lacing and retention .  m : earthy with a little grapefruit at the begining and a little pine at the finish . light carbonation .

aroma is mainly of brown malts with a slight roastiness and nuts . nothing else to note here . kinda boring really , but right there with the style .  pours a hazy amber colour with one of the most impressive head i have ever seen . a frothy rocky mountain large off white head .  i almost gag every time i take a sip of this . tastes like day-old miller high life with some bread , chocolate , and coffee mixed in . it looks like cola , and at first it smells like oh , say , a bottle of old milwaukee . if only it tasted even half as good as old milwaukee . please , for your own sake , stay away .

light whiffs of fruit sweetness and sprinkles of hop . very bad stoned !  my beer poured a dark , murky , opaque mahogany color with a gigantic , creamy tan head that took forever to fade and leaves chunky lacing down the side . my foam looks like a root beer float it is so solid and creamy looking .  mouthfeel is smooth , but almost unpleasantly so .

it smells of mild biscuit grain , light piney hops , a bit woody , and some funky floral hops .  say what you will about guinness ; yes , i know they 're a bunch of gimmick happy corporate whores , but one thing is undeniable ... there is no other beer on the planet , that looks , smells , or tastes , like a guinness on tap . the cascading effect is awesome . for the first third of the glass it leaves a solid wall of lace all the way around without a break in it . held to the light it 's surprisingly clear and reveals a fiery red hue .  a : solid black , modest lacing even at the beginning , but once the beer was gone so was the lacing s : malty , chicory , lingers nicely t : dominated by coffee ; bitter stout ; the oak comes through nicely ; not very complex m : casked , so it does n't really buzz in the mouth overall , a really good beer , but not as complex as i was hoping ; still , very worthwhile

not much to say about the aroma . you have to work for it , but when you get the whiff , it 's nice . nutty taste .  this is a great looking beer for sure . a hazy mix of orange and yellow body with a huge white head . the head is at least three fingers in size and is airy and thin so as to not steal much of my beer , but still has great retention .  m. a little too sticky , it feels syrupy , but without a sweeter taste it fells a little off .

there is the light smell of caramel along with a whiff of alcohol ( which is a surprise considering the abv is not terribly high ) .  a : poured perfectly . nice pinkish , beige head with a good retention and very good lacing for this style .  mouthfeel is full and seems overcarbonated for the style , but overall has the typical heavy/slightly syrupy mouthfeel characteristic of wheat beers .

nose is slight with hints of fruit , apple in particular . mouthfeel is very carbonated with a light citric tingle .  pours a deep deep dark brown with a monumental rocky khaki head ... . beautiful .  mouthfeel is fine - it 's a very light lager .

what i liked most was that it was well balanced and not a hop bomb in my opinion . i love sierra nevada pale ale and i think fans of that will like this too if not more . very drinkable and probably could go through quite a bit on a warm sunny day .  bottle and served in my expedition snifter ( along side of the 5 & 8 ) : a - very dark with some ruby highlights and the best head of the three with a good creamy lace upon the glassware .  body is ok , nothing special but not bad . very boozy finish .

scents i can pick up are grain , oats , cream , irish dry stout-esque . there is also some sour and hop notes . i reckon this is probably the epitome of an oatmeal stout .  a- deep black with a giant tan head . retention is awsome and it laces down the entire glass .  m : light bodied and well carbonated .

750ml caged and corked popped the cork with little trouble . most , strong dark ales have a slightly more scarlet color . husky , corn-like , slighty witte-like nose belying the yeasty belgianness of the beer . despite the nose , i would definitely drink this again .  a nearly perfect pour . smells and tastes of the usual hefe spicy , peppery yeast , clove and banana , with a touch of citrus ( maybe lemon ) sourness .  m : the body is not as thick as i was expecting . it on the thin side as far as stouts go , but drinks very smoothly . i would have liked a thicker body , but that 's just being picky .

i really miss schlitz . schlitz has more of a hops flavor than any other american lager that i 've tried . but i think that schlitz is the best american adjunct lager out there today .  this brew poured a medium creamy long lasting dark brown head of small to large sized bubbles .  mouthfeel is a little thin , though .

s : hay , citrus zest with light fruits on the background . crackery malts come through more as it warms .  a- pours a deep black color with a huge , fluffy , brown head that leaves tons of lacing as it goes down .  the beer poured hard but the carbonation ended up being low and the mouthfeel medium .

served in a ufo hefe glass . t : very good . d : excellent .  pours thick and black with a big fluffy head with excellent retention . looks rich and dessert-like .  the bier finishes quickly but is not overly dry . the malt department is a little thin for me but damn well done !

overall the aromas seem slightly restrained .  poured a hazy golden yellow with a three finger white head that remained throughout the glass and even continued to grow if left to sit for long . insane ! maintained phenomenal lacing throughout the glass . first off , the appearance on this one was ridiculous for the style .  mouthfeel the beer is slick on the tongue with strong carbonation . the body is a little lacking , medium-light .

smell - pretty faint but hints of floral hops and sweet bready malt . a well produced pa but smell lets it down .  a- pours a deep oily black with a three finger tall foamy brown head that has incredible retention ( after 5 minutes there 's still a finger worth left ) .  feels quite creamy at first , almost in a draft-stout kind of way , which struck me as odd . would rather it be crisper and a bit more carbonated , though .

the smell is rather clean with grain upfront , other than traces of floral it is very clean to the nose . the taste is excellent , light bodied , refreshing and crisp .  poured from a growler into a pint glass . pours a deep , clear ruby-brown with wonderful garnet highlights when held to the light . a fat , frothy head of light tan foam shows marvelous retention , holding tight throughout and lasting to the finish , grabbing tightly to the walls of the glass , leaving behind thick , bubbly curtains of lace as the glass empties .  do not know if this was an aberation , but this caused a lower score in mouthfeel .

s- some roasted coffee malts , a little peat ?  poured black , with a brown head .  finishes with a sweet malt taste m- medium bodied with decent carbonation , not as full for an octoberfest as i 'd like but still good d- very drinkable and easy to use to introduce others to a seasonal beer

the aroma is very weak though .  bear republic big bear black stout is an impenetrably black ale with a huge , chunky , foamy , light-chestnut colored head that coats the glass .  the taste is metal , sweet malt and finishes a nasty bitter . this is not a beer to be revisited unless it is on tap . i need to quite trying these imported green bottled beer . i do n't think i 've had a good one yet . on tap is a different story since kegs should n't get light damage . of course then there 's temperature . . .

i found little to know aroma at all .  guinness is one of the worlds greatest beers , hands down . rich , tasty , creamy , heartwarming .  pretty weak mouthfeel , it 's a bit watery . i 'm enjoying the flavour and aroma quite a bit but the mouthfeel is a bit weak . but lacking in mouthfeel .

nice head , very dense , lacing right off the bat that coats the glass all the way down . a nice chestnut/mocha brown that lest light pass through . s- malt sweetness , perhaps a bit of smoke/spice , and that 's about it . still , par for the course , and inviting .  the appearance is the epitimy of excellence . huge mountainous head supported by sunshine golden body , medium carbonation , tons of rocky , chunky lacing left behind only to be washed away with the high alcohol gobbles .  mouthfeel was the only thing i was n't too keen on- felt a little spritzer-ish .

s - mild aroma ( i wish i let it warm up a bit , at 11 % i would n't be surprised if it opens up ) . soft woody hops . touch of melon . d - the hops are strong enough to slow you down , and while not harsh in your mouth , the alcohol lets you know it 's there .  a very nice hazy orange color with a huge off-white head that subsides slowly and leaves lots of nice lace .  the body is rather thin though .

s - mild chocolate aroma .  bottle : poured a dark porter with a super huge medium brown foamy head with super great retention and lacing - almost to the point where i am wondering if something is wrong .  m : medium-full bodied , zero carbonation , silky . d : lacks the warming feeling that is usually related to a winter warmer .

s - malt ; i always find that sa beers are lacking the aroma department t - malt , malt , malt : notes of caramel and toffee a discernible along with a slightly vinous , fruity quality .  great streaks of lacing that never disappear .  m : over carbonated - fizzy .

has a light hop aroma . moderate carbonation , with a silky mouth .  a : beautiful . three fingers worth of foamy mocha colored head . lots of lacing here .  mouthfeel was a bit heavy and undercarbonated , but that may have been more of the fault of the bar i was at , and not the beer its self .

the nose is n't prominent at all . all i can pick up is some muted honey cream and some pale malt sweetness with perhaps some clove . despite the short list of adjectives i used to describe the flavors , it 's actually very , very good for the style . this is a very good belgian strong pale and worth trying .  pours a beautiful burnt sunset orange with crystal clarity , finger of foamy head has good retention .  the head vanished quickly , but the carbonation level remained high . the aroma was overwhelming sour cherries ... mouthwatering sweet aroma that shows a huge proportion of cherries used in this brew . definitely on the sugary sweeter cherry beer side .

the aroma is pretty muffled by the head .  as the beer was going down in the glass , it left an incredible , thick creamy lacing all over the glass . appearance was pretty cloudy , light copper color .  mouthful mouthful is okay . has decent carbonation , but i 've had better as far as carbonation goes .

s - caramel and a slight coffee aroma . t - there 's a chocolate flavor accompanied by a caramel taste .  it pours a thick , viscous black with a large dark tan hea that slowly recedes .  mouthfeel : there is a lot of bitterness .

aroma is mellow . nothing super amazing going on here .  poured from a 750ml bottle bottled on november 10 , 2011 into a tulip . a : pitch black with a 1 finger foam head . exactly how a stout should look .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .

aroma- not much aroma , lightly floral . taste- floral , not bitter enough for my taste mouthfeel- smooth drinkability- high , odd aftertaste , not sure if i want more herbs or less in this beer .  big bulky beige head 1 1/2 inches . a thin head remains throughout no matter how long it sits ( very nice ) .  taste is more of the same ... some wild floral flavors , hints of citrus ... seems like the dominant flavors have switched from the citrus to the floral characteristics . i like it , for sure , but could use some balance . i 'm not a big fan of the bitter taste left in the mouth ... but it 's still plenty drinkable . a definitely above-average ale , but not the best .

smell : almost nothing to say here , the smell is very weak , it seems . from what i *can* detect , there is a gentle grassiness coupled with moderate sweetness . it 's unoffensive , and get more flavorful as the beer warms .  the head of foam was nothing short of exceptional . it had a 1 1/2 inch creamy head of tan colored foam that looked good enough to eat .  this is a seasonal brew , do n't know if it is offered everywhere or if it was given adequate time to chill before serving so i 'll reserve final judgment for later .

smell : malt and flowers , some pine . not getting the citrusy blast that i like from an ipa , but otherwise pleasant enough . overall : very good ipa for those who prefer balance over hop bombs .  pours black , black black , with a big , dark , thick cloud of a head .  m : still a bit watered down , but again , it 's better .

s-the nose is light , nutty roasted malts with hints of herbal ester in the back . t-the taste is more full , lots of nutty flavors up front , roasted bread rolls , notes of dough , lightly roasted malt , faint herbal hop in the back .  this thing pours up a crystal clear copper with big rocky white head that leaves behind some of the prettiest lace i have seen in a while . great head retention and beautiful rising bubbles in this incredibly clear beer just make this look positively stunning .  mouthfeel : typical red stickyness drinkability : i love this beer .

mild aroma of bready sweet medium malts : crystal , munich , etc . very nice . light carbonation , full mouthfeel , quite chewy . this is a robust , yet refreshing and drinkable beer .  a wonderfully thick head sits on top of an incredibly amber colored beer . my favorite look easily .  mouthfeel is thin for a stout imo , but not bad .

faint roasted malt aroma , perhaps a hint of sweetness .  poured black with a thick brown head . the retention was great . very creamy and capuccino like looking head .  mouthfeel was my only complaint .

the smell is pleasant , overall light and grassy , but not that potent .  appearance : dark black color , with big chocolate brown head , medium carb smell : chocolate , with malts , and some wood taste : bitter dark chocolate , coffee , alcohol , and roasted malt mouthfeel : dry , slightly bitter , rich full body drinkability : a drinkable imperial stout , the high abv is moderately masked .  m - lots of carbonation maybe bordering on too much .
smelled of carmallized apples and alcohol . nothing extraordinary .  pours black with a dark brown creamy head . very nice beer to look at .  thin to medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

smell : pretty faint compared to what i was expecting . some burnt malt , stout-like aroma . faint hops aroma , crisp ut a littel disapointing . improved as it cooled revealing more burnt malts . wonderfully complex stout .  poured into michelob celebrate glassware ; awesome head retention for several minutes . fantastic lacing .  no sediment at all when bought fresh . this really brought out flavors you could not taste beforehand . a wedge of orange or lemon is a nice touch also . best served a little warmer than most beers . goes really well with food . a beer you could drink all night especially during a good bar-b-que .

mouthfeel and smell are nothing that stands out for the style but not at all bad either . amber but not as dark as others of this style , quite nice to look at , a few bubbles run from top to bottom .  i also love the brownish patina imparted to the deep red colour as it sits in a chalice .  mouthfeel a bit thin .

pours golden with a very light floral aroma , pure white head .  this beer is so dark that it makes the glass appear as if it 's jet black . it 's beautiful . no head , no carbonation , just black .  it 's a black colored beer with ruby edges . fairly nice nose , with a variety of dark fruits , as well as a bit of chocolate and coffee . really nice nose . flavor is fully packed , loaded with dark fruits ( blackberry , plum , cherry and currant ) , as well as some notes of dark chocolate , coffee and a light hint of alcohol . i like it .

smell is nearly non-existent with some dark maltiness . easily the best dunkel i 've ever had .  huge sticky head alone has a personality all its own . gorgeous golden haze pour that has no room for improvement , while in a class all its own .  a - it was still cascading when the glass arrived to the table ... settled into a deep , deep brown body with a brown head ... the head was creamy yet bubbly and it retained as one finger tall ... sheets of lacing were left s - there was a lot of chocolate in the nose with some subtler coffee notes ... dark fruits were present as well as a noticeable hop presence t - again , the chocolate presence was throughout the entire beer ... it tasted like bittersweet chocolate ... the dark fruits came out in the middle ... i would say dates were most prevalent because there was a nice , sweet caramel note throughout ... the coffee flavor showed up briefly at the end as well as the hops ... it did n't leave a bitterness on the palate though m - light bodied ... this was indifferent for me ... you would think the nitro would have added some body , but it actually came across as watered down o - the description said this was an homage to yard 's brawler ... i believe i had three of these one night ... the chocolate flavor is nice and it 's all around ... there are other players that join in the flavors ... you ca n't beat 2.6 % abv , talk about session ! ... my only complaint is the watered down mouthfeel

s : dark roasted malts and coffee . kind of disappointing for the style and look .  a : solid black body topped with three full fingers of rich , dense , medium-brown head that just barely poke above the rim of the glass ; incredibly persistent retention and a practically solid sheet of lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit too watery and perhaps a bit chalky .

s - nice smelling , friendly , but not a whole lot there , pretty weak .  it packs in beautiful cascading , lively carbonation , a firm & rich off-white head and amazing levels of retention . that and a bold black color make for one masterful visage .  this beer poured nicely with a creamy white head , giving off nice citrus aromas . the flavor was shocking , however , reminding me of kool-aid orange flavor , and with almost as much sweetness . i could n't distinguish any hop bitterness , though it could have used some to balance out the excessive sweetness . this beer tastes as though all the yeast were filtered out , and then orange kool-aid added post-fermentation

the smell was not very distinctive , clear smell of hops with a hint of sweet vanilla and a very mild fruity smell to it .  i havent seen a head that tall in awhile.pcb 's cabot street wheat poured a thick frothy solid white head that lingered and left a lace around my whole glass.it smelled of bananas with a citrus twist.the color was a cloudy light yellow.it yielded a banana wheaty taste with a touch of sour lemon at the finish.it leaves a dry feeling in the mouth with virtually no aftertaste.a very good light beer for a hot summer day !  it was my first fruity beer . it kinda tasted like an apricot . i was expecting most of a fruit taste like wine , but no . and i liked the picture on the bottle . and since it came ithaca i just had to try it . over all the beer was worth it . it 's good . : )

aroma was weak with only a bit of honey and mostly chocolate and wood .  pours an opaque orange gold with a massive , fluffy four finger head . gorgeous , a pour and a swirl can barely keep it in the glass . lots of visible , whitish sediment swirls around under the head . tiny champagne bubbles collect on the outside under the rim , sliding shimmering down the glass into a frothy lace after a tilt .  the mouthfeel is medium , slightly watery .

smells slightly sweet , grassy and floral notes , some fruit maybe ... pleasant enough , but nothing spectacular . nice . this is probably not what a hardcore hophead expects in an ipa .  pours a cloudy yellow with amazing white head that stays through out the whole glass .  mouthfeel is a little too tingly for me with the carbonation .

smells deep , malty , nots of caramel , bread and munich . slight metalic note as well .  a : pours a clear golden with a massive frothy , rocky head with great sustain .  this was my first encounter with pumpkin ale . i must confess that i could not finish the bottle . i had the distinct impression that the beer was trying to taste like something and not quite getting there . fearing the latter , i tossed the bottle after about five sips .

nose is very tame and toasty .  this beer poured a black body with a thick dark tan/black head . a beautiful sight to see .  aroma of fresh fruit and a bit of must , faint barnyard . taste starts with blackcurrant , very dry , moderately sour . hints of vanilla . finishes with more fruit and some mustiness . complex . would love to see it age .

12oz bottle poured into a stemmed tulip . appearance- to be honest it pours out looking like old coffee . ( i thought maybe something was wrong with the seal on the first bottle , because it looked so flat , but the second bottle didnt fair much better ) smell- typical of a stout . very roasty with a nice hoppiness as well . taste- now , i like a roastiness with my stouts , but this tastes a little like burnt chocolate .  poured from a bottle into a pint - exceptionally clear , copper colored with a one finger head that was almost latte colored , enough carbonation to keep plenty of lacing and a little bit of a head until the end .  nice golden color with plenty of carbonation . the head of foam was really thick and creamy , but it dropped down to a this lace in about 15 mins . at first i was n't crazy about the taste , but about 3-4 sips into the beer i changed my tune . it is not like any beer that i typically drink , so i did n't what to expect.interesting brew , i would buy this again .

very subtle , nothing spectacular . t - light initial wheat flavor that follows with a sweet/citrus aftertaste .  the reserve special black bier was a beautiful sight resting in a dark horse souvenir pint glass . it was black as night with a dark tan head indicating the level of roast of the malts used .  m-medium carbonation with a fairly dry finish o-listed as a pale lager ?

smells of caramel and ... pepper ? very faint .  a - giant white lumpy 3 finger head with fantastic retention ! ever-so-slightly hazy straw yellow that 's profusely effervescent .  mouthfeel : a bit thinner than expected , but not bad .

a - pours a nice deep inky dark color befitting a proper russian imp stout . s - dry biting hops come through with a dark roasted malt earthiness and just a touch of currant or other earthy dried fruit . not too complex or strong of a smell , though . d - incredibly well-balanced beer whose hops and malt come together in unison .  very dark , nearly black , dark ruby edges , huge three finger head that falls slowly , becomes rocky , excellent lacing , and a cap that sticks around throughout .  in the mouth , it 's rather average , with light carbonation .

s : light hints of baker 's chocolate , with malts coming in next . not very much more to offer here , overall it 's not very strong . t : rich , malty sweetness , with cocoa powdery chocolate flavoring coming in next .  appearance- deeper colored golden pour with a full inch plus rocky head with a good 1/4 inch of staying power . great looking beer .  m - a little harsh , not as smooth as other ipas .

smell : i personally do n't smell much with this ... a little bit of chocolate and hazelnut .  great looking pour for a white ale .  creamy flavor does not carry over into the mouthfeel ; light bodied beer without much carbonation .

when inhaling deeply i manage to smell a lavender soap aroma with some malt and spicy hop .  into a pint glass , it poured a transparent straw/gold ; heavily carbonated , two fingers of bright white , and great head retention and lacing .  nothing to write home about when it comes to mouthfeel . kind of a club-soda feel to the beer , tingly . though there seems to be a strange `` romanian roulette '' effect where every sixth beer is kinda soapy .

leaves some real nice lacing on the way down . i smell the hops , but nothing too disctinct .  on tap at ebenezer 's 2/13/11 a : pitch black and completely opaque . massive 2 finger mocha colored foamy and rocky head that was there to the finish . i ca n't recall many big stouts with such an impressive looking head .  dare i say it seems a bit on the thin side . the meatiness in the flavor is not backed up by the body . not bad , but just a little disappointing ... this is a fine stout .

it smells fruity sweet and alcoholic . t : the taste is initially fairly sweet , with hints of dark fruit .  poured dark brown with a light tan head .  i can feel it in my cheeks . it does n't have any off aromas specifically , but it definitely has the acidity for it . undrinkable , i 'm pouring it out .

n : lemon peel , citrus and some kiwi ( ? ) with some sweet malt smells . hops come and go in the aroma , knocked out a bit from the orange and coriander .  this beer pours an inky black with a dark brown head .  refreshing when ice cold , pleasantly balanced when it warms a bit .

my poured stubby elicited little smell , but the initial flavour was a rounded coffee chocolate.the flavour fell away though , to a minimalist charcoal toast it felt smooth and soft , perhaps too soft in the mouth . this is a strongish brew at 6.8 % and the coffee chocolate predominance makes it an enjoyable stout but one for moderation  bomber picked up from the brewery , opened after some months aging into goblet : a : quite nice hazy light-golden orange color with a substantial , creamy , lasting head .  the carbonation is surprisingly strong for the style .

smell : overall very mild caramel , brown sugar , and pine cones .  ) tasted 10/02 : bronze/bright amber color with good tan lasting head .  the mouthfeel is sort of watery , but it 's alright . this drinks very well .

aromas is of carmel malts.nice , but a bit weak.body is medium with a bit too much fizz for me .  a - pours a very dark brown - almost black - with a two-finger , well-carbonated , beige head that slowly dissipates to a 1 cm head . very attractive drink , as well as bottle which is slightly shorter and wider than most 12 oz bottles .  this beer has a fairly heavy body , a bit too much for my tastes .

aroma is faint or nil . sharply carbonated and very little up front hoppiness . a welcome refreshment from over-oaked beers that have been popular with us craft breweries the past couple years . i would have guessed oak aged english brown as much as german dunkel , though .  on tap at the pub ... the body is bright dark orange , but totally clear , very cool . an off white head leaves a thin cap , with great lacing , stellar ... the aroma is really successful in that the citra hops come across as orangey and sweet but they are literally cut but the balance of the other hops which reigns it in with some nice bitter pine .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied to me . could be a little thicker on the tongue .

solid macrobrew beer . sometimes you just need to kick back and enjoy something fresh , and heineken delivers . if you are cutting calories go light , they taste the same .  bottle into an english pint glass appearance - dark brown/red hue reminds me of high grade saddle leather . a very handsome brew , sir .  it has a pretty high carbonation .

light-medium carbonation . medium bodied . starts and finishes sweet this could be mistaken for a belgian . the high abv ( 9 % ) is not really noticeable . pricey - $ 4.50 for a 330ml bottle from wine society tyngsboro , ma .  opague black extremely heavy coffee colored heading . that leaves excellent lacing and keeps a nice collar all the way down to the last gulp .  the palate is somewhat thin for the style but it 's still smooth .

a- beautiful rich amber with a dense creamy head . s- a little faint , but my allergies are clogging my nose a bit so , it 's probably better than i can tell . some floral , some hoppy spiciness . first i get the fresh pine and resin notes , very bright and spicy , with floral overtones throughout . i do n't like bitterness and its the only fault i have with this beer , but since it is a tribute to hops its really not a fault at all .  a - dark caramel brown in color with some golden hues around the edges of the glass . hue , foamy off-white head with excellent retention .  m - thin with medium low carbonation d - not a bad amber .

somewhat light and delicate but still flavorful . very , very drinkable . hearsay is that the house yeast strain was not used in this beer which , in my opinion , is a good thing .  absolutely beautiful orange red body with a thin white head .  m - thought it was a little flat , but not bad .

nothing outstanding .  pours a pretty deep black with dark tan head that clings to the glass . looking quite appealing .  m : carbonation is a little weak ( especially since i poured moderately , and received an aggressive head ) leaving a mouthfeel thatis not strong enough for me to consider it cask-like . a little watery ... d : all things considered , i really enjoyed this beer .

smell is mostly of malt and a bit of hops not much there .  drank on-tap at hot tomato 's , new haven , ct poured a hazy amber with a two-finger , bubbly , white head that left huge ridges of lacing all the way down the glass .  carbonation is a bit low for the style .

roasted barley and nuttiness are present , but not overwhelming . the nuttiness is reminiscent of some yeast esters found in other styles of beer , though i ca n't say that is the source . very little hop aroma . taste .  what a gorgeous beer ! incredibly dark brown head , near pitch black color , and smells just right .  i also find it a little thin .

appearance - was excellent , as dark and opaque as any stout , very little head with no visible carbonation . smell - some mild sweetness from the malt with a hint of that coffee taste associated with dark beers .  this is the first tripel i 've ever seen that does n't pour like a homebrew . it is pleasantly clear with a rock-solid white head . then , after perfectly maintaining its integrity for five minutes , i look away for two second and it completely collapses for form a nice ring-around-the-beer with some craggy lacing left behind .  ill start this by saying i am not a lager drinker by any means . the smell is very summery with hints of citrus and the taste is very malty . the taste is very rounded and balanced . nothing is too harsh or overpowering it all just sort of settles around itself . would drink again !

dunkels ; pours a clear , deep copper-brown w/ a thin light tan head which dissipates quickly leaving a moderate lacing in my pils glass ; a subtle smell , cereal grain , toasted nuts , and hints of dark fruits and noble hops ; a crisp , malty flavor , nutty w/ a caramel-like undertone , faint fig/date-like notes as well , an excellent finish ; very dry and light bodied with plenty of co2 , this beer feels like it evaporates off your tongue ; a very drinkable beer , i 'm def .  look : dark brown with a good solid 1 inch head with great retention and some spotty lacing smell : smoked pork comes to mind .  mouthfeel is decent , this beer seems to foam up in your mouth .

this is one of my favorites , this is the alt which is available year around at the brewery on tap . the bottle pales in comparison to the tap version . love to spend a rainy afternoon enjoying an alt and the good company at the brewery . when at the berwery , i hope you get to meet nick , one of the last great bartenders - great way to spent a portland afternoon .  a- a perfect golden look in the glass . looks great .  m- medium body that was slightly under-carbonated . with more carbonation , all the flavors would bite that much more .

the aroma is light and a little metallic . a nice english style ale , in that it has the tea like dominance along with a leathery and slightly fruity finish .  a- black beer into ayinger glass , huge head with infinite retention , probably 4 fingers on average . nice light mocha color and a ton of lace everywhere .  m-explosive carbonation . tough to gauge the feel over the bubbles . a bit too carbonated for me .

lacey nice head : enough for taste , but not too much . a light mouth , followed by a rich , wide bitter taste , that lingers on the tongue . ) this makes it easy to quaff , yet still satisfying to linger over . paired exceptionally well with cold sesame noodles .  bottle : poured a deep opaque brown color ale with a huge dirty white color foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  very good light lager . hints of barley and hops , with a smooth slightly dry aftertaste . this brew had a short lived white foamy head and lower than normal carbonation . i would highly recommend this to any light beer drinker .

s- i get some modest hops here . while the smell is lighter , i get the full range , oily-hops oders , a lot of earthiness and pine-notes , even a little citrus . a nice surprise i did not remember is how balanced this guy is .  a-black as hell , 2 1/2 '' incredible light brown cappucino froth head . this beer looks fantastic . s-roasted malt aroma is so subtle it 's barely there .  i 'd love to try this on cask , if only to taste it more directly without all the carbonation dancing across my tongue .

smell is faint , dusty coco , hops and caramel .  in a snifter at falling rock in denver on 9/12/11 a - exceptional head , white and everlasting . decent lace .  in the glass , the elderberry dominates . the taste just off , sour in a nasty way , more like rotten fruit than any sort of pleasant tartness which might be expected from the berries . we gave this a decent try to see if it would get better , but in the end just could n't drink it .

mild roasted malt aroma .  the foam was wheat in color , bubbly , thick , smooth and left a ring around the glass til the end . the color was a dark burgandy/all most black with an orange red highlight in the light .  body is light and a bit watery , not too syruppy at all .

fairly non-assuming .  black to extremely dark brown in color of the body . huge rocky head that is coffee color .  m : crisp feel at first , mellows gradually before eventually becoming a little sticky/gummy . light-medium body .

smells neutral at first , then smells a bit sour . starts a bit sweet then gets tart .  frothy tan head .  t : bitter chocolates and cold black coffee .mmmmm m : a bit thin in the mouthfeel , slight warming in the finish which i found dry .

surprisingly underwhelming . wow !  pours a moderately clear reddish hue . massive cap of tan foam does not seem to want to go anywhere , stubbornly leaving sheets of lace on the glass .  the body is pretty light though and clean .

the smell is quite pleasant , kind of like a forest with a lot of wet leaves on the ground .  plenty of bubbles could be observed rising through the body , in short , it looked great ! the head produced somegood laceing as the beer was consumed .  its sucks to know that in a different format this could be so much more . body and carb is okay , but by this point i 'm already at the meh stage .

s- only could smell sweet and smoke . the only off area was the smell which is usually the area that lacks in most of my reviews . overall this was a great beer .  a light orange marmalade cropped with a white , creamy top , it looks damn delicious !  i was not a big fan of the mouthfeel of this one . i 'm all for thick imperial stouts , but somehow this one was much more syrupy than i liked , it felt a little to sticky sweet in my mouth .

smell is suprisingly light . some malts and a citris hop profile , but not in big quantities .  served up a breathtaking deep copper amber that is crystal clear . the head is slightly off-white and looks superb with tightly packed , shiny bubbles that stick around forever and leave near perfect lace . if this beer tastes nearly as good as it looks i will be most happy .  the taste is also very floral and hoppy , but its a smooth onset of flavors , doesnt smack you like other ipas , which ca be good or bad . the flavor doesnt last as long as other beers in this catagory . overall a pretty good beer , i think most peple will enjoy this one .

as for the odor , maybe my sense of smell was n't at its best , but i did n't detect much of a scent . the taste was very smooth , not nearly as bitter as one would expect from an esb , with a hint of caramel .  2009 vintage a- deep violet , crimson red just a beautiful awe-inspiring color and massive towering head that seems to be independent of the beer and an entity all onto itself .  smell was sweet , with a citrus hint and strong english ale smell . initial taste was interesting , and i was n't sure about whether i would like it . by the end of the bottle , it had become one of the best beers i 've tasted . i would n't recommend it for any parties , but in small groups of like minded people i would say good call . very drinkable beer . looking forward to trying more from the brewery ( if i can find it )

not much smell , quite light on the hops , but still has a nice floral character .  pours a nice amber with 2 fingers of head . gorgeous lacing also like nothing i 've ever seen . a solid 5 for appearance .  the taste is also fresh but a with bit of watery mouthfeel .

the aroma is average . it has a weird black malt scent that is a bit tart smelling .  slightly billowy , about 1/2 '' and slowly drops . looks sticky . very natural . not bright orange . i think this is as good looking as an ipa gets .  m : average , nothing of note .

the smell was not too intense but definitely of apricots . my first apricot beer , and i was n't disappointed .  big firm plush head , one of the most impressive i have ever seen . opaque black hue as expected .  the only complaint i have is that the texture left much to be offered . overall i great beer .
mostly amber ale aroma with hint of spice .  great , great look .  the only detraction i can fin is the below average body .

) aroma is mostly malt but not very impressive overall .  the classic appearance is the widget induced/nitro-draft style , which produces a paler , more uniform head with typical nitro bubbles ( tighter ) . it was almost foamy and left a nice lacing on the glass from the four pulls i took . this is what a stout beer should look like , imho . perfect . the dark , almost black , appearance of the guinness is beautiful .  mouthfeel was ok .

smell - decent malty pale ale aroma .  appearance 5/5 clear dark brown with a good dark tan colored head that stayed around , and left good lacing as well .  mouthfeel is on the thin side , but not bad . crisp , clean , pleasant in the end -- not overwhelming , a little tart .

the aroma was very subtle with a floral haze .  '' the appearance was awesome . huge head all the way down the glass .  under carbonated and somewhat thin bodied , there is a coffee flavored finish that is truly amazing .

probably our favorite beer from calgary beer fest 2009 so i may be a little biased . honestly 1 good looking ipa ... hazy copper color , excellent head with good retnetion and huge webs of lacing to boot . ahhh ... the let down ... as in aipa i have come to ecpect a bit more in the nasal dept . this offering certainly score on a nice balance between hop and sweet malt ... but does n't knock my socks off ... if it were an eipa i 'd score it higher . carbonation level is almost perfect ... allows all the flavours to come trhu without any fizzy bite . very drinkable and is now my goto ipa  this beer poured pitch black with a thick light brown head out of a 12 oz . this is how a stout beer is supposed to look !  flavor is more of the same with enough body to keep the brew honest . good mix of sweet and bitter and a weaker mouthfeel that allows for more on a warm summer day .

orangish in color with white head that sticks around s-not much on the nose as i would expect . more malt than anything t-lots of different hops . more piney than anything .  oysters ... hmmm ... pours a blackish black with a black interior and black edging . nice looking bubbling dark brown foam . really attractive .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and is a bit watery .

not a lot of aroma up front . a few quick whiffs provides a subtle hint of ginger root .  i had it at the bruery out of a bottle , poured into their tulip glass . the head held strong , and had an attractive texture , the color , an attractive bright beer-colored beer .  the only thing i was not pleased with with this beer was the mouthfeel .

the aroma suggests yeasty caramel cream and maybe some grassy hop but overall a pretty neutral effect , with some rubbing alcohol , nothing too alluring but it 's okay . the tongue detects lots of stuff ( unlike the weak aroma ) including earthy pine and dr. pepper medicinal sweetness .  a careful pour into a tulip glass evokes a billowing , explosive cloud of soft white foam , decorated by a tiny glowing golden body alive with bubbles . the head is continually fed by a steady stream of bubbles , and holds at over two fingers throughout the drink , lacing the glass in a fashion not unlike shaving cream .  it was watery with no carbonation , and had a bitter aftertaste . but it had good flavor and decent body , and was fairly clean and easy to drink .

i do agree the the smell is light but i get hops and very faint citrus .  poured 45 degrees fahrenheit into a tulip glass . comes a deep amber-red with a thick off white head above a vortex of champagne bubbles . gorgeous .  the carbonation is heavy and it adds harshness to the palate . medium-full body .

smells piney and malted .  the pour is ebony in color , the head inconsequential in size , the structure patchy clumps of large bubbles , the color a light chocolate .  drinkability - taste is pretty good , stays consistent throughout , isnt too thin , and has a reasonable abv so overall this would be a good beer to have a few of if you options are limited .

scent is hard to get a hold of i ca n't seem to get what i am looking for in this style . i do get nice hops , citrus and sweet malt but it is not as pronounced as i would expect . drinkability is exceptional for this 9 % beer .  black color with a solid brown head . head does n't retain for very long , but wonderful lacing follows this brew from start to finish .  m - takes a major ding here for not having much carbonation . it has a medium body , but the lack of bubbles make this seem borderline watery .
s-the nose is light , pale malt up front , notes of citrus with grassy hops behind .  tons of effervencense comes up through a beautiful hazy straw color .  very carbonated feel on the tongue .

s : some bourbon and booziness , but for me the nose was pretty underwhelming .  pours to a beautiful deep dark brown body with a hint of ruby red when held to light . hosts a decent 1 and a half inch rich tan head , leaving some lace as it fades .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh with the 8.0 % alcohol , but i have found very few tripels that can hide the alcohol content .

not much aroma at all to speak of , which is fairly common among the tripel 's , largely due to the clear candy 's which do n't impart much of a smell . great flavor , a creamy , full body full of a chewy malt and some fruit notes , yet clean with the clear candy .  opaque amber-brown pour with a dense , 3-finger white head and tons of lacing .  taste : mirrors the smell , but the flavors are weaker than their aroma counterparts because of a thin mouthfeel .

interestingly , taste is unlike the smell ... and that 's a good thing . aroma is typical lager , run-of-the-mill beer .  a : the finest bubbles i have ever seen in a beer cascade through the auburn colored beer to leave a creamy off-white head with great lacing and retention .  ) i would like a little more bready/chewiness as the mouthful feels a tad more thin than what i 'd prefer for this style .

omg , the hops . maybe that was the garlic potatoes . but i want to get back to my beer .  pours a dark , opaque mahogany tone with a solid finger and a half of a beige-colored head . decent retention , good lacing , and a lasting cap .  mouthfeel lots of fizzy carbonation , lighter bodied , finishes dry . the high carbonation combined with a thinner than usual mouthfeel really did throw off the beer making the flavors less prominent than i feel they could have been had the aforementioned two things been toned down a bit .

is 23 % and you can smell it , almost like a whisky nose . not much on the nose exept alcohol and a little molasses .  appearance - i really like this one , a rich caramel color and moderate foaming taste - hmmm .  as readily available as bud , and a whole lot better . a great fall-back session brew , which is good with a meal , or having several at a baseball game .

12 oz . the nose is rather subdued , without much going on other than some faint piney/herbaceous hop notes and a little whiff of biscuit . wonderfully drinkable and overall an excellent apa .  a=a nice , beautiful dark amber-brown , with decent-sized creamy head , that leaves noticeable but faint lacing . nice , very nice .  palate : medium body , thinner than expected actually , but goes down smooth .

this is a pretty solid maibock from my local brewers . the smell is somewhat lacking , however . a feint little bit of sweet with some caramel malty notes , but only when huffing the glass like a shoe polish addict .  this beer reminded me an awful lot of duvel , but niot quite as good . poured to a highly carbonated golden yellow , with thick pilowy white head that lasted the entire beer , and left excellent lacing .  t : wood chips , obviously , tastes like a sauna smells , charcoal , molasses , savory like breakfast sausage , soy sauce , real sharp sweetness that 's broken down by hops lurking in the background and that 's absent at the finish m : medium body , very low carbonation , i 'm surprised this was n't the cask ( it was n't but they did have it ) , dry bitter charcoal finish . the mouthfeel was a big drawback for me , it was very flat , considering this was the draft veraion .

loads of burp from a very clean , light golden fizz and a nice hopped edge on the aftertaste . certainly wo n't stand up to serious beer for beer competition but this is the type of refreshing hot summer beer that 's best served very cold for thirst quenching . like i say this is the best choice for a breakfast bar beer - nothing else .  this beer looks amazing in the glass . extremely rich orangish-copper hue .  feel is smooth and well-carbonated though a bit on the thin and watery side . medium-full body , not too heavy . leaves a nice sticky coating around the mouth . a bit thicker and less bitter and it 'd be great .

this beer is great , it is really drinkable and similiar to a beer i love by dogfish head. , it pours brown ( obv ) and isnt too thick though , which makes it nice and drinkable . nice caramelly roasted malts and color , try this one if you are into nut browns or similair types .  the lacing is astounding . pretty appealing .  the mouthfeel is just a little light for a tripel style . just a little watery and fairly light on the tongue .

smell of some sweet malts , that 's about it .  strong aroma of coffee and chocolate . this stout is pure blackness and even thick then disappates to thin dark brown head .  m - nothing special . just a regular lager thing .

buttery nut aroma .  dark gold , lightly cloudy , with a very big creamy off-white head slowly shrinking to a puffy , rocky smaller head and foamy lace .  texture is smooth but only slightly fizzy , leaving a slightly sweet fruity finish .

s : subtle is the word i would use . there are floral notes and spice notes , but only if you really work at concentrating the aroma from the glass . t : lemony and slightly spicy .  appearance & gt ; lovely golden amber hue . lively .  nothing spectacular in terms of mouthfeel , but i 'll buy it again .

nose is tangy wheat with a bit of a roasted flavor and a touch of herbal hops . good overall and interesting as this is my first dunkel .  a : thick and black , dark almond head ( more like a thin disk of residual bubbles ) s : strong note of alcohol , bitter dark chocolate , coffee m : very alcoholic feel ; initial taste of a dark stout followed by the heat of a liquor akin to scotch .  the colour is a light straw , probably the weakest colour i have seen in a pale lager , the head is very pleasent and has some serious glass cling ... the aroma is very skunky when first opened but quickly disappears and the taste is highly sweet malts on a thin body , very nice for dining , not a stadium brew ... i first reviewed this brew in march of 03 , approx 10 monthes ago .

the nose is initially a bit harsh with a faint scent that borders on nail polish , but might be coming from the alcohol .  appearance : this one pours a very dark mohogany with an incredible red hue . great head rentention very frothy .  have you ever canned tomatoes ? if you have , you should be familiar with the smell and flavor tomatoes have when cooked . this beer had an overwhelmingly strong odor and taste of spicy stewed tomatoes . it was too strong to drink . i know this is not normal for this beer from the other reviews of it i have read ( and the style does n't allow for many strong flavors ) , but it was only days past the best by date and had been stored in a refrigerator . there was also some floating particles in the beer which i also assume is not normal , pilsners typically being filtered . i will come back and rerate , but i 've been told by some fellow raters that i should take this beer into account for my rating .
smell is pretty mild with just a hint of roast malt and caramel .  poured out of a bottle to a beautiful dark color . really a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel was ok ; about the same as urquell .

slight cocoa powder and multi-grain . would 've scored higher but i did n't detect much smell from the bottle or my special samual adams glass .  beautiful red orange color . a tan head sits on top for a while . a very pretty beer . we tried it with some honey ham and then some apple pie and it was terrific with both .  it smells of rotten banana peels , rotten apples , and molding compost . the flavors are very sweet and kind of medicinal . it leaves a clove laiden aftertaste behind , making you think you just had an artificial banana milkshake . i just do n't understand what two brothers was going for on this one .

appearance - black with a little off white head smell - theres not too much to the smell , kind of a sweet roasted smell to it taste/ mouthfeel - has a chocolate roasted flavor , is very smooth and a little thick .  appearance - deep muted red , like the embers of a fire almost . the head is light beige in color , extremely dense and creamy like melted marshmallows on hot chocolate . the lace is a full blanket all the way around the glass .  this is a very good pumpkin beer . picked a 6 pack up at the local market , came home on a chilly night here in rural mi , and my girlfriend and i finished the whole six pack . lots of pumpkin taste , beautiful color , and an overall great seasonal choice . i would n't drink it in warm weather , but on this cool fall night , it hit the spot . i could see picking this up in the future to bring to a bon fire , or to enjoy while i hand out candy on halloween . cheers !

murphy 's stout on tap is one of my favorite dry irish stouts . this style of beer does not have much of a smell , but the taste is wonderfully sharp and smooth at the same time . murphy 's is perhaps a bit less bitter than guinness , but they are close . the mouthfeel is very smooth , and i personally find this to be an extremely drinkable beer , and i am happy to drink it all night .  pours a honey colored amber color with a three finger tight bubbled head with lots of wispy lace from start to finish .  initial taste of a sparkling mouthfeel with a puckering sour cherries that coat the mouth incredabily . the palate duration is average . medium body .

the aroma is a bit faint , but mainly malty with notes of toasted grain and a hint of grassy hops .  this beer has probably the best head i 've ever seen on a saison . saison de lente pours a massive 3 finger white head that has almost a pancake batter like consistency . the head retention is fantastic . the lacing is just magical . a thick french lacing accompanies the glass even when then the glass is empty .  less fizzy than anticipated in the mouth .

s : herbaceous and slightly spicy , with some suggestion of lime citrus and fresh berry fruit . overall intensity of the smell is weak , giving an impression of vacancy . t : begins off-dry , with pithy grapefruit peel and crackery pilsner malt .  a : nothing to complain about here - dark black , with a mocha colored head that hung around for a while .  nice dark brown color with fantnaztic lacing ! smells choclotly with coffee . tastes even and thick with cocoa sweet caramel flavors continuing thru . good for its class this porter represents well , its much better than its younger brother . would drink again .

the smell is hard to recognize at first light hops and a bit of a bready taste . the taste followes right along with the smell but i get a bit more of the fruit .  a - the beer looks great ... it is so clear , it 's almost unnatural but it 's pretty to look at . it 'd be damn hard for a beer to look much better than this .  i wish the carbonation was a little more noticeable in the mouth .

s - i am hard pressed to find much in the nose beyond a light , pleasant flowery hop . very good beer , though i feel the appearance and aroma are weak for a bspa .  wow , orange , slightly reddish , as it let 's the light pass through ... it 's beautiful . such a strong head , off-white .  a : dark reddish copper ; flat head ; strong carb ; not much lacing s : strong raspberry aroma , very inviting ; occludes other smells t : expected sweet -- it is n't ; the raspberry dominates , but it 's quite sour , draped over a wheat-beer-like base ; i must confess , this tasted terrible to me ; it tasted like nothing else i 've had , so i do n't think this is something against the genre m : good carbonation redeems the experience a bit overall , a terrible beer , for me .

sticking my nose into this thing there is a bit of pine , grass , earth tones , but not much else .  head exhibits very impressive staying power , and impressive lace . color is a beautiful dark and cloudy orange , yellowing around the edges .  i like a little heavier of a mouthfeel than this offers , but the lighter feel is not surprising considering the crystal appearance .

the aroma was sweet and floral .  750 ml bottle cage & cork & gt ; chimay gob deep , dark amber color , red hues with a blissful carbonation with a two-finger deep head at first , solid white , thick and dense and lots of life , the retention is as good , if not better than any i 've seen . amazing look .  it is about a medium mouthfeel , with almost no carbonation .

nice lacing as well . a seriously good-looking brew . smell : malt right off the bat , with a certain underlying spiciness . the taste is terrific & # 8212 ; for a pale ale . not the best seasonal , per se , but a really tasty ale .  pours a deep brown , transparent with an off white head . huge head that sticks to the glass and remains about and inch thick . tight head , quite beautiful .  mouthfeel is fairly thin but not unpleasant .

smell : caramel and mild bitterness are detectable .  the appearance is amazing . it pours really really dark brown , safe to say black . it leaves a thick lacing around the glass that is very very intimidating .  mouthfeel is a bit too thin , especially in view of the heavenly head and ample lacing .

the aroma was quite lax , nothing really going on in the nose , it smelled a little spicey and nutty , but that 's all i got ? the taste is solid ; nice mix of unique spices and a grea tmalt taste with a sweet tone as well , i found it hard to grasp what exactly was in here but it was dispersed throughout very well .  a : nice bright golden color with a nice creamy head that you dont usually see on these american witbiers .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with medium to high carbonation .

s : very feint smell , chocolate note , but a bit of roasty malt as well .  from a bottle this poured a pale golden color . very clear , well carbonated with fine bubbles of co2 and topped off with a very attractive creamy head of foam . this certainly looks like a premium beer on the highest order .  m : um . it was carbonated and did n't leave any odd off flavours on the palate .

and now these famous waters are again being put to good use as the principle ingredient in local ales . spartesian is a soft , summer ale . it is exceptionally pale in a dramatic hue of sun-yellow . fortunately , my tastes stray far from `` timid '' and i was able to settle in to a satisfying appreciation of this very pale beer . it has low co2 , no smell , little forward hop flavor , and a vivid lemon color . but the smooth body makes it an easy drinker on a summer 's day and i was left wondering if that billowy mouthfeel was attributable to olympia 's famous artesian well water .  crystal clear straw hue with a two finger dense and frothy head that slowly settles to a thick cap , leaving a solid wall of lacing in its place .  a sticky medium body with good carbonation . a bit too sticky for me .

the smell did n't give much away other than chocolatey malt and hops , so when i took the first sip i was surprised and utterly pleased . notes of fruit , a little nutty with a slightly bitter spicy hop aftertaste .  330 ml bottle consumed at a certain way , on to the beer : it 's black with a some hues of ruby red . the head formed on top is extremly thick , is tanned in color , and still holds on top until the last sip . did i mention is shows some rings of lacing ?  the taste is awesome m : medium bodied , perhaps a bit too heavy , with decent carbonation , not the best , but is good enough for an apa .

smell : strong grapefruit was the only thing that really hit me . nothing to write home about on the nose . taste : wow . an outstanding american ipa .  the liquid is dark amber and clear and is topped off by a plentiful marshmallowy tan colored head . the retention and lacing are out of this world . mountains of foam cling to the glass indefinitely .  the body was light and there was not enough carbonation .

what i do get is small whiffs of cocoa which smells pretty good .  a - wow , the gentlest of pours brings forth a beautiful ( slightly clouded due to my misjudgment ) light orange brew with the most ridiculous pillowy head i have ever seen , four fingers to start , sticks around for what seems like forever , and leaves great lacing s - pear and apple , along with a little cut grass , lemon zest , lots of yeast , clove and pepper t - smooth maltiness , slightly tart , with a lot of green apple , a little fresh hay , some yeasty goodness .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but thats a minor complaint .

s : light and hoppy , but i think maybe my glass smells a bit wierd .  liquid is a dark amber topped with a thick finger of brown foam and dense and substantial lacing . carbonation is also very prevalent , making this model stand out much more than previous years . visually stunning .  s - some grassy hops paired with caramel malt t - slight hop bitterness resolving into some serious roasty malt , but then it 's all gone fairly quickly with just a hint of woody bitterness m - quite light with just a hint of carbonation on the back of the tongue ; the slight bitterness endures for a whlie d - quick drinkable , though the excessive roasty malt will probably get in the way ; little to no alcohol warmth nice drink ; did n't expect it to be as dark as it is - listed as an american porter , but it 's almost a supercharged brown ale .

smell : very sweet aroma with a caramel note to it but really very weak in the nose . very impressive flavor for a beer with such a weak aroma . mouthfeel : smooth , clean on the palate with a nice roastiness that lasts on the palate even after the beer is gone . aside from the weak smell i was very impressed with this beer .  poured into a tulip . billowing head , color to the amber side of golden and nicely hazed , outstanding lacing .  first off , great pics , great blurb on the back , just fantastic presentation . this beer is belgian to the core , color , nose , taste . there 's an abject fizziness to the brew i could do without , reminds me of shasta in the summer of my youth , a memory i did n't need to dredge up . taste is sweet & light . barring the cost , this is the kind of beer i could drink all night . this is a solid beer , but not the hellion i was expecting .

not much nose , but what it lacks in smell , it makes up for in taste . hard to believe this brewery nearly bit the dust .  amazingly slow head cascade action . clear from yeast or other floaties .  the mouthfeel is thin , however , and it 's over-carbonated .

the smell is very boring , some mild piney hops and presumably cedar , and definitely did n't impress me as i tilted the glass back for the first time . unfortunately for all other ipas , the standard to me is pliny and it 's pretty damn hard to come close to pte in drinkability .  the color was hazy lemon yellow with two fingers of rocky , yellow-tinted head . the cap retained itself beautifully and the lacing was in solid bands .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied .

nose is extremely mild - had to stick my nose in it for a solid thirty seconds to get anything . dirty malt , i guess , but it 's hard to tell .  had this at a recent ba gathering at milly 's , and brought a growler home . this is a beautiful beer : as black as can be , with a thick coffee-colored head .  rated as a stout the mouthfeel is a bit thin , the carbonation is a bit high , and the finish is a bit less than one would expect .

aroma is of sweet malt , grain and corn , some tart sugar notes like an apricot .  motor oil black with a head like you would see on a rootbeer float .  mouthfeel is light , and carbonation is set at medium .

it smells nothing special really , typically acoholic smell really , a bit like whiskey .  a classic looking hefe , a orange/golden color with a billowy , white head .  light bodied for what i was expecting , but then it does n't claim to be a porter or stout .

no discernable aroma at all - kind of weird .  a : black on top , fades to reddish/brown at the bottom when held up to the light . nice lacing . a real gem .  some hop aroma and flavour , a little to light in the body for my liking .

poured into a some big ass glass ... appearance-amber body , very dark pale ale . some skunk , not sure what the date is on this bottle ... taste-tart granny smith apple along with some sweet caramel malts .  looks like a cappuccino with a marshmallow melting into it . leaves amusing puddles of lace behind and seems murky and cloudy . exquisite - a marvel to behold .  alex dumped this on this ! ... pours an ugly apple cider color , murky medium brown , not much carbonation ... the aroma is terrible , generic wood , rotting pears , and vanilla . ca n't stand this ... the taste is dry hopped wood ; a piece of wood that was drenched in dry hopped water . this is ugly , and smells and tastes terrible . skip

a- pale golden yellow , has about 1/2 in head laces beautifully with lovely activity s - really nothing there , watery slightly malty with just the faintest buttery sense t - wow super smooth with a lot going on .  poured from an inch or so above the glass leaves a big off white to light tan head that settle into bubbly sort of carbonated lacing or decent worth above a clear coppery to reddish which also seems to have a golden glint to it , very appealing .  mf : a bit thin , light body , medium to high carbonation d : another winner from sierra nevada .

s - bright hops and citrus predominate , but overall not particularly strong odors .  pours a deliciously cloudy , rich red with a nice thick & dark tan head .  active carbonation to form lacing but it does n't feel on the heavy end of the carbonation spectrum .

a pleasant aroma for sure .  a - golden with a slight haze . massive 5+ fingers of head foam up . excellent retention with a thick cap that remains .  m : medium light body with medium high carbonation .

smells of some heavy brown malts , some toast , a bit of spiciness underlined with a hint of booze . overall , a fantastic and robust offering from a favorite producer . puts countless other pas to shame and raises the bar in an excellent way .  the most beautiful foamy head i 've ever seen , and it lasts forever in the duvel glass , sitting atop a gold so intense it almost glows .  but a little watery .

not much at all in there .  a - dark , almost black with a beautiful one and a half finger head that is very creamy , love the cascade effect .  mouthfeel & drinkability : lighter bodied and less bitter than most other ipas , which makes for quite easy drinking .

not much of a nose on this english ipa .  pours a great red color with an off-white head which sticks around for a while and clings to the glass . the taste is somewhere between a dark lager and a stout ... it 's got a good malty taste with a great strong finish .  the nose of the beer is strong and gives off a nice floral hop aroma . the flavor is sweet and semi-tart with fruity tastes . behind the sweet fruit , there is a slight but smooth alcohol presence . the earthy hop bitterness comes in at the end and fades away with the semi-dry finish .

the beer 's scent was almost entirely hops for me . it seemed to be a one dimensional flavor profile to the scent . i did n't get very much matlyness in the smell . the flavor was really where this beer started to pick up .  pours almost oil black which was a pleasant surprise . medium/thick lumpy head that reveals most of the aroma right off the bat .  mouthfeel : a bit thin the only thing i can say i 'm disappointed about here just seems watery i even recall the original munich formula having more body but hey sturdy carbonation excellent o-fest .

smells ok ... ca n't exactly put my finger on what is wrong ... but it may have something to do with the `` party pig '' it came from .  appearance : this beer is magical . a perfect brown head sits upon a black body , grabbing the glass and not letting go as i drink .  m : a bit overcarbonated , dry , thin , light-medium bodied .

rather subdued smells of hops and citrus and i 'm getting a bigger than expected malt .  this amber ale pours with a clear amber body topped by a thick head with lots of lacing left on the glass .  m - the hops lingered a bit too long and had a metallic feel at times .

there was very little nose to speak of , just a bit of a sweetness , like caramel . it was very drinkable , and as with newcastle you can often find this when theres nothing else in the bar/restaurant worth drinking and it would certainly get the job done .  a fairly large ( nearly two finger ) head of light brown foam sits atop . an ominous looking brew .  decent carbonation , a little thin on the malt profile for the style .

t : this beer has a little malty but mostly hops , actually more hops than expected . m : reasonably full d : very good , i had a second pint  a- really nice big belgian-style head on top of a fizzy , slightly hazy , light straw colored body . looks lovely in a belgian tulip glass .  i am starting to view the boston beer co. as a-b or miller taking a stab at the craft market but still wanting to appease the masses rather than being strict to beer styles . a big dissapointment for an apa

as a long time drinker and former hamms beer route salesman this is still a beer that holds up well.ca n't count the cases of this that has passed my lips but wish i could find it in the bottle . now if they would only bring back hamms preferred stock ... we 'd be back in hog heaven . for the money its a real drinkable beer .  pours nearly pitch black with a big frothy , creamy mocha colored head . looks similar to a ris . great lace , great retention .  m : medium body and high carbonation .
