s : aroma is of roasted malt , coffee and a hint of bitterness . t : taste of roasted malt , coffee , a bit of sweetness and a nice bitterness through to the finish which is quite dry .  burnt copper color , with haze-of-yeast and a soft , bright white head that stays around forever .  ( i actually do not care for this sweetness , but the beer still has great flavor ) m : nice carbonation , but the body is a little weak .

s : toasted cereal grains , earthy and a bit nutty . very light sweetness with some light caramel and toffee notes . d : pretty drinkable and tasty . hits the spot if you 're looking for something malty but not toasty or heavy .  poured into a tall hobgoblin tumbler , there is a huge billowing light tan head . very impressive presentation .  if you closed your eyes and smelled this you would think your smelling a good octoberfest beer due to the scent of carmalized malt and faint hops . has a carmel toasted nut flavor on the tounge and finished dry . i like the fact that this irish red is a little more bitter than most red ales but still not overpowering . tongiht i will be reviewing 4 of hook and ladder beers as i bought a gift pack that came with 3 bottles of 4 different beers . the beers i got were backdraft brown golden ale pipe and drum irish red ember amber ( a type of black and tan made with their backdraft brown ale and golden ale ) . try these beers if u can find them they are good

the smell was rather plain , hints of roasted grain and toaste , slight metallic nose , otherwise not much there , the taste however was great , a nice marshmellow smoothness up front followed by a warming dark roasted and coffee flavor with backing of chocolate , goes great with pie and ice cream , highly recommended .  a - deep dark , opaque black color with a thick head , excellent retention s - gentle coffee-like roasted grain , malty , no hops noticed t - roasted grain characterized by coffee and tobacco flavors ; hop balance but no detectable flavors ; fairly clean for an ale , but faint hints of yeast esters noticed ( but appropriate ) m - medium-to-light body with moderate carbonation d - this is quite an enjoyable milk stout .  m - decent body with a bit more carbonation than i 'd like from this style .

s : i was a unprepared for the smell , as the malts had a big impact . if i was pressed for details ( i suppose that 's the point here ) i could pinpoint some caramel . t : i think the flavor of this beer is gorgeous . do n't let that push you away though , because it is n't a kriek by any means . kudos to the widmer brothers .  a-pours a slightly clear copper/amber color with lots of thick white head that leaves outstanding lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and harsh from the acidity and carbonation . also finishes quite dry with little to no bitter .

the beer smells like fresh paint .  this beer pours a slightly cloudy golden orange color , with a thick , fluffy light yellow head . the head fades very slowly , leaving a thick cutrain of lace .  m - light body , with a carbonation level that is probably too sharp for the style .

s : fresh cut grass scent is present up front which is followed by a grainy malt sweetness . rather simple scent , but i was n't expecting anything complex . pretty average straightforward .  great retention , and lace as one might expect from a northwest ipa .  malty and corny .

a sweet malt . earthy hops , i sense not from dry hopping , but more likely late hops additions . i i had it served from a 12 oz bottle a bit too cold , which undoubtedly muted the aromas and flavors , tending them toward the bitter .  bomber poured a clear dark reddish brown nearly black with a lasting brown head .  slight hint of the hop flower but the malt dominates , sweet , crisp , fresh and pleasing to the senses with the start lightly sweet , satisfactory malt presence , and top light to middling in feel . this is a style where i like the lighter body , as it lets the flavoring hops shine through , quite quaffable , a damn fine session beer me thinks , and i thank royalt for this bottle .

smell : resiny with some floral sweetness . not real strong .  ( a great place ) poured a wonderfully rich yellow color . it was cloudy with a half inch of creamy white head . nice lacing with this beer .  m-its a little undercarbonated but the balance of the sweetness with the malt and subtle hops make for a relitivly complex october beer . d-easy to drink and very nice to have this time of year , easy to session .

smell is a little off out of the bottle - a bit glassy , but the mouthfeel and drinkability are high .  wow , what a good looking beer . dark dark , dark body and small light brown head ontop .  m - smooth and thick , but hard to hold onto . unpleasant taste does n't do it well .
s : typical lambic funky smell .  beautiful dark dark brown to black color with a nice brown head .  m : mouthfeel is decent , goes down reasonable smooth even with the slight burning sensation .

nose is slightly malty . flavor is dark fruit and some alcohol burn .  i love nitrous beers - they have this amazing waterfall effect as the head settles . the beer 's head was a nice creamy tan color and featured some light coffee/mocha scents . appearance - 5.0/5.0 - love the waterfall effect of the nitrous , tan creamy head - very full taste - 4.5/5.0 - silky smooth - coffee and light chocolate taste feel - 4.0/5.0 - no aftertaste , extremely smooth in mouth smell - 4.0/5.0 - very light with coffee/mocha accents drinkability - 4.5/5.0 - way better than a guiness - very tasty , smooth - i will be repeating this beer .  the body is surprisingly light with moderate carbonation , helping to make this very drinkable .

yet anothe winner from rogue , pours a deep amber with a big head , aroma is faint , taste is bold spice and nice toasty malt , almost peppery , delicious . mouthfeel is pefect as seems to be the case with all rogue brews . a superb amber ale , right up there with red rocket ale in my opionion , a very enjoyable brew .  they are the best ! beautiful pour , orangish tan with a perfect beige head .  unfortunately , it is basically flat , with a heavy mouthfeel . overall , this beer would be unbelievable with good carbonation .

aromas are faint , a bit of spice and floral smells . but not much on the nose .  poured into a glass stein and had an above average white head . it looked great in the stein .  m- very carbonated and light for a lager .

a little roasted grain and a whisper of coffee . i 'm a little disappointed . t : i think this is the widest gap i 've encountered between smell and taste scores . the smell was a let down , but everything i was hoping for in the taste is here . m : this had the smooth silky body i expected from an oatmeal stout . the smell score was lacking , but this has it were it counts .  fantastic lacing & head retention is als really good , a peresitent film hugs the orval goblet all the way down s : slight hints of choclate , cherry & oak barrels t : choclate & oakyness up front .  mouthfeel is a bit fizzy , and another beer where bottle-conditioning would have a positive impact .

the original yuengling lagar ( which is good ) brought me to this beer and i was very impressed .  lovely hue , a truly good bright ruby red , with a collapsing , but pleasantly silky head of yellow white . it 's a really lovely looking american red ale , absolutely what you want from the style .  much like the ingredient list on the back , there are scent of malted barley , malted wheat , hops , and yeast which gives it an almost caramel scent . starts out making you think this will be a heavy tasting beer with its malted ingredients like a stout but instead it finishes rather light . drinks rather smooth as the malted ingredients really hit the taste buds . finishes rather clean smooth . a decent beer with a rather interesting drinking experience .

soapy lacing stayed behind . very crisp aroma of burnt sugars , yeasts and nutmeg . very sweet . and drinkable ... to a point .  poured a beautiful amber color . wonderful lacing . just a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel is about average for an ipa .

smell was unremarkable , not necessarily the biggest fan of 4 roses bourbon .  appearance : fantastic dark ale , glows slightly ruby when held up against the light . one of the best heads i 've seen - 1.5cm thick , creamy and slightly off-white . good retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery and cool in texture , it goes down nicely and is a little bit better than water .

regeneration very good . hoppy front end , chocolate notes , roasted malts and a long finish , nicely balanced , oatmeal , any spices were subdued .  a : distinctly black with a fluffy , pillowy 2 finger khaki head that resides to a one finger head . very impressive lacing .  mouthfeel was unremarkable .

very grassy on the nose with a touch of pine and skunk . also a bit of a musty smell , and a hint of smoky sweet malts .  appearance - slightly hazed yellow/straw . puts a good finger and a half of white foam on the glass . a nice ring of lace frosting at the high water mark .  drinks a little heavy because of all the sediment but feels watery and thin on the palate . adequate carbonation but not incredible lively .

s - slightly sour and horsey on the nose , somewhat saison-esque , with a brighter malt/hop aroma in the background .  poured into a fluted glass around 6c a : copper and crystal clear , with a nice 2 finger tan head that lasts a long time and laces nicely .  m : thin , do n't take that the wrong way though but easy drinking .

s : faintly nutty , with no alcohol detectable . overall very mild , not really noteworthy .  a : this thing has a huge head . a perfect billowy light-tan colored head with so much fluff , it might as well be whipped cream . the beer is a darker shade of brown when poured , and nearly black in the glass .  has a very light mouth feel , which makes it a more-then-one beer .

a deep brown color gives the initial stout impression but a light citrusy aroma is present leading one to believe it 's and ipa .  drank on-tap at miracle of science bar & grill , cambridge , ma poured a gorgeous , crystal clear , dark orangey-amber with a clingy , off white , one-finger head that lasted the duration of the beer .  mouthfeel is a little thin and aftertaste is a little too much ... like the brew has gone stale , although i know it has n't .

that bright yellow can is like a delicious beacon calling to me at the supermarket . the taste i 'll admit is n't hoppy , or even very stong but rather subtle and beautifully simple , zen if you will . a real guzzler that 'll quench your thirst without fucking you up too bad .  this beer poured a beautiful gold with a rock-like head that persisted in all its glory for a few minutes before collapsing into a nice ring-around-the-rosie .  m : a little thin in body d : good .

nose is kind of small and basic . mild green apple , sense of sweet malts and candi . not very big or noticeable or even complex .  pours a very dark brown , black in the glass , with a nice tan head that maintains down the glass . excellent rings of lacing .  take this beer for what it is ... a nice `` treat . '' it 's not something you will want to drink all night long . but for a nightcap , or change of pace this beer fits the bill . the vanilla taste is not overpowering , it 's there , but not so bold and overpowering that it seems fake .

s - heavy horse has a classic aroma of toasted malt with notes of caramel , toffee , and a pinch of nuttiness but is hindered by a dry , strong mineral finish .  the beer poured beautifully into the glass : a bronze-brownish coloured pint with a thick off white head . the main thing i noticed throughout the duration of the pint was the excellent retention and lacing that the head left .  the mouthfeel is decent , but could be a bit more robust to support the flavors .

on its incredibly smart looking clear bottle it even claims to be a bitter ! best compared to the very similar budweiser and millers from the us .  this beer poured a very dark black color with very little light getting through it .  i got this beer in the beers of the world gift box for christmas . immediate taste is a lil sharp and bready with a hint of citrus in the smell . it was not an out of this world experience , but it is a very light and enjoyable beer for everyday or get togethers .

smells not so much and like ripe guava ( combination of the hoppy cirtus and sweet frutiness ?  black color , pitch black .  presentation 11.2 oz ''ceramic '' bottle with blue foil over the cap no date on bottle . pours with a think creamy head that dissipates as quickly as is rose . light brown with a hind of deep red . a smell of caramel and alcohol , taste is more of the same with a slight earthiness to it . finishes cleanly .

s : i got virtually no scent until it warmed up and i got chocolate and nice coffee but mostly roast and alc . t : great taste , smooth high gravity , the coffee taste is great .  appearance : pours orange in color with a huge fluffy white head that stays around for some time . lots of bubbles floating to the top .  m- a little thin , but not too bad . nicely carbonated , with a slight bitter hoppiness at the tail end .

s : smells of pumpkin , nutmeg , also something sour i ca n't put my finger on . t : taste is much more impressive than the smell ; tastes like a boozy pumpkin pie but the sweetness is held in check nicely .  appearance : beautiful hazed orange with honey lemon corners . a huge 3 finger off white crown with loads of retention and lace . the crown is really frothy and gets nice and dense like whipped cream after you let it settle and repour a few times .  but it has quite a few pros : this beer is intended to be consumed with food . if you want to have chinese food with a light drink then this one is just what you are looking for ! it 's a typical lager : crystal-clear blonde , discreet taste and weak aroma . i usually do n't drink lager beers but this one i can have by the barrels while there 's food on the table . this beer is what you want to drink when you do n't want to drink !

s - fairly dissapointing . for having lots of fuggles and goldings i was expecting a good hop smell . smell improves after drinking and warming also m - a little zippy with the carbonation but still well bodied .  huge rocky off-white head with good retention . carbonation bubbles rise to the top which makes the head more active than a tornado in a trailor park . fine looking beer !  i 've always liked this beer , and if they beefed up the abv and gave it a little more body , it would be the perfect porter . why grant 's beers share these characteristics i do n't know , but if they ever did beef 'em up a little , they could truly be a contender .

smells of noble hops and that 's really about it , pretty much standard for a german lager , i guess . tastes more bitter than i expected , and a little sweeter than i expected .  great black appearance with cascade of bubbles when poured that lasted a minute , leaving 1/2 inch tan head that stayed until the glass was empty .  t & m : for a doppelbock a little thinner bodied than is usually expected .

s - sweet , malty nose with strong notes of molasses . smelling this blind i would not have guessed ipa .  extreme amount of head over poured just from opening the bottle . dark almost brown color .  the middle is kind of hoppy , but somewhat thin . the finish is dry and quite hoppy . a decent light beer .

i was intrigued to see `` north coast brewing '' as the creator of this saison ... poured with a nice frothy long lasting head . the nose was scant.. i do n't think there was one.. maybe i 've got a cold.. over all is a nice saison . it could do with some more `` earthiness '' to the flavor . it 's hard to characterize but i find the flavor profile somewhat without character.. or something pleasantly memorable -- something that signified `` north coast brewing '' saison.. very cordial on the palate- and a very enjoyable 750ml .  stunning ruby red/black beauty with superb head retention .  mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .

looks great , clear burnt orange/ harvest orange color that has hints of brown . smells has some vague fruity esters , lemons , a hint of pepper , almost a hint of tea leaves . upon re-drinking i can gladly up the score a bit but still feel there are better saisons out there .  immense multi-layered head with frothy , large bubbles at the base and fine meringue top . lasted for ever , leaving beautiful lacing behind .  this is a bit thin , but still great .

-- horrible ) . beer does not have much of a smell to it . maybe a mild roast , some malt , not much at all . beer is super smooth , beautiful full bodied beer . for some reason the first time i ordered it i expected some smoke but was pleasantly surprised by the lack of it .  had awesome retention and never showed signs of totally leaving .  i have had ipas that went down a bit smoother but this one is n't bad it still goes down good but with just a little more carbonation and bite .

not too much aroma , but you can detect a sweet , double ipa smell through the cloudy yellow foam .  poured a very nice deep copper with fantastic head and nice lacing .  mouthfeel was very thin for the style , but added to the higher level of drinkability .

smell : not much , some yeast , some fruit taste : nice cherry flavour , not overly sweet by anymeans . mouthfeel : starts creamy and thick but finishes crisp with the carbonation coming in on the finish dinkability : quite good , i could certainly have more than one .  sampled on 4-7-09 pours a clear deep red/brown , with a huge , foamy , clingy , off-white head that leaves crazy thick lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit light .

trying back to back kolsch beers today , poured into a standard pint glass a light clear golden with a large fluffy white head that never fully settles , another spritzy lookin klosch , this head a great head to hit as well.aromas are muted , only some light toasty grain , this is a crisp dry kolsch , spicy/herbal hop and toasted grain flavors mainly , i like the crispness of this beer.now this a perfect warm weather brew that again isnt a throw back beer , i like this alot .  a : this pours an entirely transluscent orange color with red hues and a finger and a half of slightly off-white head that laces better than any beer i have ever seen .  surprisingly light mouthfeel makes it a fairly easy drinker for a 9 % er

the smell is pretty faint .  i poured this one from a 12oz brown bottle into a tulip pint glass . a= this stout poured black as night with zero light penetration . with a very aggressive pour , the dark tan head rose a full 2 '' and took a long time to settle to a thin cap .  mouthfeel : light/ medium body with excessive carbonation that somewhat hinders the flavor .

aromas are slightly amber malt , chocolate and coffee .  bottle poured into a tulip glass . brilliant clarity . thick white crop of foam with good retention and moderate lacing .  medium body , maybe even a bit thin .

s very little smell but the slight aroma was a pleasing , coffee , chocolately one .  appearance - black with no light passing through . good tan head on top . looks like a very nice stout or porter . nice amount of head but with even less lacing then their other beers .  the only downside of this beer was the mouthfeel , which was fairly flat and watery , probably due in part to the low % abv .

nose has some citrus rind , soapy alchol and prickley pine but all relatively soft . would have been close to a 4.5 if the nose was a little more developed .  this beer has perhaps the most beautiful color i have ever seen from a beer . my beer glass looked like a precious gem with this beer inside of it . it had a nice white head that seemed to have just a slight bit of pink .  a really really long aftertaste in the nose .

5/5 s : light/medium aroma . hints of dough and hop , but not real strong . t : interesting . very faint on the malt end , but a hint of some dough and rye ( hence rye ale , i suppose ) .  this brew is really gorgeous . nice hint of red , obviously , but the cloudiness swirls around and give the beer a nice look . head is off-white and puffy ; almost too big even with a careful pour .  a little less carbonation and this probably enters `` special '' territory .

smell : i 'm really not getting much aroma off this . perhaps a hint of grasses , but barely . taste : nice malt taste with a light bit of citrus ( lemon ) and grasses .  enormous thick and lasting beige head , colour is very dark brown , cloudy .  yack ! i 've had this lots over the years , but this time it got a major problem with butterscotch . aroma smacks me down wth that butterscotch - ugh . but , somewhere in there is some malt and a little chocolate , good malt . flavor is butterscotch - blaaahh . ca n't finish it . draft lines are clean here too . no more , pleeeeze

smell : a bit musty , some hints of banana in there , but not as appealing in the glass smell-wise as it was when i cracked the bottle . quite nice .  a : amazing , witth a light brown head that initially takes up the entire glass . if you get this on nitro watch as the head melts into one of the best beers you 've ever had .  smell : balanced scent with undertones of both malt and hops ; predominant smell is faintly sweet yet mainly grainy aroma . taste : well-balanced flavor , neither hops nor malts are predominant , the combination of which is apparent throughout the beginning and middle , dissapating for a clean finish . drinkability : refreshing and palatable , the quality of yuengling speaks for itself . definitely a beer that can be enjoyed regularly .

s - lacking a bit in this department . roasted malt is about all is decernable .  draft at teresa 's in wayne , pa pours a very dark brown with foamy tan head that forms a lacing that lasts throught the whole glass .  light-medium bodied with crisp high carb .

smell is very mild , slightly musty and dry . sure sign of belgian yeast .  pours jet black with a thick , luscious brown head .  ordered this one in a taproom and was vary pleased . this beer is solid , as one might expect from north coast . it 's is as good as any pilsner i 've had . it drinks easy , has a hint of subtle fruit flavor , and smells very good . it also pours very nicely from the tap with a fluffy head . i 'd pick this one again on draft and might pick it up as a favor for a host when a house guest .

bland/plain smelling . some cereal grains and buttered toast . t : just great . sweetness throughout with some alcohol .  appearance- beer pours a wonderful looking amber golden with a thin wispy head one finger high of whipped cream foam . this is about the most perfect appearance i 've seen for a marzen . very impressive from an impressive brewery .  does smell a little like `` beer , '' as my wife would say . so sweet on the tongue . slight raspberry tartness but it is like drinking raspberry sorbet after it melts . it is still trying to recover from the sweetness . a good once in a while beer . sorbet beer , i tell ya .

s : not much of a nose on this . ethanol , some roasted malts , hops and citrus . t : what the nose lacks is more than made up for by the taste .  pours a luscious and very tempting opaque sable with a thick , frothy tan head that leaves a fair amount of lacing .  there is a very little carbonation factor in this beer .

smell : some bready caramel malt sweetness . not a ton going on here . overall : a solid irish red .  poured a dark golden orange to light amber in the glass ... yes , almost the color of the jewel amber . lots of beautiful bubbles in the pour reminding me of a guinness that end up creating a full 2 finger craggy beige head that melts to sticky lace .  im stoked i can try a beer from this brewery even tho it is a collaboration but ive got nothing but good things to say about mikkeller and heard good reviews on these other two so looking forward to it , it pours a very light honey hue with decent carbonation that leaves a one finger head with sporadic lacing , the aroma is floral hops , apricot , bananna and a nice belgian yeasty aroma too , it has an average mouthfeel for the style almost syrupy and has tastes of yeasty bread , citrus and of course a pleasant floral hop finish with the alcohol well hidden , this is definately an easy beer to drink and if it didnt cost $ 18 ( aus ) i could drink it all night .

what i could detect was rather wheat-beerish : some cloves and bananas , maybe some lemons . decent light-amber color , too . very nice taste , with spicy oranges and other citrus ambling arm-in-arm with light bananas and some hay . of the american bpas i 've had , this was by far the most drinkable : not overly bitter or ham-fistedly hopped , but nicely balanced and quite drinkable .  an absolutely gorgeous looking beer !  i picked this lager over the ale 's offered , due to the miserable heat wave here in no . cal . it was an appropriate choice . saaz hops seemed to be prominent with good malt base . a nice refreshing beer . nothing spectacular but very acceptable when in the mood for this style .

smells like burnt , lightly smokey malt with no real hop or yeast profile . tastes firmer than it smells . smokiness presides over a rich , very dark malt profile of nuts , peat , and burnt grain .  appearance : a wonderful amber color .  body is medium , and perhaps errs to light every once in a while , which does n't help the flavours as much as it could .

my first beer with agave added . smell : hints of honey and orange blossom , slightly muted .  pours crystal clear orange-amber color with a dense 2 finger off white head with great retention that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts the entire glass .  m - smooth going down , a bit thin , finishes dry .

s - roasted malts , but there is some brine or olives on this that makes me feel like it has turned a little bit . there 's some good and bad , taking this to average .  starts off creamy white and then cascades from the bottom of the glass to the top changing to black as it goes . there is a thick off white head that lasts forever and covers the sides of the glass in foam and thick rings that mark each swallow .  m- a little too carbonated for my liking , that makes this beer have a little `` sting '' to it ( especially if it is served too cold ) .

the brew is a clear amber , looking a lot like a munich oktoberfest . aroma is mild , with little indication of the beer 's hoppy palate . wisconsin amber has a lot of the drinking characteristics of a pilsner jazzed up with some medium-roasted malts .  this beer was a very nice , deep red/brown color , and it had a very nice and thick head .  easy drinking but it has a different mouthfeel , it almost leaves a film in my mouth .

a - clear , ruby red , aggressive poor produces no lacing s - not a lot going on here , maybe some figs or plums and vanilla or caramel t - wonderfully subdued representation of the same aromas in the nose m - very smooth and creamy with just enough carbonation for a clean finish d - impressive for 10 % .  poured a solid black , even when i held my led flashlight up behind it , with about an inch of thick , sturdy light brown head that had great retention and moderate lacing .  its perfectly balanced and not overly done . m very medium , which i find most all stone beers to be and i dont really complain about . the carbonation is present and isnt overly aggressive or submissive .

smells of sweet malts . a little nuttiness . not all that fragrant . for the taste , sweet chocolaty maltiness , hazelnut and a little hop bitterness on the finish that lingers .  bear republic tribute ale is a very clear , very lively , deep crimson brown berr with a huge , lumpy , beige head .  all of the good notes that a belgian has , with some american notes such as a much higher rate carbonation , more citric fruitiness . the high carbonation almost makes me question whether or not it 's natural , but i doubt stone would rape this brew with added co2 like the macros do .

it did n't smell like much , which is dissapointing . i look forward to the roasted and hoppy aroma of russian stouts , but this one did n't come through very well .  pours out a slightly chill-hazed brassy tangerine with a wealth of tiny bubbles making their way to the head . head is massive , foamy , and almost spills over the top . leaves some near solid lacing on the glass .  it feels very thin in the mouth , close to water .

aromas are a bit faint in this brew.. ( though i 've never tried it fresh its truly hard to pick up much of a bouquet in this one ) . of what 's left of the aromas , i found there to be bits of carob and cocoa , a hint of spice ( maybe coriander ) and an almost nutty character to it . for flavor this beer packs a much bigger punch than its aromatic qualities . initial flavors are of carob and an almost slight smoky characteristic . overall this brew has amazing flavors , though its aromatic qualities have not kept up as well imho , but for anyone who is aging these bad boys , i would only give them another 6 months.. i do n't see how this one would hold up the last 9 years of the vertical epic series .  this beer looks perfect ! the bright , clear yellow beer , the fluffy white foam , the constant stream of fine carbon dioxide bubble , the everlasting lace left by each sip , it was exactly how a beer this style should be made to look like .  mouthful : somewhat over-carbonated but generally decent mouthfeel .

all are very light scents .  appearance : deep , rich , amber red . poured semi-aggressively to yield 2 fingers of nice , tan , creamy head which started to reveal some interesting pitting after a bit . moderate lacing .  beer/brewery - old fezziwig ale/boston beer company ( samuel adams ) city/state- boston , massachusetts style winter warmer abv 5.9 % ibu 27 date 10 dec 2011 serving type 12 oz bottle glassware pub glass appearance mahogany in color with a thin head with a brownish white color aroma- fruity and winter spices , all spice , clove and nutmeg i think taste pumpkin pie without the pumpkin , a lot of clove , also has a bit a of a bitter ( non hop ) after taste mouthfeel very light and bland ob feeling conclusion other than the after taste this is a great christmas beer , not quit a winter warmer as they abv is a little low , but still a good flavor to think of around christmas .

smell is very faint - a little bit of strawberry , and not much else . the taste , however , is just fantastic . the wheat beer flavor is at the forefront , but the strawberry smooths it out wonderfully .  a 330ml bottle fills a duvel tulip with garnet elixir topped with lots and lots of creamy head .  light body with a very active carbonation .

mild roast with a bit of fruit like character .  pours from the bottle to a reddish orange with medium off-white head that lingers , and excellent lacing .  could use more malt or residual sweetness but for a regular american coffee stout it does the trick mouthfeel is a touch thin and watery but there is a bit of creaminess from the nice carbonation that keeps this one going .

aroma is not much . just pils lager aroma . taste is great .  a pretty good looking beer .  the reason behind that tenacity turns out to be that it 's a bit overcarbonated . there 's a great nuttiness in the flavor here that i 'm seeing as chesnuts , but it could be the power of suggestion , and a little bit of roast . tasty , but just a tad too gassy .

s- fresh and pretty subtle . nothing too strong .  firstly , i dont know if the nitro can should be listed alongside the on-tap version , because they are completely different , as the on tap version is far superior than the widget-can . anyway , if kept well , the pour is the classic we have all come to know and love .  mouthfeel if very alive and crisp at first sip . maybe a bit overpowering on the carbonation .

s : faint scent of roasted malts , chocolate , and coffee . t : a combination of sweet roasted and chocolate malts with hints of coffee .  bottled april 22 , 2009 poured into a pint glass amber with a very thick white head . very good retention and lacing .  i found that the beer smelled and tasted rather skunky , unlike most other beers that i had tasted and was deeply disappointed by it . it felt ok in the mouth and looked very nice in its green bottle but was not worth my time .

even after warming up , the smell is minimal , with a hint of hops . this a good session beer and is very drinkable .  it pours a rust-colored brown with a roasted 2-3 finger head . this looks as good as any of the big ipas made by stone , smuttynose and company .  it 's almost too sticky and thick to be pleasureable , kind of like a toned-down bourbon county stout . i 'm not a big fan of the finish , which comes off like sweet wort of a stout ( oily and a bit thin ) . m : very thick , with some relief , but then a lingering silkiness .

nice black color with edges of brown , poured to a medium head that dissipated quite quickly . some malty sweetness up front which fades into a roasted malt taste . very small hop bitterness and most of the rest of the bitterness is from the roasted malts . goes down smooth and is quite tasty . ~jonathan passow  this beer looks wonderful . a beautiful mahogany red , cloudy and rich topped with two and a half fingers of rich foam . the beer leaves textbook rings down the glass as you drink it ( rather quickly ) .  m : medium mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

the aromas were very muted . i picked up malt , cask , earth , and some very mild hops .  this beer pours a clear , dark reddish amber hue , with one thick finger of foamy , creamy ecru head , which leaves a swiss cheese paint job of lace around the glass in its wake . one damned fine lookin ' beer !  the mouthfeel is medium with some sharp carbonation .
the malt smells wonderful but no hop aroma .  pours a beautiful dark brown , nearly black , with a tan head of about one finger .  feel is thin bodied overall , but well bodied for the style .

s : somewhat subdued citrus & pine hops with a caramel sweetness . t : really well balanced and drinkable .  looks really nice with the carbonation streaming up all the sides . great retention with the full finger staying around the whole time . great rings of lacing .  this is the least impressive quad from the trappist breweries ... do n't get me wrong , it has a similar taste profile , although not that perfect as a westy 12 or a rochefort 10 , dark fruit , plums , candy sugar , but i did n't like the mouthfeel on this one . too much sparkling going on ... pretty funny thing is i just absolutely endlessly adore the la trappe quadrupel oak aged batch 1 version ... so so so much better then the regular one , especially when the oak aged version , bottled this summer , is coming around fantastic ! i like their dubbel more too .

the aroma was nice , but nothing special .  a- body is a moderately pale amber hue that pours with a nice 2-3 finger foamy white head . body is uniformly translucent and has the head has great retention with lots of lacing left all the way down the glass .  m : thin mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

special cask for crockett 's public house in puyallup . smell is slightly fruity , slight pine , honey , and earthiness .  pours a translucent medium copper with some awesome bubbling and a thick doughy head .  the mouthfeel is larger light with a very , very slight fizz .

smell - light and hoppy with a moderate aroma of malt .  pours a bright orange color , slightly carbonated , with a thick pillowy off-white head .  ( m ) - this is where the beer starts to fail in my opinion .

musty aromas and smokey grains come in strong with this one . this aint no fru-fru grand cru micro .  beautiful amber color gives this lager a real boost .  m : mouthfeel is a bit thin , considering how robust the initial flavor is .

to me , boddingtons is the `` caramel '' version of the `` chocolate '' guinness if that makes sense . it 's a smooth and very drinkable beer that you can just put down without even realizing . not much of a nose , which would probably be its biggest problem . it 's a staple , not something that pushes the boundaries , and it should be appreciated as such . it 's best on draught and pairs well with many deserts .  a : hazy yellow with a frothy head that has great retention ; what a hefeweiss should look like s : grainy with the typical banana and cloves poking through the hay/earthy/straw graininess t : a nice balance of earthy grainy yeastiness and banana and cloves ; subtle spice nodes ; a tiny bit thin on the way down f : pretty good mouth feel but a tad thin at back end d : wonderful drinkability ; the quintessential hefeweiss beer ; great especially for a hot humid day .  mouthfeel : thin yet flavorful .

aroma was a bit lacking .  poured a deep dark black with few brownish ruby highlights observable when held to the light . creamy tan head the lasted the whole glass ... superb retention .  good carb , but feels a bit thin and watered down in general .

smells alright nothing spectacular just a sort of generic beer smell .  very big head on this one . very big and fluffy ... looks like powdery hills of golden snow .  mouthfeel is fairly carbonated , a bit sour , finishing dry and crisp .

s - light malt scent , and not much else .  pour produces an impenetrably obsidian ale with better than an inch of fluffy and dense mocha foam that loiters on top and fades gradually , leaving thick lacing .  i 've never had this in europe because there are too many good beers over there to risk the experiment , but does it taste better over there ? anyway . the carbonation is nice and the golden hue is lovely . but the smell and the taste are the real reason i drink a beer and this one fails . sorry . i would prefer any american macro brew to this and i will drink alum for the buzz before i 'll drink those so this must be a bad beer .

no strong smells here , picked up on roasted barley a little bit .  this poured out a rich golden color with a lovely red-orange glow that danced reflective light off my fingertips . a rush of tiny bubbles formed a thick white head that dissipated at an average pace , leaving foamy crystals that clung to the sides of my tulip glass . superb !  the feel is a little odd . it does n't seem to be too carbonated , but the bubbles sting like sprite against your lips .

s : chocolate malt , cocoa , coffee grounds and a hint of plastic that fades out after a few minutes of sitting out .  pours a lovely , crystal clear dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' tan head that persists all the way down , coating the entire glass with heavy lacing . the best looking ipa i 've ever seen .  lively carbonation is a bit excessive , but the body is quite smooth .

i put my nose in the head nosing for the nose . a robust bitter hopped start with enduring bitterness throughout the flavor with roundness or body to the flavor supplied by a malt character . a nice long finish consisting of the same lingering bitterness that dominates the flavor . this beer really has a finish quality about it- memorable .  one of the prettiest looking beers i 've seen , a reddish cloudy haze glows from within , with a pink thick bubbly head .  12 oz bottle poured into weizen glass , only glass i could get at my buddy 's house a : great pale golden color , light head with decent retention , great clarity s : great floral aromas t : not a pale ale that is actually an ipa , not overly bitter and slight maltiness m : good carbonation , could be a little thinner o : great pale ale , not just a copy of other american pale ales .

it had a mild malty aroma with good lacing and a very smooth palate .  pours a deep , opaque blood red with a really pretty cotton candy , rosy head that settled into a soapy haze .  magic hat usually disappoints me , not that their brews are n't good , it 's that some of them just are n't tasty- till now . magic hats roxy rolles is right up there with ithaca 's cascazilla and troegs hopback amber . a definite seasonal must have for me . great ! ! !

smells of barley malt , with a hint of dark chocolate .  jet black in color with a huge , coffee colored head on top . just a clasic looking stout if there ever was one .  very basic but very good m= average carbonation and average weight .

aroma is a bit muted .  pours a tremendously jet black coloring , with a dark brown , foamy head that dissipates as you drink .  mouthfeel - foam is scarce and small bubbles and light caramel that fades quickly . slightly thin .

subtle aroma , what is there is nice ; roasty , malty , sweet . taste is very good ; sweet molasses , malted chocolate , bitter chocolate , a little hops , finishes bitter-sweet . it is very pleasant to say the least !  pours beautifully , flat opaque black with a thick chocolate milk-colored head that dissipated but not too quickly .  m - surprisingly , its a bit thin and lacks carbonation .

smell : a hint of caramel candy sweetness is all the nose picks ups .  the cascade hop explosion was still there , but i was able to handle it this time around and i really enjoyed it . ruby-amber color , bordering on red . awsome color .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is too light in my opinion .

the aroma is thick with heavily caramelized bananas and dates.sometimes it reminds me of nail polish .  a . great appearance . 3+ fingers of super dense head . excellent retention . great appearance , lackluster smell , very interesting taste , good mouthfeel , drinkability good and overall uniqueness good .  m : medium body with a sticky quality when it enters the mouth .

purchased a growler of this for $ 6 on a wednesday . a- growler makes nice popping sound when opened which is real nice . s- very sweet and malty , but not so much hoppy . the hops presence began to show as i was drinking . m- well carbonated but drying on the finish .  this beer looks great , clean and clear , good carbonation and head .  mf- raw resinous and sticky , becoming oily , medium carbonation , slightly astringent , dry and grainy in the finish d- well rounded ipa , but not the best around .

this beer is faintly ripe with doppelbock scents of caramel , mixed dark and roasted malt , heated figs , and an end hint of port wine . smell is the weak point of maximator , but only because all its components are so weakly displayed .  amazingly attractive .  this review is from notes in my `` travel journal . '' obviously the beer is now `` retired . there is some berry in the attack . the flavor smoothes out to leave a clean finish . it is a very drinkable beer , but not what i normally seek out .

yummy ... pours a heady white-over-bronze trophy , some modest lacing which arches around delightfully un-predictable shapes ... i think i see a war-elephent trumpeting hannibal 's decent from the alps ... smell was somewhat subdued , i did n't have any good glassware handy , i used a big wine glass . smell was suggestive of good things to come , but nothing terribly fancy . this is where the fun really starts .  nice clear copper color with a decent tan head , nice active carbonation , and nice sheets of lace .  bought this over a month to two months a go and decided to give it a go . it is an ipa so it does have a nice bright orange to copper color . the taste and the smell are sweet and fruity , the only bad thing i have to to say about it , is the taste of tea is very lacking . i cant pick it up but , other than that i wish that stone , ishii and baird made this more as a yearly offering , cause its really good

absolutly no head during the pour , only around the sides smell seems to be weak but the taste packs a punch .  one of the best looking beers . the cascade effect is great and the lasting tan head is inviting .  i think this batch was contaminated . so , this review only applies to the specific beer i drank . it had a floral hop finish . so , that extra ester punch made it deviate too much from the pale ale style . so i ca n't say i liked it , i 'd try again and find a better batch .

the smell was a very solid , but not incredibly inviting cocoa presence . the mouthfeel was incredibly lucious and creamy , just like a porter should be .  batch 265 a - pitch black body with a huge amount of coffee head that is frothy and sticks around s - chocolate cherries with some sour and funk laying around t - just like the nose .  m : dense and creamy with low carbonation .

s : not much going on hear , some toffee and yeast t : very malty , toffee sweetness , some spice .  pours an absolute black , that sucks light into it . rocky tan colored head emerges , disappates very slowly , and leaves nice lacing .  had to give it the maximum points for appearance , because even out of an imported bottle , it looks just right . comes in with an alcohol bite that 's almost like an imperial . pertty nice taste , though , and if you had some , i would n't refuse .

first of all , i am very dissapointed to hear that warbird brewing company has closed . warbird has produced a very drinkable red ale .  this beer pours a gorgeous clear deep orange amber color with a 3 finger ( on an easy pour ) of offwhite/tannish thick sudsy head . the head retention on this was ridiculous !  cons : the low carbonation level does hurt many factors of the beer , but it is such an exquisitely brewed offering , it 's only a minor issue .

the aroma was underwhelming but neutral grainy .  look is beautiful . perfect 1/2 inch head when poured carefully into a surly pint glass .  the mouthfeel is light carbonation , somewhat on the watery side , but very drinkable .

smell of alcohol and malts . color was bodacious . mouthfeel was like heavenly night blooming jasmine with a hint of mirliitons and cypress buds .  they share the same appearance if poured into the same glass , and the head is excellent . the taste is almost identical , with the can version being perhaps a little more bitter . i think these nitro cans are a great invention .  m - a little strong on the carbonation for my taste .

the smell is pretty light , but its of roasted malts .  750 ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . pours a cloudy corn silk hue with a pillowy cloudy white two finger head . super sticky on the sides with a head that sticks around forever .  very pleasant indeed . great hop character . this is a fairly balanced ipa . hard to say , it might just be because this particular bottle is more on the room temp side , but i would like more effervescence . a good beer all in all . i will be sure to drink it again , only a little colder and faster . more drinking , less typing ... .

s - smelled like a quality stout.though i really could n't smell any coffee like odors . t - sweet toffee & coffee with some bitterness .  a very nice brew that started with an absolutely great black color with an outstanding head and lacing .  m : thinner than i expected , pretty fair amount of carbonation , once again a little more reminiscent of a porter than a stout .

lots of yeast sediment in the bottle . smell - not much just a little bit of citrusy hops , candy , a bit of alcohol , and a bit of sweet caramel malt . smells of cascade hops . taste - starts out with a sweet caramel malt taste , followed by some grassy and earthy hops , a bit of citrus twang mostly as graperfuit and then the bitterness .  a beautiful appearance , two thick fingers of creamy light coco head with spectacular lacing coating the glass .  maybe a touch too much carbonation .

good color - darker than i might have expected s - a little sweet .. i dont find this beer to have a pronounced smell of any kind .  superb retention .  the mouthfeel is the only thing i think could be improved here and it very well may just be that i am having it from a growler .

groggy hazy brown color in the body . a little sour , but the malt comes through in the aroma . flavor is a superbly sweet caramel malt , but with a kick of almond .  as black as an overcast night in the woods with no light . thick creamy , milky , tan head .  this beer has a lot of flavor for a light . too bad its not a good flavor ! nothing impressive at all here . i 'm not sure what they are putting in this beer but its not worth the 7.99 they are charging for a six pack . i would recommend pabst blue ribbion over this any day !

i was n't able to pick up a great deal of aroma , only slight hints of malt .  browning 's bourbon barrel imperial stout pours a very nice , pitch black into a snifter with a small , light tan head that leaves lots of lacing behing .  a light , medium in body . extremely active on the palate ; too carbonated , that really takes away from this hop-filled wheat 's pleasanty flavors .

it went down very smooth and i enjoyed it . however i was expecting more taste , the bottle says brewed with imported hops but to tell you the truth this beer tasted very similar to the less pricey michelob golden draft light sold here in minnesota .  perfect looking .  not bad at all , really , although a bit thin for the most part .

smells very faint , alcohol and nutmeg with a bit of almond and herbal dust .  looks picture perfect . despite my allergies , i can actually smell floral hops .  mouthfeel was ok , not too thin , right amount of carbonation .

if you get it in a bottle it 's not as good since they distribute this beer in green bottles and you start to get some skunkey flavors . this is a very grainy pilsner with a slight hop aroma and taste . this beer is very true to style . that said , if you like a hoppy beer then pass on this one .  pours with an excellent appearance , thick tan head with small dense bubbles and a clear hazelnut color .  the mouthfeel has a little bit more carbonation than i would like a brew of this calibre to have , thus the 3.0 .

smells are light too , and crisp . nothing sweet or piny to note .  pours a pitch black color with a huge brown head into my glass .  as with several anchor offerings , i feel the carbonation is a bit overdone , but is n't powerful enough to be overly distracting .

a : transparent light amber colored beer , that has a good head to start off with , but it dissipates fast . s : hoopy but nothing special , not that potent . t : overall good . mild hops taste with hints of citrus , and a bit of a bitter aftertaste , but nothing overwhelming . very much so torn between 3.5 and 4 .  750 ml bottle , procured at the pacific park market in aliso , a : pours a pretty much opaque burnt orange . huge frothy white head from the bottle conditioning , leaving lots of lace .  the taste is ok. it seems a little flat coming out of the can compared to the tap . nice clean finish , no lingering aftertaste . definiteley a session beer if drinking from the tap .

get some caramel , licorice , and molasses in the aroma . a rather enjoyable brown ale that has a slightly different taste than most brown ales .  huge off-white head formed with large bubbles , eventually forming large craters in the top of the incredibly retentive head . as good of head retention as i 've ever seen . perfect dipa appearance .  pours a three finger light tan head that fades quickly to a ring leaving a little lace . dark cloudy amber color . light carbonation and light bodied . caramel nose . starts balanced but then a caramel flavor that stays to a clean finish . a tasty wheat . $ 2.49 for a 500ml bottle from john 's grocery iowa city , ia .

smells a little citrusy and and a little wheaty - nothing impressive . a very lemon-like taste that finishes a little bitter and a little like cherries .  a : aggressive pour yields 1 finger of dark tan pillowy head with great retention .  t- roasty , sweet malts , coffee and dark chocolate m- starts off nice and creamy and full , then towards the middle loses a bit of it 's body and seems to get watery , only to return with a solid finish .

this was my first experience with an arcadia ale and i most likely will never try their beer again if i have to pay for it . smell : harsh up front , but sweet and hoppy at the end .  a : pours a cascading nitro-foamy head in a black background . the beer itself appears black at first blush , but upon close inspection is actually a very deep ruby/mahogany . it is a gorgeous beer .  m - the feel is not terrible .

aroma is mild , too mild , but i pick up on dark roasted malts , cocoa , light caramels , ans very german-smelling hops . tastes better room temp , smells better too as it warms .  a : deep brown with a nice fluffy tan head . 2-fingers to start , slowly receding . perfect .  had some fruity and clove flavors but was covered up due way too many hops for the style - not to mention that it was bitter . i barely finished it . other reviewers liked this beer and seemed to have a much different experience than i did which leaves me to believe that they have consistency problems or maybe they use different formulas for each location ? btw this one was sampled at the brewpub near the fleet center .

aroma - a pretty grainy first whiff , light roasted malt and a bit of chocolate come out on setup . fades a lot and does well to maintain some faint roasty aroma . taste - sweet , fully roasted malt and milk chocolate malt .  the appearance is outstanding ! s : expresso like smell with subtle malty aroma .  i 've been waiting to try this one for some time now and it was well worththe wait ! i could smell it 's fruity aroma as soon as i opened the bottle , it has a nice dark cloudy amber color to it that is topped with a nice thick head . it goes down very smooth and just warms up your mouth , and you can really taste the spices in it .

s : citrus hops that had a sourly strong detergent scent that was a slight turnoff at first .  looks very lively . this looks amazing and out of control .  body is fairly thin , but that is expected for the modest abv .

s - okay , you can smell the malt and you can tell there are hops although they are not predominent as in many ipas . d - very drinkable .  pours an absolutely gorgeous dark cola body that illuminates to a caramel-amber when held to the light . creamy , light tan bubbles form a sizable froth on top and slowly settle to a thick veil of foam , thanks in part to a vigorous carbonation level .  the mouthfeel seems a bit week and flat , but it 's not bad .

poured deep brownish black , thin head smells of dark roasted barley , not too overly impressed but typical .  12 oz bottle into pilsner glass a : beautiful ! crystal clear yellow body topped off by one inch of white creamy foam .  if i had to log a complaint , it would be that this stout is too thin and less of a cream offering . however , it is full of flavor and easy to drink despite being 6.5 % abv .

smell is still rather clean . light hop backed by a light grain nose .  great `` belgian '' lacing & very good head retention smell : sourness & then woody , lactic notes .  the body was a bit too thin for my tastes in this style .

the nose was lightly fruity , yeasty , and malty , but not pungeant enough for my preferences .  pours a fluffy , thick , white , three-fingered head , fades very slowly and leaves gobs of lace .  mouthfeel is a little on the thin side .

col.or was a lemony , sunshine-yellow with ne-quality clarity . nose had a solid lager sweetness , none of that adjunct b. s. mouthfeel was full with a lot of carbonation scrubbing away all of the b. s. on my tongue as i swirled it around .  the geary 's hsa pours a beautiful dark amber , sticky-icky up the sides and a beautiful 1/4 inch head .  m : full bodied but way too over-carbonated .

this brew poured a very beautiful dark brown color with some nice red flecks . the aroma on this brew has a bit of caramel and some faint malts . not a whole lot of aroma coming from it . as it sits a bit , there is a little bit of a nutty aroma . there is n't much else . though there was a bit of lack in the aroma department , this brew makes up for it in the flavor of the brew . it begins with a wonderful blend pale malts , which is quickly followed with a nice punch of caramel and cocoa . it was exceptionally good . i enjoyed it very much this is a great drink .  what a great looking beer .  too much carbonation for this style ( -1.0 ) .

the nose was the least offensive part of this beer : ripe fruits , some bitter chocolate the taste on this beer was absolutely horrid . rotten fruit mixed with tobacco and cardboard . new holland produces some fantastic beers , this just happens to not be one .  i enjoy just about everything this beer has to offer .  m-medium body and syrupy with a grainy tough texture . strong carbonation and a slightly messy carbonation in the finish .

n = some hints of alcohol , skunk , fruit , but not a good indication of the taste .  a- deep , opaque brown/black . beautiful , rich , thick , deep dark tan head that lasts forever . even with an appropriate pour , the head was deeper than i 'd ever seen .  ; very sweet ( perhaps overly ) m : a bit syrupy overall , a fantastic barleywine style ale .

a malty aroma with some notes of coffee and nuts greeted me before my first sip . this is a very good full flavored beer that hides it 's 10 % alcohol very well .  pours the blackest black with no light coming through .  mouthfeel is medium with more carbonation that i expected due to no head showing up .

no aroma to speak of , which is unfortunate , because it would complement the interesting flavors . somewhat malty , but this is obscured by the many flavors rolling around - sweet pear and apple , a bit of butterscotch , with gentle hops riding beneath .  the head poured out at 1.5 fingers and stays that way forever in a rocky , creamy form that just refuses to recede . gorgeous appearance .  poured from bottle to tulip glass a : brilliantly clear pale yellow color with huge 3+ finger head that fades very slowly n : nose of a light belgian type wit with some light malts , touch of spices , toasted quality , touch of yeast t : starts with more malts and toasted quality , pretty light otherwise , a touch of light fruits and banana , slight earthy marzen quality , no spices m : very light and somewhat watery f : finishes dry and very crisp with a fading earthy marzen taste , would make a good session beer final thoughts : its a very light tasting oktoberfest/marzen .

the smell is a little sweet and citrus-like . the taste is clean with citrus and the normal wheat malt experience .  nice downward bubbles on pour ... dark brown to black with a slight ruby edge , a tan creamy nitro head , and lace like wallpaper .  bittersweet finish . kind of think and syrupy on the palate .

s- not a whole lot going on here . some sweet hops and a touch of hops .  `` mad bitch '' has an great look . upon pouring it creates a beautiful white head that lasts for the duration of the drink . the beer is an opaque , honey color that is incredibly appetizing .  m - nothing special just went down really easy ... .it was n't bad tasting ... .i was surprised how quickly i finished it because it went down fast .

it 's flavor is very rich w/ a slightly bitter finish . the maltiness is very enjoyable . another fine beer from victory  it pours clear ruddy amber with a very thick and creamy tan head .  a little more carbonation may have helped this one with its texture . just a tad thin , becoming a little dry but not crisp in the finish .

there was n't much aroma to speak of , but what there was was sweet and just a bit spicy .  had great lacing and retention .  light in body and fairly thin on the tongue . smooth and lightly carbonated .

d- not a huge fan of the aroma but other than that it is a really nice beer .  bottle : poured a golden color ale with a huge pure white foamy head with great retention and lacing .  m : light-medium body with an oily mouthfeel , and a dry and resiny fade overall , not a bad beer , though it does stray from traditional belgian dubbels in a few aspects : not as sweet or yeasty as the classic belgian examples , a little hoppy for the style , and its too light .

s : the weakest aspect of this beer for me . general maltiness is all i get . t : the key here is balance ; a supremely well-crafted beer .  there is a magical cascading effect within the beer as it settles . a beautiful off white head remains perfect throughout the experience lacing is awesome .  wow this has to be one of the worst ideas in beer history . trying to cross a pale ale with a belgian and what you got is something that is a distant cousin to both . instead of leveraging the style 's strengths this beer doubles down on their worst attributes . a very hoppy tatse that fights like a strong ale . not a fun beer and a true shame that it might discredit weyerbacher 's other great beers .
the smell is sweet and lightly spicy this lightly floral and more hoppy than a typical ale of this style .  found this one at julios randomly ... a : awesome look .  medium carbonation .

s : notes of bubblegum , a bit of pepper , and a hint of orange , very faint smelling beer . t : starts out like it smells with a bit of a sweet bubblegum flavor with a bit of a sharp pepper but then does a 180 and has a bit of a dry/bitter hop taste , it 's not too strong but it 's definitely there .  appearance - pours with a nice , clear golden head , some dark reddish hues provide a little tint . two fingers of whity rocky head with a crusty top and lots of good stick .  light to medium bodied , carbonation seems to be at the right level .

happily , though , if you give it a minute or two , the stench fades away some , to reveal a nice malty aroma underneath .  bottle poured into a pint glass appearance- beautiful ! one inch light tan head that slowly disappears .  lacks hops . lacks malt or any toasting . crisp , dry , clean , even a little bit bitter and metallic .

smell is nothing exceptional : some obvious coffee and a touch of dark chocolate .  a- pours a splendid black color with a thin milky looking head that lasts the entirety of the beer and copious rings of lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit of a problem for me . the carbonation level is also a factor , making it hard to enjoy in gulps .

based on tasting notes poured golden with 1/2 '' of white head , with good head retention & very good lacing s : some herbal & lemony hops t : lemony hops , & a little breadyness .  pours out like chocolate syrup , fills the glass pitch black with a very dark tan head . billowing foam despite a very cold serving temperature , thick chunks of lace , crazy retention .  m - a little thinner than i thought and more carbonated than i would expect .

little uninspiring .  beautiful looking beer to be sure , dark , dark brown with a very attractive frothy tan head . just looks so good in the glass .  the taste is sweet and smooth , with a hint of hops but the most prevalent taste is of lemon . finishes with a very refreshing aftertaste . i would defiantly suggest this beer to even non craft beer drinkers .

unfortunately , the smell does n't measure up to the appearance . it 's ok , but nothing spectacular . well , the taste certainly is nice . complex , malty sweet , and again , i taste the cherries . for 8 % , this is extremely smooth and drinkable .  poured from the bottle into an oversized wine glass . a beautiful golden color with a fat head that loses size very quickly , but still sticks around some .  the body is is a serious letdown , nowhere near rich/full enough and it crosses the line into watery . the carbonation is appropriately subdued , and does n't overtake the lackluster body .

s - kind of muted actually . maybe some slight dark fruits and touches of rum soaked bread .  black with a nice brown head that leaves good lace rings .  mouthfeel is surprisingly light but overcarbonated .

the aroma was light as only some malts were detectable . overall a very nice brew that was very flavorful but not overwhelming for the food .  deep brown pour with a gigantic , rocky , tan head .  like drinking sour grass , probably the best way to put it m - low carbonation , slightly astringent d - not very drinakble , i had to leave a third of it

pours a light brown with a reddish tint , it dosnt have much of a scent to it except for a slight cirtus .  nitro-can encouraged frothy tan head , superb retention , some lace , almost opaque hue .  ) it has very low carbonation witch makes the mouthfell very average with about that of a tap bud lite , only a little tingle from the carbonation .

the smell is more toasty malt than anything else , but if you must know that anything else is somewhat grassy barely grapefruity hops and a decent amount of caramel .  12 oz bottle poured into an '08 osa pint appearance- pours a deep brown with a large dense tan head , sticks around forever . incredible head retention and lacing .  this beer poured a dirty blonde color , with a haziness that made me suspect that i would n't enjoy this beer too much . aroma was malty , and flavor was a sweet maltiness with only a hint of hops . this was n't what i was expecting from an american pale ale , and i really did n't enjoy it . i may have gotten an old beer , but there is no date code on this beer , so i have no way of knowing its age and it gets what it gets ... most of this one is going down the drain .

smell : roasted , malty scent with a burnt undertone , and hints of coffee .  this is a beautiful looking beer . not much lacing or retention , but the color alone gives this one a prefect appearance rating .  m - exceedingly bitter . needs to be a little creamier for this style d - not a session beer .

smell iis ok , but slightly astringent with little discernable difference between malt and hops . beyond the astringent aspect , there is a slight flowery essence . i would highly recommend this beer as a delicious , drinkable ale for a hot and sweaty day .  a : light orange color with the most insane head i 've ever seen . off white and very very creamy head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and syrupy with a bit of sharp carbonation .

the aroma is surprisingly weak and consists of a vague smell of roasted coffee .  this beer is a handsome black with a pillowy light tan head that has great retention and lacing .  m : very thin mouthfeel however strong carbonation makes overall body light but full .

appearance : pours into a sam adams glass a clear pale yellow with a loose-bubbled white head on top . smell : quite sweet with indications of wheat and lemony citrus .  the appearance is simply beautiful . a rich brown that seems to be characteristic of most trappist ales . this actually sort of reminds me of the way eku 28 eisbock smells , which is odd for a trappist .  it is a bit thin , bordering on watery with adequate to slightly low carbonation .

s-yeasty , wheaty aromas , slight citrus with minimal phenols .  a : forms a nice 1.5 finger frothy head in my sa perfect pint glass with very good retention . it 's a crystal clear beer with varying colors , being auburn orange at the thinner parts and ruby red at the thicker , and a good amount of bubbles floating up from the etch at the bottom . perfect appearance at least .  wtf did they do to this beer ? this is the first time i tried it since they put in the new brewhouse and i 'm not impressed . this used to be a wonderfully drinkable beer with orange and subtle spice flavors that made it quite refreshing . now its just overloaded with phenolics and all you can taste and smell is cloves . i ca n't get past the phenolic flavors enough to even finish a bottle . just horrible .

s : sweet malty smell of molasses . t : the smell is very accurate to the taste ; sweet heaviness with a clear taste of dark molasses . i would have expected more in the way of aroma but that is n't necessarily a bad thing .  appearance & gt ; looks like an giant-sized perfect pull of espresso .  tastes pretty amazing really . watery on the tongue but ends dryish .
maybe a bit of sulfur .  light copper with a thick , mousse-like , sticky-as-hell head .  mouthfeel is just ok-nothing too incredible but quite drinkable especially at the 6.5 % abv .

it has a cloudy light brown body and a malty fruity combination . it 's a very well rounded brew and just a little different .  pours a vibrant amber with dark gold highlights and great head retention .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and somewhat tannic , but the overall effect is quite interesting .

overall i enjoyed it , the smell still does n't please me but the beer in general is quite good .  a : beautiful head about 2 fingers thick that never goes below a half finger thick , ever . golden/amber in color , looks like honey . honestly , one of the best looking ipas ever .  m : medium to full body but needs more carbonation .

overall : 3.85 appearance : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | mouthfeel : 3.5 | drinkability : 4 740  on-tap at beachwood bbq , on to the beer : the head retention is great on top this coal black beer . great , thick lacing sticks to the glass .  i always drink my high life out of cans ! it looks like beer , smells like beer , and tastes like beer ... to keep it simple . this is my go-to macro , and will always be as long as miller keeps it the same ! prost !

the nose is nearly all sweet malts , some toffee and notes of banana esters . not too heavy or dark in the nose .  ( a ) - pours a clear golden yellow/orange color that produced a huge foamy/fluffy white head with great retention .  this beer is not awful but it is not good either . if use to be better , i think , back in the days before aluminum cans and pull up tabs . beer is fizzy and gives a good head and that is about the only good quality it has .

smell is less then expected for a german hefe , little bit of wheat , a little cloves and yeast , no bannana like i was hoping for .  poured a slightly cloudy , amber to copper color with . nice frothy two finger off white lasting head . ample lacing cling to the glass .  the taste is very good , it could use a bit more body but the flavors are great . tons of chocolate and roastiness dominate the profile but there is also some caramel and hops . the bitterness is at a great level in comparison to the sweetness , especially for the style . the guy below me has it right : not quite edmund fitz or blake butte but this one is one of the supeb examples of the style .

smell : sweet malt , floral hop , light brown sugar , light bread , light whiff of dark fruits . the nose was a little light and the beer itself is more hop forward then what i would consider perfect for a esb , but on the whole a very simple but good brew .  pours a hazy golden color , with a huge fluffy white head . what a sight , as the head rose easily above the rim of the glass , and held there like an ice cream cone for a lengthy period of time .  picked up a few of these `` oil cans '' at a local liquor mart . this is the only place i 've seen them . i like the regular fosters occasionally , and have fond memories of it from various parties and times in life . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i liked this , i guess , but the drinkablility was hampered by a fakey sort of bitterness that did n't hold a candle to the fuller 's and young 's of the world . kind of caught in my throat . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .

lacing consists of large swaths of bubbles clinging to the glass , which dry out over time . smells fairly bright for a porter . roasted dark malts are at an appreciable minimum . ah , the nose does n't do the taste justice .  a- pours dark black . one of the prettiest beers i 've seen .  m : a bit light in the mouth , but it kind of coats your mouth as well .

light nose of little consequence . the taste is very nice with limited and pleasant spiciness and a nice bread sense .  just an over-sized glass with great markings . excellent to look at . a clear golden pour with a very generous head .  ambrosial start , lots of malt , the top skimpy in feel with the finish having a delightful hop spicy bite , the carbonation moderate and the aftertaste droughty and long lasting .

some rich roasted malt aroma is prevalent if you can get past that head that acts like a aroma seal .  ) pours a beautiful glowing , hazy , golden color . really gorgeous and appealing appearance .  reminded me a bit of bmc with a bit of syrup added for sweetness . the taste is more of the same with a quick malty dryness at the end that seems to say , `` ha ! had you fooled..you thought there was about to be something pleasant here , did n't you ? in fact , this may get sacrificed to the kitchen sink . as i always say , in total fairness to the brewer and his ( or her ) intentions , this may have its fans , but it most assuredly is *not* for me ...
s - roasted malt - not a ton going on here t - toasted malt , some underlying hoppy bitterness to balance it out the taste .  excellent lacing . great looking ipa .  mouf & gt ; easy , average .

the smell does nothing for the beer , it is very light , made me not expect much from this beer .  appearance : pours a motor oil black with a 1 finger creamy milk chocolate brown head . excellent lacing . like all the other yetis , this one looks perfect .  the body of the beer is actually approaching medium and the carbonation is not overly fizzy as many macros are .

s : not a lot of aroma . mainly sweet , bready malt . t : quite earthy , probably from the yeast , as well as the hops . d : very drinkable .  a quick swirl brings nice crimson flashes to the glass , quite amazing ... the aroma flows to my nostrils from feet away .  my first taste of it was great , however it lacks in the balance of the malts , and has sort of a over roasted taste . altogether though , this beer in my opinion is the best of the coors brand and i would recommend for something new . not a everyday beer though .

nose is predominately light brown sugar , and a hint of ginger .  presentation : it was served in a tulip glass from tap at the pizza plant italian pub . appearance : looking into the glass it had a deep reddish brown colored body with a creamy light tan head . the head was long lasting , thick and it left tons of sticky lacing to cling to the sides of the glass in thick rings . ( very impressive ) smell : the aroma hits first with a bit of boozy alcohol .  there was a very light mouthfeel , but an extremely dry , crisp finish .

smell - smells of soured cider . so far , both the appearance and smell remind me of damnation . slight hints of citrus , brett and funk are also noticeable . very funky and delicious .  bottled 10/31/11 a : pours jet black with a nice finger high layer of dark mocha head that laces the glass nicely .  m-medium carbonation . medium body , slick .

s : i was expecting a big nose on this but it actually had a relatively unpronounced aroma . essentially a soft malt aroma with some distinct raspberry and grape highlights . these characteristics strengthen as beer warms . t : tart and almost too sour raspberry flavor is prominent .  appearance : pours an off-white , two-finger head with good retention . even , abundant lace left on glass .  the mouthfeel is a little lacking in carbonation too .
smell - nuts , caramel , malt , some hops .  the body is as dark as night ; it is absolutely impervious to any light .  mouthfeel is okay , no carbonation to speak of .

s : nothing really distinct in the aroma . the alcohol definitely stands out and the smell reminds me of a good whiskey .  poured a translucent mustard/straw yellow with a huge , rocky , white head that faded into clumps of white froth . beautiful lacing .  mouth feel : a bit thin on the palet , or maybe the aroma and taste make you expect more in the way of mouth feel .

smell : light malt sweetness is so soft it is almost hard to detect .  a : very good looking brew - copper/red clear body with white head .  it must be said that this beer is a bit astringent on the palate and a bit thinner than i would have liked , but it is still rather drinkable .

this was by far , the worst `` beer '' i 've ever tasted . if this bottle was n't infected , and was supposed to taste like that , i 'm downright confused .  a : pours absolutely perfect ! cloudy , creamy orange body with a glorious mountain of head that fills just to the edge of the glass and hangs around until the glass is empty .  mouth feel is thin pretty characteristic of bbc 's beers which makes this a really drinkable session stout with a lot of flavor .

smell : the alcohol is very evident , a sweet syrupy smell and raisins are the only other aromas i pick out . taste : the flavor profile is dominated by raisins and syrup , with warming alcohol in the finish . overall : one dimensional , and cloyingly sweet .  appearance this beer is absolutely gorgeous . the body is a dark , orangish-brown and murky with lots of carbonation and had a bountiful , brownish-white head that was full without exploding and pitted well on top of the liquid leaving some awesome , shaving cream foam around the edges of my pint glass .  a rather thin aqueous body with less carbonation than expected , but otherwise nothing wrong with this brew .

the aroma is malty and sweet with a decent amount of spice and just a hint of hops . fairly malty and somewhat uneventful but still pleasant . very sweet with more malt and lots of spice and fruit : orange and cinnamon , nutmeg , cardamom .  a - black as night with a thick frothy brown head . fades slowly leaving a thin solid layer of foam on the beer with excellent lacing .  the mouth was a bit oily but not unpleasantly so .

i detect citrus and fruity aromas , but very faint .  the appearance was outsatnding ... a creamy head that lasts forever with a beautiful cascading efffect ... almost pitch black in appearance .  it is slightly watery on the palate .

s- perhaps it was my surroundings , but the aroma was very subtle . picked up a little roasted caramel mingled with unmistakably belgian sour yeast .  this one is jet black with an enormous off white / light tan head . this head is quite frothy and laces incredibly .  m : starts off creamy , but i 'm pretty quickly struck by how watery this is . the carbonation is decent , but i find this surprisingly thin .

s : mild malt aroma with a slight hop note in the end .  pours a completely opaque pitch black . light brown head with some big bubbles around the edges .  m : fairly thick , carbonation seems a tad high .

certainly has that belgain yeatiness to it as well as the smell of good old alcohol .  perfect head retention and plenty of lacing left behind in the glass .  mouthfeel is ok , but too watery and thin feeling for my tastes . drinkability is quite good , the only real flaw i found was the weak mouthfeel .

s : dried apple skins , a little banana and some bubble gum on the nose , although even as the beer warms it does not release much aroma . t : on the palate one finds freshly baked bread , some apple and pear , and a bit of spice . its flavor and aroma profile is on the milder side .  pours a deep , opaque mahogany , almost black . there 's a 3-finger cafe au lait head with a moderate amount of layered lacing .  mouthfeel : high carbonation gives the impression of a thinner mouthfeel , and the carbonic acid and alcohol bite knock this one down a little in the mouthfeel rating .
