i just had a hop devil and that leaves me with only one more hop devil and one troeg 's pale ale , so i decided to save those for another day and steal one of these from my sister . something sweet like candy with a touch of an adjunct ... corn maybe ? maybe a banana like runt t : pretty much follows the smell .  the white head is huge and pillowy and leaves wonderful fuzzy navel lacing .  a-garnet with small ring of foam s-raisin , pancake syrup , faint vinager t-assertive sour front , sour cherry , some malt sweetness , dates m-medium , with average carbonation d-very tasty !
aroma was a pleasant roasted malt , but nothing stands out .  it pours a dark brown to almos black color with a huge fluffy tan to light brown head .  under carbonated .

the aroma is slight clove , some bubblegum , but that 's about it . taste is rounded and smooth , with the clovey and bubblegum from the aroma , but also with alcohol warming and candy sugar flavors . medium bodied and drinkable , it 's good but not really a first class beer , and not worth $ 6.29 a bottle ( 22oz , john 's marketplace , portland or ) .  pours vibrant pale gold with lively streams of carbonation sustaining an impressive large white head and leaivng lovely lacing .  not too many micro 's that come out with a light ale . hats off to them for bringing this to market to allow folks who are used to drinking american mass producted swill to move into a easy drinking michigan micro brew . lighter than sam adams but more flavor then the bud and miller 's of the world .

the aroma is sweet grain and yeast . it 's not a strong smelling beer by any stretch . i really had to get my nose in there to pick up any aroma . the flavor is delicious .  the pour is beautiful . intense rich brown/black , with a two finger dark brown head .  the beer really lacks in body . carbonation is great . overall this was a good beer but the body creates a void .

the smell is a little off putting , but once you take the first sip it is very easy to get over the smell .  pours deep red , with some f*ing amazing head on it .  taste/mouthfeel : this beer is slightly oily , with a very limited carbonation .

had an imperial pint at mac 's taproom , slighshot is a clear pale copper with a small off-white head that leaves moderate lace . smell is very muted , especially when first served a bit to cold , sweet soft cereals and grassy hops .  enough of the stupid remark , bust out the old guardian glass and opener and get on to the beer : it 's magnificent looking ; a darker shade of gold , tiny bubbles that are clearly visible from a few feet away , a thick creamy top that seems to last forever .  the mouthfeel is thiner but still good .

esbs are not stop traffic hot chicks , but they are the type of chick that can give good head ... so this is on par . nose ... surprisingly musty , tones of malt and caramel are lurking around the back of the joint but are n't quite in the door , nothing offensive , nothing aggressive ... not much to quaff here taste etc ... tastes a bit like the smell except the aftertaste really develops nicely , up front it is slightly bitter with that musty flavor that leeches into the fluggel type flavor and rounds out with a mild cascade floral/p [ ne hop character . this is perfect at cellar temp ... nothing too complex here but man this beer just is a pleasure to drink .  pours a coal black beer with a good reddish brown head .  a wonderful beer . one i have had before , and thought it would be great for the new year . it 's dark brown hue and brownish colored head was delightful . the taste of cocoa and hops pleased my nose . the roasted flavors were soothing , but left a little bit of an after taste .

edit & lt ; this is actually a review for `` guinness extra cold , '' ( that 's right - they were actually bragging about how cold a stout was ) which was damn near ubiquitous in otherwise decent pubs throughout the uk when i was there in the summer of 2001 . guinness extra cold is basically the same as what one often gets when having a guinness in an american bar . oddly enough , when i was in england two years ago this was the only kind of guinness i found in the pubs i ventured into .  ths one poured a dream , you shoulda seen it , looked like a photo from a beer book . billowy head sticking out of the glass all proud and boastful , very cool .  light copper color with a large head s. malty with a slight resiny hop smell t. more bitter than sweet but well balanced with roasted malt m. a little to acidic and carbonated for my tastes d. a good lighter amber ale that i can heartily recommend

pours a hazy straw yellow with a healthy tan head . smell of grass , pilsen malt , sweetness and hay . there seems to be more flavor and it is extremely smooth with very few flaws . very drinkable ; even sessionable at this high abv .  best before 26.09.05 appearance : awesome . poured with a nice long lasting beige head .  mouthfeel is very dry with almost no carbonation .

it does n't really have any overpowering aromas . both the hops and malt are pretty subtle . it 's very drinkable , especially for a pale .  poured a deep , uber cloudy orangish color with good carbonation leaving a nice white cap s : loads of faded hops , fruits..apricot and others with booze t : big faded hops powered by fruitiness and booze .  cake/nutty malt up front with a huge , thick spiced tea hop flavor headbutt with the swallow . not just season 's best , but saranac 's best . i usually find them to be just an average brewery but this stuff is nice .

smell : yeasty wheat , dry and straightforward , expect for a slight strofoamish hint in the background .  appearance : the brown head that just will not die . halfway through the glass i 'm still looking at a thick 1/4 ince layer of foam . there 's dried up , sticky lacing all over the glass , too . a perfectly dark taste for a dark brew .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .

s : ho-hum aroma , even as it nears room temperature . ends flowery and just a little soapy . ) compared to the bracingly hoppy ipas 'round these parts , but i do n't mind .  a- pours a brownish color with red hues noted against a white background . the clear nature of the beer allows me to see the carbonation , which is modest looking at best . the head is plentiful and puffy looking , retaining well and leaving behind a thick film of dense foam on the glass .  m- smooth , but a tad thin . carbonation is good , as is the thoroughly smooth finish with a tad of warmth .

s : as much as i let this warm , the nose really never developed whatsoever . am a bit disappointed ... t : oh wow ; whatever the lack of aroma hid is more than made up for with taste . dirty earthiness adds to the fudge , a gritty/grainy sweetness , accentuated by malted milk balls .  pours a viscous black and creates a textbook appearance for the style .  m - a little thinner than i imagined , though based on the aroma , i might have been expecting a double ipa .

the aroma has some piney hops and faint tropical notes , but it 's not too convincing .  ahh , maudite . a beautiful beer from a beautiful brewery . pours a dark , stained oak or cherry colour . nice , 2 1/2 finger froth head that clings to the glass .  incredibly light with cereal grains , very grainy taste , hops are nowhere in site . there are way better summer beers out there .

dont really pick up much of an aroma , some malts , some hops , but not much really . great balanced taste of malts and hops .  reviewed 1/8/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a golden somewhat cloudy yellowish color . big foamy frothy white head with good lacing .  i always look forward like most do the annual stone anniversary brews.poured a rich deep amber with a tight and sticky one finger off white head , big hops in the nose with a mix pine and herbal/leaf , there is a gummy , fruity-like sweet note as well.the mouthfeel is a bit sharp i will say it crashes down the gullett at first , it does begin to smooth out after a few sips but still seems a bit harsh.no holds barred hops hit the palate up front with big pine and big herbalness , a healthy does of sweeter alcohol gives a slight burn along with a bit of dark fruit.very good but seems like it something that should sit for awhile , still another fine one from stone .

s - aroma is mainly bitter chocolate and a hint of brown sugar along with just a hint of hops .  a massive , three-inch head rose up to the top of the tulip glass . lacework aplenty . a real beauty .  mouthfeel is way more thin than the head and lacing made me think it would be . very quaffable .

was presented in the proper bitburger glass with the full head expected on a german pilsner . the smell has a uniqque sweetness .  poured out of a 16.9 oz bottle into a tulip style glass . i held it up to the sun on my patio and admired it for a few seconds . ( cue music ) there were two inches of white head that led to a nice white cap that never dissipated .  just some `` laying down '' advice : had the extreme plesure of six-year bottle conditioning tasteing , in which years 4-5 were exceptionally good . year 3 was quite good , with anything under that seemingly `` young '' tasting . after year 5 the qualities that make it a stellar barley wine were fading .
aroma - limited nose , a fairly standard pilsener aroma .  it poured with a big , long lasting , and super stiff foamy cap .  mouthfeel is soft and a little heavy .

this pils pours a very pale golden color with white head . nose is clean with some herbal hops in there . palate offers a nice dose of flavor though with herbal hops that bitter it up nicely , balanced with a gentle malt sweetness .  pours a dark reddish brown with a huge off white head with huge fat lacing .  perhaps another way to explain the feeling would be a textured shandy . noting the high praise this saison received , i have trouble fathoming such a bad experience .

a- golden nearly opaque with a small white head s- light wheat and a little citrus . not a whole lot of fragrance going on here t- nice balance between the hops and malt . not sickening , just certainly present d- love it and i drink it quite often !  sticky lacing all the way up the glass , and infinite retention on the eventually short head .  4/5 m : surprisingly thin side of medium , slightly tongue numbing , spritzy .

as far as smell goes , uh ... .there was n't much to mention . i could smell some hop fragrance but it really did n't stand out as exceptional to me .  a- glourious golden yellow with a fluffy and foamy white head that retains well in the tulip glass . dies to a fluffy ring and nice cloud that leaves thick lace all along the glass .  nice carbonation , but this comes off as a little thin . this should be more drinkable considering its thin body , but as this is a stout , the thin body is a bit of a turn off .

s : musky and earth aromas . burnt cherry and very malty . farly nondescript as far as i am concerned . i did not know what to expect , but this is an exceptional beer . though , to fully appreciate this , i need to be more familiar with the style .  really beautiful beer , pours a hazy golden color with a huge frothy white head that retains impressively and leaves nice lacing .  m : the thinnest , lightest imperial i can remember , but the intensity doesnt have to be overpowering .

not a big nose on it , but the taste is quite good . i get an almost nutty , roasted , and woodiness to it too .  it pours a decently frothy tan colored head .  flavour is better than expected- a little woody and slightly spicy , with a thick strong maltiness . i 'd like the hearty body on this one , were it not for the turbocharged carbonation .

the dortmunder style is one of my favorites , easy going , not an everyday ( though it could be ) and thisone is done well . a frothy , pillow-like white head that stuck around and laced oh so well . the aroma was not overpowering , maybe alittle grass-like . this homebrew could be a great macro `` try-this '' offering great job , great beer !  this is the dead-on look for a pilsner ; pale straw color with steady streams of bubbles heading for the surface . the head is huge and sticky and clings to the side of the glass as if it were a life-or-death matter .  do n't brewers taste the beers they brew after they 're done ? how many sips does it take to get stone juxtaposition to the center of my sink drain ? i think this beer is really spent burnt coffee grounds blended with colgate toothpaste in a bottle .

hazy and color brings to mind pineapple juice . carbonation factor is high.get some funk in the aroma , not overpowering .  a : pitch black , slightly viscous . excellent head formation and nice lacing . this is how an ais should look in the glass .  a touch lightly bodied , with an oily , but thinnish and passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

the nose is surprisingly mild , with just a hint of mild flowery hops .  poured out of the bottle into my samuel smith 's pint glass a jet black in color with a nice 2 finger tannish-brown head that settled to about one finger after a few minutes .  thanks walter a-a nice rich amber , good head , some lacing that turned into a small bubble ring s-a slight bready smell , some citrus ( makes me think of citra hop ) slight sweetness and then tart t- close to the same as the smell , there is a slight tangyness in the middle of the drink , it 's a good thing m- it 's moderately lively not as much bite and tingle i was expecting , a clean wet finish o/d- overall i really like this , it 's not the craziest ipa but it 's more than just decent , drinkability , i can see myself finishing this growler , this is a tasty beer and one i really like

s : a very light scent in general but the coriander spice fragrance comes out with a slight clove banana type aroma . t : has a truly unique flavor .  pours a cloudy amber brown into a wine glass with two fingers worth of frothy , white head . the lacing clings to the inside of the glass for dear life , and is quite exquisite .  an american classic . good fall back beer , or one to enjoy when a less complex brew is desired .

i 'm usually not much of a pale ale fan , but this was pretty good .  poured into a pint glass , this turned out to be a really beautiful beer . it was an amber color with a thick off-white head that persisted throughout the time it took me to drink the beer . there was an amazing amount of lacing .  the carbonation and the color were good , but this did n't make up for the off taste and smell .

roasted aroma of chocolate , sweet coffee and a slight cinnamon bun finish . oxidation . whoa !  $ 5.00 / 750ml bottle county market grocery store stevens point , wisconsin appearance - a haze of golden yellow to a pale orange with a lasting frothy white head . very much carbonated as a constant flow of tiny bubbles speed to the top if the beer from the side and bottom of the pint glass .  the mouthfeel is light , but hey , its a light beer ! for drinkability , again , one of the beers that could probably never offend me .

s : not a big smell . yeasty . overall : the smell does n't set you up propery for how the taste hits you in the mouth .  a - pours black with a nice light-tan head . looks great . sticks fairly well to the side , just about as good as a porter could .  remarkably good . but pay attention : almost 10 % alcohol , but you hardly remark it . it does not have that much body , but it surely has a delicate taste . i 'm a bit more inclined for brown beers , but this one is really good , and not brown at all .

though , if i had to guess , i would not have picked this out to be a saison . smells of bready malts , with some 'sharp ' somewhat earthy notes , - hard to describe .  pours with a vast amount of co2 . produces a beautiful light tan head that sticks around forever . the body is dark amner in color .  lowish carbonation and a light , smooth mouthfeel .

smell mildly sweet with a slight hop skunkness .  a : pours a vigorous 4 finger creamy white head with excellent retention . lacing is amazing considering the light body , with layers clinging to the side of the glass like a ruler .  m : very carbonated .

i remember when i reviewed jw dundee 's pale ale as pretty decent too . very lively . smelled like malt , there was n't much else . it 's more of a craft lager , which makes genesee go up on my scale even more .  excited to try this one ... a : looks perfect . deep murky copper color with a thick 1 inch white head that fades decently .  smooth mouthfeel with a moderate amount of carbonation and just a little watery in the finish .

aroma is soft , but of coarse hops , but for the most part rather clean . medium in body , and smooth .  the imperial stout was very black in color with a dark brown head . very pretty .  it is a little light in body but i 've noticed that porters and stouts are generally lighter from a can .

poured a nice caramel reddish hue with a light white/grey head with miniscule bubbles around the edge and on the head smells like dough and sweet malt tasted very similar to aroma , sweet malt , doughy yeast and a very faint fruit hop flavor .  appearance- pours a crystal clear brownish red , almost cognac , with four fingers of beautifully structured soapy bubbles . the head peaks well above the rim of my glass , and compacts to a creamy , hefeweizen-like consistency . outstanding lacing leaves sheets behind . excellent .  had this on tap when i was being introduced to the lager style of beer . it 's smell is very specific to the beer and is appealing if you are craving a medium-bodied lager . its has a malty intake and a bit of a spicy , hoppy after taste . it goes down smoothly but the taste tends to stick around and interfere with ordered food . it is very drinkable but as stated , but be careful when drinking this with food .

sidenote : waitress tells me this name of this beer was chosen because a song by the same name was being played while it was brewed . aroma is toasted malt and caramel .  very pretty two-finger head .  mouthfeel : heavy , chewy , slick , low carbonation borders on flat .
smell was at first scent , that of a macro lager . not a whole lot in the smell department.. taste was pretty complex , yet smooth .  i 'm very impressed with this beers look .  heavy mouthfeel .

the nose was lightly malty with a slight fruitiness accompanying the sweetness . the finish was bittersweet and extremely pleasant .  dark mahogany color with a 1 finger , light tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  taste some roasted chocolate flavors . flavor lingers on the tongue after each sip . not quite what i would consider a savoring beer , but tasty none the less . i could drink this beer around the fire in the winter or after raking leaves in the fall .

pulled it from the cooler in a bottle at around 8pm and took a sip , whatever kind of sweet , watery whatever , but it down and played a pick up game of football for around fifteen minutes . when i returned to my beer it didn`t even taste the same , when this beer gets a chance to warm up a bit its flavor really shines through , it tasted so smooth , like a golden apple dunked in orange juice , with toher very warming herbs , a great brew to transition into autumn brews .  a : orange colour and a huge 4 cm head that sticks around due to the high carbonation .  feel is a bit coarse , but just a bit .

smells of burnt toast , nuts and vodka . fortunately the taste is so very much more than the smell .  this is a great looking beer , more black than brown and , when held up to the light , a beautiful red highlight appears .  nice aroma of hops but i would hope for a bit more being a hops lover . the celebration ale , from the same company , seems to hit the spot more than this beer but still worthy of a place in the fridge and still better than many micro beer ipa ii . sierra nevada seems to me to be the only mass beer company that brews excellent beer for `` mass beer '' prices .

to be honest , the aroma is the worst part of this beer , because i love the taste .  pours a pitch black color with a two-finger head that fades down to some lacing . good color for the style .  carbonation is fizzy on the tongue where it should be soft and creamy .

smell : very faint nose until it gets warm .  this beer was poured a very dark rich chocolate brown with a thin tan head . with this beer being pushed nitrogen , it had a ton of lacing and the head lasted the entire beer .  mouthfeel was somewhat on the thin side , but still quite acceptable .

one of the finest smelling beers i 've ever come across . very inviting . tasted much along the lines as the aroma , with the hops perhaps just a bit more apparent . quite pleasing . mouthfeel was good , with a medium body which went down nicely .  excessive packaging ... appearance : pours a thick , gloupy black and then cascades out an amazing amount of dark tan head that haves great retention and is very creamy looking .  finishes dry with nice mocha notes & a touch of charred grain mf : very oily & smooth as all hell with low carbonation & nice stickyness .

incredibly fresh hop aroma . absolutely unbelievable . must try these galaxy hops for my homebrew soon .  deep mahogany in colour , crystal clear when held up to the light . the head poured thick & white then retreated to a light surface covering , still maintaining the lace on the glass .  the silky smooth mouthfeel was fantastic and carbonation was spot on .

2010 bottle had a ton of suspended sediment in a burnt orange body . wow , aroma is the big winner here . pumpkin pie with crust as it warms ; some clove came thru as well , and even somewhat herbal . pretty authentic pumpkin flavor - vegetable/squash quality , and good amount of spices , incl cinnamon , nutmeg , and clove - but not overpowering . decent volume of malty sweetness / richness ... touch of campfire as it warms . outstanding drinkability - this is the most aromatic and flavorful pumpkin ale you can buy at this level of abv .  a= pours a beautiful dark brown almost black color with a great two finger perfectly toasty looking head on it that holds awesome retention and wonderful lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel : amazing . creamy and smooth , thick .

full and rich , with dried fruits overtaking the nose . lots of vanilla in here , as well as some caramel and licorice . t : quite a lot going on in this brew . nothing too special here . d : so scarily drinkable . at 11.5 % , i feel that i could sip this all night .  ) aug. 15 2008 @ hop cat ba / brewery grand opening event , served in tulip glass . opaque black , creamy tan head , beautiful bubble suspension after pour , wow ! looks thick smells of roasty heavy malts , dark fruit , smooth and creamy , mmm taste is of thick heavy bitter chocolate , hot alcohol , rich and smooth , compared to keg this is way mellowed , not as harsh and easier to drink , amazing ! , raisins , chocolate , slight coffee , earthy peat , mm mouthfeel is oily slick , smooth , creamy , viscous , a sipper for sure - delicious !  a - opaque for sure ; not quite black , but very dark brown ; 1/2 '' tan/light brown , creamy head that diminishes to a thin layer pretty quickly ; lacing here and there , around the glass s - very nice aroma going on here ; notes of roasty malts , dark chocolate , hints of milky sweetness , and nice qualities of gingerbread too t - dark chocolate , vanilla , cinnamon , and ginger come first ; milky sweetness lasts from start to finish that is reminiscent of espresso ; slight bitter finish with roasted coffee beans and ginger as well m - medium to full bodied ; slight dry finish ; some carbonation that feels nice on the tongue ; can feel some warmth from the 9.2 % abv ; texture is very milky , creamy , velvety smooth o - i just ca n't get over how exceptionally smooth this beer really is .

this smells just terrific . the flavors on the palate generallyh replicate the nose , except they 're not as intense and the brown sugar and chocolate seem to dominate the flavor profile .  a : jet black with a nice dark mocha head that sits just barely above the beer . perfect for the style s : has a very nice mellow scotch smell that is not too harsh along side a slight sweetness of vanilla and honey .  m - they got the `` rick creamy '' part right in the description . the beer has moderate carbonation and has a nice creamy feel to it . it 's incredibly creamy and smooth and fits the style well .

s : smell on this beer is amazing . i gave this beer a 5 . the beer smells like a cream stuffed pumpkin . d : drinkable for the style but still 1 bomb is good for me .  the appearance is red brick with a light tan head and supreme lacing .  m - the mouthfeel is fantastic . creamy , smooth and light with a perfect amount of carbonation .

smell is hops - straight , beautiful hop smell . seriously , smells awesome . okay , taste is lagging behind a ways .  a : black it is ! with a thick brown head .  m : really a standout porter . carbonation is perfectly dialed in and gives a very subtle tingle on the tongue .

s - awesome on my nose well hopped .  appearance- beer pours clear and golden with a half finger of creamy white head with ample lacing on the sides of the glass . carbonation rises from the bottom of the glass as if this were a pilsner . very nice on looks at least .  m : great , chewy and resiny , full-bodied and robust , with a smooth finish , compared to the rest of the sip , just what i 'm looking for in a double ipa .

it pours like a big , english old ale . smell- fat and sweet , it 's a beautiful display of wood and chocolate covered cherries ... but more like the liquid that surrounds the cherries . notes of old leatherbound library books and rum soaked dark fruits abound .  huge bubbly head .  the mouthfeel on this ale was great , and i think the mouthfeel of just about any beer is enhanced by cask conditioning . it had a nice thick feel on the tongue .

just great . t : similar to the smell but with bit of smokiness .  for me , the appearance of a well poured guinness is stellar . the deep rich near-black mahogany tint of it , while the flow of bubbles seems to defy physics is near magical . always great poured over a bent spoon atop bass pale ale or harp lager as well !  mouthfeel : full bodied , chewy , carbonation is spot on .

very nice and original beer - more body would have been better but still a great treat from a great brewery .  dark brown with hints of red , and a solid beige head .  it has a wonderfully creamy mouthfeel that makes each sip a pleasure .

no head retention or lacing huge oaky , fruitty boozey nose , beautiful t : dryness , raisins , dates , & breadyness with a slight booze presence up front .  a beautiful dense white head lasts for a while and laces all the way down the glass . the color is a unique peachy-orange that is slightly opaque , and catches the light wonderfully .  the texture is likewise decadent , being somehow both silky and creamy .

s - wow , what a blast of aromas : floral notes , pine and citrus smack you in the face . t - it tasted of spicy , piney hops with a sweet , burnt toast maltiness . it is extremely hoppy and fairly easy drinking considering the high abv .  on tap at iron hill north wales , pa . served in a pint glass ... a - jet black with a 1 finger mocha head brought out to me . the head was unbelievably thick with amazing lacing that coated the entire glass .  fairly light in body for such a big beer , drinkability is good . the mouthfeel was amazing thanks to the silky , rocky head which remained throughout the entire glass .

coffee and lemon aromas , very rich and inviting . thick , thick , thick mouthfeel ... molasses , some coffee , and a dense and vaguely cherry flavor . bitter as all get out .  a : deep copper with a light tan head , excellent retention & lacing .  bordering on chewy as you work toward swallowing . carbonation was excellent on tap , just enough to contribute to a dry and clean finish despite the initial sweetness of the beer .

smells like halloween ! very welcoming . it sure is an imperial . very crisp , sexy beer . spices are rounded , clove , cinnamon , vanilla bean , and most importantly , fresh pumpkin .  lovely auburn red color blows me away .  huge bodied and full ( again , suggesting iipa classification ) . this is a beauty on cask .

s- awesome char smell with chocolate and roasted coffee , and supported by a rich dark fruit sweetness . hoppy bitterness is a fantastic undertone . m- nice smooth mouthfeel .  a : poured with a large , white fluffy head that was very long lasting ... never got below 1-2 fingers size . body is a beautiful , dark orange color , with excellent clarity .  m : so good i ca n't get enough . nice thickness with light carbonation and a good oily texture make this a delightful treat for my mouth .

has a solid malt flavor with a huge hop aroma . i could use a tad more bitterness but that is just a personal preference .  a : a stunning deep brown near black with cranberry highlights . a inch of toasted head comes after a medium pour . the head slowly fades to an impressive 1/3 inch . lacing on a dark beer ?  has that totally coating feel like a warm thick cask draught , just almost oily in its feel and velvety ( aside from the alcohol ) . really like this about this beer .

this beer smells incredible . a strong aroma of hops and malts immediately made itself known as soon as the bottle was cracked . excellent lacing .  its dark amber color and white head give way to perfect lacing as i drink down this wonderful libation .  perfect mouthfeel for a beer of this kind with controlled carbonation and appropriate body .

nose is amazing ! huge assertive orange spice . the single most assertive bold orange spice nose i may ever have smelled . beautiful . mouthfeel is rich and lightly creamy with nice carbonation and a nice texture and feel . flavors are just plain weird . there is an herb quality and character to this beer , initially stange and offensive that become very appealing . i suspect that one will love or hate this one ; and , it deserves a taste ; it 's unique .  pours a thick , dense black with not so much as brown on the edges and a deep , thick tan head that rises above the lip of my snifter . this is as good of looking a stout as you will ever see . the head slowly recedes into a nice cream capping the beer leaving some nice lacing .  first sip is velvety smooth textured average body with minimal carbonation .

smell has a great malty dark fig aroma . very warm smell . taste is also very malty .  on a fairly gentle pour into a pint glass this pours with a huge ( 2/3 of the glass ) of white billowy slightly tan head .  and even so , it is still incredibly smooth , and the alcohol flavor can not be detected . the body is huge . one of the thickest beers i 've had the pleasure of eating . very good stuff .

smells of strong peat , as you 'd expect with the name `` islay '' , but there is nice chocolate and roast balance . sweet flavour actually . very creamy mouthfeel , very sweet .  a careful pour produces a robust , sandy colored , three-finger head with excellent retention and lacing .  m - this is one of my favorite parts so far about this brew . moderate amounts of carbonation that whirls around your tounge and warms it in the process .

smell : ridiculously aromatic , spicy/floral hops , as well a very fruity malt profile ( plums , berries , peaches ) .  amazing lacing & head retention , really pretty to look at s : hints of choclate & some roasted malt as it warms t : rich choclate up front , then a little grainyness & some bitter choclate .  m : medium viscosity , very smooth and creamy on the palate , with low carbonation .

a : pours a pale yellowish amber color with frothy white head and lots of lacing on the glass s : smells like major hops , citrus , grapefruit , some pine ... the usual great dipa scents t : tastes just like the smell , but the hops are less prevalent that i expected .  you get the beautiful nitrogen show and then it settles with a dark brown , almost black , body with a nice light tan head .  mouthfeel is full bodied and smooth that feels pretty creamy on the tongue .

brewery states they did pick up some brett recently , popped the cork off ... corked talked about brett to me , more fruit than funk . hops stay modest . mild tartness , infancy of the brett ? it does have a ghost-like funk within . sweet roasted finish , pretty much burnt sugar . not a hair short of being great , the brewery admits to some funk ... wish i had another bottle to see where it goes .  the appearance was amazing ! starts out pale in color and gradually becomes oranger in a way that i have never seen in a beer .  m/d - the mouthfeel and drinkability are exceptional . this is a simple brown ale that i could knock back one after the other .

the aroma of this beer was the highlight for me : banana , apple , belgian yeastiness , other fruits ... really great . golden yellow in color with a small ring of head at the top after it settles . alcohol comes through very nicely . sweet aftertaste is enjoyable .  pours a very inky black with a dark brown creamy head . very oily and sudsy , looks great .  m - thick , very smooth and very viscous with little carbonation .

do n't be turned off by the little green specks floating around as they are chucks of hops leftover from fermentation and help accentuate the huge hoppy aromas . pours a nice creamy golden color with slight greenish hue to foamy head . aromas of malts and hops give way to dried fruit .  enjoyed in a pint glass a : moderate pour yields 1 finger of thick dark brown head that sticks around .  mouthfeel . amazing , thick rich and seems sweet but comes together .

the smell is exactly like a cafe mocha -- dark chocolate , buttery , and quality roasted coffee . the taste is very intense on the chocolate but the roasted coffee malts come through nicely too .  this is a delicious looking beer ! dark with a creamy , full head .  starts with roasted coffee flavor , mouthfeel is incredible smooth .

: ( looks and smells awesome . dark chocolate color with a small tan head that does n't stick around for too long . this smelled of chocolate before i even managed to get my nose near the glass . smells like hershey 's . i really really wanted to like this beer , but it was tough to get through the bottle and i was sharing it . if only it tasted like it smelled , this would have been great .  solid finger of brown , almost black head . incredibly dark body with nice lace . darkest head i 've seen .  taste- wonderfully intense malt , and a big bready character that thankfully outweighs any unpleasant sweetness that the malts could impart . fantastically effervescent , it rides into the mouth and over the tongue with confident grace ... all the while alive and outspoken .

pours dark orangey brown , slightly hazy at first , then extremely cloudy as i pour in some of the yeast dregs . the aroma is huge - sweet brown sugar and honey with floral notes , alcohol and some breadiness . flavors are very aggressive in this fresh form - a huge honey presence meets with the aggressive bittering hops and some dark fruit sherry notes . excellent barley wine , both in its fresh and aged form - a testament to the value of bottle conditioning and cellarable beers .  '01-'02 : starts by pouring a jet black , your unable to see through it , with a nice dark tan head that settles with deep fluffy pockets .  perfect silky creamy carbonation .

this beer gives you a great looking glass ... smell- ... and a great smell ! incredible smell , might be the best smelling ipa i 've had so far . really nice batch . smells like a field of flowers and with its distinct flowery smell that might remind some of opening a pot of honey .  pours a pitch black dark into snifter glass with a rich , creamy head that lasts a great deal of time and a heavy lace remains . probably the darkest looking beer you will find and a wonderful head .  mouthfeel is very good , a light bodied beer with excellent carbonation ; it dances on the tongue and finishes smooth .

smell : wonderful aromas on this beer .  the retention was downright insane and it essentially sat there like whipped cream . beautiful looking beer .  good and special beer , cloudy , double fermentation , yeast , hops , malt and wheat are present in smell ; taste fruity , and floral like grassy and herbs ; good for mexican haute cuisine , try with pasta and salads ; mouthfeel exceptional , well balanced and litlle strong for the palate ; 96 % recommended .

many `` damn '' s and `` holy s*** '' s could be heard as we sniffed the mercifully small portions in our tasting glasses . tons of whiskey , vanilla , burnt caramel , butterscotch . taste features big woody vanilla along with chocolate , caramel , coffee , and big booze ( how could it not ) . lot of whiskey . some sweetness , but really nowhere near as sweet as i thought it might be . feel is thick and syrupy , but look at what you 're drinking - this is one of those beers you could probably pour over your pancakes .  a- damn sexy looking in my pilsner glass . it sits atop a slightly hazed , deep red almost apple cider colored body .  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . exceptional in this category . appearance and mouthfeel are certainly worth noting .

glassware : tall 14.4 oz glass ( i love pouring it to the halfway point , let it sit and agitate it by swirling it aggressively just like scotch whisky ) appearance : amber brown hue on the pour , with a reddish head nose : i loved every moment of this brew , i sat for at least 2 hours sniffing on this puppy ( if only these guys aged their ale in pappy van winkle 's bourbon barrels , i can only dream ) palate : loving the booziness of it , sweet caramel , vanilla oak and maraschino cherries . all in all , a decent coating with a medium to long finish . pairings : a relatively inexpensive bahia blu robusto went very well with this drink , the hearty cedar core blends well with the sweet caramel and vanilla oak .  classic stout appearance -- black body with a thick creamy dark-tan head .  m- awesome thick mouthfeel on this seasonal .

lovely , bright cherry red color ... head is large at first , simmers down quickly ... aroma : mmmmm ... .complex ! quite a rich and invigorating aroma , i postpone consumption to prolong my time drinking it deep into the nose ... really nice !  pours a bright hazy copper chestnut color with a medium creamy off white head that retains fairly well and laces the glass .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel . very smooth , lightly carbonated .

probably the best smelling brown ale i 've experienced yet . t- almost porter-like at first , with up-front dark malt , lots of nuttiness , a bit of dark roasted grain , and a slightly metallic finish .  poured a dark hazy brown , tan head , with good retention .  aroma : not overpowering , but hints of citrus-y hops well balanced with malt mouthfeel : medium-bodied with a nice oily coating of the mouth . very smooth with just the right carbonation .
great smell good apperance .  in a tulip the beer was near black in color with a light brown head . the head lingered well , and left abundant lace .  perfect carbonation to it .

( s ) - very aromatic . very dynamic & layered . again , a good taste that followed suit to the smell . great aroma . lends itself more to a better drinkability score due to a lower abv than alot of strong ales out there ; thicker than most too , but it fits it well . this might benefit from further aging , but its great now .  pours a beautiful slightly hazy amber color with a large two inch off white head . excellent retention and some great lacing .  mouthfeel is damn near perfect for an o'fest , i think . impeccable balance .

smell : very sweet . some booze cuts through the richness . incredibly decadent . taste : one of those beers where you say `` wow , '' after the first sip .  pours a very deep brown from a 550ml bottle with a two finger head that retains . it 's opaque and pushes pitch black .  great mouthfeel .

one of the best smelling beers i 've tried .  this beer pours beautifully , glowing , hazed apricot amber in color with 3 fingers of fluffy froth topped by rocky peaks . retention is epic and lace coats my maredsous goblet .  m - full body , viscous and chewy with low , delicate carbonation , very smooth across the palate with some heat from the alcohol/bourbon content .

this beer smells amazing . t : very roasty , lots of coffee , lots of chocolate , some sweetness in the background .  the colour is pitch-black ; the two finger head is pale beige , airy and uneven . massive amounts of lacing .  m : very soft carbonation and easy on the palate as a good session beer should be .

aroma of roast , ash , chocolate , dried fruits , vanilla , bourbon , caramel malts , and alcohol . taste of dark fruit , some tropical , sticky molasses , roasted malts , vanilla , and bourbon - alcohol .  nice tight eggshell head . nearly brilliantly clear .  f : wonderfully thick .

s : wow , this beer smells amazing . whiskey and bourbon dominate the nose . i could literally sit here and smell this beer for the 15 minutes and be perfectly happy .  i love the look of this in the glass , nice pale yellow color , frothy white head . it looks like it was dry hopped to me .  m : super creamy as it should be .

aroma : an amazing , complex aroma which far exceeds any other pils aroma i have smelled . lemony , peppery , summery , yeasty and malty all zipping around my nose . taste : does n't live up to the aroma but is n't bad .  great looking beer !  the mouthfeel is dry with a long and deep finish which is full of blackened malt and char . very very nice .

absolutely fantastic aroma . t & m : sweet chocolate , citrus hops , and toasted black malt all make their appearance .  the pour was very good and this is easily one of the best looking beers i have ever seen with its excelent head , color and champagne like bubbles .  excellent ! incredible smooth and silky mouthfeel .

smell is pure oranges and very faint hops but the smell is amazing . taste did n't lead up to the smell kind of a big build up and then aahh .  bottled in feb. 2009 , batch # 9 ... appearance : pours a very pretty deep orange , copper ; very clear with tiny bubbles and a huge sticky white head . this is a great looking beer !  m : full-bodied , a very firm and brilliantly sructured beer .

s : smell is the best part of this beer in my opinion . strong scent of hops . reminds me of some other good intoxicating herbs . i really love this hoppy goodness !  a - brilliant copper color with a finger of thick solid off white head .  mouthfeel & gt ; exciting ... not too bubbly . full score .

gives a snootful of dark chocolate and sweet dark molasses from 6 inches away , truly intense aroma . flavor is gently dominated by the chocolate , leans a little toward chocolate flavor extract , but nothing definitive .  this beer is absolutely stunning in appearance .  m : perfect carbonation amount .

cranberry nose with traces of brett-like peppery suede funkiness ( either from the kombucha or actual brett ) , black cherry , dried peaches , honey , and cider . it 's one of the most distinct and delicious smelling beers i 've come across in a while . it 's clever enough to inspire analysis , while still being relatively drinkable , in spite of the co2 struggles .  pours jet black with thick mocha head .  it 's thick , creamy , rich , and robust .

the first impression i got when i took a long deep breathe in the the glass was sweet malt and chocolate , oh my god , chocolate ! it seems as though i was sniffing a fresh glass of dark chocolate milk . it just smells creamy and smooth . the taste was roasted malt and grains combined with the chocolate .  a : this dark lager poured a beautiful clear amber color that showed off a ton of carbonation . i was extremely impressed by the appearance of this beer .  the mouthfeel , though , was the best part . it fills your mouth with mousse like consistency with very round edges .

decent lacing left behind . s - wow , great aroma here . immediately there is a lot of pineapple and coconut aroma making it clear that this has been barrel aged . lots of stuff going on here .  a : absolutely beautiful looking brew .  the mouth feel is perfect - not watery , not syrupy , well carbonated , and very refreshing .

i stick my nose to the glass to get a better whiff of the hoppy goodness and i sneezed 3x . this is all about the hops . as the aroma foretold , this beer is all about the hops . the beer is drinkable now , but it is a big beer and pretty green .  looks the part . `` glugged '' into my tulip glass and created a nice tight brown head that leaves lots of lace as i drink .  mouthfeel is full bodied and super smooth . very enjoyable .

s - easily the beer 's most remarkable feature . wonderful aroma of blackberries and blueberries with a slightly sourish tint . t - although it does n't quite live up to the aroma in terms of complexity , this is still quite good . early palate some sour dark fruits are balanced out by a moderate caramel flavor .  a : the pour is deep deep burgundy with a really large thick creamy off-white head . the slow dissipation leaves lacings galore .  you can feel how well-crafted this beer is : perfect body ... thin , but not too thin ; carbonated , but not overdone ; hoppy aftertaste , but not a tastebud destroyer .

s - huge chocolate nose akin to hershey 's chocolate syrup or even a tootsie roll . the aroma is simply amazing . very solid chocolate stout with an 11 % abv that hides behind a wall of bittersweet chocolate goodness .  gorgeous , classy looking beer .  extreme balance and smoothness in this beer , its quite good . big full body with a champaign like fizzyness . im impressed .

smell is downright incredible , with lots of oily hops , citrus , and a complexity i ca n't describe .  highly envigorated light brown head of fine bubbles that left behind a nice lacing on the pour .  m- great mouthfeel .

a great aroma greets the nose , with soft cherry fruits and lots of toffee sweetness . a hint of floral & piny hops lingers in the background -- -very barleywine-line , which i enjoy . the flavor has the typical wee heavy malt profile boosted by a vinous barrel note . overall , a great special release from real ale , and probably one of their best beers i 've had to date .  from the nitro-can , started as a full glass of thick , creamy foam . slowly the foam turned over from bottom to top revealing a deep yellow beer with a steady half-inch foamy white cap .  the mouthfeel is light , with excellent particulates that roam the mouth . a most excellent brew that i would n't hesitate to try again .

awesome . the taste is again huge with cherry flavor without sweetness , cherry pits , a decent amount of sourness , with a good lactic tartness on the finish .  made a great appearance , poured a classic beer golden with a very large creamy foamy white head with a lot of sticking .  matches perfectly with the thickness of the body .

things are looking good , very good t : a little bland at the front but it builds slowly with some nice coffee and chocolate flavors .  nice white , foamy head with great retention .  very nice feel in the mouth -- rich , thick , tingling bubbles , kind of evaporates on the tongue . medium-heavy body , quite a bit of honey , i get this apple quality .

it smelled of the mediterranean sea and beautiful , long-legged , not to be fucked with , italian women with sensuous lips . a very sweet , lemony ipa that is excellent for what it is , and enjoyable , for a time .  a - pours a deep mahogany color with an inch of fluffy golden head . so far great .  the texture is just flat-out perfect and this is about as easy to drink as you can want .

smell ; perfect balance of rich , nutty and sweet malts and citrusy hops . beautiful aroma and the american hops work nice with the rich malts . taste ; starts with a sweet , sappy , resin flavor , mixed with white sugar .  the pour reveals very fine de dolle bubbles . the beer is a beautiful copper color .  silky smooth on the tongue and exceptionally creamy .

i prefered the tap version as the apricots were so intense in the aroma as the bottle had more funk and barnyard . apricot , lemon and peach flavors . moderate acidity for a cantillon . the palate could be drier and the carbonation more lively but this a stellar offering by cantillon once again .  the pour is absolutely beautiful on this one .  m : the mouthfeel is dense and creamy and frothy ... and almost stout-like . excellent .

drank it on draft at legacy and at reading country club i have also had three cases of it made for them by the lion in bottles it is smooth favorful light and not biteing , nice head great smell very refreshing to drink it is a amazing product that they have made it is very nice to just sit and drink again and again .  amazing looking beer .  incredible mouthfeel .

hops are juicy smelling . very complex and citrus-fruity aroma . t : mmmm ! d : this is a tasty beer on the verge of being terrific . a solid offering , i would have a few of these .  a-dark ruby to light brown with a huge tan head . clear .  m : very thick , borderline creamy . superb .

on tap at the austin ginger man . the aroma had a sweet wheat flavor along with banana , lemony citrus and a moderate clove spiciness . very flavorful and well rounded hefewiezen aroma . i get lots of clove flavor throughout the beer .  i enjoyed this stout as it warmed up to room temperature . this is as black as you can get which is expected for a stout .  mouthfeel is incredible , one of the smoothest beers i 've had .

smells great ( but nothing like a gumball imo ) . incredible . very bitter for a pale ale , or pale wheat ale , whatever . it certainly smelled good , but nothing more than the typical tropical fruit-heavy pale/ipa .  it poured amber in color with a creamy-brown 3+finger head that lasted quite a while . it left gobs of sticky lacing all over my glass .  mouthfeel : has a great mouthfeel . it has exceptional smoothness .

5.0 s : lots of oatmeal is apparent . this may be the most oatmeal laden beer i 've had . awesome balance between sweet and roasted flavors . 4.0 t : the taste is just about as good as the nose , but the mouthfeel is too distracting for me to enjoy it .  came out a murky amber-gold with a good inch 's worth of head on it . great retention , and perfect lacing rings after each sip . beautiful .  m : very creamy feeling , small bubbles , not too sticky .

massively nutty aroma , packed with roasted peanut butter , walnut brownies , and nuttella - very inviting . not terribly smoky ( more roasty ) , just a mild edge of charcoal that also lends a hint of toasted marshmallow . plenty of coffee notes as well - this is just about perfect , exactly what i want in the style . strangely , there is not a hint of alcohol in this beer - which makes this dangerously drinkable , but still , not exactly a lawnmower beer !  a dark body that exhibits a reddish tinge when held up to the light , with thick lacing spiraling down the side .  mouthfeel is a heavy but perfect . heavy with lots of lactose , light but fizzi carbonation .
smells great ! ! !  perfect looking beer .  m : the carbonation on this one is perfect . perfect mouthfeel .

aromas of lots of different berries ( strawberies , blueberries , blackberries , and raspberries ) . i would get a different berry every time i sniffed . the berries were done nice ! good thing i like all the types of berries in this one .  a - pours a dark , cloudy copper with an amazing two finger light brown head . the head on this beer was huge and crated with never ending retention and thick , gooey lacing .  the mouthfeel is incredibly creamy , with the tastes of chocolate and dried fruit coming through .

smells amazing . chocolate and some buttery , boozy notes emerge with warming .  a - golden yellow with a huge , chunky white head . excellent retention ang big chunky lace up and down the glass . beautiful beer .  mouthfeel : thick , creamy and full-bodied , smooth with just enough carbonation . spicy warming alcohol remains through the finish and leaves a tingly sensation in the mouth and a nice warmth throughout .

for the record , fresh - this might be the mightiest tasting ipa out there . smells like mango , citrus , pine needles , pineapple , melon etc . also has a nice sweet malt aroma in the background . lots of piney resin with a pineapple/mango twang . o : overall , a finely crafted ipa . among my favs all-time and easily my top 3 from out west .  pours a dark brown-black with a huge creamy tan head that retains well and laces the glass .  the hop particles make it sticky as hell , the rim of my glass is sticky , my lips are sticky , and the mouthfeel is outstanding ! as far as double ipas go ( which let 's face it this is really comparable to an ipa ) , i still prefer either pliny or any of the alpine ipas , but this is a nice change of pace .

the nose on this one is about a mile deep . i get tons of nutmeg , chai tea , cinnamon , vanilla , ginger snap best describes the aroma . i ca n't stop smelling it . most , if not all the aromatic qualities come through on the palate . very creamy and spicey . overall the drinkability is good . great aroma , great flavor and mouthfeel .  this beer was poured unhurriedly into a flute . lots of swirling carbonation and three solid finger s of thick creamy head .  the aroma speaks strongly of roasted grains , as you would expect from a stout , while on the tongue the beer has tremendous body .

wow , one of the best smelling old ales i 've ever smelled . as it warms up so many different smells come out , yet it stays balanced . i thought this beer smelled amazing and was very complex and balanced . while the taste was a step down and a tiny disappointment after the smell , it was still very good . i thought it also had an amazing mouthfeel and while definitely a sipper , the abv is well hidden .  convict hill oatmeal stout pours a solid black with ample dark brown head .  i keep tasting chocolate ice cream ... dry chocolate ice cream ... not cloy at all ... very fantastic finish and mouthfeel ... german beer ftw will buy again !

richer . the sweetness comes through much more . i highly recommend storing one of these away to turn a very good experience into a great one .  poured into a tulip . this beer is a beautiful gold . stunning and fragrant .  mouthfeel/drinkability- sublime mouthfeel , super-easy in the mouth .

s. pears on the nose once i open the bottle . i 'm excited to take a sip . not a great representation of the style , but a surprisingly champagne-like beer : they hit the bottle 's stated target on the mark , but i 'm still disappointed that all of the wonderful scents did n't fully transition into the taste .  color was a little hard to see as it was fairly dark in the bar but appeared to be a very deep red , that while really dark was no opaque . slightly off-white head that left excellent lacing on the glass . not sure if it was the branded oversized wine glass or what but this was probably the second best looking beer i 've ever seen .  beautiful .

another great beer from denmark , this little country is no slouch in craft beer world.poured into an imperial nonic a near jet black except from some chocolate brown highlights when held to the light , a large blooming lighter mocha colored head atop.to me the aromas couldnt get any better , a fantastic display of chocolate and resiny hop , maybe the best aroma of any stout i have come across , if you like the hops no matter the style its spot on.the mouthfeel is a little sharp and not as full on as i would have liked.bitter chocolate , dark fruit , and a healthy dose of resiny hop make for a well rounded flavor profile , if that mouthfeel was just a little more smooth ! a really good beer that is close to being great , love the hop play going on .  first pour into pint glass from 22oz bottle- brilliantly clear straw color . head was bright and high but fell to an inch for the remainder .  it is full bodied and creamy in the mouth .

pours a hazy amber/orange color with a small white to light yellow head , very bubbly . nose is amazing , fresh and fruity , mango , grapefruit , pine and sweet fruit juice . taste is much less fruity than the nose , but it 's still top notch , for a regular ipa it sure packs a hop punch , very bitter and palate tingling . a really nice addition to lawson 's hoppy line up !  a beautiful brown with red highlights and a tan head that lasts and sticks .  5.0 on the mouthfeel with a huge creamy full-bodied mouthcoating that covers every bit .
s- totally amazing smell . just like pumkin pie .  beautiful ruby red color .  velvety mouthfeel and smoother than sinatra .

s -- the deepest , richest coffee smell i 've gotten from any beer . lots of other coffee stouts have this `` stong '' of a smell , but none that i can remember have such a deep roasty smell , its hard to describe since i am not a coffee drinker .  extremely cloudy , almost milky thick pale orange golden color .  this beer feels absolutely perfect in the mouth .

very pleasant and layered . t - very hoppy at first , but the finish balances that out with a mild and sweet maltiness .  much darker than one would expect from a trippel . rays of light are subdued by a swampy haze .  m : this stout has an amazing creamy mouthful like a well done milk stout without being too creamy or way too thin like most crap stouts . medium to full bodied ; a really nice medium carbonation on this one .

rarely , have i encountered an iipa with a nose as complex as this . it 's earthy , fruity , funky , dank . wow . dripping with pine and citrus oils . behind the woodsiness and sweetness a delicate floral aroma gently emerges ... seriously could smell this and be happy . thick , oily dark orange pour with a sustained white , frothy head . shit this is good . thick and mouth coating body never becomes oily or cloying . dripping and oozing with oily and resinous hops throughout but still manages to show a wonderful balance . thanks a ton brian !  a - poured out a clear , orange color with golden highlights . it had a very small , white head of bubbly foam .  m : perfect . it 's thick without being cloying .

the smell is amazing . like i stated above , i 'm not big into coffee , but even this is appealing , and impressive to pull off . this porter does nothing but give off an intense and clean cafe au lait aroma , straight to the point . it 's greatest attribute is the aroma however , that is really phenomenal .  pours a hazy yellow with very little head .  the mouthfeel is where this shines , exceptional medium body and smoothness .

s- this beer smells great , typical ipa smells ; pine mandarin , pineapple , grapefruit .  very small tan head with minimal retention and lacing .  perhaps my favorite aspect is the full and very creamy mouthfeel .

the nose was amazing . hints of fruit , plums , raisons , apples , yeast , with a few earthy woody notes .  pours a somewhat cloudy red mahogany , with minimal head .  m= smooth and crisp . feels resinous as well which is great for an ipa . d= super drinkable .

the aromas promise a dandy ; juicy dark fruit ester , roasted coffee , pineapple , chocolate powder and molasses , and hints of bubble gum . a silky mouthfeel , slightly oily , and a sharp carbonation that does n't bite too hard is quite enjoyable . dark fruits , plum , sweet tobacco notes and some coffee and cocoa but not like the nose indicated .  a - hazy , pale straw yellow color with less than a one finger white head . leaves little to no lacing . color is right on for a pilsener but the head/lacing is disappointing .  mouthfeel is as silky as they come , the sensation over the tongue is as pleasurable as quaffing god 's nipple lactations . taste is , however , the killer here because it 's just not as explosive as the complex nose and full body could easily have supported .

big hop aroma -- a bit sugary , citric and piney . lots and lots going on just in the scent , and i can feel the back of my tongue tingling already .  lacing is okay , head is minimal , not much retention..leaves barely anything on top aroma : sweet and fruity , hops ( citrus ) taste : malts come in well and finish off with a citrus hop finish .  the body is just fantastic : full , creamy and smooth .

nice . d - i 'm coming to the conclusion that i 'm not a huge fan of hoppy beers . but this is nice . while i ca n't say i 'd like this all the time , i 'd definitely like to revisit it .  pours a caramel with a light tan froth , good retention , & average lacing .  full bodied , heavy on the palate and full of flavor . i love it .

probably the best aroma of any ale i 've tasted all year . amazing ester profile .  sampled at the bbf a - pours a nice slightly hazy pale light gold almost orange with a very light head that fades quickly leaving minimal lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional ! this beer is smooth , silky , creamy .

lovely aroma of figs , coffee , licorice , lavender , pinesap , chocolate & mint . the dark roasted malts smell so very fresh , almost as if they were right there damp in the palm of your hands .  pitch black with a thin mocha head that disappears instantly . no lacing , pretty standard stout appearance .  m : medium body with a fantastic carbonation balance ! amazing here !

refreshing , quite complex , and just the right temperate on the citrus .  when poured with vigour , it ends up a pale and bright golden colour , with minimal head , although what 's there leaves some very dense and intricate lacing .  the texture on this is great . with the silky texture and sweetness , this is a good sipper , but nothing you 'd have more than 2 of in a single sitting .

i smell a fruity and floral characteristic along with a strong citrusy hop overtone . this is a classic ipa and the brewers knew what they were doing with this batch .  pours a bright copper color with a thin white head , a little lacing .  still i thought the aroma was alittle weak , but once it hits your mouth it is amazing .

smell : sweet and pungent . horseblanket nose . spicy belgian funk is reminiscent of a gueuze .  the serving glass and size might have affected the appearance negatively . appearance 3/5 deep amber , slightly hazy , with a moderate off white head , poor head retention and some lacing .  a great take on belgium ale ; apples , pears , lemons , apricot and orange flavors nustle their way thru a carbonated full bodied swig .

fantastic smell of sweet banana and a slight tart cloves .  my pour created a finger of tawny head with decent retention . color was a slightly hazy orangish-amber .  m : the mouthfeel is perfect . full and creamy with a little grittiness in the texture .

s - smell is phenomenal . right after you uncap it you 're hit with cinnamon and nutmeg and plenty of pumpkin .  poured rather hazy in the glass with minimal head after a vigorous dispense .  the mouthfeel is outstanding . substantial , but not quite so thick as to confuse it with a stout .

the aroma is amazing ! sweet bourboney ( sp ? ) aroma , along with just the right amount of hops and a hefty malt sweetness . very good . all the flavors and aroma go together so well , and the low abv make this a very sessionable brew .  pours cloudy and warm chestnut under a diminutive cap of slightly pink foam that receeds to a film suddenly and quickly .  mouthfeel is exceptional . it feels good in the mouth but leaves no lasting memories on the taste buds .

aroma is as good as it gets ; fruits , flowers , grass and everything in the yard makes this smell like a spring day ; impressive . medium to light bodied , its taste is interestingly hoppy with a lot of fruits , but the bitterness is not prominent , and it is well balanced by an underlying sweet maltiness which increases its drinkability a lot . for the sake of comparison , this was on a small tasting with alpha king and arrogant bastard ; the taste is better on the other two ; but drinkability and aroma are better here .  pours a very clear , pale yellow with almost no head , even trying .  the mouthfeel is fucking perfect : it 's thick and creamy .

this is good , but it 's a little overrated here . it 's tasty and it smells fantastic . i know real porters have sour ale , but usually that sour ale adds creaminess , here it almost has a coors light sourness ( acrid-overdrive ) to it thats off-putting .  it started a little harsh and sharp in its heat and hoppiness ... it softened up quite a bit with the chance to warm to room temp ... the beer pours dark but thin ... dark roasted brown color with crimson highlights under the lights . opaque at the deep points , but the thin edges reveal themselves , allowing plenty of visible light to shine through . it allows the milky carbonation to open up ... higher levels of carbonation here ... not surprising that rd finishes hot and dry . the thin character allows for increased drinkability ... a very solid beer .  mouthfeel is super creamy and silky smooth .

pretty tasty with a great aroma .  a : pours a murky orange/ruby color with a thin cap of fluffy tan head that sits on top .  mouthfeel- this is an exceptionally smooth saison , with the mouthfeel rivaling that of the saison dupont , my favorite of the style and one of my favorite beers . the tank 7 is definitely a thicker beer , very complimentary to the flavors .

nose is certainly affected with the trademark jolly pumpkin barrel aroma/flavor.. light vanilla wood without imparting too much diacetyl . finally , i 've found the beer this balances with perfectly.. the creamy whipped dreaminess of the barrel versus the stark , bright , ripe fruits of an american dubbel.. this exudes a mindblowing aroma . superb . blueberry ice cream scent with a blondie underneath . delectable . taste does n't disappoint either . jolly pumpkin seems to be a real one trick pony , but this is one of the times when that pony executes its trick perfectly .  santa 's little helper pours a flat , inky black into the glass . a thin tan head quickly dissolves to a thin ring around the surface leaving behind only a couple spots of lace on the glass . other than the flat appearance it 's top notch .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , rich and creamy it 's quite thick and chewy without going over the top .

a : almost totally opaque , thin tan head that generates late and dissipates quickly , not much lacing s : smells like a campfire is the best way to put it , some light hops and malt , but mostly that charcoal mesquite , wow t : again , the campfire , but a little more subdued , some chocolate notes in the middle , with a hop bitterness in the back that mixes with the rough , almost metallic charcoal character m : pretty thick , coats the entire mouth and stays with you for a while d : a true sipper , amazing for the style , but it 's so intense , i had a little trouble finishing the bottle , one would be enough for me for quite a while  a : dark orange , very translucent . you can see that it 's quite fizzy . layer of golden foam quickly dissipates .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , substantial and even sticky .

beautiful beer at 6.8 % abv certainly packs a punch , a - perfect for the style , a big fluffy head fell away at moderate pace , lacing well , pours a hazy orange s - a highlight for me , big amarillo hop aroma , citrus , fruity no negatives in the aroma dept . t - a little bit less than a std dipa bitterness but still kicked liked a wild goat , beautiful flavours , crystal or other malts coming through m - well controlled and certainly right for me .  this poured a clear medium golden , white foam head , that left broken lace all the way through , taste was nice , rather bold hops , up front , then mellows , to a bit of a sweet aftertaste , citrusy notes , fruit and hop nose , bit of apple , and lemon . mouthfeel was a little chewy , but fairly rich and full , drinkability is very good , nice summer brew !  mouthfeel ; very tight and lively carbonation , slick and creamy in the finish , pretty complex and admirable .

huge hop and malt aroma , very typical of stone .  12 oz bottle into a tulip . appearance : opaque , deep copper brown color with a disappongtingly small tan head that quickly faded to a thin cap before disappearing completely .  the mouthfeel was very very thick and creamy and not as thin as say a sierra nevada .

smell- unbelievable aroma ! overall- has a great aroma but falls short with the taste .  appearance : really cloudy , reminds me of a wit . pours yellow with an orange tint .  deliciously smooth . coating the entire mouth with a lasting finish .

a special cask tapped last night at the j. clyde . s : an absolute explosion of floral and citrus hop aromas -- it smelled dipa-esque . a rich crackery malt backbone is evident , as well . a solid offering , and if gpbc decided to make the aroma of this beer into a car air freshener , i 'd be all over that .  a - golden amber with a thin off-white head that dissipates quickly .  excellent mouthfeel and not too heavy .

5.0 s : this is my absolute favorite type of dipa , i can tell already . it has a malt bill that can stand up to the hops in flavor and complexity . hops are citrusy with emphasis on orange and grapefruit . malts are full of caramel flavor and dark fruitiness like a barleywine . i did n't know what the hell i was tasting . the malts were a big disappointment as it was n't as complex as i would have liked . mainly just has the caramel flavor . 4.5 d : i would definitely like to have this been again , but not too often since it 's quite expensive .  a- dark amber with large off-white head that slowly dissipates to nothing .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is full bodied with low carbonation , and oh so smooth .

s - beautiful dark malt and deep cherry aroma .  i was unaware this was an unfiltered beer , so i got lots of yeasties in the beer which made it cloudy and sort of foreign looking . i dont really mind it , but it doesnt look good and could serve as a detractor for some . nice white head and some decent lacing .  bear republic really , really nailed the mouthfeel on this one .

the aroma is both unique and memorable , with a cornucopia of fruitiness : pineapple , mango , strawberry , and starfruit . the hops taste grassy and resinous , but the highlight is the tropical fruits derived from the yeast ... excellent stuff , even though it 's not the most cohesive-tasting flavor profile . a crafty anniversary beer..complex , tasty , and original . kudos , real ale .  once left to settle after the pour - i felt it was a bit murky looking , like dirty dishwater - not really a ruby colouring - i guess ill settle and say it was pale brown .  m - smooth , silky , full body with the perfect amount of carbonation o - great brew !

s : the aroma is fantastic . natural lemon scent and orange zest , mostly lemon .  12oz brown bottle with a bottle code that i ca n't decipher . thin layer of tan head holds its own and leaves some lacing on the glass . opaque brown with amber hues when brought up to the light . coffee flavors comes in slow but becomes a dominant flavor middle to end .  t- the taste is starts out very smooth and creamy from the mouthfeel with some of roasted malts quickly followed by a nice bitter finish . m- the mouthfeel is silky smooth from the oatmeal with a moderate amount of carbonation . d- very good stuff , and not too boozy for a 9 % beer even though you can feel the warmth .

i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a darker color than golden , with a small white head and okay lacing ... s : the smell is very strongly grapefruited ... t : wow , a very potent hop flavor . the bitterness is actually quite light ... m : crisp , pretty light , and slightly dryish ... d : a really nice beer .  poured a bomber into a pint glass , producing a decent head , a golden amber color and not much else .  mouthfeel is silky smooth , really nice . body fairly full and the beer leaves an impression all the way over the tongue .

anyhow , when you have a need for hops , this one certainly takes care of the fix . aroma , yes , just like it should be- huge citrus , flowers , grapefruit rind , oranges , probably lemons and limes if i was n't diving in so fast . this beer has a nice solid body holding in a creamy , milky nectar thats very smooth . the finish is bitter but smooth , maybe a little woody from all the hops . it only lacks a little malt complexity in the flavor , the malt seems a bit basic but does hold up well to the hop explosion .  a : pours red-brown , with slight haze and a light haze that quickly drops to nothing .  mouthfeel is utterly smooth with just a hint of carbonation ... placidly perfect .

s : the smell is very balanced and i am loving it . mild fruity esters mix with sweet bourbon , vanilla , and coconut to form what is probably the best smelling beer ( non-ipa ) i 've had before . d : fantastic barrel aged barleywine . great job mayflower .  appearance - cloudy yellow color , with small head that faded out .  the feeling in your mouth , however is gorgeous ! smooth , silky , incredible.. so incredibly good that i actually said 'incredible ' in a french accent because it deserved such smoothness ... i 'm not going to lie , as for drinkability.. i 'm not as into this as anchor 's or even sierra nevada 's , christmas offerings this year , but it is still very drinkable to this lass .

s : sweet dark frut nose come out followed by a chocolate toasted malt . on second whiff i am reminded of chocolate covered cheries .  pale orange like an unripe loquat . smells just like a pumpkin pie . taste like a pumpkin pie with a lot of spices .  this beer has an excellent mouthfeel .

s : abundant floral hops , definately some cascade . the perfect combination of floral , bittering , aroma , in a showcasing of hops that is presented beautifully , well balanced and tame but not lame .  pours hazy reddish orange with a thin head that soon becomes patchy .  ( not a huge coffee stout fan ) ( blasphemous i know ) the greatest thing about this beer is the smooth creamy texture that is present while drinking .

the smell has a great citrus/banana smell to it that captions your nose the second you pour into a glass . very satisfied with the smell . taste - the taste is very good . the smell and taste together make this an exceptional beer to drink .  served in a tulip glass at american flatrbread in burlington , vt . pours a cloudy yellow/golden color with a thin white head that dissipates quickly .  really wonderful . the mouthfeel is the most impressive and outstanding attribute of this beer .
smell is fantastic ( i love hops ) .  orange hue , thin head , dissipating quickly , leaving lace on the glass .  mouthfeel - heavy body with mild carbonation . it 's perfect to me .

the aroma is very deep -- anise , fennel , mocha , coffee and a burning alcohol nose -- awesome . really a marvel . strange .  appearance - like a pilsener , golden , small head , medium high carbonation . laces reasonably . mouthfeel - just right for pilsener .  mouthfeel : delightfully creamy and full-bodied . very pleasant .

nose is quite complex with some really nice notes of oak , vanilla , chocolate , roasted malt , and some light coffee . the taste does n't mix these together quite as well , but is still tasty . great feel coming from all different directions and quite drinkable for the big beer that it is .  the beer poured black , with a tan head that had low retention and lacing .  mouthfeel was virtually perfect .

exceptional smell of toffee , caramel , nutty . wanted to eat something that smelled like this . slightly bitter note on the nose . sweet with a more bitter nutty taste .  granted i gave it a swift pour as i was n't expecting this much sediment .  mouthfeel : fantastic . great carbonation , no real aftertaste and washes easily over the palate .

s- super hoppy and sweet with a mixture of predominant pine flavor and underlying grapefruit notes ... absolutely exquisite . t- taste is very reminiscent of pliny the elder but possibly better balanced .  orange in color and cloudy . a pretty color to be sure but otherwise not outstanding . lots of sediment in the bottle , so pour carefully .  the mouthfeel is full and velvety .

i do n't know if the age helped , but this smells fantastic ... deep milk chocolate ... . nice bourbon and vanilla notes ... hints of brown sugar and cinnamon ... really a great nose . flavor loses anything from the nose ... a bit of dark cherry essence rounds out the ris flavors ... fudgy toward the finish.. oak seems a bit musky/tannic.. medium body with good carbonation .  golden-orange color , almost transparent and practically no head .  m : great carbonation feel with a nice medium body . amazing here . perfect !

unbelievable . taste , too has a very pronounced graham cracker taste in it , along with pumpkin , of course .  a- motor oil black with a milk chocolate brown head that seemed inconsistent on tap . on one pour the chocolate-brown head took up 3/4 of the total pour and took several minutes to dissipate into a manageable 1-finger head . on another pour there was no head whatsoever and even when swirling the glass was difficult to generate any frothiness . the body was pitch black with no light getting through .  mouthfeel : exceptionally smooth and silky as can be .

huge pepper aroma and a very pronounced and balanced flavor . thanks to the lovely folks at elysian fields today , very gracious hosts .  nice oily sheen to this ; some head retention & above average lacing s : plums & other dark fruit , a bit of leafy hops t : boozey plums , dark cherry , woody hops , dryness & a bit of cakeyness up front .  mouthfeel is what always gets me on these beers , i love the chewy creamy coats your throat feeling here .

probably the sweetest ipa i 've run across . aroma of candy and berries . nicely hopped with clear strawberry and other berry notes .  pours a golden yellow with very little head .  mouthfeel : spot on in my opinion . medium to medium-lite body with perfect amount of carbonation .

smell : the best part of this beer in my opinion . extremely complex ! i smell the chocolate and coffee but i am also overwhelmed by the super sweet heavenly smell of vanilla . taste : i was so happy that the taste was so refined , understated , elegant and smooth . drinkability : love it love it .  somewhat muddy at first pour . very , very dark-ok i will call it black . low caronation head wise but seems lively enough .  extremely smooth tasting beer . bodied is so full its nearly chewable . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and very smooth .

one of the best smelling dipa 's i 've tried . nice dry finish . o a great dipa . enjoyed this beer very much . this is a hop monster with a nice sweet malt complimenting everything .  pours an orange-caramel color with a pretty large white head .  m - perfect carbonation .
