s : about what you 'd expect from an ipa- flowery , with lots of citrus . i 'm detecting lemon , melon , and other tropical fruits . i 'm used to lemony scents from ipas , but this one has something different- it 's the distinct melon i 'm getting from the nose . t : very `` clean '' tasting , lots of citrus at the beginning . the ending is quite bitter , but not a much as some ipa 's i 've tried .  poured into a snifter , an opaque muddy looking deep red/brown color . a small 1/2 finger head forms and dissipates quickly . leaves no lacing . this is an interesting looking beer but not above average .  amazingly smooth going down ; full bodied with light carbonation .

really loved the nose .  pours a straw yellow from a 12oz bottle to a standard pint glass . dissipating to a half finger head with good lacing .  mouthfeel is heavy and smooth with a nice small bite of carbonation , wonderful .

ah the smell of the hop flowers , dominates this magnificent nose that is also sweetly malt , fresh and clean , the quintessential dry hopped aromas all present , sweet malt start , the top moderate in feel . finish is delicately acidic , boom , the hops slap your palate and cling till the very dry and lovely finish , just plain yummy !  a - the low , poorly retained off-white head is disappointing as is the hazy golden yellow color .  t- pretty solid all around . very smooth , robust , and thick .

the spices really compliment the berry smell . very unique and inviting . the highlight of this beer is the incredible aroma . t - not quite as impressive as the nose leads to believe .  '' -- german proverb mahogany brown with reddish caramel edges and a thin slice of khaki colored foam that should have been bigger given the increasingly aggressive pour . the featureless head shrinks to a barely covering film in minutes and leaves no lace .  incredibly smooth mouthfeel , likely due to the aging .

this is a lovely slow-sipping beer .  pours hazy copper with a creamy 1 finger tan head that faded about average time ; good lacing that clings to the glass and leaves rings .  the mouthfeel was phenomenal . to have a cask conditioned beer is such a treat , and i 'm glad my neighborhood bar always has one beer on cask .

amazing smell -- coffee and chocolate dominate the aromas with some caramel in the background .  ) poured into a pint glass a : pours golden pale orange with less than a finger of thin white head . not great retention .  perfect creamy mouthfeel .

oh , man ... the aroma on this is , perhaps as the name implies , heavenly . almost a perfect balance in the nose -- fruity , pine needles , grapefruit . and this one goes through three `` hoppings , '' kettle , hop back , and dry hopping ... awesome . the flavor is just about perfect . a fine balance of hop flavors , including a nice grapefruit bitterness and a light bready undertone . but , as a whole , this is a very drinkable beer ... and quite delicious .  hair of the dog adam slightly chilled , served in a wine glass minimal carbonation and no head , just a few large bubbles .  mouthfeel is thick as hell and creamy , perfect for a big ris this is smooth as hell , much smoother than beers with this much ash flavor usually are .

it has fantastic light floral hop aromas . the alcohol content is n't particularly high and their are some superior apas around .  poured with a smallish fine cream colored to very lite tan head and a little lace .  wonderful full mouthfeel .

smell : great aromas of licorice and chocolate . overall , the beer is a bit rough around the edges , perhaps from importation , but that is certainly part of its charm .  a - pours cloudy dark amber with medium head . my glass had some dark particles in it .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel . easily drinkable .

it has a great smell of having trouble explaining other than sweet . this is a very drinkable beer but there are many more much better .  good bubbly , head . the variance in size of bubbles making up the head , almost give it a lumpy appearance .  mouthfeel was phenomenal - silky smooth and with a slight hops bite on the tongue , giving 'way on the finish to a great caramel sweetness .

really delicious smell t : very tannic finish ... almost too much . not as sour as the smell suggests , but very nice . lots of flavor going on !  a - pours a deep brown with very distinct ruby highlights . thin off-white head and very little lacing .  thick with just a little bit of slickness and just enough carbonation . sly fox oatmeal stout is a solid beer with a fantastic mouthfeel ; probably something i would order again .

aroma is powerfully sour and very champagney . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .  appearance : medium carbonation , 1 inch head , dark brown smell : malt , chocolate syrup -- like bosco , and cream taste : chocolate , burnt malt , nut , and cream mouthfeel : sweet , medium bodied , smooth drinkability : this is a surprisingly sessionable stout .  the finish lingers for a while , almost spicy with a slight alcohol burn m - pretty ideal for this style i thought .

330ml bottle served into an snifter glass.enjoyed on sep11.pours intense orangish copper in color , chill haze appearance.crowned by a creamy light yellowish off-white thick layer froth.brief retention leaving some spotty lacing.yeast & intense caramel malt aromas . buttery bread , toffee hints & slightly fruity -apricot & peach- notes to the nose.spicy , orange zest & subtle coriander flavors.gentle warming alcohol.sweet bitterness in the middle.medium but intense body.soft carbonation.dry bitter finish.smooth fruity aftertaste.a beer for a long & paused drink.a nice warming beer .  poured a hazy orange/dark peach color , providing not much of a head and leaving behind hardly any lacing to speak of .  mouthfeel : very thick and very very smooth , wonderful mouthfeel .

s - coffee . geez .  appearance is a brown to dark copper color with not much head .  where this brew really stands out is the creamy mouthfeel . that smoothness works to perfection with sweetness , but does n't work quite as well with bitterness .

wow , the smell is the absolute best part of this brew - strong on the citrus . when first tasting dreadnaught , i picked up more piney hop taste than the smell indicates . the more i drank , however , the citrus hop flavor came through . i paid $ 8.99 for this bomber and it was worth it ( although pricey for an everyday beer ) .  a - nice dark caramel . not much head , not much lacing .  the mouthfeel was spot on and the taste was close behind .

the smell was excellent . i happen to love maple ( though i confess it is n't something i usually have in my beer ) , and the rich malty aroma of nutty maple notes was divine . ah , well this is a toughie for me because i 'm sure that this is the perfect beer for my girlfriends who are n't so crazy about things that resemble hops , barley , malt ... or hmmm.. beer .  2007 vintage . poured into a snifter . no head after pouring . thick and black . minimal carbonation . the appearance of this one is the only thing that must bring it down in the ranks as the other attributes are top notch .  mouthfeel was awesome . farily prickly carbonation with some slight drying on the finish due to the barrel aging .

definite beer geek cologne going on .  poured from the bomber into my harpoon ipa glass the appearance of this beer is only average , there is a good 2 inch head but its only off white , and the beer is a dark reddish brown when held up to the light , yes thats right light makes it through this imperial stout .  m - huge , thick , syrupy , creamy , perfect carbonation .

the hazelnut scent was so strong and so nice , it easily could have been mistaken for frangelico .  it tasted kind of dry , rather like champagne with the flavoring of berries and just a hint of carbonation . this was a very good beer from leinenkugel and i will be very happy to buy it again .  feel is pretty rich for the style , although it 's medium body it 's almost full really , with such a rich , smooth feel . excellent . honestly , it 's not very typical of the style at all , but i 'm not letting that change my rating .

three floyds beers have a unique aroma . the hops come across , thick and flowery . ive heard they use amarillo and columbus hops for aroma . many brewers could learn from these folks . milk chocolate , coffee , a little toasted malt with just a mild flowery hop flavor on the finish . slick , smooth and rich mouth feel , very nice , very drinkable .  2009 vintage pours a very effervescent straw color with 3 fingers of fluffy ivory colored head . hazes a bit a the bottom , duh ... average head retention & lacing s : grassy with apple peels , plus lemons t : apple peels , white grape , lemony hops & a wee bit of dirt & tartness up front .  full creamy mouthfeel with a low carbonation . thick , thick mouthfeel .

the aroma is phenominal . funky , yeasty , wet wood , barn yard , and sour lemons and oranges .  12 oz bottle a : dark brown under a very small off white head . no retention and no lace .  m : nice and light , yet still has some body . very smooth , good carbonation , good residue . exceptional .

pours a deep amber ruby body with a nice modest off white head . smells of a massive combination of strong barley wine and oak . there 's flavors of raisons , plums and caramel on the nose with lots of vanilla and toasted notes from the oak . bourbon and dark fruit play out initially .  appearance : the beer is a slightly cloudy beer . with good head retention . the beer has a thick white head when pourd and reduces to a thin lacy head .  but the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible .

smell is excellent and unique . predominate smell i get is apricot .  this beer had an inviting lightly roasted grain aroma , rich amber color , and a crisp mouth feel . while i am primarily an ale drinker , this lager had enough body to satisfy while being light enough to have a few .  body is medium-full for style , and this is just about perfect on the way down .

s - huge pine aroma that is quickly and easily enjoyable . massively beautiful from the get-go , with underlying citrus notes . a perfect , varied aroma that promises wonderful delights within t - slight pine taste , bit of grapefruit , pure hops abound . d - very nice , but perhaps lacking a bit of malt balance making this a bit more difficult to enjoy .  a- hazy reddish brown with ____ head that dissipates to a ring .  m= perfect dryness and crispness .

i have to say that the smell of this is fantastic . t : wow , the taste is a bit of surprise .  a-pours a mostly clear yellow-gold w/just a touch of haze . white head with average retention .  m - creamy and rich . the carbonation is very laidback ... almost feels as if it floats on the tongue . very soft ... puffy , in a way .

the grapes come through again from the aroma but the flavour depth is n't as good as the nose . a decent ipa with lots of great aroma but lacking a bit of flavour . a really nice showcase of the nelson sauvin hop and a great idea from mikkeller .  this beer pours a mirky brown with a sizeable light tan head .  mouth is extremely crisp , clean with tremendous carbonation and a nice light body .

s : holy hops ! strong citrus and pine hop aroma , sweet and fruity , not very bitter smelling . t : follows the nose , tropical fruit and citrus hops dominate , followed by piney flavors . o : this beer gives me a rock-solid .  pours a super black with no head and no lacing . another flat looking beer .  however , the mouthfeel of this beer is phenomenal , on the tim of your tongue it tingles , in the middle it is smooth as silk , on on the edges it is a touch syrupy ( amazing ) a good beer , but not worth the price they charge for it .

this is delicious beer . the aroma is just like liquor soaked fruit , with a hint of cinnamon . it 's got a nice clear amber color .  planet porter is a lightweight porter with a sienna brown color .  mouthfeel is outstanding . super thick and syrupy , that flavor coats the palate forever .

raw in your face noble hop aroma . just amazing . poured a tiny bright white head that disappeared when i looked away . the hop flavor does n't approach the strength of the aroma , but that could be a good thing .  pours muddy brown with a tan head than disappears . almost opaque and ... yeah brown is the only color it can be called .  the carbonation is perfect . i love this .

smell is simply awesome - like a buttery biscuit drizzled in honey , sitting in the middle of a pine forest . amazingly drinkable for the abv , and this is how the beer becomes dangerous .  normally a bright deep ruby color , the cask version of the beer was a hazy brown with virtually no head on the pour .  bitter black chocolate moves into the woodiness and finishes boozy m- creamy , full-bodied , coats the mouth and boozy heat d- really impressed with this one .

pours bright orange , with a nice soapy head incredible hop aroma , tangerine , grapefruit , malt biscuit and some caramel sweet upfront with a bitter pine , citrus hop bite and a hint of booze very creamy , delicious and pretty well balanced for a double ipa overall it was a very enjoyable beer .  looks like typical malt liquor , yellow , no head .  m : medium body with the perfect amount of smooth , yet lively , carbonation . truly excellent .

when i pulled the cork out , a delightful smell hit me right away , but went away quickly .  continuous streams of bubbles , but i would like a better head retention .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect for a porter , so smooth and silky .

a-pitch black with a nice tan head that thins s-chocolate , red wine , licorice , and black pepper . strong and complex ! possibly some ginger in there too .  a- slightly hazy light amber with floaties , and a half finger head .  the mouth feel is the richest and thickest i have ever tasted in a beer !

this is quite possibly the sweetest smelling beer i 've ever sniffed .  this one pours a dark and murky , dirty gold in color .  m : fairly full body is well-attenuated for its strength , with an off-dry finish . perfect balance imho ... just enough residual sweetness to keep the alcohol from being too drying .

the smell was full of bourbon , as expected , that blended well with the fruity aromas expected from a tripel , along with spiced notes .  i got just a little head in my chalice , and what i got did n't stay long .  mouthfeel- damn , this sh*t is creamy ! smooth , medium carbonation , but goes down super smooth . nice light bitterness in the aftertaste .

syrupy but not in an over the top fashion . s. phenomenal , tons of coffee , vanilla caramel and sweet chocolate , with a sense of dryness . there is a lot of complexity in the nose , i like it . t. sweet bourbon , oak dryness , all smells mentioned above , bitter coffee all the way through al little rough on the mix of flavors but still great . creamy and crunchy . i would categorize this along with bell 's expedition stout as being a bad boy of the style . its not a smooth and user friendly drink .  a - poured a cloudy golden yellow with very little head . lacing was average .  perfect mouthfeel .

smells wonderful . cloves , banana , caramel , fruitiness . nice comfortable warmth from the alcohol . not something i could see drinking a ton of at a sitting , but delightful as a one off .  pours a clear golden , big white head forms , billowy , goes fast , no lace to speak of .  tiny bit of alcohol flavor let 's you know it can do some damage m : super creamy dipa , full bodied , good bubbly carbonation ( do n't know why there was n't much head though !

excellent . sweet and sour fruits cominate the taste , but caramel malts creep slowly in , along with alcohol , honey , and even some wood . the feel ends up pleasantly sweet and smooth .  poured a 1 finger white head that dissipated to random bubbles . laced in thin broken rings .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , like an expensive champagne and it finishes very dry .

s : tropical fruit city - tangerine , pineapple , mango with noticable pine . put me on the beach in cancun . d : a quality double ipa from avery in colorado , the price in bottles prohibits me from buying this except for every so often , but it 's a quite good beer for hop fans .  faded whitish lemon yellow with a waffer thin cap of white foam slipping right off to a skinny collar .  m - perfect body .

smell is amazing ! nice and sweet and very hoppy . very appealing and aromatic . a very good blonde .  pours a clear orange with a two fingers worth of fluffy head that subsided quickly . a good bit of lacing down the glass . this is a highly drinkable beer that masks the alcohol well .  all the great flavor of the bottled lhms here , but perfectly creamy and full in texture . this only further reinforces my belief that nearly every big beer should be served nitro .

just unbelievable . on the palate the beer is very good , but does n't blow my socks off . very nice beer from stone brewing .  pours typical saison ... hazy golden straw , filled with hints of brown highlights .  the mouthfeel was amazing . nearly full-bodied .

this has to be one of the most interesting beers on the nose ~ lots of malty rye mixing it up with a bready note , lots of spice ( a mild chai cocktail - mostly clove ) , some green spruce notes ( probably juniper berries ) and gobs of orange and lemon zest . overall a beer that really smells great , tastes pretty good , and finishes nicely .  rather short head with no retention or lacing and the faintest of foamy rings on the cap .  the mouthfeel is freakin unbelieveable for me . unique and probably the finest mouthfeel i have felt in any belgian , ever .
the smell is outstanding - i was salivating from the roasty nutty goodness .  appearance - decent looking burnt orange/peach color .  mouthfeel is heavy bodied and velvety smooth .

the aroma is great , extreamly fresh .  pours out a very dark color , black , with a bit of ruby/brown highlights on the edges . a cm thick brown head sits on top , looks fairly dense , but falls away kind of quickly , leaving only a little bit of lacing .  full rich mouthfeel , particularly fun after back-to-backing the hansenns cassis .

c : thick and dark h : jet black n : hellllooo cognac ! hints of coffee and roasted malt huge thanks to hopscotch for sharing this barrel aged treat that is good till 2020 ? really ? will the world still be in existence in 2020 ? did you order an imperial stout with your cognac ? this approach is often reversed by brewers , as people like to have the abv hidden in big beers .  a- poured into a glass with a thick 3/4 '' foamy white head , which quickly dissipated , leaving no lacing behind .  mouthfeel was creamy and exceptional . i was surprised to be able to drink the whole thing since i am not a fan of coffee at all , but this was a pleasant change of pace for me .

very very unique beer , the nose right off the bat informs you of it . rich aroma of the carmel malts used , very heavy scent , but goes along nicely with the character of the porter . really good on a cold day in warm house kind of beer .  pours a clear , pale golden color , with minimal head , but fair lacing .  sweet malts are offset by crisp hops together producing a wonderful balance and mouthfeel . sooo smooth !

the smell is aggressive , and with high standard , quite classic . a vanilla character from the oak treatment adds nicely to the vibrant sweet malty caramel butterscotch toffee brown sugar molasses notes . really nice ! ! the flavor is quite nice as it reflects the nose yet has a surprisingly black licorice thing going on , especially in the really enjoyable aftertaste .  i have no idea how fresh this bottle was . the best before date was very faint and hardly ledgible . light amber/gold , airy head disappated quickly but did leave decent lacing . top rating for drinkability comes from the fact that it was pretty darn good despite my doubts about the age .  mouthfeel was absolutely terrific .

the smell is very potent . vanilla , cocoa , brown sugar , port wine . rich , sweet vanilla mixed with tart flavor that almost resembles a lambic ( kinda like ommegang 's three philosophers 2 % cherry lambic effects the overall pallet of that beer ) .  apperance : rubarb and red apple in color . head was minimal and so was retention . color was light and tan .  m/d : a full body that is creamy and velvety smooth .

nose is fantastic - fruity and bitter , a bit earthy/grassy and just a tinge of honey sweetness ( think hopslam ) .  pours a light bronze with notable carbonation .  this beer has an amazing mouthfeel , very full and luscious , super smooth .

smell : wow , mazing ! roasty , dark chocolate , very coffee forward , sweetness . taste : very good , nice and roasty . overall : very good beer , i would certainly want to have this again .  whether pineapple , blood orange , or , especially , mango , smells flatter nostrils , so far as to think of fruity candy without becoming sickening fact . by cons , viagra - the so-called present - seems conspicuously absent except by micro-extracts .  m : incredibly creamy leaving a nice coating around the mouth that tingles slightly .

t - while the aroma is astounding , the taste does not do the aroma justice . it 's one of my top 5 ipa 's , i 'd say , but compared to the outstanding aroma , the taste is considerably less in amplitude .  pours a beautiful deep brown , very little head quickly recedes- no lacing .  m- feel is exceptionally clean and smooth .

sour raspberries + classic cantillon funk = awesome . i love it . t : raspberry essence jumps into my palate and my nose as i raise the glass , and as soon as the beer hits my tongue the fruit gets displaced by intense sourness + moderate cantillon funk . delightful . o : i expect every cantillon i drink to be amazing , but based on other reviews i really was n't hoping for anything special from the framboise .  appearance- pours out a muddy brown color with a small off white head . a good amount of particles floating around .  m : the feel is thick and chewy with a nice creamy texture .

very inviting , to say the least .  pours out pale yellow and sits a gloriously bright orange in the glass . a small , a forcefully poured white head sits on top , but is soon gone .  the mouthfeel on this beer is abosolutely amazing , almost like carbonated cream , it is wonderful and invites another sip immediately .

really complex nose . smoke , bourbon , dark cherry sour notes . the taste was excellent . really nice with the bourbon not over powering .  looking forward to this evem after the disappointing eipa and apa a- very hazy , milky even , brown . white head looks like warm milk froth . lots of stuff floating about .  this is one of the thickest beers i 've had . very heavy and smooth mouthfeel .

the nose is very complex with hints of soy sauce and salty taffy .  64oz growler poured into tulip glasses : a : pouring into a tulip glass from the growler purchased yesterday at portsmouth brewery , the alt is surprisingly headless . other than that it is a gorgeous ruby red hue .  mouthfeel is perfect , my ideal belgian .

s - amazing nose ; delicious notes of chocolate , slight coffee , and super smooth oat , with roastiness present but generally transformed into the aforementioned dimensions . it reminds me of the smell of instant caf mocha , prior to the addition of hot water . ) finally , there is an appreciable hop that comes in at the end and lingers , providing herbal and vaguely floral notes on the finish .  well ill be once ya get a good pilsner , it does make a difference ! very sturdy brew here , started off by a lemon yellow pour , with a smallish white head ( lil disappointing ) .  silky silky smooth on the mouth , it makes it feel as light bodied but if you take the time to get a feel it 's almost medium . just fantastic . o- this is deffinitely a good saison , the mouthfeel is the highlight .

wonderful mixed aroma with qualities of malt behind the wonderful saaz hops . this is a really nice beer .  a- medium amber with a quarter inch white head that disappears very quickly , an inviting unfiltered cloud lingers as you continue to sip .  m - creamy and full in the mouth , so good , this is just what i want in a marzen .

sweet and sugary , but delicious and unique . alcohol is absolutely brutal on this bitch as the heat slaps you in the face with the force of 10,000 fighting japanese midget minnow farmers .  it did not have much of a head , so i was a little dissapointed . but hey , what a beer .  m - extremely smooth .

this is a really great nose . tastes not quite as good as it smells , but still solid . smells great and is solid all around - worth a shot .  drank from a bottle the taste was that of really good choclete and hints of coffe . no real bitter taste had a light smell of choclete to it over all etremelly drinkable and refreshing . alsohada light carbination not too much or little justenough to givethe right amount of fizz this beer is in my opinon up there as far as import beers farsuppour to a guiness wich is overlly bitter .  this was the first belgian i ever had . it has a very creamy smoothness that i really love . finishes long and dry with more fruityness .

s - mmm , what a good smelling beer . delicious smell , and a lot of it .  pours a hazy mud brown with little to no head .  mouthfeel the best part of this beer , really smooth with just a little bit of carbonation .

looks less viscous then i had expected smell is bourbon all the way . probably the most bourbon i have ever smelled in a ba beer . the smell prepares you for a very chewy brew but the mouthfeel isnt so .  pours yellow/gold with a small head that goes away immediately . lots of dry hop floaties in this beer , not as much as green flash west coast ipa , but you get the idea .  perfect . d- a remarkably smooth beer , although a bit mild .

s : wonderful fruity belgian goodness . caramel malty dubbel is a smell warms me up even on a hot evening . allagash has some of the nicest smelling belgians that come to mind .  bottle poured into a tulip a : pours a translucent amber color with an eggshell hued , fizzy thin head . the fact that it 's considered an american amber is truly an insult . it has the appearance of an amber , but the aroma of a belgian and the flavor of a porter .  round velvety texture , excellent carbonation , and ( as you would expect ) some warming . exceptionally satisfying brew - if not my absolute favorite from unibroue , it is the one i return to most often .

citrus ( grapefruit ) - yes , strong and good , wow . apricot flavor notes .  unclear , amber , with some carbonation seen rising up through it . no real head at all , just a bit of white dusting and some dusting gathered in a ring .  all kinds of malty goodness going on here - silky smooth , slightly pinpoint carbonation .

i 've had a few of these and this one plays up the humidor to 11 . incredible . t. the jai alai flavor is played down a bit to the predominate cedar flavor . the grassy and citrus hops are very nice with a good malt .  pours a fairly clear dark straw with just a wisp of white head .  m-grand canyon deep and gordian knot complex . amazingly tantalizing on the palate . while it looks still in the glass it bursts with palate stimulating carbonation with each sip . like an amusement park in your mouth ! this is a highly enjoyable and palate stimulating sipper . a mighty fine drinking brew .

the aroma is honeysuckle and dark fruit , complex , tropic , and soothing . mouthfeel is brighter than i would have expected , but leaves a slightly gritty film on the teeth . the taste is not nearly as complex or abundant as the smell and alcohol does not feature much part in it .  ruby red with brown and garnet highlights . not much head , pink to off-white .  a great feel that has a body that replenishes itself .

s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  poured a hazy pale gold color with a thin white lacing barely covering the top of the beer . the head all but disappeared after a few minutes and did n't really leave any lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is of a super smooth , velvetty batch . this may be one of the smoothest , silkiest brews that i have had .

glorious aroma of silky dark chocolate and dark-roast coffee beans . very pleasant . the dry , slightly acidic roasty finish leads well into another sip .  poured slightly chilled in flared glass a : no head , decent beads , clear mead color s : honey , persistent smell of honeysuckle t : light ale , very floral , very complex ; lots of honey , lavender ; it 's like drinking a fancy handsoap ( meant to be a compliment ) ; buttery undertone ; ok , let 's call it soapy , but i think this flavor profile calls for that .  ideal texture for an ipa .

the aroma was quite exceptional . never before have i whiffed this nose of smoke in a beer .  poured into a tulip glass . dark opaque effervescing with a slight reddish hue .  for the style , this is an exceptional mouthfeel .

aroma has pleasant vinous overtones , port . superb taste is exactly as expected from the nose . the figs are turning .  pours an effervescent amber with 2 fingers of cream colored head . average head retention & lacing s : caramel , leafy hops & breadyness t : breadyness , some crackery notes , & a bit of toffee up front .  the mouthfeel is full and warming , in fact , this beer is a huge belly warmer .

great nose on this altbier . very mild fragrance , overall , but perfectly to style . perfect for the cool austin weather this time of year .  shared a 6 pack with some friends ( peacebone116 and his wife and my wife ) , sadly didnt have the option to get an appearance since we drank them from the bottles on a picnic . a n/a since it wasnt poured into a glass , so ill go middle of the road with a 3 .  the beer itself is pretty thick , and mixed with the lingering foamy head , it feels great in the mouth for savoring what taste there actually is .

very nice . the taste is quite good , mostly dominated by malts .  a - poured a cloudy orange-colored body with a slim , bubbly off-white head that reduced to a wispy film and a thin ring of retention , yielding sparse lace that slid down the sides of the glass .  what got me hooked was how smooth and creamy this beer was . fantastic . this beer is by far one of the richest and creamiest beers i have ever had .

the smell is outstanding . you can really smell the hops from across the room , but not overly strong , they smell great . the taste is very good , but you can unfortunately taste the alcohol at the end of each sip , it lessens more and more during the session as the beer warms up a bit .  there is a decent amount of head but it dies down quickly .  great palate , though . even when it gets warm , great warmth and sliky smooth syrups .

very powerful sweet aroma . overall : fantastic beer , will definitely get again .  i heard such great things about this beer that i figured i should enjoy my first from the can . smooth ; very good for the summer . best canned beer i have ever had ( the rumors were true ) . recommended if you want a stronger pale ale for a backyard cook out , or a few beers doing house work .  altogether pleasing to the tongue and brain , it also had a beautifully full mouthfeel from the oustandingly appropriate delicate carbonation .

the nose ? wow ! intense citrus and definite grape fruit aroma is almost overwhelming , but in a very , very good way . never had anything like it taste : as i go for the 1st sip , i 'm almost squinting my eyes , expecting to drink a form of carbonated grapefruit juice .  a - pours a muddled brown color , thin collar , that 's about it .  awesome mouthfeel .

dipas aroma 's are awesomely hard to describe .  a - a pale yellow color with a white head that retracts very quickly , a few carbonation bubbles are running to the top .  easy to drink due to it 's creamy mouthfeel and pleasant flavor .
very nice aroma ! very nice beer .  this beer is a dark gold color , with a small cream colored head .  silky , creamy , and perfectly textured , this mouthfeel ca n't be beat .

the aroma is out of this world . a very , very bready smell . heavy yeast and a cake-like aroma . immense . the taste is very strong carrot cake . pumpkin spice and brown sugar . hits the back of the tongue with authority . rich and bready , like a sugary cake .  poured a hazy blonde very similar to a witbier or hefe , with notable carbonation . very small head , but with some lace making it all the way down to the bottom of the glass . very drinkable , especially during the summer .  m : soft , smooth carbonation , big and viscous body , excellent finish . there 's very little more that i want from a big ris d : i drank my bottle in an hour and was craving more notes : i did n't really expect much from this beer because nh have n't really impressed me with much of what they 've done but hot damn , this was impressive !

does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very pleasant and highly sessionable .  there was no lace .  taste again where do i start ... sweet , spicy dark fruits soaked in alcohol ( raisins , currents , dates ) , toasted caramel notes , bready , some brandy / rum traces , biscuity , warming alcohol , spicy hop bitterness forces itself through the sweet maltiness , light madeira wine hints ... feel - so silky smooth ... rich and creamy ... light viscousness.. low drinkablilty for this one - a beer for savouring and sipping slowly ... overall - a phenomenal beer ... highly recommended .

a very strong and pleasant aroma . tastes light honey sweetness and clove up front with perhaps a bit of orange zest fading to bready malts with trace hop bitter finish .  golden , peachy orange with just a touch of haze ; not much of a head , but what 's there is fine and white . klsch-ish aroma but with a touch more fruitiness ; apricots and golden raisins , golden syrup and scones , hints of honey and malted milk with a honeysuckle floral overtone .  mouthfeel is perfect -- light but not watery , highly carbonated ... perfect for the style .

s : as soon as i popped this one , i loved the smell of it . i was hoping after the great smell , it would have a taste i loved , but unfortunately not a taste that suits me .  clear golden with a thin off-white head .  m- creamy smooth with just the right amount of carbonation and a nice , dry finish .

wonderful aromas of fresh pumpkin pie ! i could really smell the spices of nutmeg and cinnamon , plus the fresh smell of carved pumpkin to round out the spice . t- pretty much tasted like it smelled but not as pronounced . it 's easy drinking , great autumn flavors and smells ... .a real pleasure to drink !  based on notes , picked this up in las cruces , nm poured an effervescent amber with a very modest white head . average head retention & lacing s : fruitty with some musty notes t : apricots & peach , plus some honey up front .  t/m - well carbonated , providing a prickly yet very smooth feel as it rolls across the tongue .

by far the best smelling pumpkin beer i 've had , and one of the best i 've had , period , in a long time . t- not quite as good as the smell , but still pretty good . cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin , orange creamsickle , and alcohol .  a : pours just as the name states a golden color with 1 finger width white head and really no lacing down the glass .  the mouthfeel on this beer is great , so creamy with just enough bubbles that make it not to syrupy .

the smell is quite pungent . i can smell the glass from a foot away ! sweet caramel malts are picked up in the nose , but are nothing in comparision to the huge hops assault . it is very hop foward ( understatement ) . this is easily one of the most unique and bitter beers i have ever had . the hops oils make it quite slippery and oily going down .  appearance : a hazy yellow , head fades fairly quickly , and there 's not much lacing . aside from the color it 's nothing fantastic .  the best part of the rwanda gatsinga coffee stout is in my opinion the mouthfeel which is extremely smooth and leaves a pleasant malty coffee-dominated aftertaste and a smile on your face .

the smell is amazing . coffee dominates , and while i 'm not a coffee drinker , i like the smell of it .  had to try this while at dragonmead as you do n't see many pumpkins around in april . amber color , clean with minimal off white head that fades quickly .  mouthfeel is superb . great level of spice , perfect carbonation , medium body .

smell : fantastic , lots of citrus , pine and bubble gum . it is decently balanced but could use some more malt backbone .  a - a cloudy white gold . this actually seems more `` white '' than many belgian whites . not much in the way of head , a tad disappointing .  the mouthfeel is luxurious , thick , and chewy . amazing . i am impressed with this brew . flavors are great and the mouthfeel is unearthly .

excellent ! overall : amazing aroma , very complex and inviting , but i think it set me up for a super complex flavor profile that was n't there .  500 ml bootle from germany pours dark brown with large off-white head that soon dissapears , the small rising carbonation bubbles create kind of prickly surface , no lacing .  m - the creamiest beer i 've ever had . wow . thick , smooth , perfect .

right after i removed the cap i got this instant burst of fruitiness on the nose . then when i began to pour it , the aroma segued into a toasted bready , creamy , yeasty , and neutral hopped balance . i was sold before i even tasted it . fortunately the taste was just as endearing with a bold body and a sharp bitterness nut-like quality concluding with a pleasant dry hop finale . this beer really hit all the pressure points in a good way and is highly recommended .  appearance : dark orange-copper color ; a little hazy ; very small head on the pour smell : a pleasant hoppy smell taste : excellent : fairly balanced ; mild hoppiness with a nice sweet malt flavor to balance ; very tasty ( not watered down at all ) mouthfeel : medium bodied ( im really surprised this is on 4.87 % alcohol ) ; its a lot thicker than other 4.87 % beers ; this must a have a lot of unfermentables in it drinkability : good flavor ; good body , so its going down pretty quick overall , an excellent beer .  the feel is super dry , tannic and superb on the palate , rough , sticky , and full ... easy to drink as this crushed by the girlfriend and i in about 15 minutes .

s - incredible aromas in this beer . even if is a lambic , the smells are very fine and not off-flavours .  a : pours black with a finger of tan head that recedes into a thin ring with no lacing .  great relaxed flavor , it has a nice sweetness to it , a good malt body ; it would be a great beer to drink while out on the river all day , as it has a wonderful flavor without having too much ( it was made with this in mind , according to one of the brewers ) . goes down extremely smooth with a great crisp , sweet aftertaste . ( had on-tap at the star city vfd brew fest fund raiser .

aroma is by far the best part of this beer . a veritable tropical drink in this beer ! flavor does not follow through from the aroma- surprising . i detected minimal hops in the aroma , but they are there quite blatently in the flavor .  fairly dark brown with ruby edges while holding to the light . small tan head that goes away quickly .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , as it should be fir a beer of this strength .

stalagtites of drippy lace . fantastic barrel aroma , soaked in bourbon and sun-dried , retaining it 's oaky complexity . mouthfeel is smooth and rich , alcohol really only detracts from the taste slightly .  nice bubbling and ok foam that recedes to nothing .  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is impeccable within the moderate body , big doughy biscuity malt flavour is the showcase of this brew .

aroma is amazing ... whisky , vanilla , smooth smoke , chocolate , big roasted notes and some oak . taste was a bit of a let down after the wonderful aroma . i picked up a lot of sweet chocolate , some booze , big on the bourbon flavor . this was a rare treat to enjoy i am very happy i had the chance .  it really reminds me of swamp water with little head to speak of .  mouthfeel : perfect , just like champagne .

the smell is amazing . it gets me first on the sides of my tongue .  the beer pours a hazy golden orange with a small amount of head .  m : very viscous and full . smooth carbonation and a nice stickyness make the mouthfeel very complimenting to the taste .

location cellar 70 serving 22oz the scent of this piva is spot on and really is inviting . i have n't had any other coffee stouts , so i am by far means an expert .  poured a golden/yellow color , very clear , small amount of carbonation . i 'm not sure i would call this an english style ipa , i would personally classify it more like an american ipa because of the big hop presence .  body is the best part of this brew . flavors are all in check , mouthfeel is full and fat , with a straw-like dryness at the finish . this beer is exceptionally drinkable .

s - oh my , one of the most delicious aromas i 've ever experienced . d - fantastic stout .  appears clear copper with small wispy head .  mouthfeel is lucious : creamy and oily , rich in the mouth , but smooth enough to want more and more .

when you smell this beer , you know this is a big one . lots of power and lots of liquor , much like rum with some fruity notes to me . it felt like port or a fortified wine in my mouth and the taste was rather like a really , really nice rum .  12oz bottle poured into a chouffe tulip pours a lightly chilled golden yellow with a one finger paper white cap that did n't stick around all that long . a little bit of band aid like funk just to make things interesting .  the carbonation is fantastic -- beer feels creamy and smooth- almost velvety .

smell was outstanding . malts , and dried fruits , raisins , prunes , etc , very complex and really builds the base for the beer . very , very nice . no bitterness to speak of and a lingering toffee sweetness at the end . overall an excellent doppelbock , right up there in my top 3 .  appearance : pours a one finger medium but `` light '' looking light brown head with decent retention . film eventually disappears leaving a thin ring and no lacing down the sides . average for the style . the average appearance held it back in the ratings a bit , but the rest of the experience was top notch .  m- big , full body ... oily , almost syrupy with unattenuated sugars . very chewy , and it coats the mouth so well . just wonderful .

an amazingly rich and creamy nose with strong aromas of toffee , cream , and roasted marshmallows . body is very good . drinkability : whatever hesitancy i had after seeing how it looked following the pour were overcome by the amazing aroma . a solid , flavorful drink that i would kill to try on cask .  clear gold with a small bubbling white head . very balanced and enjoyable ... perfect for sessioning anytime .  the creamy , delicious texture pairs well with the flavorful personality of the smoked porter . the dancing carbonation paired with the brews creamy-smooth feel and intense flavor essentially block dopamine receptors in your brain .

smell : smell is impressive to say the least . huge oaky brandy smells , with rasberry , chocolate and an imposing roasted malt presence . taste : everything good about the smell is in the taste , although unfortunately it still has a bit of a raw bite to it .  hmm organic and spelt so this is a no wheat wit . very pale with a light fluffy head and lots of carbonation going on . a touch of lace but not much . notes of lemon and wheat like twang . excellent thirst quencher and it goes down like your favorite cold soda on a 100 degree day .  m : full-bodied , silky smooth , velvety rich and downright luxurious in the mouth . these guys have this whole mouthfeel down to a t. notes : malty rich , fruity sweet , and explosively spicy , this bspa is quite enjoyable !

the beer smells absolutely beautiful . like bittersweet chocolate and espresso , with some caramel and molasses notes . this beer smells really fantastic . taste is a lot of the same .  pours a light copper with a soapy light tan head . poor retention and scant lacing .  mouthfeel is full and round .

a- nice burnt orange coloring with a decent head and great lacing s- unbelievable aromas ... the tropical fruits are just amazing . you could mistake this for a glass of juice . t- kind of a letdown from the smell , but really the smell set the bar ridiculously high . this is definitely one of the better iipas i 've had the pleasure of tasting .  a - pours with a thin fizzy white head that dissipates quickly .  smooth , creamy , almost velvet like . really enjoyable .

the nose is amazingly sweet .  its got a very smooth and full taste with a good amount of hops , malts , with a sweat finish . at 7.2 % abv its got a good kick to it , and enough of these will get you drunk dialing real soon . as far as altbiers go , this is a damn good one , especially for an american made one . so grab yourself a six pack and enjoy .  mouthfeel is fantastic ... light , dry , well carbonated , and quite bitter .

a - very good , very light golden orange - pretty decent head retention s - the most unique citrus nose of any dipa i 've ever encountered . upfront dried fruit basket and grapefruit blast to the senses . i can pick out the citra hops , that for sure . bitter dry , crisp finish . very , very good beer .  a very cloudy orange color .  m : rich and creamy . very chewy and thick . little carbonation .

very strong smells of pineapple and pirate beers waft away from the glass . there is caramel , yeast and citrus along with the sea , like the belgian pirate-themed beers i have tried . cold weather seems to encourage the brewing gene ... slainte .  a - transparent and dark copper almost brown . a thin tan head that neither sticks on the glass nor hangs around too long .  unbelievably smooth in mouthfeel - bittersweet chocolate and bitter roasted notes played effortlessly on your tongue .

the aroma is amazing . major chocolate aroma with a dose of roasted malts , vanilla , toffee and cocoa . sort of a letdown on the taste .  it poured a dark brown color with some red .  so creamy and smooth it 's almost not a beer ...

smells very sweet , of caramel and spice and a definite alcohol presence on the nose . i love it . one of the best smelling beers i 've put my nose to .  pours a hazy , reddish-brown color with almost no head .  mouthfeel is exceptional . very smooth , great carbonation , but not enough to distract from the flavors going on .

d - spectacular aroma displayed on a solid background of malt . the aroma is still so full and excellent that it makes up for any weakness in the flavor profile .  cloudy , even dusty , in fact it is opaque . the color is a rusty ochre with no head to speak of .  m : one of the fullest and creamiest dipas i 've ever had .

smell is phenomenal ; coffee , mocha , vanilla , kahlua , coffee cake ... the aroma is outstanding . perhaps the best porter i 've ever sniffed . this beer is simply delicious . slight let down from that a+ aroma but minimal . tastes like the smell but with some malt and roasty notes . very drinkable .  brown color beer with some ruby notes .  the mouthfeel is great ... medium on the palate , but slick and well carbonated ... compliments the black pepper flavor perfectly .

it smells great . t : the taste didnt exactly match the smell but the taste was good too .  12oz bottle poured into a pint glass pours a copper-straw with obvious carbonation bubbles rising to the surface . any head quickly fades to nothing .  thick creamy mouthfeel and mild carbonation . smooth silky mouthfeel is lucious .

the aroma is possibly the best feature of this brew . very sweet and flowery , almost of lemon , chamomile , and honey with very strong hop overtones . a nice light amber color , slightly darker than the 60 minute .  first off , i thought this beer was very delicious ... and i will certainly buy another ! i do n't know if i poured mine incorrectly , but it was very cloudy ... which i thought oktoberfests are supposed to be clear ( i 'm thinking about spaten , sam adams , and the like ) . in fact , i loved it !  full effervescent body , huge amounts of carbonation . an unusual beer that 's quite good .

i loved the spicy taste when i first tried it , reminded me of christmas in the summer , and the smell was very delightful . i would definatly get this beer again if i was out with some buddies , and being that it is a summer beer it was perfect for a summer night in georgia .  appearance is dark yellow with a few big bubbles which hung on the glass .  thick rich and creamy mouthfeel . for such a rich and big beer it is remarkably smooth .

a very complex and inviting aroma . the taste really follows the nose , with a sweet melange of spices careening across the tongue . it 's very complex , but unfortunately does n't smell quite as good as it tastes .  i poured this beer from the bottle to a tumbler at 45 degrees . color was amber okay head that decayed pretty fast .  perfectly carbonated , with a thick chewy body and a strong alcohol burn .

the aroma is sensational . sweet , fruity , yeasty .  the beer poured a hazy burnished amber with next to nothing of a head .  m - fairly heavy body and solid flavors with moderate carbonation . the flavors are spot , the mouthfeel is amazing and its very drinkable .

amazingly complex aroma of hand-made chocolates . very mild and easy drinking . definately nothing double powered on the flavor . surprisingly clean . very light body . very drinkable .  possibly the worse beer i have ever had..sickeningly sweet..i let it sit for a week in my fridge and it still bubbled over with head . tastes like sugar and the 1st beer i 've ever simply poured down the drain..is there a quality control problem here or is this standard for the beer ?  very palatable and no alcohol taste at all m - silky smooth , great carbonation .

s - great hoppy but aromatic aroma with a warming malty finish . lovely hops they are using .  aside from the sediment that slowly floated like stars on a cool new hampshire evening the overall appearance was pretty average , striking shiny copper .  body is simply luxurious - rich , creamy , and damn near perfect .

wow ... the nose on this is excellent ! tons of roasted malts , coffee beans and dark chocolate . very nice ... the taste is n't quite as profound as the nose , but it holds up well . i am really glad i had the chance to try it ... after all , it has been on my wants list for some time .  got a nice 1 finger head on the pour but the coloring of the body is fairly weak . very light orange almost the shade of a pilsner which is not a good look for an ipa . smell is very juicy sweet pineapple with the expected belgian yeast twang of clove and banana .  mouthfeel is very soft and full bodied with light carbonation .

this notes of grapefruit and pineapple . just thick hop notes here so ripe and fresh it was like heaven just smelling this . smooth and mellow delivery of the flavor , though not as strong as the aroma would have led me to believe . light alcohol notes as well and a really good medium feel to it . something i would love to try again as the aroma itself was worth the price . this was damn nice  it poured an amazingly still very dark , almost obsidian brown . there is no head , just occasional bubbles surfacing .  s : caramel , apple , sweet roasted malt t : tastes of caramel , some sour fruit like apple , yeast and hops bitterness/spice , some booze m : beautifully creamy and thick , but has a sharpness from the medium carbonation and booze o : drinkable for a bottle at least , this is an awesome beer .

smell : this one is all about that distinctive fruity grape note ( thinks welsh 's grape jelly filled grape bubblegum ) in the beginning that then gets washed over by a classic cantillon urine and yeast wave . truly unique and highly enjoyable . taste : same as the nose but more integrated and not as grape dominant as the nose .  from a growler into a frosty mason-jar mug at purv 's beer and more in peckville , pa lighter in appearance than i had expected . smell was of straight cocoa powder and a little bit of spice from the chili pepper mouthfeel was very nice considering the light color .  m : one of the most enjoyable mouthfeels i 've ever had in a beer ; medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , immensely smooth and surprisingly creamy . d : i thought that the taste here was good , not great ... but the amazing mouthfeel and complex flavor keep drawing me back in , and at much faster rate than that of many beers whose tastes i prefer .

aroma is amazing - brandy , caramel , brown sugar , dark fruits , vanilla , and oak . bummer i 'll probably never have it again , as rare as it is .  hazy light amber with a thin , off-white head that fades , becoming patchy . little bit of lacing .  the mouthfeel is , in a word , glorious . smooth on the tip of the tongue , then seeming to evaporate off your tongue leaving a crisp , somewhat spicy finish .

seems very complex , i love it . t : disappointed from the smell .  pours a copper color with what starts out as a nice creamy head but almost instantly recedes into a thin film . minimal lacing left behind .  m : carbonation is explosive ( like the cork escapade ) . tickles the mouth with just the right amount of chewiness .

a little unusual too . overall , a unique and very enjoyable iipa .  pours a clear golden with a decent amount of slow rising carbonation , with a thin white head with a bit short retention , but is not too inspiring .  m : full-bodied and lightly carbonated with a soft and creamy texture . alcohol noticable in a nice warming effect .

wonderful aroma . warm and oaky , molasses . almost get a bbq sauce scent , very spicey like a worcester sauce . very interesting tastes in this one , unusual .  golden orange body , brilliant in the light . compact , slightly khaki head bubbles out to a collection of foam on the sides of the glass . minimal lacing .  finshes warming , hoppy & bready , very balanced approach mf : chewy with low carbonation & great balance dangerously drinkable , this would put you on your butt after a couple of pints but a really nice dipa

750ml bottle with cork , like their local series . smells of the local 1 , champagne , cork , lemon meringue or orange marmalade , some tropical fruits or pina colada , wet vegetation . surprisingly , i taste the hop in the flavor more than the aroma . a unique hop . corky . kudos for making a dry and hoppy saison , and getting it to texas ! worth trying .  this -bal barleywine pours with almost zero head .  just take a sip and get lost in the nearly overpowering flavor explosion and the creamy tingly mouthfeel of this wondrous scottish ale .

aroma is powerful , though not overbearing . piney/resiny hops are dominant , yet there is also a good helping of pineapple , tropical fruit and caramel .  this brew arrived at my table essentially headless . lacing was very sparse .  a full bodied beer that is creamy smooth and goes down really easy .

s. smells like christmas . hints of cloves , allspice , and roasted nuts .  a refreshing light-bodied ale that goes down easy a- very clear amber-yellow with thin , big-bubbled head s- smells a bit like honey along with a bottle/metal hint .  appearance : cloudy burnt orange/brown - nice head retention smell : cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin spice taste : hops , cinnamon , coriander , nutmeg - similar to an american wild ale - very tannic mouthfeel : my favorite part very tannic , smooth - the rye dries the palate out so you 're ready for another sip or another bite of food .

the aroma was amazing , especially for a beer of such humble stature . chocolatey rich to the extreme . steaming hot fudge instantly came to mind . sweet and creamy with strong notes of vanilla and a touch of oak . dark chocolate came through strong up front . black coffee was noticeable in the center . this was a smooth and tasty beer with an aroma that was to die for . at 5.7 % abv , this porter was surprisingly drinkable .  a : a hazy orange color . me thinks this is bottle conditioned given all the haze.. nice white head , that dissipates into a white ring .  m - absolutely creamy and delectable ! the amazing , tiny bubbled froth envelopes and contains any alcohol sharpness that would otherwise make this 8.0 % beer a bit fiery in the swallow . superb . d - the mouthfeel makes this otherwise straight-up scotch ale an incredibly drinkable beverage . but be careful ! at 8 % , this beer is like getting a two-for-one special in each pint !

stoudt 's double ipa 12 oz bottle medium pour in a mug recent brewing , ingested 12/06 poured a hazy orange amber with a rocky off white fully lasting head with excellent lacing that left layered ring of lacing upon every sip , like reading the rings of on a tree and tracing it 's age . smelt of strong sweet grapefruit and orange , tropical pineapple banana bubble gum or starbust mystery flavor , parsnip , with light barnyard and earthy yeasty flavors . overall , a great dipa that balances a malt sweetness backbone and strong hops nicely .  first observations : whoa , what a smell ! the appearance is dark , of course ... .well more of a dark red . not much head or retention , but i did n't expect much .  mouthfeel is the best part of the beer .

an isabelline crown persists and leaves luxurious cascades of sandy lacing - those bubbles that stick rest atop viscous legs suggesting snow dusted mountain peaks . aroma is highly potent - it hits you from the moment the seal is popped . brown sugar , high quality aged sherry , vanilla , coconut , dense brown bread , faint clove ... the list goes on . the flavor profile closely follows the aromatics , but everything is present in a lesser degree . lots of flavors come and go - abbreviated tastes of bread crusts , licorice , and dried tropical fruit . the finish is quite nutty and hints at leather as well . almost like an armagnac it is a beer well suited to contemplation . the oak notes contribute a great deal without becoming overwhelming ( brandy barrel angel 's share i 'm lookin ' at you ) . definitely worth seeking out and sticking in the cellar ...  not too much retention of the white head , but did pour a nice light amber color that was very clear . not much lacing to be seen .  smooth and creamy mouthfeel makes the small tickling carbonation and otherwise heavier body very palatable . i do n't know if so much milk is my thing , but i 'm glad i tried it .

sweet and very appealing like a hopslam . t - taste is a bit different than the smell and reminds me of pliny the younger . very good . o - i think this is a very fine dipa .  on to the beer : there was no head on this beer when i received it in my tulip . the color is chocolate brown wih hues of caramel orange . very lightly carbonated , and no , this was n't from the infamous bottles of the 2008 vintage , but a keg ( sorry , do n't know what vintage ) .  mouthfeel : low carbonation leads to thirsty gulps .

smell is the leader of the pack , amazing scent of coffee , cream , smoke . drinkability suffers from the mouthfeel since this is the only non style rating , but i really like this porter .  pours a pale copper color with an off white head from a brown twist off bottle .  m- very , very thick and chewy . also quite heavy .

beer also appeared to be quite carbonated smell : hot-day-amn . the smell of this one is trump tight . the eastern spices are like aroma therapy . those clove-ish spices blend with the hops and a sweet fruit scent to create an enticing aroma . taste : from the second this one hits your lips you just know that this is an `` americanized '' tripel .  a - poured a caramely copper-colored body with modest carbonation and very little head that quickly disappeared and left no lacing .  mouth-feel was velvety smooth and creamy .

this is beautiful , and refined . man , the nose really had me going , but the taste did n't follow through .  it pretty much looks like muddy pond water , but this look in a beer is actually sort of exciting , because it signals me that i am in for an interesting experience .  great bubbly mouthfeel , no aftertaste at all .

but overall still a nice dipa and one you could drink a couple of .  a - pours very dark brown in color with some light that is able to make it through around the edges revealing some ruby highlights . the tan head was quite minimal showing very little retention and leaving very little lace .  m/d : full bodied , very smooth , velvet like .

the smell is strong with brandy ( and seemingly bourbon ) and dark fruity sweet malts , caramel , and vanilla . very pleasant . holy shit , what this beer would be if it were carbonated ! dark fruit sweetness complimented by a smooth and invigorating alcohol presence ( 12.5 % ) , much like an imperial stout ... its damn decent right now , but so much greater in my carbonated imagination .  slight amounts of sediment adds to the mild haziness . no lacing , and just about no head , but there is a slight cloud of head floating around . m- full and very smooth .  mouthfeel : perfection . the bead is neither too large nor too small .

this smells amazing . like perfumed hop elephants . but damn ... this smells amazing . i could inhale this all day . which sounds odd .  a : pitch black with a one-finger head . poor head retention and no lacing . it looks like others have had a better looking pour ... perhaps i have this beer a little too much tlc .  they served it properly too - the temperature was perfect ( not co cold ) . pretty close to perfect .

top of the line nose on this one , just fantastic . my first impression was damn ! the consensus was this was an excellent beer , & there was a marked difference once it warmed - a collection of `` yeah , it 's ok '' changed to `` damn , this is good '' after 10-15 minutes . really glad i got to try this one , thanks again tucker !  ( a ) - pours a very thick cloudy caramel color .  caramel , mocha , strong booze , brown sugar , raisins , figs , chocalate t-malt , mocha , booze , brown sugar , caramel , raisins figs , chocalate m-spicy , creamy , thick , barely carbonated d- pretty thick & filling .

the aroma is great . lots of citrus and pine notes . overall a very good and strong ipa ( 9 % ) .  appearance : deep dark brown , no head retention smell : lemon , toasty nutty malts taste : balanced sour ale , plenty of sweetness to go with the sour aspect of the beer .  m - big bodied , thick , and viscous as hell . middling carbonation fades to a really dry and herbal finish like green tea . wicks all moisture from my mouth !

d : nice big i.p.a. , best smelling i have had yet , very flavorful and the malt has been kept in check and the hops can come right through .  ommegang adoration special winter ale belgian strong dark ale bottle dated 7/18/11 and poured into a tulip on 1/5/12 a . pours a murky deep reddish brown with a 1 inch off white head .  big , viscous mouthfeel does great things for this beer , transmitting a pretty large package ( 10 % , significant ibu count ) into an easy-to-sip package .

very interesting . concrete and ginger . refreshing and smooth but a bit more bland than i expected based on the wonderful aroma . nicely mellow and subtle .  received one fat finger of head that quickly faded . brownish copper colored body was clear .  mouthfeel is where this one shines , smooth as can be and perfectly carbonated , a light yet creamy quality .

aroma is wonderful . incredibly intense malt tones and a nice sweetness detected .  pours a two finger white head that fades slowly leaving traces of lace . cloudy almost pale amber color .  nice touch of bitterness lingers as i contemplate the rich , full mouth feel . nice beer , much more approachable than the expedition .

a - clear honey colored with very little head . s - smells of ripe cherries , raspberries , honey , alcohol , mango , citrus , brandy , apple juice , flowers , and apricots . t - tastes of cherry , alcohol , brandy , citrus , candied sugar , sherry , and honey .  pours deep auburn with large bubbles in the tan head and leaves no ring or lacing inside the pint glass .  mouthfeel is astonishingly smooth and creamy for such a rich , complex ale .

wonderful aroma ! it 's fantastic !  a- cloudy golden tan topped with an off white head . the head fades quickly to a ring and leaves a little spotty lace on the glass .  amazing mouthfeel . viscous , rich and creamy without being syrupy .

smell of dark rich chocolate , coffee and molassas , having some dark fruity earthiness to it . taste is again rich as in the above aromas with some roastiness and having alchohol present , but not overwhelming .  poured chilled in flared glass a : thin head ; good carbonation ; dark cola color ; not much lacing s : nutmeg , pumpkin , caramel ; inviting t : very satisfying ; alcohol and spices ( nutmeg , allspice ) prominent ; hops are very strong , providing complexity some reviewers complain about the abundant hops , but i find that an asset in a pumpkin beer ( a style i tend not to prefer ) .  mouthfeel- soft , silky smooth texture . full bodied and rich . perfect .

smell is very sexy - pure belgian goodness . taste is very good . this beer is very drinkable . each sip is very nice as you get a great whif of that aroma . belgian yeast is very impressive - the unique flavor qualities never get old ; they are very subtle .  for pilsner drinkers , this beer has the smoothness and malt flavor one would expect , although oftentimes that leaves a beer without a distinct taste . very drinkable and when finished , would definitely look for another scrimshaw .  really big round full mouthfeel .

nose : this thing has everything : an early combination of chocolate , caramel , and nuts presents a whole pecan pie on a silver platter . all this is followed by some dark chocolate covered cherries and fruitcake aroma . it has a sweet plastic lasting flavor that warns off any hops . has a bit of a smoky swallow which is nice , but does n't mellow the bubble gum . this one is getting thrown behind bars for 3-5 - then we 'll see if it 's more under control .  here 's my first dipa from iowa ... a - pours a reddish brown / dark amber without much of a head on it s - smells dank and boozy with lots of earthy , oniony hops with citrus undertones .  m : full body , and shockingly creamy . this brew is extremely smooth of the mouth .

some lacing & no head retention smell ; huge oaky & sherry notes taste : super sweet up front , followed by raisin , vanilla , treacle/honey and tangerine notes . very complex , but a little too sweet for my tastes mf : syruppy , oily , undercarbonated , & slightly out of balance .  appearance : it poured a translucent amber color with a small white head with poor retention and no lace .  very full and creamy mouth . damn tasty .

huge pumpkin aroma with a bit of spice not unlike pumpkin pie ( which i was eating with it ! ) . my wife loves pumpkin and is not much of a beer drinker and really liked this beer .  a : hazy amber , nice small white foamy head .  it seemed to just coat my whole mouth on its way down .

mesmerizing , really .  really does look like coffee when poured from bottle to glass . black brew with a dark mud brown head . lack of lingering head makes tcois look like motor oil .  this beer is silky smooth with very well behaved carbonation - you 'll have no trouble taking big gulps of this brew !

nose : an absolutely great floral hop aroma consumes the nose . very nice ! it has a fantastic aroma , a great hop bite but a low ibu and low abv . one word : impressive .  after gearing myself up , i cracked my 60 minute ipa with great expectations . this beer has a slight hint of a head that disappears immediately and leaves a lousy lacing .  ( m ) mouthfeel is perfect for this beer .

i love the smell of this beer ... i smell molasses with hints of toffee ... nice maltiness . mouthfeel is very good . great esb !  1999 vintage , sampled nov , 2003 - no head whatsoever . solid black in color with slight garnet highlights around the edges .  t : the taste was about average for a stout , almost identical in flavor to guinness m : amazing mouthfeel , so creamy and so smooth .

s - about 0.2 seconds after the cork popped , the air was almost filled with a rich , dry oak smell . lots of brett in there as well .  the head is a light brown and the body is a dark brown.the head is very froffy.some lacing on the glass . i would like to try this on tap.this a very lively brown ale and it has feeling to it.not watery one bit and the carbonation is pleasant.another great ale from dfh .  light in body with absolutely wonderful carbonation , this is airy , creamy and the combination of sourness and spiciness on the finish is unique .

smells very sweet , what you 'd expect . perfect for dessert or a nightcap .  appearance almost resembles a cola . not as dark as other porters . little to no lacing .  mouthfeel was full and rich . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .

hints of orange and lemon dance around the intense aged oak notes , giving this beer an amazingly original and interestingly complex nose . wow . flavor is much as would be expected after the nose . sweetness rivals the heftiest of wheatwine honey-sweetness you 've experienced .  it pours a nice light amber , maybe more of a copper in color . a tad disappointing with a slight head the did fade a bit , there is some slight lacing on the sides of my glass .  had an appropriate lower level of carbonation that many ris can not compete against . rich and thick on the palate . very warming .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever tried . good amount of pumpkin . clean and delicious . lighter side of medium in body . not sure if this is a drastic improvement from regular pumking , but this is surely tasty .  poured into the typical ale house 20oz nonic pint glass . '' appearance : the beer pours a deep amber red color with a thin off-white head that does not last . i do n't think i have ever had a beer poured at the ale house that did have a nice head though .  the mouthfeel is excellent .

aroma of a quad / stout mix with the figs , plums and spices plus a hint of grape hi-c infused vanilla . full bodied , viscous without being cloying , chewy . the alcohol is amazingly restrained , not even the inherent warmth you 'd expect at this abv level .  appearance : dark brown with a tan , creamy lace . there was a hell of a lot of sediment in the bottle .  perfect in this sense .

this smelled like freshly ground coffee , chocolate , muffins , brownies , and finished with a roasted woodsy character . wow . i want to dip my whole face in this beer .  poured into pint glass a : dark , opaque looking . very little tan head that quickly dissipated . i am new to drinking porters so i 'm not sure if a frothy head is to be expected .  the mouth feel on this one is perfect . the head retention is outstanding and just adds to that smooth , creamy , malty , citrus finish .

s : extreme vanilla , boozy bourbon notes . otherwise this is solid . d : weighing in at 13 % abv , one gibcs could do you in ... yet , i think i could handle two ... and that 's saying a lot , especially after starting this session w/ one tripel karmeliet and one piraat ( both 33cl ) . an excellent extreme imperial stout .  a - reddish brown brew with a big head and a little bit of scattered lacing .  smooth and thick ( of medium thickness ) , with small abrasive bubbles ( in the best possible way ) . wish i had let it chill a little longer to see a greater range of flavors as it warmed , but still a nice experience .

the aroma is thoroughly enticing , presenting notes of buttered wheat , bubble gum , orange peel , banana creme , vanilla , and a touch of spicy , organic hops . all in all , a satisfyingly complex and tasty wheatwine from the talented terrapin brewers .  pours a light golden color with a thick bubbly off white head .  mouthfeel - very smooth with a rich body and muted carbonation .

one of the most appealing scents i 've ever came across : rich malt with heavy caramel sweetness and pronounced chocolate qualities , strong esters of fully ripen figs and dried cherries ; aromas are perfectly mellowed and reminiscent of good port-wine . rather airy initially butt seems to be quickly loosing carbonation trapped within medium body and gets rather flat . overall , a good bsda with remarkable ripen fig & dried cherries aroma . ( 330 ml , into tulip )  pours a clear , relatively pale brownish red . half finger light tan head formed on the pour then quickly dissipated . quite lightly and finely carbonated . essentially no lacings .  the mouthfeel is what really sets this apart . having had very few english cask ales , i do n't know if this is gold standard , but it is the best mouthfeel i 've had on this style beer .

huge deep malty scents , with lots of caramel and toffee and a nixe bit of earthiness , as well .  pours a murky brown-fuschia with an odd colored pink/brown head . not exactly a looker .  my favorite thing about this obviously the sweet rich malt character which adds to a very nice body for a beer of this alcohol content .

a : orange copper color , almost no head s : floral hops , not much else but thats ok with me . i love the way this beer smells ! t : tastes like it smells .  poured a deep orange color with good carbonation but no head to speak of .  mouthfeel very full and smooth .

the smell is fantastic sweet very floral and an under tone of citrus .  a - poured out a clear , dark burgundy color with a very small , thin head of off-white foam .  it 's as smooth as silk - perfectly suited as a dinner and desert sipper and easily the best porter i 've had the pleasure of tasting .

taste- delicious representation of the smell . strong hops up front , especially for a pale ale , then dry malt .  a - pours a crystal clear ruby brown with a thin layer of head which quickly dissipates leaving no lacing . very little visible carbonation .  perhaps there is similar inconsistency here , and i will be wowed by the bottles i brought home sometime in the future ... mouthfeel is by far the best characteristic , supple , creamy and light .

complex , unique , and very intriguing . lots of vanilla , caramel , and pumpkin with cinnamon , nutmeg , and allspice . big and flavorful , intriguing , and easy to drink in a non-session beer kind of way .  poured golden with a 1/2 '' white head . minimal head retention & lacing s : perfumy hops & straw t : straw , floral hops & akiss of malt up front .  appearance : amber , clear carbonated , medium head smell : alcohol , grapefruit , and citrus taste : alcohol , grapefruit , malts , hops , and slight caramel mouthfeel : smooth , slightly hard finish , can feel the carbonation ... it is amazing how smooth and unbitter this beer is for a beer with its abv drinkability : i will have this again , but may be one of the few that prefer the 60 minute ipa .

aromas are just awesome ... deep rich fruits , candy sugar , plenty of oak barrel , dark bread-like yeast character , and some orange peel in the back . maple and molasses in the sweetness , with just a touch of citrus rhind hops in the finish . not overly chewy , which was nice for this strength of beer .  this one pours very clear and almost `` light '' looking for an ipa , it 's a rather light amber with a puny head .  m : thick and rich , with a nice amount of fine , late-developing carbonation . perfect for such a big beer .

however , the smell is unbelievable . this is definitely a dessert beer .  poured this 375 ml green bottle into a lindemans flute . the first pour was clear golden with many tiny bubbles clinging to the sides . the second pour was murkier .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is a perfect beer to sip on on a lazy pm with no kids in sight !

s- smell is absolutely perfect . sweet , floral tones with a huge aromatic pineyness . t- taste is milder than expected from the ipaesque nose but good none the less .  it 's a dark lager with a brown-orange hue and very little head that somehow fades to less head .  the malt is well back but the beer still has a nice light body . the palate is a great balance of all that and a nice honey quality in the background .

this smells amazing ! t - the taste is good , not great ... yet .  hope i gave you something good.. a - pours a very hazy brown with small white head that latched onto the side of the glass .  mouthfeel is perfect and this is a pretty drinkable brew .

smells really really good , actually . i suppose old men are always less handsome when they take their clothes off .  a : 'midnight ' dark ( nearly black ) pour , with a slim head . good ringing lace that trails fang-like tendrils of tawny film ... but overall , eh it 's just an average stout , nothing remarkable whatsoever .  very excellent mouthfeel and drinkability .

s : grapefruit and evergreen needles . you can smell the aroma of bold hops from yards away . t : simcoe , welcome aboard .  i 'll be brief on this one because this is an experience that will be very different from person to person and the bottle temp is as important as its age in evaluating this beer . if you like big beer this is the circus fat lady of big drink it slow and share it with a friend . also this is a good beer to lay down and enjoy aged . malt , malt , malt ! !  mouthfeel : on the heavy side of the medium-bodied scale and creamy smooth .

a - black as can be with what started as a monster tan head that has died down a bit but still lingers s - big roasted aroma 's mingle with notes of vanilla . this is just what i look for .  not like motor oil , more like tobacco water . it 's damn near a hop bomb . very drinkable . i get a real dry finish from porters , maybe it 's relative to the color , but that dryness coupled with the hops makes me want more & more each sip i take .  entering the mouth , i immediately take notice of the huge mouthfeel on this . this is fluffy , powdery , quaffable , and has this charming soft carbonation that is typical of great beers . palate displays a superb spicy bitterness executed in incredible balance and harmony ( this and the mouthfeel are the 2 attractions imo ) , gentle woodiness .

extremely fruit-fillled aromatics - pungent apple sauce notes lead the way into a more diverse array of stone-fruit esters . lush oaky notes with a touch of bergamot in the finish - complexity grows as the beer warms . i 'm still impressed that the base beer can be improved upon by soaking up the best characteristics of the barrels it is aged in , but these special editions of harvest ale have certainly `` matured '' more than simply `` aged .  appearance : this pours a hazy brown color with no head .  what i really loved was the mouthfeel . very good for a lager style beer .

smells interesting and fun . the taste is floral and spicey .  this beer looks a bit too light for an english ipa .  mouthfeel : thick and smooth in every sense of the words -- a very pleasant experience indeed !
