smell is beautifully complex & bright , like i just walked into an herb garden : really picking up on the rosemary , floral notes that are big but gentle , something kind of savory like oregano , maybe some basil or mint notes in there . seriously , this is fantastic , i do n't think i 've ever smelled a beer like it .  bottle a pale golden , yellowish straw color . aggressive pour yielded little head , but decent carbonation and some nice sediment .  subtly carbonated , with a medium-full body and a delightful smoothness .

smell was amazing , coffee , toffee , bitter chocolate , sugar , fruit .  a- nice deep gold color , no head , but with med-high carbonation .  a - bright golden orange color with some chill haze present , two fingers of white frothy head that leaves thick froth-lace s - not too much rye here , just hints ... hops and bready malt t - hop bitterness up front , sweet bready malts in the back , only a hint of rye in the middle ... the malt backing is about as significant as it gets ... taste 's more like a straight up ipa than most rye beers i 've had m - hops tingle the tongue and give way to very thick , chewy malts that slide down nicely ... full-bodied and very enjoyable d - this is a reeeally well-balanced beer , i just wanted more rye flavor .

the smell is perfect , like cranberries , very tart and almost bitter . you can really smell this all the way up your nose .  a - poured out a clear , bubbly , light orange color with a small , white , fizzy head . not much in terms of lace .  this belgian pale ale has a strong cookie-like malt character and an exceptionally smooth mouthfeel .

this has one of the best aromas of an ipa that i 've ever had . sticky , piney , resiny aroma . i find this to be a very drinkable ipa .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass a - pours a dark copper with virtually no head . perhaps that explains the lackluster head ...  mouthfeel is really exceptional , which along with the smooth flavors is what i really like .

strong vanilla notes , sugar , and faint chocolate aroma..southern tier really has a knack for completely nailing the nose on their brews t - do n't know if i could drink any more than the 9oz i was poured . this is incredibly sweet , and extremely rich . a perfect dessert beer .  poured into a snifter on 7/5/10 many thanks to pdxhops dark brown in color , settling black in the glass . in fact all foam disappears save a ring . no lace .  thick lushious body and moderate carbonation .

exquisite critrusy , lemony aroma ; actually smells 'juicy ' . just amazing . flavour consists of traditional hefeweizen attributes with the addition of citrusy , american style hops .  very nearly black in color with good clarity on the pour . the head is a nice crema color but settles almost instantly .  feels amazingly clean and fresh while keeping the flavor of charred wood and grains . smooth , creamy , full bodied , and almost a velvet nature . the carbonation is played on in the background as an overcoat . the simplicity of it overwhelms me .

the smell is very fresh , crisp and clean ; truly wonderful . lots of citrus and pine aroma coming off immediately , mostly grapefruit with some floral grassiness as well , with some biscuity malt in the background . i could smell this a mile away and loved it . t : taste follows nose for the most part , leading off with citrus-pine hops with a sweet biscuity background . it 's fairly bitter , but the malt sweetness balances it just enough to keep it extremely pleasant and crisp . the taste was very fresh and very clean , ending as it began with a gentle , bitter , floral hop bite . the smell is exquisite , and the taste is juicy and not as dry as many similarly citrusy-bitter ipas , making it a bit more drinkable . with all the smaller breweries popping up in boston , and many focusing on more boutique styles , it 's great to see a new , local ipa that seems to be doing everything right without reinventing the wheel .  looks just like the dam straight .  m : the feel is excellent with fine carbonation lending a creaminess that is top-tier and a clean scrubbing finish with the right balance of crispness and aftertaste . d : an fine tripel with classic light fruit flavors mixed artfully with pepper and spice and a top-notch mouthfeel compose a very good brew .

very ripe strawberries and a bit of peach . not complaining , though ... one of the best aromas i 've ever encountered .  pours a bright clear straw-yellow color with a good inch of soft whitish head .  mouthfeel is really impressive . very gradual on the tongue and extraordinarily balanced .

smells great . big , overripe tropical fruit and citrus with a little bit of grass underneath . i actually coughed and spilled some while pouring and thought , `` man , that smells awesome ! '' while cleaning it up . still good , just a letdown after the nose .  dark brown color , slightly opaque , a 2/3-finger head that hangs around for a decent while before disappearing ; the drink does n't leave too much lacing behind .  again this is a beer with a very good character but i still feel it does n't perfectly balance m- incredible mouthfeel .

aroma is overwhelming with citrusy peach essence of hop . so sweet and spicy , very cali . i usually sniff for 15-20 seconds but this beer merits much more nasal enjoyment .  my old foghorn came in a 7 oz bottle warning me about the high strength of the beer . the beer was not highly carbonated either . the color was a light brownish-amber , and was noticably cloudy as well .  not the stunner i was hoping for m- beautiful mouth feel . i sure hope this is not the `` great sculpin '' i 've been waiting for for that past few years .

s : a very sweet and complex nose here . lots of caramel , toffee , dates , figs , raisins , and wood . t : not quite as impressive as the nose , but still damn good . lots of caramel , bourbon , oak , and apple .  produces a weak brown head with poor retention and no lacing .  the mouth-feel was what was remarkable to me , very thick and creamy , i would liken it to a stout milkshake , really satisfying and enjoyable to drink .
s : the best smelling coffee oatmeal stout i 've smelled to date .  presentation : on tap . appearance : hazy amberish brown .  perfect carbonation .

tasted june 25th 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - deep copper , one finger off white head and some lacing s - lots of alcohol , very hoppy , pineapple , pine , grass , very yeasty , sweet malt , sugar , high octane everything , flowers , grass and tons of everything awesome t - really sweet up front and than a wall of bitter . this is a great ipa . i am starting to be a big fan of yulesmith final thought - 8 % + abv and only $ 7 a bottle . this one is worth it and if you find this on tap somewhere , please email me  pours out a deep clear . almost amber , very llittle head , a bit of lacing .  the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth and creamy , terrific . thanks bif for the sample .

this is , to date , the finest smelling pilsner i 've had .  a straw-colored pilsner that pours with an initial frothiness that falls quickly leaving a little bit of lace .  outstanding mouthfeel ! very drinkable .

s : the bouquet is quite vibrant , with grapefruit and pineapple jumping out of the glass .  bottle poured into pint glass appearance : nothing to write home about . light lacing , amber-gold in color .  mouthfeel is big full and smooth very rich and easy drinking with a really satisfing warming in the gut .

a very attractive beer . powerful aroma . moist , sweet raisins at the forefront , with bitter chocolate , roasted malt , soy sauce and sweet sherry behind .  golden amber color , thin white head that dissipates very quickly . extremely drinkable , with a lot of flavor while it is in your mouth but no aftertaste , so it begs for the next sip .  taste- for a double ipa , this beer is not on a mission to wreck the palate ... with so much flavor i 'm surprised that the malts weigh in so heavily . solid . it 's sudsy ( the name of my beloved late parakeet ) and sublime . drinkability- one real attribute about this bruiser of a beer is that the abv ( 10 % ) is completely hidden ... it 's nowhere in any of the above categories . this is more like a nectar , thick and juicy , garnering respect for each sip .

quite delicious , but not quite as good as the nose led me to believe . m. thin with a good level of carbonation d. i was a bit disappointed with the taste after the incredible smell , but the mouthfeel is really what let me down here .  pours a deep amber from the bottle , off-white head that dissipates quickly leaving thin lacing .  super creamy mouthfeel w/o any overcarbed bite .

the smell is wonderful . tannin , grapes , apples , apple peels , raisins , caramel , touch of cocoa , and a hint of alcohol .  there was pretty much no head , but a bit of lacing around the sides .  loved the residual stickiness . d- it 's remarkable how fff can make such big beers and hide the alcohol so well .

the aroma , however , is a-one , outstanding , and really well captured in the wineglass : nice , fresh pumpkin accompanied by strong notes of cinnamon , nutmeg , clove , maybe some ginger ... wow , this is the smell i look for in my pumpkin ales - imo they nailed it . that said , i feel the flavor takes a step back ; maybe the nose raised expectations too high ... still very nice , with the pumpkin and spices pulling through , but perhaps not as robustly as the nose had led me to believe ; there 's also a not entirely pleasant though subtle bitterness to it , as well as a bit a boozy bite to the finish .  6 % abv 45 ibu a : straw-red in color with a good amount of haze . there is a decent off-white head that floats atop this brew .  delicious . and i think what makes it delicious is not entirely a taste thing , but a feel thing . so smooth and creamy and round without any heaviness or stickiness . and it 's an appropriate textural delivery for the huge fruits here ( again , fig , plum and raisin dominant ) ; smoky cherry continues to remind of pipe tobacco ; a more general/generic smoke flavor nicely sneaks in with warming ; and there 's a milky chocolate essence entering into the flavor that i did n't detect in the smell .

the smell of tangerine jumps right out at you the moment you free this beer from the bottle . tangerine just fills the room . this is a unique ipa . fruit fresh from the tropics start this beer off . mango maybe ? the flavor actually kind of mutes itself in the middle and the hops kick in during the finish and stay . the hops are very citrus in nature and somewhat floral . i do n't detect the piney nature of a lot of ipa 's .  there was absolutely no head or carbonation and even a vigorous pour resulted only in some air bubbles on top .  full of body and creamy goodness .

head is a bright off white , watery and light , not much retention or lacing ... outstanding aroma , very funky floral muskyness , some nice brett ... taste has some nice things going , this is a musky sour brett saison , not sweetness , makes no bones about it . crushable musky saison , well worth trying .  750 ml bottle , great label , opens with a champagne like pop , a : pours a deep red umber to brown with an initial three finger head which recedes quickly to a smooth cap of foam , no lace is a surprise . arguably the most authentic belgianesque mouthfeel i 've had in an american made , belgian style beer , reminds me a ton of achel brune in this respect . very impressive .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with a dry , perfectly carbonated finish . perfect for the style .

poured from a growler into my new holland high gravity series glass a - black as can be with a small circle of tan/brown head s - tootsie rolls with a hint of hersheys chocolate . is this really a beer ? t - tootsie rolls with a hint of hersheys chocolate ... seriously though a little more going on in the flavor however .  appearance = pretty average looking clear , light golden straw-amber . not much head at all .  creamy but thin body .

s. tons of beautiful hop aroma - a spring day in a can .  sweet f.a head , leaves a spiderweb of lace atop a very dark body , little in the way of highlights when held up to the light . there are lots of bubbles breaking the surface though which is odd for a porter .  mouthfeel is wow smooth , and drinkability is amazingly good .

the aroma is nothing short of amazing . it immediately presents with big raisin , molasses , strawberry , and bubblegum . i have had most of the unibroue beers , but this was really outstanding even for them .  a : copper-bronze , off-white head , no retention or lace .  body is n't the first thing you notice , but once the distraction of the sour wears off , you realize this brew is very smooth , neither tacky nor sticky , nor drying . carbonation can be swirled up , and compliments the feel of the sour in your cheeks quite well . all in all , a crazy departure from the normal dfh offerings and dang fine weissen .

amazing , both the most unique and best smell i have in a beer in a good long time . taste- a strong and front malt body .  the beer pours a dark brown color with a frothy beige head foaming up and fading quickly to an edge layer .  the mouthfeel is great , for the bittersweetness from the roasted malts provide the ideal amount of oomph to an otherwise creamy body .

huge tropical fruit aromas on this one -- passion fruit , mango , pineapple and bubble gum . creamy , with a good warming alcohol finish .  dull orange straw color with a little haze hanging around , the head starts off big but then falls to a thin layer of lace .  in addition , there are hop oils , caramel , some sweetness and perhaps molasses along with a medium body that is oh so smooth and coats the mouth well . delicious and well balanced .

robust cherry smell that is fantastic . taste is almost all cherry , wheaty malt underneath .  a : cloudy yellow/orange color with some suspended solids . broken , thin lacing ; none near the end .  excellent for it 's style .

an interesting double ipa with a very malty edge and bitter finish . smells of floral hops , much caramel and honey and autumn mornings . honestly it smells a lot better than the taste .  pours a clear yet deep amber with a fast two finger , receding head . very little bubbling and no lacing , but good color though .  very full body that stretches the cheeks . just such chewy hops .

smell is delicious ; porter , plus chocolate , plus raspberry . highly encouraging . so wonderful up front , so nasty in the back .  pours cloudy pale yellow with minimal white head .  a nice chewy , creamy malt backbone makes each sip a pleasure .

it smelled like very strong dried apricot hops , sweet caramel malt , melted butter , and a hint of oak and alcohol . it was fairly complex , but was still clean .  pours clear golden with a thin white head . the appearance is not much to write about .  some of the best damn mouthfeel you will ever get in a beer too .

the nose is incredible as it is with many of de dolle beers . big floral esters , mint , lemon , sweet malts and subtle but detectable hops . amazing brew , perfect for summertime , actually this is drinkable anytime ... beware of the burps !  pours an orangish-amber into a pint glass with very little foam .  the mouthfeel was awesome - very creamy and full bodied .

5.0 s : wow ! this is n't the strongest smelling dipa i 've had ( it 's up there ) , but it is the most harmonious mixture of citrus i 've ever experienced . pineapple and mango are the most intense , followed by orange , tangerine , and grapefruit . 3.5 t : the taste is a bit disappointing after the nose . 3.0 m : lighter medium body , but it strangely lays heavy on the tongue . 3.5 d : pretty good , but one of the reason i really like dipas are for the awesome creamy mouthfeels .  pours a really fizzy white head over a cloudy peach-colored liquid .  perfectly suited for sipping and just right for the flavor .

it smelled of fresh lemon zest and pine and as it warmed i got notes of warm brown sugar , like fresh cookies which was most likely a result of the honey used in the brewing . the beer tasted very good , bitter but also smooth however the mouthfeel got a bit harsh nearing the end with the ethanol burn .  recieved this bottle froma friend at ab in st. louis . not a test bottle , but , a production bottle . a : milky brown , tan puffy head . nice lacing .  m - amazing . low to moderate carbonation ( expected ) and full bodied .

aroma : very complex . banana , clove , butter , bubblegum , and hints of alcohol .  pours a dirty red-brown in color and only a very thin ring of a head clings to the glass . no lacing .  wow . the thick and creamy mouthfeel is perfect for the winter months and so warm .

this is very easily the best smelling beer i 've ever whiffed . taste is very disappointing . the smell is this brews strongest point , but it is also the source of the beer 's greatest flaw .  big malt aroma ( munich-type , sort of crystal but with a light roasty component ) with some grainy cereal notes . seems a little light colored for the style , just barely off gold , with a touch of haziness . smallish head that fades after a little while . very nice malty profile . hop bitterness is well in balance but still very subtle . clean fermentation .  m- perfect for the style , ca n't say anything more .

big on the aromatics ! perceptible alcohol is offset by a great earthy wood character . perfect for the style . flavor brings on even more fruity ( apples mostly ) malt and alcohol sweetness but it 's held in check by the equally healthy dose of hopping .  a little head retention & no lacing s : slight earthy hops up front then a little fruittyness t : piney hops up front followed by fruittyness & a slight grainyness .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth , thick body , low carbonation .

aroma is a staggering , fresh , really rich chocolate .  i 've had plenty of these in my day , but this is the first i 've actually sat down with to review ... a - pours a slightly cloudy , orangish copper color , a little darker than alot of ipas . head grows to about 1 inch before settling down to a thin outer layer .  smooth and creamy , very soft carbonation . booze is extremely well hidden .

smell : smells like a nice rich coffee from sbux with tons of caramel added .  exceptionally fizzy cloudy and golden appearance .  first sip reveals a smooth and slightly creamy texture , carbonation is almost non-existent as cask ale should be .

s : wonderful nose . toasted notes with some malt character hiding behind it .  beer arrived with almost no head at all . color was very dark , almost appearing black at first .  it 's just smooth and thick enough to feel perfect going down .

above average head retention & lacing s : lemony with white pepper & orange peel t : follows the nose , also some breadyness & candi sugar , apple peels & general spiceyness up front . finishes with apple peel , lemony & herbal hops & a lovely spiceyness & just a bit of grapefruit at the apex mf : medium bodied , lively carbonation , very nice balance superb drinkabilty i could stay on this all night !  pours murky muddy brown with large bubbled brown head .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and exceedingly refreshing .

smell : absolutely delicious . the hops really fused well with the cedar in this case . love it . taste : it is a very sharp flavor .  cloudy , dirty orange color .  its very smooth and velvety , very nice .

s : smell is exceptional . tons of chocolate and brown sugar . o : a great smelling beer that just has too much alcohol taste for my palate .  otter creek turns out some very drinkable beers , but often the brewery has been short on experimentation . unexpected notes of grapefruit and light burnt sugar open the nostrils . the taste is richly satisfying yet not overpowering , with a good balance of malt and hops . mouthfeel is quite good - in this case , a little bubbly , a little syrupy - and in all this is a beer one could drink at length .  the taste and mouthfeel is where this beer shines . thick , smooth and creamy with a combination of milk and dark chocolate with just a hint of licorice .

mmmmm , a smell like none other . besides aroma , this is a mighty tasty beer ; absolutely my newest favorite ipa . i could drink a couple of these at once , but like many highly flavorful beers , not my kind of session brew .  appearance : pours an opaque bronze with a thin bubbly head that quickly disappears smell : a strong burst of malt and a bit of hops on the finish taste : toasted malt dominates , but there is a subtle spicy finish not apparent in the aroma .  the mouthfeel is dead-on creamy .

that 's a good looking chunk of froth . huge aroma with lots of piney , grassy and citrusy hop smells . mmmmm . very spicy piney hops mostly though with some alcohol and a tad bit of malty earthy smell . this is a marvelous beer that i wish i could get my hands on again .  dark brown hue with slight mahogany tints when held to the light . little head , which settles to a cream ring .  m : remarkably full bodied and smooth but it does n't have any stickiness , carbonation did it 's job , excellent .

a : opaque , poured with small bubble head , thin veil of head , gives way over time to bubbles on side of glass but when glass is rotated there is still a ton of carbonation trapped in the beer s : full bourbon nose , malty , bourbon dominates , treacle , vanilla , intense t : full-flavored , extreme malt and bourbon flavor , not a great degree of heat , i love bourbon but it seems just a bit too much , toned down once beer warmed up m : warming , rounded , creamy , good body and mouthfeel without tons of etoh , strong bourbon aftertaste  pours a deep amber color with garnet highlights and a thin head that falls quickly .  the mouthfeel is great on this one too , effervescent and full at the same time .

the aroma is intoxicating , deep and bold arabica coffee notes upfront that is fruity and intense . high quality cacao , molasses , pepper , cherry wood and a wallop of alcohol ... really outstanding . the flavor is a letdown from the aroma , with a broad sweetness that kind of smothers the coffee and roasted notes , some cherry and plum notes in the background and an alcohol bite finishes things off . an incredible aroma almost makes up for the cloying sweetness .  appearance - pours a festive reddish amber .  mouthfeel is very thick and chewy , silky and long lasting on the palate , near perfect .

as soon as i opened the bottle , i was smacked with a heavy hoppy smell , easily reminded me it 's an ipa i 'm dealing with . s : an amazing combination of hops , pine , citrus , maybe some grape . t : interesting , with the token ipa hoppiness being the most notable aspect of it all . d : daunting at first , especially for me , not a huge fan of ipas , but i have to respect this beer . the dynamic flavor-smell combinations are remarkable , and though it 's not my favorite , the never-departing flavor may be the reminder that it is something to be reckoned with .  eye candy : pours a transparent amber . plenty of rising carbonation . fizzy thin head , klacing lasted throughout session . otherwise , autumn is perfect for the fall , drinkable from early sept untill the snow starts a flying .  exactly how i like my stouts to feel -- heavy and chewy .

s : super hoppy . i love it . t : i 'm having trouble believing this is a barleywine . i know american bws are supposed to be hoppy but hot damn is this awesome . destroys your palate with an intense amount of hops .  poured from 750ml bottle into tulip glass . a : dark copper , head is generous and frothing but does n't live very long and leaves almost no lacing .  very big and chewy mouthfeel

two brothers heavy handed ipa : terrific aroma , very full and noticeable from several feet away . some heavy malt syrup aromas coupled with flowery hops make the aroma very appetizing . slick mouth feel .  i poured it into a glass and it had a small white head that disappered quick . it poured a very light golden color . while the beer was sitting on the table i looked down at it , the bottom of the glass was almost clear as water . it was n't intense .  lush , creamy mouthfeel , that really could n't improve at all .

smell : so wonderful ... the smoky peaty aroma fills the nostrils . cloying . i really did n't care for the sweetness of this beer .  2010 vintage : appearance : brownish amber color , crystal clear , small 1 finger head with no lacing and little retention .  perfectly carbonated with an amazing mouthfeel .

and all very fresh . smells like being in the woods and breathing in a fresh , brisk , spring air in the morning after it 's been raining . it almost `` bites '' . not as complex in the mouth as it is in the nose though . m-medium bodied . i 'm not normally a fan of hoppy beers but this is so well made that you ca n't help but enjoy it .  appearance : rich amber red hue . no head whatsoever . poured very smoothly out of the bottle with good amount of sediment .  super thick mouthfeel .

s : the nose is awesome . coffee . just so much going on .  pours a thick deep black with a very thin tan head . no retention , no lace .  the first thing i noticed actually was the incredible mouthfeel .

that 's what i get in the nose . fresh hot bowl of oatmeal delivered fresh to your nose with dallop of caramelized brown sugar and a heaping of fresh raspberries . a deep burgundy/purple color , it almost looks like a shiraz . i love the complexity and uniquness of this beer , but it tastes too much like a wine cooler for me to love . i just ca n't handle all of the fruit .  2004 vintage pours cloudy light brown with a few bubbles , but no head retention to speak of .  smooth as hell , perfect weight and carbonation .

this beer was very jeckyll and hyde for me . the smell is also terrific : citrusy , apricot , peach ( as others have noted ) .  small craft warning is a hazy golden lager with a somewhat diminishing , soft and splotchy , white head .  mouthfeel is sublime . kind of like a benign dreamy tingling that coats the palate evenly .

it is overpoweringly fruity and has an amazing aroma . it pours a cloudy light rose pink with a huge head.you are overwhelmed by the raspberry nose .  a decent sized white head that dissipates quickly over a macro-brew-looking yellow-clearish beer . not a great appearance . but i really , really enjoyed this one despite its underwhelming appearance .  mouthfeel is absurdly rich and creamy , silky smooth and slurpalicious . ) it 's the best feature of this brew . i mean , i like the taste , love the mouthfeel , and would enjoy having two or three of these , but that abv is on the high end .

smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing .  appearance- poured a cherry , dark brown color with almost no head ! strange .  the mouthfeel of this bastard makes the beer for me -- incredibly soft and smooth for strong ale , probably the result of the oaking .

overall , a seemingly pleasant ipa , that tastes wonderful at first , but then bites back too hard and dies flowery . still pleasant on the nose and eyes and foretaste though .  very drinkable.it is refreshing to have a microbrewey beer , that is not that bitter , and very drinkable.gets you very drunk.be careful because the alcohol creeps up on you with this beer.tasted citrus.i also tasted a bit of nutmeg in the aftertaste.this beer is very easy to drink.exceptional drinkability . this is the quintessential summer ale.a light , very drinkable , however , complex enough to be a microbrewery beer.i highly recommend this beer . this is a good recommendation to the general public.inasmuch as this beer is drinkable and light , many people will enjoy this . moreover , what is cool about recommending this beer , is that many people are not aware of this beer and micro beer 's in general.this was a perfect find on a june saturday , great beer to have at a high school or college graduation party.this is a great party beer , and will generate conversation at a graduation party , because numerous people have not heard of brooklyn , even suprisingly , in new york .  mouthfeel : smooth and creamy . alcohol warmth .

aroma : lush and full of fruit , beautiful and deliriously deep , slightly spicy , with further fruity develops , cherries and berries , but burnt . juicy hops and rich malt jump out through the nose , a perfect barleywine bouquet .  a - pours a clear light amber . a 1/2 inch white head forms into a thin layered collar .  the mouthfeel is smooth , thick , and creamy .

the nose was spectacular . sweet tar , coffee , chocolate , sappy wood all leap from the glass . molasses and brown sugar are buried within the beautiful , rich nose . overwhelming loads of flavors battling for attention .  it pours pale , cloudy gold with a thin near-white head that really does n't hang around to party .  this has an excellent mouthfeel .

vanilla , oak , maple leaf , faint rum aroma , and most of all ooey gooey caramel - sort of like a caramello bar . t : bittersweet chocolate layered with oaky and vanilla flavors , a caramel filling , and a coffee finish . i would even go as far to say this was luxurious or elegant .  pours a murky brown with a thin ring , not the most attractive beer at this point .  high level of carbonation with tons of tingle on the tongue . another excellent beer from ommegang .

the smell is extremely interesting , behind the hops it just reeks of fresh peach to me . i kept sniffing the beer throughout my time with it , just because it was so much fun to get that strong of a peach smell from a beer .  served chilled in a raftman tulip . appearance : murky reddish brown topped by a small light tan head . very little retention and no lacing , though i suspect this is ok for the style .  the mouthfeel was the best part : silky smooth and creamy thick ; a perfect accompaniment to dessert .

look : it poured a transparent orange-brown colour with a thin tannish head that did not disappear smell : exceptional . it smells delicious . a little sour with some sweetness in there .  poured into my guinness 20 oz glass , no idea when this was bottled ... there is no date listed on the bottle a-pale orange color with a small inch head s- sweet pale malt , flowery and fruity ( citrus ) hops t- very flowery , earthy , oily hops with a subtle citrus fruit taste .  the mouthfeel is amazing , thick and solid with a lingering savory finish .

light tan head for a second , poor retention and lacing ... the aroma is sweet with lots of nice sweet bourbon on the front . its a really nice smooth bourbon , makes you really want to drink it ... the taste really lets me down sadly .  pours dark brown , small tan head quickly fizzes away to a thin ring .  if you have to choose buy the triple , but as stated earlier this beer has a wonderful silky smooth mouth ... great feel for those who have an oral complex ...

m- thick and oily , slick and refreshing . d- very tart and complex flavor combination of hops .  appearance was a bit light in color and with less head than i would 've expected , but you do n't taste with your eyes , so i 'm willing to forgive that this beer is not terribly photogenic .  so very soft on the palette - really a unique mouthfeel , just velvety smooth .

very nice presentation . aroma is forresty ( real word ? ) with grassy , herbal , piney , sprucy hop notes along with citrus notes of grapefruit and lemon rind .  it is a medium brown brew with an ivory head .  the mouthfeel is a true hallmark of this beer .

the aroma is fantastic ; a huge hit of lemony citrus and grass with undertones of pale malt and yeast . excellent ; the best pilsner i 've tried .  a- pours a very pale straw yellow with a pretty white head that quickly dissipates .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

nose is fantastic ! uniquely fruity , like a cranberry-mango chutney . hops are detectable and make this a complex sniffer , probably the best smelling tripel i have ever laid nostrils upon . fruit levels take on the best from belgium , impressive . very nice brew , might be my favorite that i have had so far from the bruery .  cloudy straw colored brew the a decent head and a bit of lace sticking as i drink .  m - perfect . exactly how a dipa should be .
absolutely wonderful ! t : unfortunately , does n't quite live up to the aroma .  it pours a clear amber color ? ? ?  extremely satisfying in this regard .

quite impressive - i just could n't stop bringing this one to my nose .  i would prefer the appearance to be a little more hazy & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; but this stuff comes from germany so i guess these guys know good beer & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; the smell is reminiscent of banana i do n't get too much clove to it & gt ; & gt ; i also ge an earthy smell too & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; it tastes just like it smells & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; very easy to drink & gt ; & gt ; & gt ; watery mouthfeel not my favorite beer style but excellently true to style !  mouthfeel is about perfect , and the body is about perfect for a bock style .

a good looking beer that smells perfect , but ca n't hold up in the taste realm .  not much in terms of head , and what is sits atop a body of dark ruby . ahhh , lifts the nostrils into the heavens and beyond into the great void of ecstasy .  very light carbonation and a perfect body for a porter , combined with what i have already mentioned , makes this a very drinkable proposition .

very sweet , but extremely complex . awesome . taste is intense sourness and bitterness , which tapers off to not much else .  a shy color of inbetween orange and yellow . a nice foamy head that goes very fast , nice carbonisation as well .  mouthfeel : truly phenomenal creamy medium body with the slightest touch of syrup likeness .

the aroma is that of fresh american hops that have been sitting in the aging tank for a while . this beer is dry hopped every day for a month and the aroma tell the story . citrusy aromas that gram the oral senses and tell a story of freshness . it is surprisingly balanced and the hop aroma and flavor is a real treat . score : my personal taste score was a 93 / 100 .  the beer pours dark , not much head exists but enough to know the beer has bubbles .  mouth : velvety good . nice water . sweet , full , but not thick . medium to full bodied .

smell - a wonderful yeast or dough or wheat smell dominates , with orange or another citrus fruit tagging along . irresistibly smooth finish , tastes much the way it smells although the wheat is less noticeable .  - pours a nice cloudy hay yellow with a little orange glow to this murky wheatie looking brew . minimal large bubbly white head quickly dissipating to little to no foam at all.. left looking a touch watery.. which really is kind of expected from the style.. though it 's still rogues pacman yeast which is used in just about everything of theirs .  mouthfeel : true german feeling on this beer . medium viscosity , rolls across the palate smoothly and is perfectly carbonated . great overall feel and authenticity .

aroma is excellent . it 's full of fresh hops , citrus and pine .  a : pours very thick , big head with lots of lacing . color is a deep brown , very cloudy , little chunks of sediment dancing around making it look like apple cider fresh off the press .  ( m ) - this is ridiculously smooth despite its hop dryness and woody bite . great carbonation level and balance .

overall pretty good .  12oz bottle , no date , in sa glass a : black with a one finger tan head that goes to ring rather quick s : roasted malts , espresso , oats and a little chocolate t : coffee , faintly bitter chocolate like bakers m : full body , little carbonation quite creamy d : enjoyable could have more than one .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel .

very nice . the taste is very unique .  a_pours a medium golden brown with a minimal off white head with little retention or lace .  there 's a fair amount of carbonation that you feel in the swallow .

the nose of this beer was amazing - grapefruit , orange , mango , and pineapple and pine . the taste is just about as good . wow . mouthfeel was medium and mildly carbonated .  it has a beautiful rusty reddish brown color and tan head but it comes of as too soapy looking .  m : the best part of the beer . very creamy while still having a touch of that hop thickness you want .

smell is extremely fruity and surprisingly sour , extremely complex and enjoyable . aromas of apple juice , dark fruits , and a little olive .  not very much head on this one , but a little lacing .  one of the best mouthfuls ever !

murky , fluffy smells ... well , wheaty and sweety ! the perfect hefe .  tomos watkin osb pours a deep amber with just barely off-white two-finger foamy head .  the mouthfeel was creamy and medium-bodied with light , soft carbonation .

apricot golden body , tiny hop flecks visible and a classic ivory creamy , spritzy cap . the nose is very aromatic like a freshly prepped bowl of ambrosia . lots of ripe citrus in the nose , specifically tangerine and ruby red grapefruit . the taste is crisp , hoppy and i could tell upon first drink the mouthfeel is superb . i 'll say it , it 's overrated a little .  the beer poured more of a light gold color rather than the copper that the label described . about 1/3 inch of white head that left behind a watery white lace .  the mouthfeel was outstanding , felt like a cask beer , rich , creamy , smooth .

if you like hops , you 'll like this . it is overloaded with hops , but very very tasty .  a : pours a dark brown color . a thin tan head forms and recedes in an instant .  this is a big , complex , full bodied beer . the huge amounts of malts in this thing are chewy and even feel like they stick to the teeth some .

aroma : it has that rare smell that is as full and alluring as you 'd hope it would taste : banana bread , roasted chestnuts , cloves , hints of chocolate , estery and phenolic notes . the finish is very clean , with lingering bits of pepper and chalky dark chocolate . mouthfeel : it has a very smooth feel even though the carbonation is quite prickly . the dark malts give it a fuller and more flavorful character than most saisons , although incorporating them also reduces the peppiness and refreshment of a traditional saison . would i get it again ? : yes . it 's a solid beer , and though not the pinacle of its style , a welcome alternative to traditional saisons . bottled : february 25 , 2011 served : may 6 , 2011 price = $ 8.99 at whole foods ( nyc ) additional notes : - international bitterness units : 30 - malt : pilsner , rye , crystal rye , black malt - hops : pilgrim , saaz  it pours a lovely clear caramel brown with red highlights . very little head sits on top , and what little there is disappears almost immediately .  m : creamy and delicious . everything is dead on here .

nose is simply stunning . soaring sour limeade with an intense barnyard element , a good smack of leather , and just a hint of very sweet malt .  part of a taster flight , about a 5oz pour to a funkwerks tulip . pours a nice medium yellow with only a hint of haze , small white head that dissipates fairly quickly and no lacing .  it is dense . the mouthfeel is warm even though it was chilled . it is excellent as it warms in the glass .

smell : ah ... it 's been a while since i smelled something so interesting , so refreshing . sour concord grape juice , light farmy funk , an undercurrent of yogurty lactic tang , nutty sherry , and oaky port . really , a great nose . taste : sour through-and-through , with a spicy , envigorating tartness that swells in intensity as you hold it on your palate , then dissipates slightly before a clean , bracingly tart finish . very good , very bright , and very refreshing , but i do wish there were a bit more depth in the malt profile . this is exceptionally flavorful , interesting , and drinkable , especially at only 6 % abv .  a- pours a hazy brown color with a one inch head that dissipates leaving almost no lacing .  medium bodied , excellent mouthfeel .

smell is a tart , floral aroma with crisp , clean edge ; simply put , it 's delightful . this ale 's taste is a crafty hop blen dover a clean , crisp start .  i 've had the bottle , and there is some weird floaters in there , but they did n't bother me . there is little head and is a nice amber in color .  the mouthfeel is perfect for the style ; adequately carbonated and finished silky and creamy .

this has got to be one the best smelling ipa 's out there . the fruity and hoppy flavours balance out perfectly to leave a tasty , dry , almost graperuit-esque finish which is just fantastic . this beer packs a mighty punch .  pours a cloudy brown with murky red highlights when held to light . smallish off white head dissipates quickly .  the mouthfeel is smooth and nicely done . excellent carbonation drinkability is good as well .

s : this beer smells incredible . huge vanilla aroma that is mixed with a huge coffee aroma .  the beer pours a dark copper , forming a 1/4 inch tan head . light spots of lace on the glass .  the mouthfeel on this is exceptional , so smooth will alcohol masterfully controlled .

the smell was everything you would expect from a beer as hoppy as this . the smell of hop oil was big .  fresh batch courtesy of viggo . pours a fluffed up retaining head , with lace remaining in glass.. smooth easy creamy drink , creamy and well-malted , well-carbonated .  the first thing i notice upon the first sip is the awesome mouthfeel on this one .

outstanding imo . a : normal , yellowish/orange .  appearance : pale orange golden with a slight chill haze . wispy white lace lays on top . notes : in true rogue fashion , this is a hoppy beer .  the mouthfeel is thick and rich with a nice amount of bubbly to round it out . the taste is full , many-layered . . . wonderful . a little vineous though .

s - toffee , cocoa powder , nutty , then as it warms sweet citrus oil , green pine needles . slabs of caramel mix with alcohol vapors and fill the glass with a robust sweetness . t - starts with a mix of semi/sweet chocolate , sweet toffee malt , then an undertow of hops rush in with mint and citrus . the aroma is so good it 's hard to explain .  in munich , appearance is not indicative of taste , apparently . the beer is super light , looks like a high life/budlight/corona . i loved this beer in the liter glass beer steins with a pork knuckle .  mouthfeel is perfection . perfectly carbonated and very refreshing .

deliciously hoppy nose - massive sweet fruit backed with gritty , resinous hops . extremely fragrant , and powerful . palate is less robust , with a subtle , but pleasant hop character riding over the top of a smooth , buttery sweetness . this leaves it extremely drinkable - very smooth and refreshing . an excellent and tasty little ipa .  a - poured a dark copper with a one finger khaki head and no visible carbonation . no retention and slight lacing .  the mouthfeel on this beer is almost perfect . a nice smooth drinkable beer .

aroma is huge apricot honey-butter you smell from across the room . amazing . super wowowowow . an incredible rich aroma : great smelling beer . taste is an underlying sweet walnut toffee with apricot honey-butter with a huge fruity citrus hop bitterness that lasts forever .  pours a hazy amber with a thin white head .  keeping with the chocolate milk theme , the mouthfeel is fantastic .

smell is one of the best ever , strong flowery , grassy smell . slight grainy smell also . you know what is about to happen .  demon fish , 750 ml bottle .  the balance here is seriously excellent though , and the mouthfeel is probably the best i have encountered in an ipa , period . truly a creamy elixir , perfect carbonation .

the smell is utterly fantastic , easily one of the best smelling beers i 've ever come across .  despite a vigorous attempt at a pour , i got no head at all .  mf : it has a thicker mouthfeel than i expected , and it was wonderful .

i just about busted a nut getting the # $ # cork off in one piece..ahh make that several pieces that did n't fall back into the bottle ... but after a long and arduos process the cork was successfully removed.. poured a dark brown ... relatively clear..absolutely no head ... mouthfeel is very uncarbonated..i love the nose ... molasses ... .brown sugar ... .dark fruits ( plums , dates , even burgandy cherries ) ..a bit of oak ... just an awesome smelling beer.. the flavors are similar to the nose but much more tame ... .dark fruits ... molasses ... oak ... good taste to this ... my biggest complaint is the loose mothfeel ... very uncabonated which gives it almost a watery texture ... seems almost thin ... overall , the nose is great and the taste is very good but the body leaves something to be desired..definitely worth trying ... i wo n't be buying any more though ... .  a- cloudy yellow with a small white head .  this has been sitting in the cellar for about a year and i am convinced it has the absolute perfect mouthfeel .

smell : best feature . raisins , a bit of anise , nougat , milk chocolate straddling dark chocolate all while riding a wave of mocha coffee . while good , it does n't live quite live up to the aroma . mouthfeel : carbonation is a bit higher than normal .  appearance : poured with a large light tan foamy bubbly head , that dissipated quickly to a thin layer leaving just about no lacing . the beer is a cloudy orange brown color .  mouthfeel - wonderful body with great carbonation and just beautifully drinkable .

the aroma of it is amazing , almost a pumpkin cider type smell .  poured from 64oz growler into 250ml jenlain flute glass . appearance : pours a dark reddish-brown color with a small off-white head that dissipates quickly and leaves behind no lave , but some foam floating on the glass .  it 's definitely thick , but it does n't feel anywhere near as syrupy as it looks . o : this beer has a great appearance and mouthfeel .

really smells nice . the taste mimicks the nose ... .nice balance between the cloves and banana notes ... also some subtle but enjoyable caramel maltiness .  a : pitch black color , no head , no lacing s : raisins , figs , sweet woodiness t : sweet oak , raisins , figs , smoky chocolate ; finishes with a nice smoky wood bitterness m : medium-thick , lightly carbonated , velvety smooth o : this did n't quite live up to the enormous hype , but it 's still a world-class beer nonetheless .  m - wonderfully full bodied , sticky , smooth . delightful .

it really reminds me of the nose i get off a really good heffeweizen ( spelling might be wrong , but there ya go ) . it 's a bright and inviting smell and makes my mouth water .  12 oz bottle bought from the wine cask in cambridge , ma pours rich ruby brownish red with a nice tan head at first which disappears quickly and does not return with swirling . if it was an older old ale i would not let this effect its appearance score , but i dont think this is very old .  great mouth feel on this one . no hops or bitterness present at first , but bitter in the finish .

nice maple , nice cognac pipe tobacco aroma going on as well as some nice syrup smell . great . t- initially , some nice matliness , caramel/maple , then some dry hops .  appearance : nice cloudy golden color with a medium head .  silky smooth thick bodied with a perfect amount of light carbonation and a ridiculously long lasting , balanced tart and sweet aftertaste .

sweet tropical notes , mainly mango accompany a major amount of hops in the scent . there was a lot i liked but overall very good .  appears a hazy yellow color and a heavy pour yields a thin , large bubbled head that fades to a sheen rapidly .  the moutfeel is exceptional - full bodied and thick with appropriate carbonation .

smell : by far the most enjoyable aspect of this beer . the smell is incredibly complex with a strong prune backbone and hints of everything from lemon to chocolate . i like smelling it more than drinking it .  finally got some last night on tap at mad mex . looks average , served in a snifter , no head , mild lacing .  first gulp of this was outstanding.. nice creamy , mouthfeel to it that just bombards your mouth with sweet , delicious beer flavor .

very sessionable , but only an adequate porter with the exception of the nose which is amazing .  pours an incredibly viscous murky brown with very little to no head or lacing .  mouthfeel : a smooth sugary viscous mouthfeel that is balanced nicely by the carbonation .

i absolutely love the smell on this beer , but i also love peaty islay scotches . the smell reminds me of a campfire on a beach , with the peaty campfire smoke , wet wood , and leather aromas . the complex aromas are a little subdued on the palate . tons of different flavors in this beer , but none really stand out in front .  light golden color ; a little lighter than expected . smells hoppy ( citric , very grapefruit-like ) with an underlying sweetness . hops are very flavorful ( citric ) and also bring a decent bitterness , but are never harsh at any point . very tasty and drinkable beer that packs a punch .  wonderful body .

the nose of this beer is simply amazing . pure fresh cherries , almost like a top notch but soft lambic . some light caramel and hops could be smelled as well , but mostly fresh fresh soft cherries . light caramel tone , but just very clean and malty . the bottle is a little disapointing to be honest , but on tap this beer is simply amazing . fresh cherries and soft clean crisp malt .  a pour down the center gave an initial 2 fingers of tan head , which diminished rapidly to a little foam around the edges ... a little disappointing . the dark color is n't opaque , if held to a back light . dark hues of deep red/garnet highlight the edges . no lacing either ( also disappointing ) .  mouthfeel is perfect - smooth and velvety without being clingy or cloying .

the aroma is absolutely wonderful ... full of freshly crushed green , leafy and sweet hops . nice . the carbonation is mild to moderate . pleasantly surprised by this one..i thought this was going to be another average pale ale , but this very enjoyable .  this pours almost black . not too much head and it went away a lot quicker than many other imperial stouts i 've had .  m : absolutely wonderful ... smooth & creamy .

aroma is whoa grapefruit ! nice brew , maybe a bit over the top , but for an anniversary brew , you do what you have to .  bomber , a : pours mahogany with a small off-white head , fair retention , light lace .  full bodied with creamy carbonation and a lingering sweet licorice finish .

smell- that of very fresh raspberries . not the fake sugared and candied scent , but a kind of smell you may catch at jamba juice when you order a smoothie . taste- a tad sour and tart at first , which turns to a nice sweet flavor . not as fresh as the scent was . tasted a bit like jolly ranchers .  pours like a pale ale , orange/amber with just a bit if white head . no lace . it 's a chili beer , who gives a damn .  m - perfect . it 's velvet on the tongue .

poured into a chimay goblet.. well , the name does n't lie ... this is a pitch black with a creamy but small head ... laces unbelievably though.. this almost has an ris look to it with its perceived thickness.. this has one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced ... it has all of the aspects of a great stout with an added extra of smokiness that reminds me of a nice thick cut bacon ... it 's just wonderful ... it 's loaded with roasted malts and i might even get a little touch of hops here as well.. just magnificent ... very rich roasted flavors here ... loads of dark roasted malts with that smoke that i was getting in the aromas mix wonderfully with a tinge of hops on the finish ( although not much ) ... there 's a thickness to this that belies the export stout style.. i would guess ris or double stout all the way here ... there 's a meatiness here as well that i would assume comes from the smoke.. it 's a nice brew , i know that.. i 'm really digging it ... i 'm very glad i got to enjoy this brew.. it 's loaded with rich dark flavors and the aromas here are ridiculously delicious.. the whole experience was terrific.. very nice export stout.. very drinkable although at 8.5 , it could hurt you quick ...  the body of the liquid was hazy , but i would hesitate to call it cloudy . as the head subsided , it left a very sticky lacing on the edges of the glass that looked like bar soap froth on a wash cloth . average for the style , but nice never-the-less .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is outstanding . it sparkles just enough to give the palate a good tickle , but not so much that it scrapes away all of its flavor .

the aroma kick is amazing , a strong citrus , fresh piney hop nose . overall , highly drinkable , in the west coast pliny type tradition .  appearance : poured with some off white foamy head that dissipated quickly after leaving almost no lacing at the top of the glass .  it 's wonderful . alcohol tingles a little in the mouth and it 's certainly present in the aroma but buried 'neath the fruity yeast . expertly woven into the beery fabric of this brew .

whatever , it sounds good . it pours a very deep brown color , just a hint of blood red at the bottom , with a small , short-lived beige head .  a - completely opaque black , lets no light through . head is a very light brown that settles at a film . lacing is average .  light carbonation , rich smooth mouthcoating sensation from the oatmeal .

smells awesome . if this tastes anywhere near as good as it smells , i will be happy . the smells are simply fantastic - if i have another bottle , i may just let it sit and inhale the fumes rather than actually drinking it .  since i have said it for all of the other beers i 've reviewed in this category , i will say it for this one as well : pours a clear , piss-yellow color with a small white head . head disappears quickly and leaves no lacing whatsoever . it 's my first asian beer , but when comparing with any of the american and mexican macros and even a lot of the europeans , this is top class .  mouthfeel is intensely smooth and velvety , creamy and luscious . lactic milk sugar contributes a boatload of palate-smudging heft . although it 's not one for sessioning , it has a sublime quality that makes you savor every sip .

s : a really interesting mix , i get a strong strawberry aroma mixed with a heavy caramel smell . there is also a nice hop/citrus aroma in the middle , some tangerine maybe . overall a really nice beer , very drinkable .  stone ruination ipa pours with a frothy off-white head which fades in a few minutes .  mouthfeel : deliciously smooth with a nice , crisp finish . the high alcohol content gives it a nice warmth as well .

in my opinion , racer 5 is one of the best smelling beers on the market . one whiff revels a cascade of piney and citrus hops aroma . it 's the quintessential west coast ipa aroma . for a beer topping out at 7.0 % , racer 5 is ridiculously drinkable .  poured into a piraat tulip glass . has a 1cm golden head with but does n't linger with some mild lacing .  a bit astringent . fantastic , full body with a very creamy feel -- pretty impressive .

smell is boatloads of grapefruit , orange rind , and lemon ; really fantastic in the aroma department . taste is brisk , with a light but flavorful hop attack , refreshing wheat tartness , and perfect carbonation .  pours with zero carbonation , and not as thick as expected . no head retention and has a dark brown body .  mouthfeel : excellent light and crisp mouthfeel which is perfect for this style .

s : smells phenomenal ! booze , oak , and sweet sugars upfront . breadiness on the backend . t : good . not great . has a nice boozy / oakiness to it , not a whole lot else .  my first brew from four friends , on-tap at flying saucer charlotte served in a standard pint glass a dark amber with a thin quickly diminishing head .  nice caramel aftertaste held on the tongue by the thick mouthfeel . creamy thick mouthfeel and modest carbonation .

sugary , carmelized , sweet smell . fruity pebble cereal is the overall smell result , very nice ! it 's smell is amazing . picking up a faint vanilla extract smell as well . delicious . it was hard to move my nose away from the smell . but , yeah ... lets get onto the taste . not as amazing as the smell , but still good . mouthfeel is creamy , and dry . while this beer may not be spot on for the style , it 's quite unique . it 's positives by far outweigh the negatives .  pours a solid finger of light tan head over a cloudy yellow copper liquid . looks like a wheat beer . no sediment was in the bottle .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth . an excellent feel .

aroma is fabulous , even at this temperature . delicious . well worth the $ 6 canadian that i paid for it .  murky amber with a golden hue . very thin , patchy white head .  mouthfeel is very delicious with some creamy notes but some nice crisps and sharp grassy hop notes .

a - pours an orange copper color with a layer of fine bubbles on the surface s - lots of piney and citurs hops , lemon , orange , just a totally amazing aroma t - grapefruit & orange upfront , sweet malt & a slightly bitter hop finish , a really flavorful hopbomb m/d - medium body with good carbonation , just a really drinkable beer , somehow its 10 % which you really have no way of knowing  a- cloudy amber body and a small off-white head ( barely any head ) s- sweet grapes , some sweet bready malts t- follows the nose ; at first sweet dark fruits , sweet malts and there 's some wheat body m- medium body with light carbonation and it 's almost syrupy o- i dig the style and this a good overall beer .  mouthfeel is great . just the right level of thickness here .

the aroma seems to transcend the dopplebock style with a delightful boozy elixier : notes of dark rum , brandy , sherry and the like . currants , produce , fresh grass , and a slight hint of citrusy hops provide a great balance to the smell . this is not a beer for the faint of palate . i 'm not exactly sure how i feel about samichlaus ... one one hand , it 's an exceptionally complex , well-crafted beer that probably deserves its own style .  appearance - this is peculiarly shiny and clear , almost a bright orange , with little head .  a festive arrangement with great depth mouthfeel : really nice - creamy and complex drinkability : good

amazing . t : sweet malt that has plenty of peat flavors that i love so much in scottish ales .  hazy apricot-looking color , left a creamy light tan coating after the clean-up of the initial opening of the beer , left some spotty lacing and some slight traces of carbination .  full bodied and silky .

smell : delicious and complex . truly a melange of different aromas . coffee bean , caramel , toffee , chocolate . wonderfully palatable . drinkability : very drinkable . excellent complexity of flavors .  here goes ... i bought the beer , a single bottle , in a grocery store in oristano , sardinia ( italy ) . does n't match the bottle at the top of the page , but it does say `` stout '' and it 's strong @ 7,7 % , so we 'll call it the ceres extra strong stout . enough background .  the alcohol is kept well in check allowing the finish to cascade over the palate with a ton of character and wonderful texture . strong , long finish .

s : cranberries , some grapes and apples . good hop character . very complex and well done aroma . t : finish is slightly bitter but nothing overpowering , with a warm alcohol character that becomes a little cloying .  my first ballast point . a- hazy dark gold topped with dog slobber .  initially the softness of the carbonation and the sweetness of the fruity flavors makes it like a sweet soda ( can anyone remember tahitian treat ? again with the yeast character and the near rancid presence ( the brett i presume ) , yet the overall soft flavors and soft feel are greatly appealing and enjoyable . the light , fine and bubbly carbonation brings an element of childhood fun to the drink ( how about fizzies , anyone remember that ) as it brings a tickle to the nose and tongue . light overall feel and great softness . soft and light and tasty ( again in a soda pop manner ) .

the beer is certainly lighter than i expected with an almost straw color . the nose on this brew is phenomenal ! i 'm immediately transported to magical grapefruit land as the beer screams citrus into my nostrils . there is a piney base note to this smell to that compliments the soaring citrus very well . not on hops of course , as the grapefruity citrus notes yielded to a piney bite on the finish , but rather the malt character . while still a world class ipa , i felt that the backbone of this brew just was n't quite as strong as i would have liked and the huge hop profile was almost overwhelming .  appears a light gold with a dense 1 finger white head that lasts for a minute .  the mouthfeel is velvety and thick .

s- very large coffee smell . great complexity . t- taste starts with sweet fruits and a little bit of chocolate then is balance excellently by fresh bitter coffee .  it looks pretty much just like an ordinary old dark beer . its really really black , the head that rises with a pour is small and off white , there is really no retention at all , no lacing .  m : a great , great medium body , that grazes you at the tail with sharp carbonation .

smell : the aroma of the beer is full of hoppy promises . oily pine tar resins combine with a citrus and tropical fruits explosions of grapefruit , lemon , mango and pineapple bombard my nose .  pours black with a few large light brown bubbles that quickly burst leaving a glassy top without even a thin ring around the glass .  very smooth and rich taste though and perfectly balanced . wonderfull to drink though think it should be drank as i do n't think that more age makes this one any better .

s : bold and healthy hop aroma . perfect ipa smell . t : dry and hoppy .  from notes ... had this on tap in prague at a chinese restaurant off of hastalska street a : dark copper colored beer with a small but lasting head s : not much , but some malt and hops ... t : much more filling and thick than a traditional pils m : smoother and thicker , but still crisp d : very good beer , a nice change of pace from the pils abound in prague .  thin in the mouth but heavy on the tongue . perfect for the style and the season .

s : the smell is quite amazing and complex in my opinion . there are some light hops initially noticed . overall , it is very pleasant . t : after the very satisfying smell , the taste was sort of a let down .  growler poured into a weizen glass . an aggressive pour at that , but the 3 fingers of foam reduces to a skim in short order . lazy streaks of lacing here and there .  m : an incredibly thick body and big , foamy carbonation . i love the way this feels .

s - bourbon , bourbon , bourbon , buttery toffee , roasted cashews , malted vanilla milkshake , tiny amount of hops , pecan pie , and harsh booze . this is the best smelling barleywine this nose has ever smelled . perfect . t - harsh and boozy , but delicious . caramelized sugar up front with tons of bourbon .  the beer pours a dark amber/brown , forming a thin white head that fades quickly .  fantastic mouthfeel .

the second surly can i got from my man joe aka ineedabeerhere . the aroma is quite hoppy , even with all this time in the can . pineapple , grape , carrots ? you can also smell a bit of alcohol in the furious , but only after sniffing the juice . the taste continues with the depth of the aroma , and i 'm loving it . it could use a bit more sweetness to accentuate the fruity hops .  pours a cloudy orange-ish straw with a small white head that quickly sinks to a very thin ring .  the taste is a rich velvety malt with an amazing mouthfeel and a fully satisfying richness .

absolutely amazing grapefruit , lemon , and orange aroma . also has a touch of sweet toffee and vanilla . this was a beautiful hazy golden pour , with typical cask frothy head . very well balanced flavor , then a wonderful dry bitter finish . this is an amazing brew , and the cask only adds to it .  this beer is brilliantly clear and is a very pale , gold color .  m - perfect for a porter .

the aroma was simply outstanding . i have tried a number of the best coffee beers but none even came close to the nose on this one . pure and simple . every time i smelled this , i imagined myself walking into a coffee shop . the flavor profile was not quite as coffee heavy as the nose , but it was indeed more complex . malty rich up front .  preface - i always rate brews to style ... a - very average . no head . or lacing .  smooth grit with comfort .

not much there in the way of lace ... s - i could smell the hops when i was pouring this ... beautiful floral aroma with a little citrus ... like putting your nose in a bag of fresh hops t - good balance for how much hop aroma there is ... more on the sweet malty side rather than bitter ... definitely a sweet aftertaste .  the pour leaves a beige fizzy head temporarily resting on a base of burnt , amber colored beer . head retention is only fair at first but dies quickly .  nice full bodied and well carbonated mouthfeel .

absolutely fantastic aroma , but let down by it 's flavours .  `` brewed with 4 gallons of pure maple syrup '' served in a shaker pint , t-town maple brown is a murky , rusty light brown with a thin egg-shell collar .  m- full , smooth mouthfeel .

break out the smoked sausage , the perfect beer to accompany it is here . alaskan smoked porter is beautifully smokey . one whiff makes you think you 're in a great deli , loaded w/ good smoked sausage .  batch 031-34/240031811 notes taken on june 4th a- no head and no lacing .  the carbonation is very low ( natch ) , the body silky smooth , and dead creamy .

it 's wonderful . t- initial malts , some yeast , bread and biscuity notes , and strong warming alcohol .  pours nicely into beer mug forming a reddish purple body with a thin reddish white head that has some decent retention and a little lacing , and decent carbonation .  mouth is rich and sticky yet wonderfully smooth .

it has the wonderful spicy aroma that the style should always have . slight phenols , cloves , a sweet bready malt and a beautiful underlying fruitiness are all there . it finishes very very clean and does n't linger at all .  good retention , no lace .  mouth is very crisp and finishes clean , excellent carbonation . leaves a nice tingling on the tongue . drink is very good i usually would n't want an ipa for a session beer but this one i definetly would have a few more for the evening .

t - not as complex as i had hoped for , but still good . starts off with bourbon vanilla flavors with some caramel malt sweetness mid palate , then big oak flavors with a bit of spice through the long finish .  pours a decent head , disappates quite quickly , not much lacing .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible for a milk stout .

intresting , very intens smell , very nice hop aroma , tons of hops , citrus flavour , very similar to pliny the elder , i want to taste this one t : similar to the nose but not that strong , wheat , tons of hops , citrus , sweet malts , nice slightly bitter finish , this could be the little brother of pliny the elder , but this is softer , not so strong , m : very smooth , very well balanced , d : very drinkable , alcohol is well hidden , i could drink this all day long , yammy , well done struise .  into a tulip , pours a decent head initially , with little lacing and no legs .  '' love the mouthfeel .

smells amazing ! t - not too much smoke , bet definitely present .  poured a dark orange . the head was nice at first . then it turned minute and the lace ( everything ) was eliminated .  m - perfect feel to this medium bodied brew .

how many citrus fruits are there ? this one has aromas of all of them -- i 'm picking up kumquat , grapefruit , lime and tangerine ( piney rind ) at the very least . all those citrusy hops i smelled are seriously restrained in the taste . from classic to extreme , from belgian to beefy american , from populist to just plain weird , dogfish head 's got it all . i 'd be their bitch in a heartbeat .  served on a tulip glass . a - hazy straw to pale gold pour , unremarkable head , short retention , fair surface ring and some lacing .  mouthfeel is extremely silky smooth .

i can also catch a slight nose of peaty scotch if i catch it the right way . fantastic aroma here .  goes into my goblet a very dark red with a small tan head that hugs the rim .  mouthfeel is full but not too heavy .
back to the smell - oak , but the lovely old sort . . .  pour was decent with minimal head and very little lacing .  mouthfeel : fantastic . rich without being syrupy . carbonation is just right .

a wonderful sweet , almost fruity smell after opening the bottle .  poured into snifter on 12/9/09 10/6/09 etched the bottle a - dense & hazy copper ; amber highlights . semi-aggressive pour yielded hardly any head . swirling is required to garner any semblance of retention . minimal lacing ; what 's there is sporadic .  but what might be the true feats here are , on the one hand , the quality and sock of the flavors given the abv , and the insanely creamy mouthfeel on the other .

smell is very strong , like a clove-orange christmas pomander . really spicey and orange-peely , with coriander , grass and soap . if this thing tastes as good as it smells , i 'm gon na love it . the taste is dominated by the clove , soap and cookie-dough malt . it tastes good , but not as good or as complex as it smells . alcohol is notable from the warm burn in the aftertaste . all around , a very interesting beer .  ) it poured a nice pale gold with a decent head that left quickly .  perfect carbonation and ridiculously easy to drink .

s-this beer has one of the most pleasant aromas that i have smelt in a long time .  on tap @ the brewery 03-26-09 pours a light hazy yellow , my friend ordered hefeweizen and i actually thought it was the dipa based on appearance .  a faint bit of tannins in the middle of the tongue starts the finish , which is incredibly long with trailing , vineous notes of chocolate and spiced orange peel . ya it 's a bit like those warheads candies , but it 's tucked in such an incredible silky richness .

the smell is great , roasted barley , choc , some hints of caramel , delicious . taste is fantastic .  courtesy of raindog , thanks sir body is dark brown and initially wears a tan head that fast becomes one of the quickest dissipating festival of bubbles i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel was great , it was very rich and smooth with little carbonation but it fit the stout just right .

s- smell is awesome . tons of tropical fruits pineapple , apricot , and grapefruit a bit of sweetness coming through from the malts . t- follows the nose really well . a very nice hop forward beer .  pours out to a clear dark brown , forming a modest light khaki head with average to poor retention and minimal lacing .  m : perfect carbonation .

aroma is exceptional , with a great sweet citrus smell that bursts from the bottle and makes you want to take a huge gulp . this is n't a horrible beer , and if you love bitterness , you should love it .  somewhat cloudy orange appearance.head that doesnt quit.wonderful aroma-oranges , spice , malt all reign supreme.dough boy-awesome flavor ! huge malt flavor-great spicy flavor.the orange highlights are really nice.coriander , peppery.huge full body-slightly oily.very well rounded overall.a killer beer-could enjoy this on a regular basis.really has to be the best unibroue product i have had .  the head portends the exceptional mouthfeel .

looks good , smells amazing , but the taste is very underwhelming .  bought a michelob mixed sampler 12 pack for $ 9.99 wow , big surprise here ! i may be a spring chicken when it comes to beer drinking but this was one of the better hefe 's i 've had and to think it comes from ab .  mouthfeel : it is crisp , light , and perfectly carbonated .

for me , this was one of the most appealing scents i 'd smelled in a long time .  pours out semi-hazy , though it 's bottle-conditioned and there is a thick layer of yeast in the bottle , requiring a firm pour to achieve a modest creamy light-tan head with poor retention and sparse lacing , leaving a thin layer of sticky clumps .  mouthfeel - great smoothness , i was inclined to take a deep draw at the outset , very quenching . restrained carbonation adds to the smoothness .

s : it smells great . fresh , crisp , hints of the hoppiness of an ipa . mf : very interesting and different . overall : very interesting and complex beer .  it is cold and looks refreshing . the beer is a hazy gold pour with only a small white edge layer of head . hmm . was hoping for a little more froth . besides the lack of substantial head a good example of the style i think .  medium body and a wonderfully sprtizy carbonation keeps it light and makes the tartness manageable .

rodenbach grand cru , abv : 6.0 % . s : big aromas of red wine , cloves , ginger , oranges , berries , juniper and liquorice . like a mix of glgg ( mulled wine ) and julmust ( a swedish type of soda , drunk at christmas ) . t : rich , sour flavours of red wine , cranberries , apples , oranges , cloves , juniper , liquorice , brown sugar and black pepper . it 's unusual to me ( but i like it ) . i do n't know what to say - it 's the sourness that does the job for my tongue . while i 'm all alone in the dark , the aromas and flavours bring a lot of memories and other stuff to my mind - i think i 'm going to enjoy more of beers like this in the future .  appearance : very effervescent . poured a absolutely clear golden yellow , very small off white head .  mouthfeel : wonderful balance all over the pallets and each taste-bud . the slightly raised abv can give cause to the minor warmth in mouthfeel .

smell is fantastic ! nothing but chocolate covered toffee in the nose , the lightest bit of roastiness , and a hint of nuttiness . i love it .  slightly hazy , deep reddish brown colour with a thin cap of light beige bubbles . a little spotty lace clung to the glass .  it 's exceptionally smooth with little carbonation .

amazingly complex . taste follows nose and begins with dark malts and honey sweetness .  a nice dark appearance . not much head and very little lacing down the glass .  m : very soft , finely carbonated medium body .

awesome looking brew . s : wow , what a nose on this beer . sweet smelling with fruity esters along with some spiciness as well .  remarkably i found myself in a bar in portland which was bereft of ipa , but , realising that one can rarely go wrong with a deschutes beer , i ordered a mirror pond . it was somewhere between amber and bronze with a slightly acidic smell which i would n't like to expand on since my venue was bigger on smoke than beer . this was a well coordinated and very drinkable beer with a reasonable feel ( lots of small bubbles ) . i find deschutes to be the most dependable brewery ( never a bad beer ) . good stuff !  really coats the mouth for an excellent mouthfeel .

the smell is amazing , strong coffee aroma , more so than any other coffee stout i 've had , easily the best aspect of this stout . the taste is a bit more reserved with the coffee as it 's hard to beat the strong aroma , but there is a good deal of coffee and roasted malt , hint of chocolate , and a decent bitterness in the end .  minimal head and little carbonation movement , smell : sweet molasses , alcohol , roast malt .  the lush velvety texture takes control of your mouth .

very interesting beer . you can smell the hints of black & blue berries which is quite nice . it 's got a sharp taste of fruit , it reminds me almost of a fruity wine .  it had a dark bras colored body not as bronze as i would have thought . there was a lot of tan head and lace . this is a very frothy beer .  mouthfeel is velvety and smooth . great length on the taste .
very good . t - starts out quite fruity , sweet and tart with heavy notes of strawberries .  certainly does n't look overly intresting .  m- the mouth feel is excellent for this beer .

aroma is wonderfully thick , gravity holds it in check . flavor collapses the experience , tremendous letdown as the scent gave much promise .  a - poured a dark , almost opaque ruby color with extremely little head even on an aggressive pour .  carbonation is just right . mouthfeel is full , lush , but the carbonation keeps it clean .

s- jeepers creepers there 's some bugs in there . super sour and funky with lots of acidity in the nose . t- so sour and tart with tons of acidity . bright brilliant sour cherries , strawberries and underipe plums .  appearance : murky reddish brown , very little white head , no lacing .  m - rich and thick , very chewy .

s - the spicy , phenolic aroma hit me as soon as i opened the bottle , and once the beer has a chance to open up in the glass it expands into notes of chocolate , dark cherries , raisins , almonds , pepper , cinnamon , and lots of clove . d - very complex beer that manages to avoid being overbearing despite the high alcohol and big flavors . the smell is absolutely spectacular , reminds me of samichlaus , but more interesting . the flavor is quite interesting as well , and i really like the way it finishes , but there is something about the initial sweetness or phenolic character that i find a little cloying .  was a little gun shy given my last wee heavy experience..aka mcewan's certainly not as dark as my last wee ... .more like a cola in color and clarity with a rich tan head , zero lacing .  m/d : full creamy body with light carbonation , pretty drinkable for 9 % .

the aroma of this beer is amazing ! hops hops and more hops ! very deep and complex . citrus , spice , pine ... but not much of the barley makes it through . wow this is hoppy !  poured from a 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass . a : not-quite-black dark brown with a tiny wisp of a tan head that materializes with some delay but does n't stick around long and leaves a few dots of lace . the lack of head made me wonder about packaging issues , although the flavor was excellent .  medium bodied beer combined with very active and tight carbonation combines to create an exceptionally creamy beer .

smells creamy/milky with rich , almost sweet coffee , chocolate , kaluha , cocoa , and a touch of green hops . absolutely divine . the flavor is roasty with burnt/charred malts , coffee , chocolate , and a medium bitterness .  got a decent head however is was pretty weak and died quickly . coloring is light yellow that i did n't expect at first but now i see this is a pilsner thinking it was a pale ale . i guess corn ? this beer is solid !  m- incredibly smooth with a nice carbonation .

the smell is probably the best part of this beer . sweet and herbal with a touch of honey , hazelnut , citrus of some kind . the finish is very dry . pretty cool beer .  a ) amber in color , about 1/2 inch of head , which was gone before i could get my nose into the pint . no lacing . the smell is like pumpkin pie . in fact , i said to my wife , this smells like pumpkin pie .  mouthfeel is where this beer really shines , and makes one understand why some folks are such lager fans . the balance in this beer is amazing , with everything seemingly in the right preportion .
