allspice cinnamon and nutmeg all very strong a beautiful smelling ! t-the spices hit upfront with an impressive strength .  kind of goofy throw back ( 50 's ) look bottle ( works well with the duke ellington i am listening to at the moment ... ) eyeballs ... straw with a brownish tinge , nice head , withstanding well , solid carbonation , nothing fancy nothing rancid nose ... bready , almost belgian esque but a bit breifer.. malt and subdued hops like honeysuckle rather than a full on bouquet.. pleasant enough mouth action ... a nice fullness without being heavy in the least , fills the mouth amply without over carbonation , the feel is excellent across the whole pallette , this reminds me of what a `` mild '' fullers esb would tast like , quite enjoyable , nothing overwhelming , just a nice malt ( not too sweet ) start and bare bones hops that finishes dry enough to not drown out the wonderfull mouthfell verdict : an excellent session beer , not as agressive as say long trail ale in america but similar in its ease of sip and nice full feel across the whole mouth .  mouthfeel : so smooth and creamy . very refreshing .

( s ) - a ridiculously rich aroma . awesome whiffs of oaky bourbon with sweet toffee and caramel with an even more glorious smell of cocoa covered dark cherries behind it . its strong , but smells really stinking good .  pours a reddish amber with a quickly fleeting rocky off white head .  very smooth and full bodied mouthfeel , with medium carbonation .

the smell was exceptional and exciting , with a remarkable variety of spicy tones that are too complex to describe . with great anticipation , i tried the first sip , which was heavenly . and then it happened ... a nasty aftertaste that i could n't quite place but did n't like .  500ml bottle bought from the vineyard , belfast ... poured a nice rich coppery orange colour . creamy head with some rusty hints poured quite small and then faded to light wispy layer ... no lacing and no carbonation to talk about ... aroma - nice strong , lightly toasted , biscuity malts , toasty bread , juicy fruits ( figs , raisins , oranges ) , strong nutty notes , caramel / toffee sweetness , some sea saltiness , the faintest of dusty / smokey notes , peppery hops , grassy traces ... taste nice strong spicy / peppery hop bitterness , juicy and vinous fruits ( raisins , prunes , bitter oranges , apples ) , strong toasted bread notes , caramel maltiness , burnt sugar sweetness , nutmeg hints , malt loaf notes , woody / earthy hints , some grassiness ... feel - initial sharp bite then mellows out ... light / medium bodied ... very very refreshing and drinkable - excellent session brew at 4.3 % ... overall - an excellent bitter ... i wish i had bought a few more of these.. definitely recommended..  mouthfeel is wonderful . very thick , full , coats the mouth wonderfully .

awesomely complex . taste : chocolate , chocolate malt , coffee , chocolate syrup .  a : pours murky brown with little head that recedes into nothing with no lacing .  the taste is initially of a very light porter and with a clean aftertaste that becomes a fruit sensation on the palate . the hop/malt balance is the real achievement here and it really contributes to the supreme drinkability . the smell upon opening the bottle is not an effective contrival of the taste that this beer is hiding as it only gives you an idea of the rooted flavor that is to be unleashed , the supreme balance and sublime flavor . great bier .

at long last i was finally able to snag the great westy 12 , pours a deep brown with a suprisingly thin head that was gone pretty quickly not leaving anything behind.whoa the aromas are just incredibly complex and rich , some almond and raisin almost a cinnamon bun type aroma to it , just awesome.flavors are more mellow than expected , i get some star anice and raisin up front with some mellow orange tinge in the lngering finish.i like the `` 12 '' better than the `` 8 '' but i have had some better quads but still a pleasure to drink for sure .  the beer is n't as hazy or cloudy as i remember , which is too bad .  m : wonderfully smooth . nice creamy texture that does n't stick too long in the mouth .

aroma is very inviting with apple , pear , and an awesome yeastiness . the taste is n't as fruity and glorious as the incredible aroma but it is nice and earthy . there is a great toastiness to it and great caramel , bread and diacetyl butter flavor .  appearance : tawny brown , quite hazy , thinnish layer of tan frothy foam , ok head retention aroma : rich malty caramel , tangerine , woodsy hops , raisins flavor : smooth malt sweetness with hints of orange marmalade , stewed prunes , hazelnuts , and herbally hops ; finishes semisweet with a brief fruity aftertaste mouthfeel : medium body , gentle carbonation , smooth and soft texture , slight warmth in the throat other comments : quite a scrumptious bitter .  great mouthfeel .

very complex . thin to medium body with tastes of malted cereal , light residual sugar followed by roasted and hoppy bitterness . i am still amazed by the complexity of smells in this brew .  bomber this one poured out light and orangey with a bit of chill haze . left a delicate lace on the glass .  great creamy thick mouthfeel , light carbonation .

a : beautiful deep dark red , with a foamy , rich head s : unbelievably fragrant of cherries t : this is a sweet cherry beer . yummy .  long trail- double bag appearance- orange/ cooper/ red with a small but respectable head that did a slight lacing along my glass .  very rich and full bodied , smooth , chewy , all while the alcohol is hidden .

this may be the best smelling pilsener i 've ever experienced . lovely complex , floral hop aroma . pleasant light grained malt in the background . overall , a superior beer .  from a bottle provided by doublej , thanks jon , a : pours a lightly hazy gold with a spotty light white head , average head retention , some lace .  mouthfeel is quite amazing , therefore the 5 .

the smell is extremely vibrant and spicy reminding me immediately of egg-nog . despite being very interesting and flavorful it becomes difficult to drink about halfway through .  appearance : a deep brown , with smaller head and lower retention of that head . nothing overly special , though i suppose it 's on the prettier end of things as far as brown ales go .  the mouthfeel was exquisite . tiny bubbles caress , going a little foamy , opening the flavor as it hits the back of your mouth .

the smell was amazing -- probably the highlight of the beer . it got better as the temp increased . overall , it 's a pretty solid novelty beer .  a : pours a nebulous reddish brown with a fast fading small head .  the carbonation is just right here .

s : the glass was a foot and a half away from my face and i could immediately smell a warm pumpkin pie coming out of the oven with a nice floral hops on the back . t : the spicy pumpkin flavor swirls with a strong caramel malt flavor .  black in color , but lacks head retention and lacing which brings this down quite a bit .  given the balance and great mouthfeel , drinkability was quite good .

s : smell is great . bourbon , vanilla , and coffee . t : tastes of bourbon , vanilla , and coffee with hints of toffee and roasted malts . d : this is very drinkable , especially for the abv .  appearance : light golden brown , slightly cloudy with decent head retention on the white head aroma : definate piney notes , with some sharp citrusy grapefruit in the aroma .  overall a really complex , fantastic stout , one i 'd be happy coming back to over and over .

s - a fantastic aroma of lemony citrus and wheat with pale malts and a light bouquet of floral hops . the thing that totally makes the aroma is the wonderful funk from the brett yeast . tiny fruit esters of mango and pineapple from the yeast also play a small but delicious role . very complex and inviting . t - a bright sour funk bursts across the tongue right away bringing with it that barnyard and horse-blanket that is so good . it 's definitely a lively beer . d - i 'm really happy i 'm sharing this cause a 750 ml to myself would be devastating for two reasons ; a ) to my sobriety , and b ) to my taste-buds .  a hint of wheat in the flavor and the wheat bitterness that i guess is part of the beer . this beer makes me want to go back and try another sweet water blue ( a beer i didnt like much on the first go ) a beer i could drink some of i think , would pick it up for a pick-me-up .  mild-medium carbonation just enough to excite the palate . to me , this is almost the perfect mouthfeel .

a : pours a muddy muddy thick black with a little ring of head that sticks around but i was not expecting a head anyways , its just dark and inviting black as night s : smells incredibly sweet , like a sweet port , huge huge nose on this , plums and rum raisins with hints of sweet and dark chocolate . i mean there is not real reason to get more specific it smells pretty much like exactly what is listed here , very luxurious . t/mf : the carbonation is a nice touch here and allows an extremely heavy and creamy body to impart the flavor all across the tongue .  not much of a head , a ring of bubbles lines the inside of the glass . deep orange/amber in color , and a very clear liquid .  very rich and robust brew almost creamy . again , excellent . thanks be to lou91 for the opportunity .

a truly profound smell . has all the plums and figs of a dickens novel .  besides the color ( pale yellow with a tinge of orange ) , everything else is amazing .  mouthfeel- the texture of this beer in the mouth is stunning and absolutely *perfect* .

sweetish and beautiful . t : unfortunately , the alcohol flavor jumps to the front , and while it 's not quite overwhelming , it 's a large part of the flavor , which i do n't find pleasant .  pours into glass to present a dirty straw/light copper/amberish color . at first pours with a small but nice looking head which quickly disperses . there is some lacing along the edges of the glass , but it does n't quite make up for the lack of a head .  m : the mouthfeel is delightful . fairly thick for an ipa , almost creamy with mild carbonation .

hazy yellow body with short white head beautiful voluptous peach aroma . very juicy . simple and juicy , no bitterness or sourness .  poured into a snifter , it pours a moderate brown that is difficult to see the light through . a minimal light tan head is formed and leaves a mild lacing around the edges .  m - very rich and thick , has a nice little burn and pop at the end from a combo of carbonation , abv and hop bitterness .

the smell is very strong of hops . very floral and powerful . the taste it really dominated by hops and the bitterness at the end is quite nice .  this beer pours a hazy orange-red color . the head is half an inch in height , and recedes quickly into minimal lacing .  m : medium in body with a really smooth and creamy feel on the tongue .

this smelled like the kitchen while my mom bakes banana bread .  reviewed 6/16/2006 ( tap @ flying saucer , houston , tx ) : pours a dark black color body , but almost no head , tan colored , and quickly diminishing .  mouthfeel is quite exceptional .

smell : strong citrus aroma boasting orange , pineapple and sappy resin . they really knocked it out of the park in the smell , what an inviting and pleasing scent . has west coast written all over it . overall : a pretty impressive brew from cisco brewers .  minor head retained nicely , decent lacing .  mouth feel is incredible with some good champagne bubbling going on .

incredibly clean , with absolutely no imperfections in the malting or hops . extremely delicate . the flavor is incredibly clean .  poured from a capped unlabeled bottle from my buddy adam . no head on pour , some carbonation .  m- wonderfully creamy . the carbonation is spot on . one of the creamiest belgian beers i can think of .

exquisite nose has brandy , oak , vanilla , dark pitted fruits , candy malts , port wine and whiskey . taste does not hold the same complexity . some tart cherries , plums , caramel , toffee , wood , vanilla , wine grapes and cognac . past prime for sure , but still an interesting beer .  pale gold and crystal clear . modest white head ( about one finger ) that becomes a thin film and then a ring . lacing is minor perhaps due to glass washed in the dishwasher . a perfect easy drinking summer pils .  t/m : mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .

a real nice sniffer .  a dark orange body with a swiftly descending head that leaves no trace -- semi-opaque ... solid malt aroma with hints of fruitiness to develop a sense of complexity.. slightly effervescent , with a mellow , medium body that is pleasantly fulfilling ... smooth , malty presence in the back of the mouth ; little hops to speak of , but at this refreshing a taste , they 'd only get in the way !  a very smooth , luxurious malt backbone enhances the mouthfeel , but a bitter smack of hops reminds me that i 'm drinking an ipa . quite enjoyable .

the first thing that struck me about this stout was the aroma , very complex , almost sweet , with what i thought could have been vanilla among other things . the # 1 surprise was the texture and consistency of this beer , i was expecting something much thicker , more like guiness , and boy was i surprised , a much smoother , lighter consistency with a great taste and just enough flavor to let you know you are drinking something quality without being over whelming . it took me more time to get a good overall sense of this stout then i would have expected , a compliment to the complexity of the flavor .  hazy orange/gold color . big , creamy and very dry with driving , fine bubbles . alcohol sweetness is at the center of a complex of toasted nut , dried apple and dried apricot flavors . extremely drinkable though for such a heady brew .  very thick with just enough carbonation that completely fills the mouth and leaves a bittersweet flavor lingering on the palate , and a bit of a syrupy feel on the back of the throat with just a bit of alcohol heat that is perfect for the style .

amazingly strong - smells of syrupy semi-sweet chocolate and very deep roasty and toasty malts ; smells like very fresh brewed espresso ... actually , the `` freshness '' of the smell is really quite intense . taste : very burnt and roasty malt characteristics that are reminiscent of fresh brewed espresso and grounds ; faint flavors of semi-sweet baking chocolate ; i have to admit , this would be an amazing morning drink .  good initial head , but it dissipates to a single layer . the lace is spotty and light .  mouthfeel is where this beer shines the most , imo . creamy and rich and the carbonation is superfine , perfect . this one grew on me a bit as i got into it and it warmed up some , but still not a mind-blowingly good beer .

n : this is a beautiful , mouthwatering nose . smells very close to liquid pumpkin pie .  pours a blackish color on the pour . no head forms on the pour , only a slight ring develops .  m- really interesting . a dry feeling on the sides of the tongue and a sweet feeling in the back . really well done .

really good . t : milder than the smell , with a taste of mostly apples and cider , creamy caramel , and a mild woody gin finish .  poured into a weizen style glass that creates very little head atop a golden-straw colored body .  mouthfeel was full , thick , and creamy with a rich sweetness on the tongue .

smell is very in your face . yeast hits you first , with hints of bananas which are definitely prevalent . really nice beer , one that i would love to have again .  the amazing extras from alewatcher just kept coming and coming . a- not much head , but i wasnt expecting that at all . the beer is a semi murky brownish color .  mouthfeel- light palate with great carbonation that tickles the senses nicely .

smell is awesome -- the smoked pork hits you first , followed by hints of raw sugar , honey , apples or pears , and black licorice . first few sips have an element of 'burnt'-ness to them , but once you get used to it , it 's quite pleasant . there 's almost a saltiness to it , with some background flavours of coffee , chocolate , and strong malts .  this beer poured a dark brown with a minimal head , held up to the light , was n't quite crystal clear but a little hazy .  mouthfeel : fully body , lower carbonation , love it .

smell : oh baby can you say citrus hop bomb ? loads of grapefruit and a touch of lemon .  a - raspberry/brown color , not head nor lace .  each sip of this full bodied beer is smooth and creamy with light carbonation . this beer is so smooth it goes right down .

sn consistantly produces beers w/ amazing hop boutique aromas . t - flavor profile pretty much mimics the nose w/ the malts and biscuit holding the fort down so the trademark sn cascades can do what they do best . mf - creamy , medium body and goes down w/ a slick and oily feel d - balance , balance , balance . highly sessionable .  label on the bottle says `` craft brewed brown ale . clear and a dark red-amber colour . even with it 's little head it still manages to leave some spots of lace .  the rich , smooth , roasted chocolate flavor works well with the silky body . this is definitely highly recommended , as the beers tend to be from great lakes brewing company .

heat is starting to mellow with a year on it , and the fruity development of the nose compliments the flavor beautifully . freshness indicated that this beer needs some time , and boy was i right .  it looks good , but pretty run of the mill . taste/mouthfeel : jeez , this is the little beer that could . looks like any other pils out there , but the flavor is outstanding .  just a hint of carbonation on the palate - utterly smooth .

insanely tart notes of lemon zest , white grape rinds , and dry oak barrels . so incredibly tart ; for me , the only comparable wild ale is batch 2 beatification ( in terms of sheer sourness ) . fantastic beer .  amber color , a half finger of tan head that dissolved to a fine film . no lacing .  in the mouth , the tiny bubbles announce and incredibly smooth and balanced beer , with a roasted , slightly sweet flavor .

amber color with a huge orangey , frothy head that leaves crusty peaks like meringue as it dissipates . aroma is of hop , citrus , and pine .  i thought this was a pretty decent brown . the clear brown elixir is topped by a little head with some lacing left behind .  mouthfeel is as good as you would expect with an aerator . all in all , you can drink it for the mouthfeel but do n't drink it for the taste .

s - tart cherries right away with maybe just a tad of artificial cherry candy smell , and some dark chocolate . i like it . i wanted to like this because it looked and smelled very good but just took a bad turn after that .  a - cloudy . yellow . not much head .  at least it was smooth and the carbonation was just right .

seemed nice for the style .  from the growler the beer pours a murky orangish brown color . the head was n't all that great , but that could be due to a dirty growler , glass or the fact that i 've had it in the growler for four days . because of the aforementioned ( i assume ) lacing is also lacking .  creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

there is no doubt about it , it smells like blueberry syrup mixed with malt liquor and it smells good . of course , malt liquor mixed with blueberry syrup can only taste so good .  when i saw the beer it wasnt the most impressive beer i have ever seen , but i felt that when you make a cherry beer it would look like this , in that aspect the brewer had gotten exactley what they wanted . when you are making a cherry beer you should smell cherrys and nothing but . the beer seemed to be perfectly carbonated and didnt give me any reason to review it as bad . i feel bad to ever give out a bad review but to me this beer was like a fine painting that would never look good in my house but i can thoroughly appreciate the effort and time put into it .  medium full bodied , somewhat creamy .

the smell was probably what i liked most about this olde style ale .  pours a dark brown , near black , color with brown highlights around the edges . minimal lacing . apperance is nothing special .  flavor is malty and sweet , and on the finish , bubble gum ! mouthfeel is firm , and drinkability is high .

dark fruit aroma with pineapple and apricots as the main smells coming through .  orange amber color was semi clear . head was well formed but disapated fairly quickly , lacing was scarce .  very creamy and full . very dry .

s- lots of roasty malt smell , some cocoa t- notes of acrid coffee , black patent , mild hops .  a - pours a slightly hazy straw color with one finger of quickly dissipating white head . very little lacing .  let me first say that the brugse tripel used to be one of my favorite beers . nowdays its called brugge tripel and the taste changed slowly ... but a lot of small steps make a big one and today this beer is nothing what it used to be . smell of spices and a little hops , not fresh at all and a dull taste make it just a drinkable beer but nothing great like it had in the past .
very pleasing . taste is really subdued .  small , short-lived white head tops a golden colored brew , slight haze but mostly clear .  mouthfeel is good , slightly thick .

a bit too sweet ( confectionery-like ) but still nice . flavours suggest that unibroue has got a perfectly acceptable wheat beer and then dumped a truckload of apple lollipops into it .  poured from a bomber into a nonic glass . a : opaque , dark brown color with over one finger of light beige foam head . scant lacing remains on the glass .  was pretty decent mouthfeel : smooth and crisp , went down easy drinkability : good enough on a hot day and goes great w/ bbq .

hops subdued on the nose in a slightly citric tang . looks good , smells fine , nice to drink .  poured with a nice tan head which quickly subsided and a tiny bit of lace . color is a hazy amber brown .  mouthfeel : good .

the smell is also decent . there 's a decent sweetness from the malt , and this almost smells like a fruit candy cane . very unique . things fall completely apart when we get to the taste .  poured into a tulip . pours a hazy golden straw colow with a bit of an orange hue to it . no head here , just a little bit of white bubbles .  hoping it 's one of those better in a bottle beers i 'm returning to give it another try . so far so good . maybe , and i 'm stretching , some neutral hop spice . this beer makes me try too hard . these hops should be hops should be ashamed of themselves . good malt base to support hops , were they present . bottle is equally bland as on tap .

it carries a sweet , tart , caramel aroma with a bit of chocolate , roast , a bit of spruce ... and maybe chai . a very rich aroma , indeed .  a : pours a clear dark yellow with a medium head that dissipates very quickly .  taste : a wink of hops , than the shows over , a surprisingly dry finish mouthfeel : decent - nice restrained carbonation , ever so slightly creamy notes : this is the driest , and least bitter ipa that i have ever experienced .

after enjoying the living heck out of noble pils last week and seeing that my local bottle shop , bar was out of it today , i decided to give this one a whirl . what got to me was that it tasted incredibly sour . the hops and lemon seemed to be battling it out in my mouth and neither ingredient won . afterward , it tasted remarkably like a corona , the way it 's served in a mexican restaurant . major disappointment from what 's usually a fantastic brewer .  cola-like brown in appearance . carbonation is a bit high on this very fresh bottle , but i 'm sure aging a few of these will mellow that , in addition to allowing the flavors to meld and blend together . quite nice fresh though .  mouthfeel is about the only thing going for this one . medium body and appropriate carbonation .

aromas of bread ( it looks like he is grilled ) and cinnamon sweet very pleasant .  it 's like an american dos xx = no slime ! it 's very drinkable and should be consumed with lime . just a great all around , drinkable beer .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but not watery . it had a nice feel to it .

it 's a great aroma , but little else needs to be said .  pours a transparent light orange with a small white head which eventually disappears . little to no lacing .  mouthfeel is actually pretty nice , medium body and carbonation with a creamy quality .

huge fruity nose with lots of pineapple . pretty sour which also makes me think it may have been a bad bottle . hugely disappointing considering how much i had heard about hair of the dog .  mmmm ... the appearance is n't anything abnormal/fantastic/special or anything else to write home about ... it looks like an ipa .  m : crisp and clean , moderate levels of carbonation and warmth . medium body .

i wish hotd would start holding onto their bottles to give then a chance to carb up , if i was brewing , i wouldnt want to send out uncarbed bottles . the flavors are very interesting , the cherry does come through rather prominantly and has a large amount of sweetness behind it , and i think this is why the alcohol is hidden rather well , it is detectable only in some flavors and not so much in heat . the barrels come through with some oak too much not substantially so . there are alot of comparisons to a wine i could make with this actually , but i am not tomme . think of brandy angles share and decide .  a - holy crap a lot of foam . point deduction for gushing . pours a very dark brown with a thick tan head .  it has a canned fruit essence to it , but i ca n't pick up what kind of fruit . first couple of sips and i get a strong cherry pie filling flavor . i eat a lot of fresh cherries in the summer so i do n't automatically associate cherries with pie filling . not overly sweet but it does have a tart tang finish . a unique beer that i appreciate as well done , just not to my tastes .

smells great though .  without any lace or head , but certainly had adequate carbonation . highly drinkable beer that grew on my palate .  the mouthfeel is very nice , it 's very carbonated which works with the ginger presence , and the mouthfeel is at about a medium thickness .

the aroma hints at more of a tart belgian ale than a ami wheat or even s witbier . the atste is mildly tart , this is ok becasue it 's so differebt from what i 'm used too .  22oz bottle a- pours an orangish amber color with a thin and fizzy off-white head that quickly disappears .  while the mouthfeel is actually pretty good , the drinkability suffers from this same fatal flaw .

aroma has that sweet peanut aroma as well as lager yeasty aromas .  it was bottled in april 2010 , so i think i 'm good ... duped by the standard brown longneck bottle , i poured this into a standard american pint glass , and it appears a cloudy dark iced-tea colour , with a bit of swirling sediment , and a half finger of soapy pale beige head , which disappears quickly , leaving some sparse spidery lace around the glass .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

the smell was very nice and peach , but the taste was tart and hard to drink . i got a sick , quesy feeling after finishing off a bomber , not a good feeling either .  a -- old gold body and a nice medium head .  feel : moderate carbonation , medium body , exceedingly dry finish .

s : it smells hoppy and has a punchy citrus scent . smells of oranges , tangerine and apricot .  pours a dark hazy amber color with a thin fizzy white head that quickly disappears without leaving much in the way of lacing .  mouthfeel : medium-plus body . medium carbonation . some oily viscosity to the mouthfeel .

this smells delicious , close to pumpkin pie . some good , some bad on the taste .  paid $ 15 even for the midwest taster ... the appearence was a cola colored base with a nice tannish head , minimal retention and no real lacing .  m - good mouth feel . somewhat unique in feel .

mouthfeel is thin reminds me of carbonated water overall it smelled pretty good but the taste left me wanted something else .  poured a 2 '' white head which dissipated quickly .  the mouthfeel is full and nicely carbonated yet still somewhat creamy .

s - berry and more berry t - strong raspberry flavor , but very little beer flavor . it reminds me of ab wildblue m - thin and watery , nothing particularly special i 'm conflicted on many of my ratings for this beer because on the one hand , many of the attributes of this beer are on purpose ( like the pink color ) but at the same time , it 's not a beer i would pick up again .  appearance : nice dark brown but again the snow-globe of floaties that this brewery is known for . not much of a head and minimal lacing . ok , same old story , yet another very good beer from abbaye des rocs you just need to get past the floaties ( as usual ) .  medium mouthfeel .

smell is fruity with a nice yeast kick at the end .  pours a very dark , clear , brown . starts with small , fizzy , thin head that leaves quickly , but maintains a nice thin , creamy lace . a medium tan color .  i did n't pick up the barrel aged at first but the body was quite full and large . worth drinking but i believe that there is better in the 8-9 dollar bomber range .

s - bready , yeasty , fruity .  cloudy , obviously , but golden amber color with a modest white head that left a ring pretty quickly .  mouth is medium bodied , but with some good tingly action on the back of the tongue , so also good .

honey is very pronounced edging near a braggat . both in the aroma and the taste . the hops are non-existent until the finish were they are quite strong . overall i think it 's too sweet and i could barely finish the sample . too cloying .  the beer looks almost still , and so there is no head retention or lacing to speak of .  mouthfeel is nice , good carbonation , but seriously , ca n't get over that ham finish .

head is almost tan , but too white to deserve the label . aroma is like a 60-minute ipa that 's gone off its meds . a blast of hops juice . but , i could not drink your 120 minute ipa .  wheat beers are notoriously summer quafs , and the raspberry ufo is no exception .  this beer has a high level of carbonation with a very crisp and clean mouthfeel .

a- deep brown with mahogany hues , 1/4 '' tan head with little retention and films of lacing s- coffee , roasted malts , rich , alcohol , strong scents t- sweet caramel and buttery malts flavor but balanced by strong burnt astringencies , alcohol evident throughout , strong at finish , some chocolate m- somewhat creamy , stiff carbonation with ho alcohol at finish and in after d- complex malt flavor but alcohol is to strong and carbonation comes off as awkward .  this beer tastes like bacon if bacon = good and beer = good and this beer = bacon then for you , the beer = good if you do n't like bacon , do not get this beer .  mouthfeel : smooth and medium thick , low carbonation .
s : strong notes of malt and caramel , sugary smell .  '' a- one finger head goes away quickly , within seconds . orange in color with lots up bubbles .  mouthfeel - medium and smooth .

o : the beer smells great , but pales in other categories , especially taste , which is a terrible place to have the weakest link .  opaque orangish gold color with a little one finger head which makes its exit quickly .  body is on the full side of medium . moderate carbonation .

smell : classic tripel aroma , but not strongly pungent . taste : slight alcohol bite in after-taste .  almost no lacing in the glass . much darker in color than most weizens/pale wheats that i have sampled .  it was somewhat thick with some carbonation , and had a hot aftertaste .

the beer has a very spicy odor , maybe a hint of cloves or something similar in the nose .  pours a deep orange amber with a light tan head that lingers for a while .  it had a smooth mouthfeel with a little carbonation .

s : to be expected ... apricots . the smell of hops was pretty well blended , with citrusy grapefruit and a little piney coming through t : way more bready in the malts than i expected , and the apricot was present but finished the sip and left it feeling not nearly as crisp and hoppy as i expected from the finish .  rich antique golden ale , with a one finger head that gives way pretty quickly .  m- medium viscosity with a well integrated carbonation .

smells of tons of citrus and pine , with a hint of kitchen cleaner and hardwood resin . very resinous taste win a lingering bitterness and faint light caramel .  a : a golden pour , topped with a white head that lacks much retention but leaves a thin sheet behind .  fairly thick body .

i get a nice dose of floral and citrus hops .  drank on-tap at the pig 's eye pub , hartford , ct poured a cloudy , straw yellow-amber with no head but rather a bubbly , bright white , disappointingly thin film of lace .  very silky mouthfeeland light body , very drinkable and good .

the smell actually has a nice deep roasted malt aroma that dominated the nose , much stronger than i would have though , slightly sweet with a cocoa presence .  i poured this one from a 12oz brown bottle into a shaker pint glass . a= this ale poured a very clear golden color ( filtered i would say ) with a fairly low carbonation release and a 1/2 '' white head . the head dropped to zero very quickly and did not leave any lacing behind .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

smell is chocolate with some burnt coffee tones and burnt bread crust smell as well .  a - med-dark gold . t - the first thing you taste is whisky , but it fits nicely . beautiful rogue malt profile . very tasty . d - highly drinkable .  lovely thick aromas of blackstrap molasses , dark bitter chocolate , strong coffee and deep roasted malts ... awesome aromas to this one ... lazy and flat tasting ... strange bitter almost sour taste present ... . not much in common with the aromas ... thick oily mouthfeel is great but i ca n't get by the taste of this one ... drain poured this one ... maybe a bad bottle but as is , a big disappointment ...
lots of sweet citrus & bread in the nose .  pours a slighlty hazy amber with a pretty average head .  m - oily , medium body with a fantastic amount of carbonation .

o : smells nice , but that 's about it .  a : cloudy bright amber-gold body with a thin , late developing head that leaves as soon as it arrives . definitely a bit on the flat side for a saison .  m- moderate/high carbonation , medium body , lager clean . crisp enough leaving a refreshing feel .

i have never had a pumpkin ale before . it smells of spices ; nutmeg , ginger and clove . it begins deceptively cleanly with a metallic taste before the spices take over with nutmeg to the fore .  a- after a fairly aggressive pour , i get a 1 finger head that quickly recedes into a bubbly lacing . the body is a lovely orange with no sediment .  the mouthfeel was decent , medium with adequate carbonation .

smell- roasty and malty with much hop presence . hops are pretty strong , but not overpowering .  pours a nice cloudy yellow as expected but this taste of it is just .  this beer tastes like sheep shit . this may appeal to some people , but it 's definitely a very unusual belgian ale . i enjoyed drinking half of this beer for the experience . it 's so pungent i laughed out loud . it 's always fun to be exposed to a radically different flavor profile than you 're used to .

aromatics are subtle with chamomile and not overly done with honey or citrus . pale biscuit male gives off a subtle sweetness there 's an air of the honey and citrus but the chamomile hits an herbal and marshmallow like tone .  slight film persists , but no real head retention or lacing s : sour & oaky notes t : sweet cherry , then sourness , oaky dryness & small hint of vanilla up front .  medium bodied ; good amount of carbonation .

the smell is of overwhelming vanilla and roasted malt , there is a sweet malt smell as well .  pours a bright orange amber body that lends a half finger white head .  crisp and clean in the mouth , body fits the carbonation well . nothing amazing about this brew , but it 's not terrible and comes in a nifty bottle you can use for ... something ... .i guess .

it smells very spicy , like cinnamon and nutmeg . the beer looks and smells nice , but in my opinion there 's too much spice in it .  a- pale yellow and cloudy .  most everything else about this beer was great , looked good , good mouthfeel , but the taste .
aromas of roast , chocolate , and some dark fruits .  dark brown with light tan head - no real retention , and the head quickly faded away .  mouthfeel : lightly carbonated and creamy .

strong coffee aroma has me salivating , it is mixed with a lighter chocolate aroma , this beer smells rich with hints of bourbony alcohol . the taste is where i was thrown , there is an extremely lemony tartness in the flavor which may be fine in another style , but not what i was expecting here , especially after the inviting aromas . i 'm not sure if the tartness is a result of roasting the malts and the tangy acidity that follows or something else , but it masked most of the flavors and was very prevalent .  33cl bottle poured into my gordons thistle glass a- 1 finger head post pour and reducing to non existancy immediately . held to the light , a hint of light gets through to show a very dark dark dark dark ruby body .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .

s - the rich caramel and malty nose is unleashed on the pour . a light kiss of hops compliments the very malty nose . smells almost like a dopplebock . very sweet .  pours a hazy straw yellow with a half finger head that fades somewhat quickly . not too impressive .  long , earthy , dry finish . interesting , somewhat unusual brew .

s : lots of oak and bourbon . big bourbon smell really dominates . it 's followed nicely by a big chocolately middle , and a dry coffee finish .  has a fluffy off white head . an average looking brew .  on first sip you get hit with a strong citrus hop attack . from the aroma to the taste , there is just something that does n't sit well with me . it leaves an unpleasant bitter aftertaste . i love ipas and hops galore . my only guess is that the bitter citrus flavor is what threw this beer off for me .

very odd look for a dipa s : lots of citrus on the nose . grapefruit , orange and banana .  pours a not-quite-clear straw color with a small head that rapidly diminishes .  the mouth is smooth and light .

slight hint of coffee at first in the aroma that 's followed by a dark fruitiness ; some sweetness ; not really all that roasted , but nice . the flavor has a sharp coffee character that moves really quickly into a sourishness , almost like eating a raw cranberry without the berriness ; some hint of that fruit comes in , not sure what 's going on here , but it 's all over the place and not very pleasant .  this is a great bbq beer i had this beer on tap at a little resturant in cayucus with fish and chips . it was citracey and sweet . and a really nice finish .  smooth in the mouth with nice , crisp carbonation . nice feel , but flavor is not there .

this is one of the sweeter smelling stouts that i have had ... its got a milk chocolate backbone along with some other sweet fruity notes . it smells rather sugary and sweet for a stout , but i like that . beyond a pour and a couple good whiffs this beer goes downhill fast , this beer is extremely watery , and not rich like the smell would suggest .  pours out to a clear pale golden , forming a small white head with no retention and lacing . somewhat flat from the voyage with minimal carbonation , so keep that in mind for this review .  mouthfeel is nice & creamy .
nice . the taste starts out pretty good .  it looks much like a standard macro-brewers lager but the similarity ends there .  light mouthfeel with a good amount of carbonation when you drink it .

the aroma was sweet almost grapelike .  pours a dark coffee and molasses mix with a decent head at first , but does n't linger very long and the last of my 12 .oz is finished with no foam at all .  m - nice light feel with a crisp finish , accentuated with a alcohol warmth .

the aroma seems to be pretty good , nice strong malt scent that gives off the idea of caramel also giving a sweet smell .  appearance = it poured from a twelve ounce bottle with a small head that quickly dissipated without leaving any lacing on the glass .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , slightly sticky in the front and a little dry on the back of the tongue . pretty good .
everything from the nose is lost to sweetness , very disappointing .  looks thick . dark , no head , little lacing , little carbonation .  m : medium-high carbonation fits the style nicely .

smell : loads of spicy/mint hop aromas , with a casual sweetness on the backend .  a - poured a dark copper with no visible carbonation , no head as it was poured all the way to the top , no lacing and no retention .  dark brown/amber body . it is a very smooth and a sweet sipper . some hops , caramel , candy sugar and oak . not much bourbon . i was way excited to try this and actually find it to be rather average .

smell - interesting . about what i expected .  it does not have the complexity or the body of ( say ) sierra nevada or victory products but i 'd be interested in how this would stack up in a blind taste test because its appearance , color , etc. , while not remarkable , are right up there . i give costco a lot of credit for this because their beer offerings ( at least in my area ) are polarized between the ( formerly ) us macros and beck 's on one hand and variety cases on the other .  m - medium bodied with good carbonation .

good balance .  a : pours a chill hazed orange/red with a short head that is reduced to nothing quickly . poor spotty lacing and low carbonation .  the mouthfeel of this beer ( outside of taste ) was great . great carbonation , bitter hop aftertaste , medium bodied .

strong nut aroma . flavor was not very rich but was nutty with some malt .  hazy straw-colored body with a fizzy white head that tails off fairly quickly , leaving little opportunity for much in the way of lacing . a tart burst of citrus- lemon juice and orange zest- greets the nose , backed up with cloves , tangy wheat and tangy yeast .  mouthfeel is pretty good , goes well with the style of light and highly carbonated .

smells of overly spiced pumpkin pie , which is a good thing . cinnamon and clove come out straight away . the smell was completely misleading ; i think i found pumpkin in this one somewhere , but the spices are glaringly absent ( with the exception of cinnamon which comes through the nose ) it kind of leaves an off flavor behind that i do n't like .  however , deep copper color with golden highlights . no foam .  m - good carbonation and it finishes clean . good light to medium mouthfeel .
this amber ale has a huge sweet caramel aroma with a bit of spice .  little head accompanied a dark clear golden colour . little cardination and some lacing .  mouthfeel is fine and not heavy .

a very sweet and fruity smell . sweet malts with apple and pear highlights . not very subtle but quite fine .  1/5 inch head of a tan color . decent retention and good lacing .  a bitter spicy bite from the hops hit first . the light body and good crispness contrast the flavor pretty well .

hoppy sour apple tang . i 'm almost wondering if i left some 3-day old coffee in the bottom of my mug .  this beer is a fairly brown shade of orange , with almost no head , just a thin white ring .  it has good texture .

smell : cherries , wonderful fruity cherries . finishes clean but with a lingering bitterness that i find unappealing in wits .  oh , it looks like a euro pils , and to some extent , smells like a pilsner .  the same color , mouthfeel , and drinkability were there , just the hopiness , aroma , and flavor , as well as most of the bitterness seemed to have blown away .

a - stout black with absolutely no head after a very aggressive pour s - smells of a lot of milk chocolates and some coffee t - the taste follows the nose .  7.5 % abv bottle into my slender & top heavy rare vos glass . big powdery head , though quite faint & not big on sticking around . body is a glittery caramel amber with lots of floaties .  body is right- light , lively carbonation , not cloying or excessively dry .

raspberry attacks the tongue in a syrupy , soda-pop way . raspberry is over the top as an adjunct rather than brewing element . i got something like dr. pepper .  the wee heavy poured into my snifter displays a deep amber/light brown color with a moderate off-white head that very quickly diminished to barely a skim .  the mouthfeel is very full and hearty almost meaty- sort of flat .

it looked and smelled like a really nice apa but when it hit my lips i tought it was a lager or something .  very thin white head with little lace .  mouth feel is completely crisp , refreshing , and clean .

a : solid black , perhaps a bit of purple ; head dissipates quickly s : grape , barleywine , roasted or carmelized malt t : wow -- powerful start ; it 's very fresh tasting ; coffee is evident , but one must wonder what kind of coffee was used -- overroasted is my guess ; i loved the taste at first , but then it got old quickly -- it 's overly tinny , metallic and the coffee is not refined m : average i bought it as a single , and it 's well worth that investment .  the body pours quite a pale yellow , with a moderate haze and thinnish bone-white head .  mouthfeel - good feel , not too thick , kind of creamy , decent carbonation .

cloudy red beer has a hoppy smell , but not overwhelming . taste ; bitter .  a pretty dull looking beer , but on the nose , there is a huge oatmeal presence that lays on top of the roasted coffee and bitter cocoa nubs .  mouthfeel was smooth , slightly thick for a pils , and with a nice carbonation bite .

yep , it 's a black beer . it started well with a nice head and aroma . sweet fruit and coffee flavors , not too heavy .  a - let 's face it , almost all strong belgian ales appear cloudy , murky or muddy . the head is coffee with milk brown and dissipates in less than three minutes . what a shame ! m - not as heavy as the appearance would suggest , but it is substantial d - at 10.5 % abv you wo n't be having too many in an evening .  taste is thin and adjuncty . mouthfeel is good , thick and creamy .

this smells of ipa and initially it tastes of ipa with strong pink grapefruit and copper malt backbone ... but then there 's a little bite of fake-fruity-artificialsweetness ... reminds me of leiny 's sunset wheat ... almost like somebody dropped a shot of that in here ... which is not a good thing ... it really hits in the aftertaste and really turns me in the wrong direction on this beer ... i give it props for the taste up front ... and for the fact that it completely hides it 's alcohol content ... in that aspect i 'm not sure if i 've ever had a 7 % 'er that did n't have some alcohol bite ... but that off-put-taste of fake sweetener is just turning me off of this one and it will be my last .  appearance- slightly hazy , bright orange color with 1.5 finger eggshell white , foamy head . head settles rather quickly but leaves some residual lacing .  mouthfeel is very light and well carbonated .

appearance -- pours dark brown with a slim smell -- the nose is inviting : cocoa , dark fruit , toasted coconut , whiskey , vanillin wood sugars , and dry oak planks . the mellow oak and coconut so strong in the nose have vanished .  pours a very effervescent amber with 3+ fingers of rocky tan head . average lacing & head retention s : herbal hops , breadyness , a slight nuttyness .  has a medium body which is needed to carry all the hops and alcohol . low carbonation lends a nice texture without letting the flavors being cloying .

burnt brown head poured pretty thick , foamy and meringue like then faded to light covering with thick edging ... some light lines of lacing ring the glass ... aroma - dark toasted malts , metallic notes , black coffee , some dark brown sugar sweetness , light nuttiness , some blackcurrant and raisin fruitiness , faint liquorice traces , some graininess coming through , dusty hints ... taste - watered down roasted maltiness mixed with nutty notes , some molasses / treacle sweetness , light chocolate mixed with black cherry and blackcurrant fruits , light nutmeg and pepper spiciness , some light vegetal traces just noticeable , cola hints ... feel - way too over carbonated this one which really spoils it both in terms of flavour and drinkability ... overall - a bit disappointing as all the other les fous beers i 've had have been very good ... sort out the carbonation and this could be very good..  pours deep brown , with a thin off-white head .  mouthfeel : nice feeling on the tongue and also a good consistencty .
interesting . the taste is very smoky and has maybe a beer/bacon grease flavor to it .  ok retention with little fingers of lace .  m : lovely long bitter aftertaste .

aroma is very strong and pleasant grainy malt with noble hops , it certainly is much better than of the pasteurised classic version .  the appearence was ok , looks just like everyother beer i have seen before .  the mouthfeel is good , but obviously does not improve the flavor !

s - a delightful aroma typical of a oud bruin - sour cherries , with some faint mulling spice and faint caramel malt .  very carbonated , a light and bubbly beer . the head fluffs up and then dies down , a shame . the color is a golden white , a bit of a haze .  - well carbonated , dries the mouth a bit . nice smooth body , probably this beers highlight is the mouthfeel .

poured 22 ounce bottle in a wine glass a : clear ; loose white head of foam thats laces the glass on the way down s : sweetness , pine hops t : tastes like dirt , piny earthy hops take over , i do n't know the age of this beer the code on the neck is 2684311 m : standard d : passed this beer up many of times i have had quite a few of lagunitas beers and have not been impressed by many .  i was glad to see brew kettle still serving a pumpkin beer during my visit in late december ... seems like a lot of brewers plan to sell out of pumpkin beer by thanksgiving , and to me the flavor is appropriate through the new year . appearance-wise , it looked a great deal like the chief 's rye - not quite colorful enough in the amber body , and with a medium amount of head .  the flavor that by far took the lead was chocolate ! there 's an overpowering ( and for me , disappointing ) chocolate aftertaste in this beer . mouthfeel- smooth , no complaints here . drinkability- well , the bottle looks cool as you drink from it !

there is a very nice fruity sweet character along with an inviting spiceyness in the aroma . the flavor is sour , dry and reminds me of fruit going bad .  a : pours amberish color with little head s : piney and citrus hops with a touch of sweetness t : there 's a decent amount of bitterness from the hops but a good amount .  m : smooth and round .

aroma is quite citrusy with plenty of zesty grapefruit and a hint of pine . it also has a tiny bit of tropical character and some sweet non-descript malt . this beer smells very nice and has a nice hop flavor , but it seems a bit out of whack . much better than the dreadful ipa my friend ordered , but overall a pretty forgettable beer .  lots of sediment just waiting to get moved around in the bottom of this beer . not enough foam or head , or lacing for an ipa imho .  everything about this beer was pretty light - light , crisp malt scent ; light fruity taste ; light body . feel - 4.0/5.0 - refreshing , which was really nice .

a - looks like dr. pepper or even a cherry coke s - caramel popcorn up front and bold , hint of caramel t - it tastes like caramel popcorn , candy , hazelnut and then finishes with a little coffee m - average on carbonation and finishes dry d - this beer is quite different but gets a little old because the smell and taste is like candy when i first opened this beer it hit me right away with all the popcorn .  a - clear , deep honey color . the head is thin and leaves scattered lacing .  m : medium in both body and carbonation .

aroma is spot-on.. lite roased barley and dark roasted malts and chocolate overtones ... even smells creamy .  the beer pours a delicious straw-gold with a tight head that quickly fades . nice clean malt presence with just the right amount of noble hops , a touch of dms ( just enough to give it a full lager body ) and a light carbonation that helps the goodness go down .  ) mouthfeel is just nicely carbonated and light and the only reason the drinkability is n't higher on my ratings is because after a few 40 's your out of the game for a while .

aroma - sweet toasty malts beneath a charred grain . nice dimensions in the nose . as it settles , some chocolatey notes come through as well .  some sediment and good lacing .  m : good mouthfeel , its crisp , refreshing , light bodied with moderately high carbonation .

smell is impressive relative to low expectations - i 'm skeptical of hop-forward beers that are n't locally made and consumed fresh , but this one still has a resiny punch in spite of it 's journey from scandinavia , with a little oxidized biscuit malt as well .  what a quality ipa ! clear dark orange pour fresh from my sly fox growler into my sly fox pint ( now al i need are sly fox underoos and i 'm all set ! ) this growler was filled up two days ago . finally , this pour is topped off by a beige head that fades to a scant slick as i progress thru this one .  carbonation done very well .
s ) roasted grain . coffee bean . earthy - dirt .  a coppery orange with minimal head that leaves a thin lacing around the glass .  m : medium body and moderate carbonation .

s-chocolate milk mix , rich , earthy cigar tobacco , nutty malts .  appearance : poured with a big white foamy head that dissipated to a thin layer on top leaving no lacing . the beer is slightly cloudy with a yellow golden color .  mouthfeel was the highlight of the beer - it was almost velvety smooth . carbonation was low as per the style but if they 'd added a few more hops to dry out the palate it would have been near perfect .

sfruit and caramel jumps out right away , faint alcohol , plums , some spices , but not sure what they are , mildly sweet and floral tlike drinking fresh flowers , also spicy , some sweet honey and caramel notes , starts mildy sweet like candy , then sucks all of the spit out of your mouth with its dry , perfume like finish .  deep gold/pale amber in colour . thin , foamy tan head fades to a respectable layer of foam . chill haze is very evident .  the mouthfeel is very nice.. feels heavy , thick , smooth , and not over-carbonated .

very good coffee and chocolate smells here .  this pours a nice dark brown with an off white head . little retention and virtually no lacing .  mouthfeel - it does have a pleasant rich/buttery mouthfeel .

the wheat wine here seemed to me to be just like a regular barley wine to me and my friend who split the bottle . i was thinking that it would be a nice lighter strong beer before the dinner we had but it was heavy and boozie . i have n't been able to see much of a difference between wheat and barley wines .  lots of yeast sediment floating in a thick yellow-orange haze .  m : nice and thick d : not something ill try again .

smells of honey , biscuits , citrus , and some spicy hops . not one of my favorite ipas , did n't seem very balanced , nor was it very hoppy , just sweet with an overly bitter finish that does n't seem to be produced from the hops .  '' pours to a slightly hazy dark orange-caramel with a small white head and just ok retention and minimal lacing .  at least its silky smooth and the alcohol is well hidden . this beer , in my opinion , is the weakest of their stout series .

s : floral & citrus hops .  appearance : without the sediment , it pours a hazy , dark gold body with lots of foam . the only problem is the short shelf life of the head as well as the lacking of any real lacing .  still for such a big beer it had a great body , just not sure if i would want more , until it got about 5 years on it .

falls surprisingly fast for a hefe and does not leave a whole lot of lace behind . overripe bananas , cloves and bubblegum galore ! there is some nice wheat tang to offset some of the sweeter , fruity yeast esters .  on-tap at beachwood bbq , a : pours brown with a mild white head , no real lace , average head retention .  smooth creamy medium body .

yellow with full head , freshly aromatic of herbs , grass , and mint . unappealing .  pours an amber brownish tint that holds an inch thick white cap .  mouthfeel is round and full , thick and sticky .

almost no head at all even though i did n't pour it gently at all.smells sweet and very fruity .  lovely little bottle , but i will say it looks much bigger in photographs . the head fades quickly and no head retention to be seen .  the body is full and the carbonation is light . mouthfeel is creamy .

smell is rich , malty , oak and caramel .  on tap @ the office in cranford 01-16-09 a- bright golden color , a lot of carbonation , when i 'm at a regular bar drinking this i almost feel like i 'm one of the bmc crew but if they only knew ... s : yeast hops and some sweetness from the malt .  light body , good carbonation .

smell = lots of alcohol and zest . a candy like sweetness , smell almost exaclty like strawberry twizzlers . intesesting scent . taste = too sweet and syrupy with the alcohol packing quite a punch to boot .  it comes with about a fingers worth of off white head . little to no retention , no lacing left on the glass .  m - the brew is wet at the lips but finishes quite dry . impressive . ~ unfortunately i 'm going to struggle finishing this because of the flavor .

smell - pumpkin with some nutmeg maybe a bit of brown sugar and cinnamon . overall - i just wish that this beer tasted more like it smells but that might just be me being a fan of spicy beers .  pours mahogany with 3+ fingers of mocha head . average lacing & head retention s : roasty malt & chocolate , plus a slight iron scent t : chocolate , roasty malt , & some dryness up front .  body was medium , and the liquid was fairly smooth overall . 3.03 rdev -19.5 % look : 3.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 3 | feel : 4 | overall : 2.5 1366
smell is rich caramel and roasted maltiness with a distinct dairy sweetness .  it 's what purple haze wants to be when it grows up .  mouthfeel is medium , clean with a bitter hop aftertaste .
strong nose is dominated by the scent of roasted malt .  a - pours a pretty clear color with a fizzy white head that dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel : light , carbonated , crisp .

love the idea of a beer from utah being called polygamy anything , although i 'm not sure how the people who run that state would feel . anyway , at first glance this is a beautiful dark red porter in the glass with a nice chocolate milk head that did dissapate a little quick . the taste of chocolate malt is very mild , if fact you have to wait 5-6 seconds after you swallow to really taste anything . i could drink this porter but for a purist , this would not hold up . a nice try , and not a bad brew , but not worth any extra effort either .  pours copper with thick tan head that slowly fades to patchy layer , scant patches of lacing .  mouthfeel is very creamy as expected from the nitro can , but i couldnt get past the taste that just did not agree with me .

a bit of tobacco , which i will give to some oxidation in the 11 year old beer , s : coffee , touch of molasses , t : a tad too much black patent malt , imo .  this score might be a bit lower than appropriate , as i drank the beer in an opaque vessel , and in a dark room -- did n't get much of a look , so i just gave it a middle of the road score on appearance .  m : fizzy carbonation that smooths out a little into the sip and works well with the body of the beer .

i 'll disagree with the majority of reviewers and say it actually smelled pretty nice .  brown color with tons of yeast floaters . very thin tan head . nothing special to look at but not terribly out of character for the style .  this one is crisp and carbonation is at a good level . body is n't as light as i had expected ; this one 's medium-bodied .

the nose comprises lemon zest , a light funk , cardamom , hay , and mandarin oranges .  acloudy reddish brown with a thin tan sheet of foam on top , no head to speak of , but laced well as i drank it down sspicy , raison , plum , apricot , pear , lots of fruity smells here tnot much like the smell , buttery toffee flavor , maybe some mild fruit tones , flavor is very mild and enjoyable if you like mild ales msmooth and velvetish , medium bodied , not much for carbonation dvery differentthe smell really threw me on this one ; i expected the taste to be more fruity .  goes down smooth , no bite , and finishes with an appropriate amount of stickiness . carbonation is on the lower end of the spectrum . nice feel .
aroma is nice with a caramel , malt , brett cast .  darkish amber in colour with a persistent head , albeit it quite thin in texture .  mouthfeel is light to medium and has a soft feel .

i had the sour face when you suck on a lemon . the aroma is good and very profound with strong notes of figs , raisins , and heavy malts .  1 pint 6 oz bottle eyes : pours a straw to yellow , pretty average looking , not much head , nothing too exciting looking at it nose : grapefruit ginger ale with a citrus twinge more towards the tart variety.. lemon ices hops mmmm almost smells like a sparkling soft drink ... drool ... taste : like a light american pale ale with an exceptional tart finish with a gentle hop bite .  mouthfeel : light/medium with a tart , crisp finish drinkability : i really do n't crave another of these ; this certainly would n't be a lawnmower beer for me conclusion : just kind of unsorted ( also kind of an odd bitterness on the finish ) ... i tried this a year or two ago and was n't a huge fan ... now that i 'm reviewing it ... i 'm still not .

s : sour aroma with apple , citrus , and raisin notes . d : this brew looked and smelled good but is way off the mark on taste .  a : pours a deep brown with dark ruby highlights around the edges . about a half finger of foam fades quickly leaving almost nothing on top and no lacing . kinda looks like a coke or root beer .  m/s carbonation is fine , alcohol is n't really noticeable `` thanks '' to the bitterness overall i really do n't like this beer , but i guess it has more to do with me and this style than the beert itself .

nose is delicate like a bouquet of spring flowers , freesia and tea rose .  love the bottle , too bad the price is so high . a : pours a dark ruby/brown color with a small off-white head forms , comprised of rather large bubbles , and dissipates rather quickly . very thin lacing forms , but does not last .  m : solid mouthfeel , carbonation is pretty much spot on .

hazelnut & coffee dominate the nose but there are roasted malt & faint hop scents in there , too . so far so good . nope .  i love marin brewing co. beers and this is a well made ale . i just do n't think it 's my style . looked like a lager which was a bit surprising as i expected something darker .  an intense experience . the flavour is huge bitter hops - oily and rich with a spike on the back palette . the alcoholic warmth starts deep within the pit of the stomach and travels all the way up to the cheeks . next time i try it will be in front of a fire with a huge cheese platter .

nice and clear amber-orange color with plenty of sticky head . smells of maple , bread , grassy hops , and a bit of apple .  dark-brown and cloudy in appearance , the pint glass i was handed had been pre-poured , so i ca n't say a lot about the head . the sweetness up front balanced nicely with the beer 's hops , and in combination with an enjoyable , full body , the pint drank easily while sitting outside the brewery on a beautiful march day .  mouthfeel is creamy and satisfying .

smells absolutely inviting . flavor falls woefully short of the aroma .  a - poured a hazy amber color with some cloudiness and sediment visible . head was decent , lacing was minimal .  m : creamy to a crisp finish with a good carbonation throughout .

it was a very visually striking beer with it 's pale pink color and it smelled very interesting with a mix of watermelon , citrus and a hint of corinader , but i found it to taste just awful . i really wanted to like this , but there was just no way , could n't even finish off the tasting glass .  good lacing , poor head retention .  the mouthfeel is good - smooth with a right amount of carbonation .

s : when i opened the bottle i thought i was about to eat an apple . really smells like you are about to drink apple juice , with a hint of alcohol t : to me it tastes just like an an apple beer should taste .  ) ..its a pretty average looking ale pale amber , large frothy white head .  m : medium bodied with a medium carbonation .

( s ) - a spicy apple & honey with bits of cranberry . ( t ) - very dry with a musky-like honey & cranberry . has a big corn husk background . ( d ) - a basically good beer to have around for the holidays .  a moderate pour yields a 1/2-finger off-white head that deteriorates to a thin clumpy dusting and thin foam ring in just a couple minutes . the body is a beautifully clear golden amber with just a few small carbonation bubbles . some light lacing can be seen clinging to the glass throughout consumption .  mouthfeel was pleasant . a medium bodied chewiness and good carbonation .

smell : lots and lots of blueberries .  from the brewery , thanks neighbors ! a - golden in color , no head , light carbonation .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated and good level of thickness - probably the best part of this beer .

s - it smelled of citrusy hops - mostly orange peel aromas . there was a sweet maltiness to the nose , too .  a - hazy orange , thin white cap , no lacing .  m : silky smooth feel . i like the finish . smoothed out my palate .

quite pleasant on the nose without being much on the side of complex .  pours a hazy straw color with a one finger head that disappears into a ring around the glass smells of belgian yeast , wheat , and spicy esters .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is well balanced with a nice medium body , leaning a bit on the heavier side . drinkability : the mouthfeel is great and there is no sign of the 7 % abv .

appearance : dark brown , not ebony , slight retention , no lacing smell : some roasted and coffee aroma taste : flat , low on taste , just not much there .  served in a hill farmstead tulip glass . a - minimal carbonation . thin-late rising wisp of bubbles that linger on top . not much of a looker here .  full bodied with a smoothy , creamy mouthfeel .

laces well throughout process s-smells like a coffee stout ( what a shocker ) . smell the roasted coffee up front with a slight chocolate malt i think t/m-eh , it does its job well , it tastes like it should .  this beer poured a brown color with very little head .  m : very fizzy , light on body , about right for the style .

but since it 's summertime , i 've been drinking more beer and have been quite impressed with the quality of crafty beers out there ( if only i did n't live on the upper east side of nyc , where you do n't get much of a beer selection at the supermarkets and delis ) . i was not a big fan of this beer - i enjoy ipa 's , but this one seemed all hops and nothing else .  paid $ 9.99 for party source to fill my growler ... the beer pours a very dark brown base , with a medium white head , 20 minutes of head retention and a speck or two of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel was full and sweet .

smell is actually quite strong , a blast of medicinal malts , along with hops .  brown bottle into a sam adams glass . the body was golden brown/amber with a pocked , off-white head .  had a funny texture in the mouth and could definitely taste dried fruit but could not discern the type .

smell : sweet in it caramel and rum raisin like scent .  poured into a 12-oz mug , this beer is a murky orange-tinted brown color with almost no head retention , and in fact barely a hint of foam at all on top .  the mouthfeel is really soft and creamy , as i figured cask would be .
smell : grapefruit , peach , yeast when it warms .  could n't get a head going on it . no lacing . dark brown in color .  m : crisp , clean , would call it refreshing if it tasted better .

the smell of yeast and citrus filled the nose . the smell of banana is also there .  if you 've ever had melbourn bros apricot , this kind of reminds me of that in terms of taste . very spritzy -- like carbonated pineapple juice with a zest of lemon . almost no head when i poured it , but you certainly do n't need head on this beer to catch a good aroma ; it 's exceptionally strong .  maybe i could not taste the `` rare '' but this really sucked compared to the 2008 classic gueuze which is a fantastic gueuze .

sherry-like oxidation is unfortunately , very profound in the aroma . nuts and ripe fruits are present in the aroma as well , with hints of peanut brittle , caramel corn and mocha . the mouth experience is quite tame , considering the style . unfortunate oxidation initially on the palate , while on the mid-palate ripe fruity esters and mocha hints are present , which leads into a caramel , port-like finish .  12oz bottle into pint glass pours a deep gold color , one finger off-white head , with a decent amount of chunky particulates .  buttery thick mouthfeel .

it was nice . taste was primarily strong rich malt .  appearance : pours a rich honey color with practically no head . this beer hits the spot quite nicely .  m - good mouthfeel . a little heavier thanks to the lack of filtration .

smell is sweet and quite hoppy , smells a lot like raw carrot . sweet chocolate and coffee aromas that are heavier .  presentation dark brown glass 330 ml bottle with freshness date on rear label . a- midnight , dark opaque brown , very slim off-white head which disappeared quickly .  medium bodied and decent carbonation .

piny , a bit fruity , very pungent .  gold color capped by a thin head . it does n't look as bright as i expected so i take a closer glance . i see a fine haze of tiny particles in the glass , though i only poured in half the bottle .  mouthfeel : thick and what you would expect from a ris .
smell : raisin and roasted malt .  served in a flute . transparent amber-brown body with visible bubbles streams . no cap , lace , etc .  it is pretty full bodied and creamy .

deep mahogany body that looks more like a dark brown ale around the edges than a stout . i can smell a bit of malt sweetness as the beer sits on the table in front of me . lifting it to my nose i get more of a bourbon and peat note . alcohol , malt , caramel , vanilla , and smokiness intertwined . the initial sip is a bit edgy with almost a sour note on the finish .  a- straw with some haze .  mouthfeel is heavier than i 'd anticipate . i wish i liked the flavor of this because its heaviness is spot on .

nice aroma . chocolatey and roasty .  pours a hazy golden color with a one fingered head that quickly fades to a barely noticeable cap .  nice creaminess from the malt . probably the driest amber ale i 've ever had . usually not a bad thing , i like dry beers , but this was too much , there needs to be a little sweetness there to bring it to life . should n't be called an octoberfest and would n't try again .

s : some really great aroma here - coconut , vanilla ... not sure how else describe the slight alcohol aroma but reminds me of spiced rum t : big alcohol burn .  pours a golden yellow , just a touch of haze and a rocky , bright white head .  mouthfeel is about right for style , perhaps a touch undercarbed , but all else is acceptable , though it showcases a flavor profile best left behind the curtain .

s : a fruity smell predominates , some citrus notes , but a cherry and raisin aroma is stronger . a mildly piny hop presence is there as well .  absolutley no head or film . wonderful color and clarity , but the lack of head/lacing/film dissapoints me .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , light-medium bodied and pretty dry .

smell is thick hop resin , extremely floral and sticky . nicely complex , with a strong bitterness and sweet underlying malt character . taste is bitter , earthy , and vegetabley . the flavors are deep , dirty , and almost unpleasant .  color is a deep garnet with amber highlights . gave me a thin cap of tan head and very little lacing .  mouthfeel was nice and thick ; you know you 're drinking a dipa .

nice notes on the nose - lots of toffee and caramel with a pleasant citric fruit character piping through , perhaps a little pineapple which stops the rich malt and caramel from becoming overpowering .  the color and clarity are oustanding , but a lack of retention or lacing is concerning .  m- very smooth . medium carbonation fills the mouth a little . d- good .

smell is very nice . lemon grass , citrus hops , with a very nice and strong caramel malt backround .  no problem though , taste is fine , colour is nice and although there is no head and very little in the way of lacings , the body is pretty nice .  strong carbonation . m. very bitter and the carbonation is clean and tart .

smell - apples , citrus , yeast and alcohol .  a hazy dark yellow color with a head that i missed since i looked in another direction ( for 3 seconds ) while rvdoorn poured the beer .  m : light body , moderate carbonation , nice crisp body .

had a very hoppy aroma upon first sniff . second whiff hints at fruity aromas that almost smell like a fruit salad .  orange hazy full head reduces to a thin layer .  the body is pleasant and perfectly appropriate for a light belgian ale . full of carbonation , relatively light in the mouth , easy to drink ; no complaints on this front ; this beer only becomes a problem when you have to smell it or taste it .

pleasant aroma is light and spicy , clean fresh ginger .  appearance : light amber color , lighter than paulaner 's version with decent amount of carbonation smell : slightly fruity notes and a little bit of hops come out as i swirled the brew in my glass .  m : thick creamy mouthfeel .

pretty neutral fruity aroma with hints of spices and alcohol .  pours very dark brown , almost black with slightly effervescent light tan head , very small patchy downsliding lacing .  m : well carbonated and thick , fairly heavy . fits the style .
the aroma is of dark chocolate and malty with a hint of coffee lurking in the shadows .  huge bubbles due to strong carbonation and no lacing .  m - pretty good .

i like this nose quite a bit . t - no where near as tasty as it smells . this looks really nice and smells good too , but it falls short once you get the stuff into your mouth .  a - poured very little head , and left very little lacing.. and i know my glass is clean . looks like an ipa ... nice orangey-amber glow .  the mouthfeel is smooth and oily and the carbonation is alright .

s : lots of sweet dark fruit , candi sugar , and some sweet lighter fruits as well . t : prunes , figs , candi sugar , cinammon , and a little lurking booziness .  pours a thin a off white head that rapidly dissipates into the ethers . body is deep brown-black . the oakiness becomes a bit more pronounced ion the flavor along with some of the accompanying bourbon . new hollands crown jewel indeed . i drank this around cellar temperature which really seemed to bring out its full character .  really nice body all around ... overall - i would really enjoy this beer if it were n't for the bubblegum flavor , it 's really off putting and not very pleasant .

smells surprisingly good . the berry aroma really stands out here and is not what i would call subtle like the label implies . i was really pleased with the aroma , but this is just way too much .  dark brown but not black like i was expecting . decent one finger head that leaves quickly smells of rich chinook hops and a sugary malt sweetness .  m : the body is medium to full with a fairly high carbonation . this is actually one of the best things about this beer .

aromas of strong piney hops and roasted malts with hints of caramels and toffee , however the hops dominate the nose . i have had good , bad and average black ales .  pours a deep amber with very little carbonation . no head in trappist glass , just thin ring of white bubbles clinging to the sides for dear life .  there 's big citrus/grapefruit hops , but then a nasty onion/vegetable taste . mouthfeel is fine .
aroma is malty with pleasant notes of bananas .  pours a deep red/brown with no head at all .  m/d : light and smooth feel on the mouth , drinkable but not something i will ever get again .

4.0 s : nice aroma . it smells like a tripel meets saison . for the most part , the goofy ingredients get lost in the mix .  on-tap in a flute at the capital ale house in richmond , this beer arrives orangey and crystal-clear , with low carbonation and a thin , vanishing head .  the aroma contained notes of malt , hops and a discernable alcohol content of medium strength . it had a stong alcohol flavor that was very over powering the other flavors . it was smooth yet burned as it went down . truely a devilish brew !
the aroma is of cocoa and grapefruit , orange and floral notes .  once you get past the weird label , you find a decent ipa .  m : light-medium bodied , creamy , smooth and crisp .

the color was not as dark as i expected for a stout , but it looked nice , had a nice roasted smell to it .  this beer pours a deep rich medium brown/orange color . very hazy and little head , about one finger on the pour .  this has a very creamy mouthfeel to it despite being fairly well carbonated .

super cru appears like it should , starting out with a leather-mahogany color , frothy head . does n't smell too bad either ; nice belgian yeasty notes and the added pear .  a : golden-yellow , fizzy white head , no retention , very little lace .  mouthfeel is crisp and drying , as it should be .
a - looked good s - smelled good t - this beer has an aftertaste similar to when you chew on a fir tree limb .  pours a very dark brown color with a quick head .  the mouthfeel is medium and creamy .

strong sweet , vinous malty scent .  12oz bottle poured into an oversized wine glass pours a murky brown colour with just a thin head and a light lacing on the top .  firm mouthfeel , big and solid . very imperial .

initial aroma of wheat dough and spices faded as beer warmed . mouthfeel was slightly tingly , yet not what i would expect from a white .  the head is a moderate-lived cocoa-colored affair that recedes into a floating patch of film on top of the brew . a few rings here and there , but generally no lacing .  appropriately light in body without being too thin .

smell was quite nice though , a great mix of wheaty goodness and raspberries .  a- poured a amberish coppery orange color if that makes sense . one finger off white head that shows light retention .  however , the mouthfeel was very nice , which lent a overall smoothness and softness to it .
