man this pours pretty , smells of licorice and molasses .  pours black with virtually no head , just a light tan froth that leaves minute dots of lacing .  the mouthfeel was quite good , though . well carbonated and it felt good going down .

pleasant aroma of amarillo hops with notes of mandarin/tangerine .  batch 1 bottle 198 of 228 pours a cloudy peach color with a decently sized white head that slowly reduces to a ring of foam .  i believe the bottle i got was 8.75 percent.. looked pretty good for a esl , smell and taste reminded me very much of great western extra gold.. very malty with a nice solventy sweet-like alcohol burn ... carbonated perfectly , making it halfway drinkable , still hangover juice as far as imports go.. cheers !

a - poured a black color with no head to leave any lace s - is of roasted malt with chocolate some smoke and a little pepper t - follows the nose with some smoke and chocolate but the pepper is the dominant flavor but not overpowering m - this beer has a thin watery body with no carbonation to it d - i still liked it but the lack of carbonation killed this beer to me it was an interesting experiment that tasted good but literally fell flat  12 oz bottle , pours a hazy amber with very little head , even with pouring into the middle of the glass .  this beer feels almost delicate .

a : dark but not black - can see through it up to the light - pour was unimpressive - really no head to speak of from a bottle - no lace - nothing - looks like coke in a glass s : chocolate , vanilla , malt , milk t : very strong bitter in here with the malt , vanilla - seems like they put too many hops in this for it to be a milk/sweet stout .  i love this beer . ok , maybe that is overstating it , but this is one of the most drinkable beers i 've ever had . it does n't generate much of a head when poured and that combined with the yeast dominated taste may make it a bit meek for some . if you like yeast , though , this beer is for you .  the mouthfeel is notably well contoured . dark and hearty though at times cloying .

) s - the aroma is simple , but in its simplicity it places the style perfectly with a nice malty sweetness and hints of toasted nuts and chocolate .  on tap at the anvil in houston , tx a : pours a murky , cloudy reddish/brown color . a minimal tan head forms , but recedes to nothing in a second .  we 're okay though , as next time we get a samuel adams winter sampler pack , i 'll give her my cranberry , and i 'll have her boston lager . it 's not a bad beer , it 's just not to my liking . i ca n't even really say why . a bit sweeter than i 'd like , and just nothing that stands out and says `` i 'm great '' .

such a teaser the nose- complex and swirling with sweet notes of cocoa powder , toffee , freshly ground coffee , raisin , prune , brown sugar , peach and apricot . ) with a low carbonation , a mild and poorly integrated sourness , and a bigtime cloying sweetness upfront- the unfortunate result of the beer 's sweet chocolate flavors clashing head on with the brown sugary fruitiness . like i said , the nose is nice , but it really ends there .  a : deep prune-brown , minimal wisp ring , minimal legs , no lacing .  taste/mouthfeel : mostly hops . heavily malted finish . drinkability : a bit heavy and not quite as good as other european lagers . overall : probably the best gateway to this style .
s : very nice . clearly a stout . lovely sweetness .  pours a murky orange with a thin , clingy head . nothing special in this regard .  there 's actually a nice amount of body to this one .

the aromas are loaded with dank hop earthiness and woodiness from the oak aging . defintely also some citrus/pine and the alcohol notes finish out the smells . the tastes are good , with apple brandy-like alcohol that is hot on the tongue right off the bat , but this one is too syprupy for me . the oak is there , but not in a good way , and the thickness/syrup qualities , detract from the hops .  there were a few big bubbles , but very minimal head . there was lacing but it did n't really stick to the glass .  mouthfeel is light with a good spike of carbonation .

a full white head of three fingers , over one finger hangs for awhile , good lacing ... the aroma is pretty nice , lots of clove and wheat , sweet and nice , surprised ... the taste is not good at all , the clove turns in banana vodka , harsh , alcoholic , astringent , not good .  pours an opaque orange/brown , thin tan head forms , disappears to a thin ring really fast , some lace spots .  taste is a very light malt sweetness upfront with a moderately bitter finish of good length and crispness . a pretty uncomplicated beer , good for the style , a good lawnmower beer .

s -- good smell , a bit of the hops and malt . kind of smells like an ipa t -- taste was initially promising with a slight hop taste to it .  a : muddy brown with limited tan head that quickly fades but leaves lace on he edge .  nice carbonation and creamy mouthful .

a big sniff presents brown sugar , molasses , a touch of butterscotch , and a tad of bittersweet chocolate .  served a crisp yellow with a thin diminishing head .  mouthfeel is good all around- enough carbo to temper the bitterness , moderately thick , finishes dry . a damn shame .

smell is nice wheat , spice , sweet malt .  cloudy caramel colour with little to no head .  m : fuller side of medium-bodied with moderate carbonation that tickles the tongue and throat . this aspect of the beer is really nice .

aroma is strong with caramel malt , toffee , brown sugar , molasses , and a bit of alcohol .  it poured a very dark brown , and is black in the glass , with no highlights . the head is disappointing . very thin , tan , and does n't last at all .  mouthfeel is decent medium bodied and goes down smooth .

the smell reminds me of peaches in a can with syrup and is slightly interesting . the taste is oily hops on top of a decent amount of malts but is just not very good .  it pours an average golden amber with a decent off-white head , but appearance is this beer 's weakest suit .  feel is pretty smooth , nothing weird here .

super resiny , herbal , and piney nose ; really smells like a shit load of dry hopping .  like most traditional gueuze and like most drie fonteinen , this is pretty damn good stuff but compared to drie fonteinens 50th anniversary gueuze , which was consumed earlier in the day , it was clearly obvious that this was the lesser of the two . hazy nectarine . a good gueuze .  crisp , clean mouthfeel with flavors of dry , pale malt . at first , i found myself wanting more flavor , a la boston lager , but the mouthfeel and resulting drinkability really brought things back up for me in the end .

aroma is pungent with herbs , mostly sassafras . i really enjoy the aroma of this . simply too sweet , and the herbal essence is too overbearing .  i was lured into the purchase by the pretty pink cherry blossoms on the can and my desire for the neverending hokkaido winter to end.. the beer is a thin yellow , with light , fast-fading bubbles . there 's a light , roasted grain taste which appeals ... until ... the incredibly nasty aftertaste hits , which sends shivers through the body .  m - nice . thick .

aroma is actually quite good . sweet rasberry aroma , mixed with a nice lager like smell .  taste is of a clean blonde , well done and superior to macros , but without much interest , thin bodied and typical .  feels very creamy but that does n't make the beer more drinkable to me .

a : pours a slightly cloudy light brown , no head to speak of , appears rather lifeless in the glass s : nose features healthy dose of roasted malts , mild caramel notes , no hops t : taste is nothing like the nose promised , very thin and watery up front , muted ashy malts , bad balance , not quite as enjoyable as i had hoped mf : very light body , mild carbonation o : the nose is quite nice with this brew , but that 's where it ends .  appearence ... slight haze ( no big deal ) but the color is way off . looks like an amber .  m. medium-high carbonation , zesty on the tongue .

s : super sweet chocolate is the main thing that i get at first . the beer is sitting a foot away from me and all i can smell is cocoa puffs .  a- golden yellow little no white lace / head s- a slight skunky smell to it light hop odor t- tasted like your average heineken , nothing to really stand out m- went down smooth , slight aftertaste the beer skunk after taste very thin d- not bad would have been better on a hot day , not one i would run out and get again but might have it if i were out for italian .  smacks-you-in-the-face astringent . zippy on the mouth like you 'd expect .

odd sweetness behind the tartness , still had no problem drinking a few glasses of it at la mort subite cafe in brussels though .  the color is an awful yellow .  feel medium body , pleasant texture , some drying and bitterness in the finish .

does n't look like much , more like a cheap domestic pilsner , but smells pretty inviting .  appearance : crystal clear pale yellow with a thin ring of lace that has trouble staying around .  m : medium-bodied with low and sightly creamy carbonation . there is a slight sticky feel and syrupy feel .

i also get a sort of hospital sanitation aroma . i always think sahti smells very interesting and inviting as well as completely authentic . t - quite mild .  appearance - super clear pale and yellow , looks like discolored water .  very refreshing in the mouth , its best quality .

looked nice and had a nice aroma to it , but i just never got into it .  a : pours out a light yellow amber , with less than fingers width of off what head that dissipates almost immediately . leaves no lacing .  m : the carbonation is pretty much just right , and it 's smooth .

sampled from a 12oz bottle at the falcon 's christmas in july tasting sharp citrusy aroma with a grapefruit rind approach with some dry toasty malt notes . it 's unfortunate , but i i 'm cerrtain this was a well travelled bottle of what feels like it should be an otherwise fine beer .  the appearance is pale gold with a small head .  mouthfeel is crisp , the whole drink is refreshing due to the good carbonation .

smell : cocoa , as expected , along with some good roasted malt . smells like a promising porter .  this unusually plain pale ale is a pee yellow , and has an aroma of musty basement inhabited by a cat . it is a little less than ideal for a standard american pale ale , but will certainly do in a pinch when decent beer is needed for mindless television watching .  m : medium body and very good amount of carbonation in my opinion .

spicey , fruity , and perfumey nose .  it was a light , translucent yellow in the glass with a filmy head . a thick lace would form as i sipped , but it would quickly slide back down into the beer . but it was not as wheaty as a hefeweizen .  mouthfeel is medium with good level of carbonation .

smells rather good , nice and woodsy with slight citrus and forward hops at the end . fairly different from the nice smell . kinda disappointed .  seems like this cheap import is on sale every week at winn-dixie . this pours a light , watery yellow with a medium-sized , but thin head .  taste - 3.0/5.0 - light `` summer '' type beer , prob good if really hot , some malt crispness feel - 4.0/5.0 - smooth , light , refreshing drinkability - 2.5/5.0 - would have again , if it was hot , but not enough flavor make this a go-to beer

s : fresh smell of citrusy hops . t : unfortunately not as good as it smells .  a - pours a very pale golden colour , finger f head with no retention or lacing .  this beer does have a nice smooth , dry mouthfeel .
s : dominated by citrus , get a lot of tangerine , citrus , pineapple , and an earthy belgian yeast kick , light pepper .  straw yellow appearance with very little head .  medium carbonation .

i 've heard things about this one , so was pretty jazzed to get to try it at the firk ' last night . it pours a mostly clear peach juice topped by a finger of off-ecru foam . the nose comprises apricot , light brett , green apple , light caramel , lime , and light toffee .  odouls premium & extra smooth na brew pours weak yellow from a 12oz green bottle with a twist off cap . head goes to about one finger then poof , its gone ... no wisp no lace ... the top of the brew is smooth as glass .  lighter body and a nice lively carbonation .

aroma is strongly chocolaty , with a hint of alcohol . taste is a let down after the nice aroma . roasty cold coffee with maybe a smidgeon of bitter chocolate and metallicness .  pours amber without any head .  mouthfeel is sticky and sweet with a nice roundness and full character .

aroma starts with a tropical fruit note , some fruit salad and then turns into pine . smell is the best part , downhill from there .  light , but clean golden straw color . i dont want to hijack my own review with a comparison to other lime beers , namely miller chill , but i feel i must . while miller chill actually does a litle something for me with its somewhat confectionary and artificial salty/limey taste , this beer is just a weak light beer with a hint of lime . id almost rather pull the faux pas of putting a lime wedge in a slightly more flavorable beer .  '' m - actually a nice and robust mouthfeel , i just do n't really want to feel this beer in my mouth because it tastes kind of terrible .

uh huh , this smells like a chocolate stout . another one of trader joe 's deals here . aroma is better than flavor .  the soapy white head sinks quickly into very poor lacings .  good , solid creamy feel with enough dryness to get you through .

s - smells actually quite nice , a toasty bready malt , chocolate , and some curry power .  ugly dirty brown .  mouthfeel was good and thick , but was n't enough to save this beer from being a disappointment .

pours and looks like a glass of diet dr. pepper s : caramel , banana , sweet bread dough . t : tastes of wheat and toasted corn .  well this stuff sucks . get drunk and visit a frat party .  i did n't want to buy this because i do n't trust twisted pine to sell me a good beer . since i am a sucker and i love hoppy beers i bought it anyway . the smell was very hoppy citrus , pine and something off i could n't place until i tasted it , butter . this beer was quite disappointing and i poured out the remaining 13 or so ounces after i finished my first glass .
the aroma is sweet melon with some grassy , fruity , spicy floral hops .  *did not mind would not buy* app : haze pale yellow water .  carbonation is very fine , which leads to a good mouthfeel .
smelled of sweet malt , rich and heavy .  a - pale straw color ; clear .  mouthfeel - some creamy smoothnes , well-carbonated .

the smell is also quite pleasant and interesting . apple skins , lemon zest , belgian candi sugar , complex alcohols , malt backing , and dry-ish . it is a terrible combination .  appearance : pours amberish brown in color with a surprising amount of sediment in the beer .  m : chewy and viscous . if anything , the aging has tempered some of the trademark trainwreck mouthfeel and flavors of base dark lord , so i 'm impressed .

s - fruity and sweet and alcoholic . very different than a raspberry lambic .  a - pale gold with a small head that quickly dissipated to only the larger bubbles and no lacing in moments .  nice mouthfeel .

easily swirled . the nose knows : roasted malt , expresso , burnt brown sugar , toffee , hickory bbq tang , hop bitterness to balance . expresso , bitter chocolate covered hops , quick bittering and alcohol evident in the finish . the nose is more diverse . no detection of anything smokewise .  appearance : pours a light-golden yellow hue , with a half-finger head that quickly dissipates into nothingness . not impressed . while this beer pours out looking horrible , and smelling average , the taste and overall refreshment factor makes it a very nice beer .  glass : new belgium globe aging notes : one year at ~60f in the dark bang for the buck ( oz* % / $ ) : 22*6.2/10 = 13.64 a : orange , white lacey head , slightly cloudy from yeast s : horse-y farmhouse brett with hints of orange t : brett dominates ( horse-stable hay , a little dung almost ) , notes of orange m : silky , coating , lingering , pleasant o : worth drinking , a little one-dimensional with the brett .

s : scent quite good , grapefruit & melon , hops .  brown 33cl bottle , best before 02-2010 , poured carefully into a westmalle chalice leaving the sediment in the bottle . pale yellow and slightly hazy/cloudy with a small white wisp on top , a poor collar tried to hang onto the glass but failed after about two minutes .  if there is , then this ska brew is a prime example ... this is the second time i tasted a bottle of this brew . this is an extremely clean tasting brew which is a great quality i enjoy , but where are the hops ? the malt and ( not overwhelming ) bitterness serve as great supporting backbones to what should be a wonderful hoppy aroma and flavor . as it stands , this brew is severely lacking in hop flavor/aroma and comes across as a brew which should be named `` delicate '' rather than `` decadent '' imperial ipa .

aromas of chocolate , roasted malts , and very light oat . tastes of roasted malts , chocolate , oatmeal , and i was getting tin .  pours a clear apple juice gold with a 1 finger quickly dissipating white head that leaves zero lace .  the mouthfeel is medium to full with decent carbonation .

aroma is interesting and pleasant , a blend of sweet tropical fruits and sugars with a musty , earthy belgian yeast and estery typical saison base .  a : lots of debris floating around in the beer . i know this is unfiltered beer , but the amount of junk in the beer is imo out of line .  you do n't get much of the sweet malts you get from the aroma so it really confuses the senses and does n't make for an enjoyable experience mouthfeel is heavy and it sticks to your mouth for minutes .

s - instantly linseed and lemon peel smells entered the room when the cap was popped . some honey-comb sweet waxy smells and a bit of powdered sugar .  pours a dark copper color with no head . good clarity , but the complete lack of visual carbonation was a turn off .  pretty much just a tingly water . very smooth and somewhat refreshing beer .

the nose is sweet malts with hints of golden fruit and a smattering of spiciness . it'sa shame , too , because i have had some really good beers from green flash ( the double stout is really good .  the appearance is pale gold with a slight white hue and a small head that fades fast .  m- a good body to it . good weight and smooth carbonation . there is a strange foamy texture in the finish though .

nose is weak chocolate , figs , and roasted barley .  this is an awesome , cheap , f**k you up-type beer . yellow , smells like alcohol and corn . sometimes you just want a crappy beer , and this is it .  pleasantly effervescent mouthfeel .

not a big fan of this one , but it 's drinkable . i expect more of a fruit profile if the fruit is in the name . sweet and low bitterness , perhaps a bit too sweet .  pours a hazy orange with tons of large sediment , it looks like floating flakes of brown shit ( yuk ) , the head is off-white ( almost yellow ) and small , it does leave some sheets of lace.the nose is lightly toasted and malty , sweet with hints of marshmellow and citrusy hops.the taste is straight forward , sweet hops fruity and citrusy ( grapefruit mostly ) with some pale malts in a subtle balance , a nice bitter edge keeps things interesting but i would have enjoyed more tangyness and depth.the mouthfeel is a little to sticky on the lips for me , the body is medium and the carbonation is low.i have always avoided taking bar flys home , this one is no exception .  crisp , good body overall .
it smells sweet and floral , but not too strong .  this pours with a fizzy short-lived head , over very very pale yellow liquid .  pretty slick mouthfeel .

smell : dry , musty and earthy , with clove , banana and black pepper .  pale straw colouring , head subsided almost immediately and made the beer appear quite flat once it had .  i like the feel with some prickly carbonation and moderately light feel and some creaminess from the head .

bottle from 99 bottles federal way , wa a : poured a glowing golden orangish color with good carbonationa and a nice white head s : citrus , booze , sweet and perfumey t : heres a story..there i was at the daily pint in sanata monica , ca decide to get a pint of the 2nd anny ipa and upon the first sip i was like whoa..to perfumey , to much booze and sweetness . the mango and tropical fruits were overpowering .  i drink miller light because it 's lower in carbs and calories then other beers yet still has a good beer taste without a bad `` light beer '' aftertaste . it might not be a premium beer for special occasions but it 's a great everyday-beer for the everyday drinker .  a little sticky and a very bitter aftertaste .

it smells pretty good , too .  pours an insanely pale color , it looks like watered down lemonade , not even sure if i have seen a beer with this little color before , has no head either , pretty boring overall .  surprisingly , the sediment was n't hard and i did n't feel a corporeal presence in my mouth . coopers best extra stout was nice on the palate ; softly carbonated and creamy . to tell you the truth , i was a bit disappointed .
good aroma , lace , but sour and strong carbonation .  extremely pale straw golden yellow in color and completely clear .  m : medium bodied , good amount of carbonation .

smell : wine , apples , a light wildness , and a dark malty base .  if you pour it good you can get absolutely no head on it , looks like apple juice when you do .  the body of this beer suits the style with the usual level of north coast drinkability and feel to it . definitely the best feature .

4.0 s : surprisingly grainy , which i like . roastiness , some toffee , and a touch of coffee . fairly simple , but pleasant nonetheless .  poured into a pint glass from the bottle a-has the look of a normal american macro light yellow with no head .  smooth and refreshing , light to medium bodied with a slight tingling on the tongue .
pretty classic pilsener nose .  light gold color with a bubbly head that dissolves right away .  m - low carbonation , tiny bubbles , overall feels pretty good .

attractive , yet eerie - too clear and unnatural . aroma boasts of a spicy , assertive hops , but the flavor profile does not fulfill the promise .  poured a pale yellow colour with absolutely zero head nor lacing .  light and creamy mouth feel with obviously knocked down carbonation .

smell : very malty with strong hints of chocolate .  a - poured into a pint glass , this beer is absolutely indistinguishable from ginger ale . o - i bought this beer on a tip that it was identical to other american macros at a substantial discount . pbr 's even cheaper and much better , though - if for some reason you 're looking to buy an american macro , there 's no good reason to pick this up .  m-fairly dry . medium high carbonation .

aroma is very nice , surprisingly fruity , almost like a belgian pale .  the opaque black body is entirely headless , laceless and lackluster with a distressing lack of carbonation .  mouthfeel is nice and thick and well carbonated . the best part of the beer .

smells very nice , with strong citrus/lemon/fruitiness , and a good dose of floral .  it poured a murky , yellow-white color . very hard to describe . it also was corn .  m : moderate carbonation with a decently viscous mouthfeel .
rich chocolate aroma with a decent bit of hops in the back ground .  clear yellow in color with no head at all .  m : medium-light body ; moderate carbonation ; smooth and clean mouthfeel .

smelled pretty good , hops & grain filled the nose immediately . after sitting for a moment , the smell faded slightly , but still nice . tasted some hops , but not nearly as dominant as i prefer .  *did not mind would not buy* app : kinda bland and yucky colored yellow , white head that was here and then suds .  feels slick , not very carbonated , and heavy . alcohol warming is powerfully strong . lacks balance and drinkability .

smells nice , a bit fruity , with a refreshing effervescent quality . does smell a bit on the citrus side .  a : solid black , no head , inert , no lacing -- wow it looks dead s : roasted barley with waffs of leather t : burned barley taste detracts from what otherwise would be a simple , pleasant stout ; very lightly hopped , so not complex m : the lack of head and carbonation really detracts from the mouthfeel i 'm a big fan of growler 's -- i 'm prouder of no other ; but this batch did n't turn out well .  there 's moderate carbonation to it as well .

rich and clean mexican beer smell . beautiful red orange appearance it went downhill with the taste .  lacing is sparse to nil . too bad the appearance is hum-drum .  aroma : hops . the crystal hops dominate the aroma . the malt is there , but overpowered by hops . but i do n't taste the balance that an esb should have . the hops weigh far more than the malt in this beer . notes : this tasted like a very good ipa , but did not have the balance i was expecting , for an esb . a great beer , but did n't fit the style as well as i would have liked .

sweat , citrus aroma . almost caramel , but not as overpowering . mildly bitter , with a heavy feel on the palate .  had this with my thai food tonight , worked alright poured golden with 1 finger of white head . zero head retention & lacing s : sweetness , a bit of grassy hops & that is it t : some honey malt , adjunct cereal sweetness & slight lemon hops up front .  good carbonation .

aroma is earthy , piney hops , maybe simcoe , balanced quite nicely with a bready malt backbone .  zero head . o : the lack of head and almost non-existent carbonation seems off .  mouthfeel is pretty good however , with a nice medium feel .

the nose is straight up cherry . almost too much cherry .  my bus driver purchased this for me from a 7-11 outside of cancun ... appears a transparent light gold with a small white head that quickly fades out . tiny remnants of lacing are left .  m = moderately carbonated . good .

nice . malty small hops in the nose .  this is typical beer of a brazilian macro brewery . a pale industrial lager as many other brazilian competitors , with a little more bitterness .  good mouthfeel for this light body but the hops balance the feel .

aroma is an intense , lightly parching cherried candy and sweet chocolate , however mildly artificial . cordial cherries dominate the initial flavor , in that sold at the counter , wrapped in red foil , in plastic trays , at a midwestern gas station , kind of way . stout character takes over with a salty and pithy stout run .  a new beer can in my country , specifically in my city , little better than its other presentation glass bottle , made by miller , a strong american brewer in my country , i think best than a & b in market participation , a 32 oz beer , like `` caguama '' , i drink in a pilsner glass , its taste is like crusehd hops , little of malt liquour reminicense , poor color , pale yellow , poor lacing , good for the mexican food , 70 % recommended .  adequate carbonation .

the smell included subtle notes of nutmeg/pumpkin .  a : typical adjunct pale and clear yellow body with circumferential white head that disspaeared quickly . no lacing . s : corn grains , some vague hop aromas and some slight cheap german pilsener alcohol smell when just poured and while it 's cold .  char davies , the artist in 1998 , made a fully interactive immersive visual/aural virtual artwork called ephemere , which furthers the work begun in osmose started in 1995 and displayed in the national gallery of canada in ottawa on june 26 , 1998. who cares ? this beer is almost close to a champaign ( and i would think that the yeast probably is champaign ) . also there is bitterness , which is nice to know that at least there are some hops to the so called beer . it is not advisable to use apples with fermenting , as the yeast creates funky flavors from apples , but this is much better than expected . although i would not want to drink this beer on a regular bases , thus low score on drinkability , i think it has a great taste like a grandsmith apples i use to eat as a kid .

the smell was pretty good . i was intrigued actually .  pours out of the bottle with just a thing layer of foam that disappears almost immediately . the body is really a dull amber body with not much going on .  the mouth-feel is thick almost porter-like with the cooling of the alcohol evaporation .

peachy wine smell , a little apple cider like .  a : pours a one finger head of decent slight cream , okay thickness , and downright bad retention .  mouthfeel was good and very drinkable ; however , it was slightly bitter ... something i was n't expecting this to have considering the malts .

aroma is malty with breads and burnt sugars . i did n't care for it , but my roommates gf said its good for girls and she really likes it .  appearance could easily be confused with a miller lite , very pale yellow with a frothy white head that instantly fizzles away .  the drink is carbonated a little more than average as well . mf- very crisp beer with little or no after taste . one of the smoother beers around .

assertive citrus aroma features plenty of orange , backed by pine .  it came served flat with no head or lace in a shade of yellow-gray .  mouthfeel was smooth , light , though i do n't know i 'd go as far as crisp .

pours a deep ruby as relatively low carbonation pushes up a meagre white head with rather horrendous retention - not bsda-appropriate at all ... '' ruby '' carries through as a concept in the aroma with some nice plum & cherry-type scents wafting up . simple , overall , but i like the way this stuff smells .  pours a hazy 24 karat gold color , with considerable amounts of chunkiness floating in it , despite a very slow pour . protein flakes everywhere in the beer , makes this truly disgusting to look at . no head and no lacing to speak of .  m : it has a nice mouthfeel .

it smells quite fruity ( apples ) and a bit astringent .  12 oz bottle poured into a pint glass a- cloudy dirty brown color s- faint sweetness , i assume is supposed to be cherry t- very weak ( if any ) cherry flavor , like a severely water down juice m- very little carbonation , feels like a soda that went flat d- fortanetly , i got this with a mix and match .  m - crisp and refreshing o - overall pretty meh .

i poured this beer a bit aggressively and it came up frothing barely over the rim of the cup with a light white head that went away pretty quickly . the smell really jumped out at me with oranges and spice . it 's a really cloudy orange color -- looks like i got some yeast in there too .  poured into a pounder glass at a rapid pace and produced a light fizzy head that reduces to nothing quicker than tom leykis can diss a beeeeatch . as soon as i poured this a huge apple juice aroma explosion . which i imagine is a byproduct of the cypress wood aging .  mouthfeel is light ( duh ) , but not too thin , and nicely carbonated , giving it a bit of a zip , but not too effervescent . probably the best part of the beer .
been a while since i 've had a stout . burnt roasty smell with coffee , cocoa , and cream ... a smokey , woody , hot cocoa almost .  well the appearance is rather limp .  good carbonation .

s : the red ale has plenty of caramel to go around , a sweet aroma with plenty of strength . too bad too , because the nose has a really nice aroma .  12oz bottle appearance - the beer pours a clear yellow colour with an average size fizzy white coloured head . the head was gone in a flash .  the mouth is thick and malty . as far as drinkability , i have to say that i would be really happy to have one of these if i was alive 4000 years ago but for now i 'm going to have to go for something else .

s - coffee with with a hint of sweetness . t - a solid coffee taste in the beginning ... and that is where it left off .  pours a cloudy dirty honey brown color with a smallish soapy off-white head that almost immediately disipates into nothingness , very flat looking . does not look like a bavarian hefeweizen . it looks terrible , then just gets by as an american wheat .  body is light and crisp and finishes clean .
smooth and balanced aroma . t/m- coffee flavor with some medicine mixed about .  appearance low head . looks uninviting .  medium mouthfeel .

one strange feature , when poured it fizzes with carbonation like a soda , very unusual and it continues to fizz for some time s-chocolate , molasses and bourbon t-when cold it follows the nose , but as it warms both the smell and tastes become overwhelmingly strong with bourbon , almost too much m-above average , but due to the abv , it 's more like whiskey than stout d-i hate to be contrary to others , but i did n't really care for this , it 's described by others as a `` sipping beer '' and while i appreciate that , if i wanted to drink bourbon i just would , this did n't do it for me  there is absolutely no head to be found on this beer when i receive it .  very smooth without being too full bodied .

smell- a nice cherry scent that was not over whelming at all .  appearance- deep french onion soup color , maybe a weak cherry cough syrup color . pours completely flat . really quite lifeless .  mouthfeel is crisp and a little sizzly . refreshingly light bodied and clean .

the aroma is pleasing with a dominant smell of overripe peaches backed by toasty malt and pecans .  very pale yellow and not much head . minimal bubbles floating to the top .  full body , syrupy like samichlaus . very similar tastes and mouthfeel .

a - clear yellowish orange , very thin head that dissapates almost immediately s - lots of bright apple and spice , by far the best facet of this one . t - not really sweet , but possessing a lot of apple and spice . not very endearing . d - very drinkable , if not the the disappointing taste .  pours a pale straw without much head .  m/d ) very soft mouthfeel .

very earthy aroma with a strong pine needle character along with some floral and citrus hop notes . strong tongue-coating pine flavor that overpowers the other notes that te nose hinted at .  pours with virtually no head and no lace .  there 's also just a hint of citrus from the orange peel ( or orange oil extract ) the smooth mouthfeel and moderate body is not unlike that of a german hefeweizen .

( s ) - slight dry paleness with a sweet lemon , honey , and biscuity wheat characteristics . bits of clay & yeast behind some minimal pine coming through on the finish . ( t ) - really dry and bitter pine that overpowers some ( from what i can tell ) biscuits and banana with a twist of clove ; but it is hard to tell .  pours a pale golden colour with less than a finger of quickly dissipating soapy white head that leaves zero lace .  m - a fairly heavy mouthfeel with all the sweetness .

aroma is fruity with white grapes , brewady yeast and a bit of cloves .  appearance - 2.0 pours a very pale straw with 1 finger of quickly disipating head .  mouthfeel : soft creaminess , light to medium carbonation , with a medium to full body .

s - cherries , duh ? but what smelled like very sweet cherries .  its a very cheap beer usually costing about 14-15 bucks . not good for sipping , only for college parties where you wan na get a cheap buzz .  m - crisp and decent carbonation .

s : very candy sweet with buttery caramel , cocoa , cola , toasted dark grain aromas t : the taste is a major disappointment , but the butter in the aroma unfortunately is the foreshadowing of diacetyl bomb .  pours an orange/brown colour , with no head to speak of . a bit of bubbles around the rim of the glass , and nothing between . no lace as well . the beer is a pretty colour , that 's about all the positive i can give for appearance .  good body and mouthfeel .

the pour ... .no ... the pop of the cork ... did n't happen . it 's cloudy partly because of a chill haze i assume . the cork came out too easily and it was n't tight . this brewery makes good beer and this does n't make the cut . i 'm dissappointed .  poured a ornage-copper color . no head .  light-medium caramel malt sweetness up front , continued in the middle with a hint of earthy hop bitterness , finishing with a more of the same . medium mouthfeel .

fruity aroma of pinnaple , banana , carmelised candy sugars , some peppery spice , and a touch of warm alcahol fumes .  a : pours a flat straw-gold ; zero head , zero lacing .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with fine/sharp bubbles .
s- lots of herbal and vegetal hop aromas and some dark roasty malt .  actually looks totally flat .  mouthfeel - good smoothness , a medium body on par with the style , crisply carbonated .

s : the smell is nice . whiskey , booze , malts , molasses , really deep and balanced .  the color is a clear pale yellow or faint gold .  m- really good carbonation , low abv and the nearly great sweet/tart balance make it actually react quite nicely with the mouth .

an impressively hoppy aroma . some citrus aromas , some biting alcohol , and caramel malt . not particularly interesting and relatively one-note , but certainly hoppy .  ( end sarcasm ) clear gold color with a failry sizable head .  light body and nice and creamy . moderate carbonation .
the aroma is of roasted/ chocolate malts and grainy alcohol hints .  pours a golden straw color with no head , even after pouring into the middle of the glass .  mouthfeel is creamy and crisp .

s- cinnamon scent is ever-present and festive . t- pumpkin and earthy but no hops .  a : pours a light purple color with a pink/white head this disolves quickly .  the mouthfeel is moderately thick and full for a pilsner and has a creamy texture . the citrusy hops create a crisp bite towards the end .
s - lightly minerally aroma , dark , malty cocoa .  poors out with hardly any head and has an amberbrown color with lots of white haze .  this is a medium bodied , well carbonated beer .

the smell was good and true to form : clear , crisp , and clean , plenty of wheat and yeast , nice and spicey , and cirtusy-sweet too .  one finger of loose foamy head settles quickly to a wisp after a vigorous pour . no lacing .  the body is nice and thick , with a flavorful malt profile : sweet medium caramel malts with a bit of roast character . hops , by the way , are almost nonexistent , which would n't be bad if not for the oxidation , which makes the faint floral flavor seem dull . overall not bad , but has the same type of oxidized or maybe just oversparged flavor common to other corporate breweries like gordon-biersch .

back in the aroma i am digging the rich toasty bready stuff . there is a bit of the aroma 's promise for maybe a quarter second , then , `` wham ! i would imagine that if the flavor held to the aroma this would be a nice red ale that i could drink a ton of , but this one just is n't right .  pours yellow and very cloudy . one finger head , soapy but dense . poor lacing and a few specs of lace .  the body is somewhere between medium and full , with a creamy mouthfeel .

not much else and not too complex , but it had nice depth and smelled good . mouthfeel : medium-bodied , getting close to edging towards full bodied .  i firmly believe that everything that comes from pabst is the same beer , but they put it in different cans for nostalgic purposes . that being said , hell , it 's not that bad . there are hops in it !  the body is on the full side , though not quite as much as most stouts ( i suppose increased attenuation should have been expected with the switch in yeast strain ) , and has a solidly low key carbonation .

good clean , refreshing scent . taste = good taste upfront but too much sourness comes through .  from the bottle it poured a dirty gold color with about a 1 '' head .  m - solid and full , with good carbonation .

even before the glass got in front of me the green apple aroma hit me in the face . it dominates right from the start and influences everything else . a medium body is again dominated by the tart green apple with a tang from the carbonation .  pours as a cloudy orangeish color . resembles frankiszer but has some sediment floating around in it - probably just active yeast culture . definitely wonky - has a smell like that of wheat beer but it is n't a wheat beer . has kind of a coriander-orange peel aroma with a touch of wheat ( appears and smells like a blue moon but with a lot more color ) .  the aftertaste lingers nicely , and the mouthfeel is firm . full bodied and smooth , but lacking an extra punch .

if only the taste was equal to the nice aroma : a little watery and light compared to a dense chocolate taste i was hoping .  12oz bottle a- pours a clear golden yellow color with a fizzy white head that quickly disappears .  a - opaque black color with a small head that disappears quickly s - rich chocolate-like aroma , mild yeast esters , some smokiness , no hop perceived t - roasted malt flavor dominates , some yeasty esters and mild hop flavors take a secondary role , very gentle mild hop finish with some lingering smokiness m - smooth creamy medium body with moderately low carbonation d - this is a decent enough oatmeal stout . the head and retention is disappointing , but the smell , taste and mouthfeel are acceptable .

smelled great very rich and malty . unfortunantly that aroma did not carry over in the taste which was on the weak side .  most things were good but this was on of the first offerings of the evening ... that said ... a golden , hazy transparent brew with plenty of sediment . yeah , i know it 's a hefeweizen , but does it have to look like the piss of a liver failure patient ?  mouthfeel was nice - weizenbock like . bananas , black beans , chile peppers and/or pepper jack cheese with some creamyness amidst the carbonation . interesting , no doubt , and worth seeking out if you want something really different .

aroma is hoppy , with some sweet malt .  a : pours light golden with a white soapy head that dissapears quckliy with a sizziling sound . no lace . d : a rather uneven beer ; looks crappy and smells below average but tastes ok and has a really nice aftertaste .  the mouthfeel is very light bodied and good for the class .
good fruity aroma upon opening the bottle .  it 's a pale clear yellow with little head or carbonation .  mouthfeel good . creamy and subtle carbonation . cant complain about this .

while i am a huge barleywine fan , i just do not like this beer at all . smell is that of apricot an fruit .  clear dark brick red pour gives way to quickly settling head with floating clusters of bubbles around the edge if the glass .  the mouthfeel was good , but the drinkability hass to be chopped down due to the smell and the taste of this beer .

aroma of sour cherries jumps out while being poured .  it struggled to pour up a decent head & zero lacing ... very light strawish gold .  mouth is no complaints , it 's low-medium body with relatively high carbonation .

the aroma was very sweet and promising with caramel malts being the forerunner .  this beer looks flat and unappealing to me .  soft prickly carbonation does cleans the pallet , of this light to medium body beer with moderate astringency and warming alcohol .
smells fine .  this is a very pale beer , very light yellow color .  m : creamy and sticks to the mouth for awhile .
the smell is defiantly banana bread , a welcoming aroma .  a : thin , clear , pale yellow -- lots of fizz , but not really a head , nor any lacing .  m - it was very crisp and sharp .

both '97 and '98 pack some serious raisiny , pruny burnt malt smells , with greater concentration in the '97 .  have n't seen the light version of pbr around to often but it showed up at a party i was at . tastes very similar to pbr regular , which is good because i find that better than the usual bud/coors/miller . it 's easy to drink , cheap , and not awful tasting.. what else can you want when its $ 12 a 30 ?  medium mouhfeel with some carbonation . smooth and buttery feel . pretty dry finish .
aroma is nice . light caramel .  a-cloudy yellow/golden color body with a thin head.no lacing and this looks like cloudy piss .  the mouth is pretty nice , feels rich but easy to drink .

carbonation is n't happening , but the nose is unsweetened chocolate sharpened with alcohol .  appearance : this beer looks like flat coca cola .  m - tongue ripping bitterness . medium to full body and tingly carbonation to go with it . good .

smell is nice , slightly sweet malt . right on par .  a : a head that lasts for an average time , that left no lacing nor foam at the edge atop a beer that 's a red-brown ?  taste is mild but the mouthfeel is full pleasantly full and quite nice .

smell : this was a pleasant surprise . sweet , floral notes and hops.. not kidding , i never thought i 'd smell hops in a beer a like this . very sweet , bready , white grapes , sugar , slightly metallic , slightly bitter and just a touch of alcohol .  pours and awkward pinkish red with a little bit of fizz that i cant even call a head . no lacing .  mouthfeel : full-bodied with a strong , expressive carbonation .

disappointed , as i am an avid stone fan and this being my first opportunity with the levitation ale . while the prose was sweet as ever , the brew itself was exceedingly oppressive , strongly hopped -- i would hands down prefer ruination to levitation when it comes to high hops from stone .  a - nothing special . pale straw colour . looks like a typical pale lager : canadian , budweiser , etc .  light body with good carbonation .

attractive lacing . smell is a rich combination of herbs and spices , with sassafras , vanilla , and wintergreen being detected . there are others there , but i am unable to specifically identify them taste also shows lots of spices and herbs and while they combine nicely , they also have there own separate taste sensations .  the appearance was an opaque golden yellow that left a thin white head that dissipated quickly . obviously , little of the head was left clinging to the glass . on the second pour in the same glass , there was more of a head , and more apparent carbonation , but still was not impressive .  bottled under license by the cheval blanc in montreal . light golden ale witha medium head that did not disapear too quickly . the honey taste is very discreet . i could recognize the usual taste of malt from the cheval blanc . enjoyable but not exceptionnal

nice . the liberator is n't quite my bag of tea .  bought as a single bottle at the grocery store . poured very pale , white grape juice look . very few bubbles and a fast dying lace . i feel its limited in how much of it you can drink and when .  m - pretty thick , smooth and a bit refreshing .

the aroma was nice at first . however , i also smelled some interesting belgian aromas , in fact this brew really smelled like hommelbier .  yellow , little head , no lacing , boring . reviewers of beer are like reviewers of art -- for many , it stops being about what tastes or looks good , and starts being about complexity and distinctiveness . if it was lighter , it might be refreshing , but it is n't light .  nice lively mouthfeel .

the smell is good , and in fact is the strongest attribute in my opinion .  pours light gold with a bit of a white head that almost immediately descends to nothing .  ) and is a deep rich molasses s : once again , may have been too cold for phenols to waft up t : slightly sweet really tasty m : nice and cold d : pour me another

s - nice hop aroma with a few floral notes .  this is a soda with a touch of alcohol . the aroma is a little funky and a lot sweet with just lime and a hint of corn . the appearance yellow with a thin fizzy head .  the mouthfeel is good ; slightly thick and very smooth . however , it is a little bubble and will sting the recesses of your mouth .
smell - the scent of brown sugar and slight spice .  very clear yellow translucent color , no head .  m : smooth and medium bodied .

s- it does have a nice smell of oranges .  poured into a pint glass ok was a little taken by the appearnce , its a chocolate ale and its dark amber with a fizzy head like a soda , about 1 finger high and disapates much like a soda as well smells of wheat and sweet chocolate notes with some semi-sweet malt , almost candy sweetness .  m : a nice , medium body .

smells of apples , seriously . yep , apples . if i was drinking this blindfolded i would n't guess that it 's as dark as it is ... then i would probably accidentaly knock it over , spilling it and making myself smell like apples for the rest of the night , but i suppose that 's not important . overall : apples ; perhaps this keg is infected , or something .  miserably thin trace of head .  it is medium bodied and smooth in the mouth .

this one was aged in jd barrels and there is a definite whiskey note on the nose . quite a bit of oak and vanilla .  appearance - murky witbeer like appearance . not very presentable appearance at all .  served in a pint glass mug a : pours a clear bronze color with about an inch of thick head s : a smell provides a nice rye scent with a very sweet undertone contributed by the honey addition t : very nice smooth tasting beer , has a slight hint of honey and perhaps a slight rye note but other than that there isnt much to comment on , smooth and slightly sweet but thats about it m : very smooth in the mouth with a slight bite on the tongue as it is drank d : high level of drinkability , very subdued taste that is great for a hot summer day but leaves the drinking looking for more otherwise .
s - big caramel malt nose with some fruity hops .  looks like white grape juice . i hate it when no head is erected .  medium mouthfeel .

odd , but oddly good . taste follow suit and starts out good , but a pretty strong metallic aftertaste ruins this beer .  there is absolutely no head or lacing . it looked flat .  mouthfeel is nice , actually - light bodied , spritzy carbonation .

aroma is a nice spicy hops with a good bready , roasted malt to it .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass , beer is a slightly hazy , straw color with a pure white , fizzy head . other than the small bits of sediment actively swimming around throughout the glass , looks like a macro lager .  velvety . good amount of carbonation .
smell-no real smell , which is good to me .  pours pale golden yellow with no head .  good carbonation .
the nose is full of notes of raisiny notes as well as distinct hoppy character .  bottle poured a brownish brew with almost no head .  m- decent carbonation , light and airy .

s - heavy on the grains , both hops and malt , with a note of something floral there , too . d - the appearance and the smell had me really pumped on this beer initially but the taste killed it for me . and afterall , it 's about the taste in the end ... very disappointed in this entry into one of my favorite genres of brewdom .  1/2 inch foamy head which quickly evaporates into nothing . absolutely no lacing at all . not a very quality appearance .  could be a bit less carbonated .

aroma- very hoppy and hints of sweet fruit taste a light citrus hop flavor , a little bitter as well , but in a refreshing way mouthfeel good carbonation , in fact maybe a bit too much .  appearance : boring , crystal clear yellow-orange . white , fleeting head .  m : felt good going down had a nice thick feel to it .

the nose delivers good fruity smells . banana and cloves are evident , but subdued .  for export only fill 12 12 02 the appearance when poured into the glass was of a plain yellow color , nothing fancy , and it boosted some carbonation .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

this beer looks good , and it smells good too , but in the end beer is not drunk for the way it looks or smells .  the beer pours a pale , almost clear , gold color ; very light .  all right taste , almost neutral , with a bit of skunkiness . goes down very smoothly .

the aroma has sour cherry , spice , and fig notes present . i 'm not sure why they 'd release this beer as their 15th anniversary option .  ) a - very pale straw yellow color .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel was pretty good overall .

has a somewhat pleasant bready , vanilla like smell to it . smells better than it looks to be sure !  a- poured a clear yellow color ... almost fake looking . no lacing on the glass .  i 'm not sure what a `` baltic '' porter is supposed to taste like ; but this one is quite different from most porters i 've had . sweet molasses aroma that is greater than any chocolate or mocha that might be found . a strong level of metal present also . sweet , almost like brandy . reminds me far more of a double bock than a porter . i can not detect any hops at all . too sweet for me , making it more one-dimensional without any complexity .

really big malty aroma . in the back some faint fruits can be noticed such as grape . this is very malty with a decent amount of metalic bitterness at the end .  this brew poured up a straight yellow color ... the aroma was sour !  decent carbonation , neither too intrusive nor too laid back .

dusky crimson-glinting brown adorned with a fat gob of buttercreme suds . rum-steeped fruit nose , a la fruit punch with cherries , pineapples , and apples , then backed with a stanch vanillin oak character . begins with a tepid fruitiness . again with the cherries , pineapple , and apples . yeast come in and sprinkles slate and sandalwood earthiness . it leaves a semi-acrid and astringent burnt coconut essense mixed with a tannic and lingering sense of black cherry skins as it rides out forcefully vinous . light bodied , but it feels fatter with some element of clinginess . the barrel-aging really just ruins this .  appearance would be enhanced with labels staying on bottle , but pale clear color ok.. still high on carbonation .  m- medium bodied with a decent carbonation level .

sour fruit to the nose .  `` the circus is the place for me with bears and clowns and noise . '' - phish despite a hearty rousing circus boy pours a mostly clear gold . 1 finger white head that does n't do too much . poor showing for a wheat . light grain , grass and lots of butter .  m/d : a medium body with good carbonation .

aroma : a great mix of sour and vinegary notes over a sweet malt body . mouthwatering . unfortunately , this is nowhere near as intense as the nose and ends up way too subdued for my tastes .  pours into a pint glass a very , very pale yellow with just a little bit of foam .  the mouthfeel is slightly creamy and very enjoyable . this drinks nicely . there is a lot going for this though , the mouthfeel in particular .
there is a nice aroma of oats .  appearance : the beer is a super hazy copper color with a head that dissipated insanely fast .  it had a medium bodied with good carbonation .

smell was sweet cherries , dark . toffee .  appearance : not the best looking beer out there , 1 finger of head that dissapates rather quickly , yellowish color almost reminds me of a miller lite .  feels right in body , but the taste is just off .

the aroma is very belgian with lots of sour fruit lacto , weaker raspberries and cherries , dusty basement .  this beer was watery and did not have much taste to it in my opinion . the hue of this beer was yellow .  m : pretty creamy and lightly carbonated . easy to swallow a mouthful .
smells of very sweet caramel malts , black licorice , taffy and pine .  yellow-brown beer with a fizzy head that dissolves right away .  m : good mouthfeel .

who woulda thunk it : ginger leads the way in the nose ... notes of caramel malts and a bit of spice , yeast round out the aroma . an intruiging ( in a good way ) smelling brew . taste takes a step back .  pale golden lager with a wispy head and plenty of carbonation .  being of fan of bocks , i was fully prepared to love this ubiquitous doppelbock . it was kind of sweet and malty , smelled great , felt nice going down -- quite satisfying . there was a slightly funky smell to it , and an even funkier taste . i thought that was more common in highly hopped beers . at $ 10 for the four pack , i hate to try it again for fear of wasting my hard-earned beer money .

very pleasant t - kind of like a apple jolly rancher diluted into water .  typical coors characteristics : dissappearling head , pale color , low bitterness .  this beer has noticeable viscosity and a big thick feel . minimal carbonation .

nice roasty aroma . but it 's downhill from here .  pours a very light , very clear yellow colour , with a minimally weak head of white , which dissipates almost immediately to a loose collar around the edges of the glass , despite a pretty vigorous pour . minimal lacing . looks very insipid .  t : slight sweet taste , but does not taste much like anything actually , fairly bland m : smooth , light on carbonation . d : mouthfeel was nice , went down easily enough just did n't care for the smell or taste of the beer .

s : smelled like caramel malts , which i appreciated and let me hopefully anticipate the beer .  appearance : light amber ... similar to an american lager but with more carbonation smell : like a cross between a budweiser and heineken .  recommended by bert from bert 's better beers . smells like dark chocolate , burn caramel , and vanilla -- sort of like an chocolate chip oatmeal cookie . smooth roast malt , dare i say a tad burnt . there 's a mild pharmaceutical character in back that i 'm not a fan of . i drank half this bottle one night and the second half the following afternoon .

s - nice aroma of cider ... that seems to be a recurring theme for me with this beer .  a - pours a clear orange color with decent carbonation . the head fizzled out before i could even look at it long enough to see what color it was . obviously no lacing here .  m - lighter side of heavy , pretty smooth .

nose is molasses and licorice with some hints of smoke ; sweet dried plums and cherries in the background . it looks like a stout . the low taste rating is simply because i did n't enjoy this beer , and i 'm very jealous of the reviewer who managed to taste this on draft because i 'm stuck with five bottles i do n't want : - )  a : darker in appearance than a bud light , slightly brighter than a bud heavy . easy drinker and goes well with a margarita mixture floating on the top of it aka : iceberg i would have to say on tap it tasted very similar only there was more head .  medium mouthfeel .

nose is pleasant , full of citrus and wheat , and an undefined spiciness .  a- no head , little lacing , the beer has a cloudy haze yellow body with a couple carbonation bubbles .  m - full bodied and chewy with a moderately dry finish with some alcohol noticeable .

an aroma of banana , cloves , spices and hops .  for a lighter beer this is good . much better than the big macros with contrillion dollar ad budgets ... sheesh how cheap could their beer be without that overhead ... but i digress good tasty beer .  pleasantly carbonated on the palate , with a dry finish .

it was very hoppy but it lacked a lot of body , deep malt and maturation . drinkability is good but i rated it low as a barleywine because this is not a barleywine in my book , sorry guys . it did smell good..like imeprial ipa though..just because you hopped it to hell and it is a 100ibu does not make it a barleywine .  i despise this brew for brainwashing my fellow americans into thinking that this sort of thing is beer . i can only thank this beer for making me truly appreciate brews of substance and character .  the flavor is a bit better as the taste of both a good belgian tripple and a solid ipa can both be percieved ; however , the flavors compete for dominance instead of blending harmoniously . i think the problem here is that tripple is a big , expressinve beer . with exit 4 the subtle flavors are masked behind a second layer of bold expressiveness . i love the brewery for pushing the envelope and i look forward to buying the next release in the series . with innovation like this , flying fish is sure to hit a huge winner sooner than later .

s- the primarly aromas here are of sweet corn and malt . i do n't really detect any hop bitterness , but rather some skunked aromas . it is quite sweet , primarily of corn and some clean , bland white rice . the corn sweetness hides the alcohol well and there 's no real bitterness to detract any novice beer drinkers .  pours a clear gold color with a thin white head . no real lacing to speak of and the head was short-lived .  m=fairly thin , a little medium . watery .

aroma is fairly sweet with a bit of cotton candy and fruity hops . although the hops a bit masked by sweetness and the aroma put off is minimal at best , especially poor for an impy ipa . a beer thats tastes very good , aroma is mia .  a : super white nose and a bland yellow body s : a weak rice or corn aroma .  body is extremely light and spritzy ; refreshing and very inoffensive in character .

s : almost no odor to speak of ( had warm bottle , too ) . t : great flavor , much better than the aroma .  a - poured out a very fizzy , straw yellow color with a fizzy , short-lived , white head .  the mouthfeel is medium-light bodied with a watery texture , and a little too much carbonation .

the smell is mild , clean and neutral . or , to be frank , very boring .  corona is probably very overpriced and over-rated . as mentioned it makes an excellent summer time beer as it managed to quench thirst . it has weak color , weak strange smell that when not skunky is mildly fruity and has nice mouthfeel for what i expected ... not great , just decent for its purpose .  a bit bland for the style . body is a bit like soda water , and fades really fast .

the smell and taste are enhanced with grain . the hops help somewhat with the taste so that it is not bread water .  appearance is a light yellow with nill head and lace .  lack of carbonation , and this beer 's thin , watery mouthfeel combine to make a less-than-awesome drinking experience .

the head was huge and creamy which gave off some strange aromas . something like peanuts and sour yeast .  can , this is pretty straightforward mexican beer , but thanks to the can , no skunky funk going on . a touch of sweetness from what i taste as adjuncts , though the packaging claims saaz hops-i do n't know about that one . i could definitely drink these while floating down the river ( face up of course ) , but we think it 's peculiar that they have white writing on a silver can , so definitely try to read about it before the third one or later .  the carbonation sort of ruins the mouthfeel from the can and hides the taste .

almost no aroma when poured . easy to quaff but not much reward for doing so . if you really like this , just buy a bud and save yourself a few bucks .  i knocked back a few of these at a restaurant the other night because all they had on tap was miller and bud products . appearance : poured slightly darker than a budweiser , but i could only tell when i held it right next to a bud . had no head but that 's no doubt the bartender 's fault .  m : thin and watery , very little carbonation , too thin to be cloying , but i 'd rather this beer be full bodied .

smell : slightly aromatic . okay .  kuhnhenn 's winter wonder lager ( 2008 ) pours up like a flat soda pop w/o much luster , but it manages to release enough carbonation to create a wisper thin beigeish-white head that barely manages to ring the glass above a rather dull , murky brown-burnt umber body . it 's rather an ugly mess to be brutally honest !  was excited to see this one.. but again newcastle has let me down again ... on the bottle it says `` blood red ale '' .. it pours a reddish-brown color.. smells a little funky ... way too carbonated for my liking .
barnyard smells of raw hay and excrement ... unappealing .  a : very pale yellow with literally no head or lacing at all .  carbonation a bit high . fails on this point . d- easy going macro lager .

slight herbal/maple scent , nothing memorable . m- same as the smell , nothing memorable , typical ale .  not at all terrible , not great , typical mexican macro that actually tasted a bit like fosters if fosters made a lighter version . nice classic beer taste upfront , thins out and fades away with a decent lingering corn and hops aftertaste . the can has a classic look that adds to the appeal .  the most negative parts of this beer include the smell and mouthfeel . the smell is pretty bland , not giving any info on the beer itself and the mouthfeel seems watered down after witnessing the color of the beer .

the sulfurous aroma however was absolutely what i would consider the worst aspect of this beer . there was a lot of bread yeast aroma behind the sulfur as well .  the pour looks very viscous . it has globs of shit floating around in suspension .  3.0 m thin .

i could n't smell much of anything other than some light hops on the nose . remarkably ordinary lager that impersonates a pilsner on occasion .  a : kinda weak head .  the flavor was both too light and 'way too bitter for a pils . it was watery and lacking in aroma . not much foam - what there was disappeared quickly . the word i 'd use to describe this beer is `` insubstantial . ''

smell -- has a sturdy vinegar character , perhaps the red wine variety . i 've smelled worse vinegarized flanders beers , but i 'm not loving this aroma .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  m : thin , watery , light-bodied , not something you 'd expect with the smell .
smell : umm , what i used to think all beer smelled like , pungent , not entirely welcoming .  it looks like flat coke .  m : water thin , light side of champagne-like carbonation .

smell : oddly this beer has no aroma , nothing . it 's rather scary , but i had my nose way down into this beer and i could n't smell anything .  a- pale straw yellow with thin white head , lots of carbonation bubbles , watery , no lace .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a fizzy carbonation .

poured from a real 16 ounce bottle , perfect pint ! aroma is pretty lacking as for the hops , i pick up faint pine , but its a dissapointment for aroma off a double ipa .  it 's appearance is a fizzy , yellow colored average looking beer . thats this beer 's only huge upside .  caramel , coffee and cocoa are there , but overall balance is towards the dry and bitter mouthfeel - 2.0 lightly carbonated , bordering on flat and a little watery .

definitely pale . the nose on this beer is not very entertaining . it 's lightly fruity , but weak in the malt department . not its finest quality , the aroma . the taste is rather pungent , but otherwise underwhelming .  on tap , looks unimpressive , same with smell .  m - light bodied , very thin feeling , and very little carbonation o - not too impressed with this beer .

s : grainy malt , not too exciting . t : creamy smooth malt with bitter hops . o : well , you 'll get what you pay for , and this one came cheap .  appearance - 2.0 poured a small white head that quickly disappeared leaving no head at all . colour is pale straw , large bubbles rising .  mouthfeel on both is not much , just clear water with a bit of beer bubbles .

smell : sweet and grains and that lingering trademark skunk !  had on tap at the wenlock arms in london a : transparent dull gold , zero carbonation and just a little fuzz for a head .  mouthfeel is similar to that of water , not much to it .

smelled malty and grainy , no real hint of nut in this bottle so far .  2.0 a : pale greenish yellow color . head is not dense at all , fizzy , and has horrible retention .  mouthfeel : thin and watery ( or slim-bodied , which sounds more positive ) , medium-low carbonation ( too low for the style ) .

smells like sour soy sauce -- like a really strong , old port . this is n't a horrible smell , mind you , just not what i was expecting . not very nice . tastes much better than it smells .  very very pale yellow color with little head or lace .  the body was light and very watery .

no real aroma to speak of with some very slight sweet grains detectable .  had bottle of this which revealed a light gold-yellow color . disappointing overall for a brewery with so much god damned hype around it . a very forgettable beer unfortunately .  perhaps age will remedy.. m : explosive mouthfeel upon drinking , but the body is very light , with the alcohol evident .

( s ) not very aromatic . faint pilsner-like scent with a slight fruit essence .  pours a clear darkish iced tea color with a fizzy 1 inch beige head that fades to nothing . no lacing whatsoever either . i was expecting something disgustingly gross but i actually really enjoy drinking this one .  m : this was the most dissapointing . aside from the lingering dry finish this was a very thin porter .

the smell is almost that of a macro lager but slightly less offensive .  a : pours a copper body with a very small off-white head with extremely poor retention and no lacing .  mouthfeel : pretty thin , with sharp carbonation and a watery finish .

smell is pretty boring , a little old bananas and corn - eh , whatever taste is quite clean , warm , cereal grain flavour lingering on the off sweet side , but then finishing with a bit of artificial cherry on the end .  this is yellow , rather bubbly with a medium , bubbly white head that steadily vanishes . the aroma is sweet perfume , grain , corn , a hint pf pine and a little alcohol evident - like a stronger , sweeter , more perfumy us macro lager . the taste is quite sweet with a strong corn tortilla taste , a definite but not unpleasant alcoholic quality , and a warm , alcoholic , corn finish that has a light bite .  m- thin highly carbonated .

smell : there just is n't a lot this beer as i 'm only catching the barest notes of grapes and wet hay . however , this seems to be another case of a generic macro beer import .  very little head , but highly carbonated and almost appears to be a pepsi , only a bit darker . it 's okay only if you really do n't like darker beers but want to look `` trendy '' and drink a dark beer with sweet flavor and little else to offend , this may be worth a try .  couple hints of charcoal & burnt toast - but just hints the whole bottle was thin and watery , and the harshness lasted throughout .

i't smells like a funky straw bale , some wet grassy notes as well .  mother lager- magic hat `` you 're never alone with a bone '' mother lager poured a light yellow with no head .  the mouthfeel is syrupy and shows none of the carbonation that the pour hinted at .

s - this is an incredibly weak aroma for the style . they 're there but they 're almost undetectable .  pours light golden , but the head is extremely bad , disappears within one minute and there almost is no lacing as well .  the mouth is super thin . the thinnest mouth i 've ever had on an ipa . d= the thin mouth makes me go for sips more often and the flavor does n't linger long ... great flavor on this one no doubt .

i am struggling to find an aroma , just some faint spicy hops .  a : the beer is a light gold color with a short white head that fades very quickly and leaves very little lace on the glass .  3.0 m too thin for my taste and my experience with better scottish ales ( like oskar blues ) .
nose was somewhat skunky - that 's it .  a= golden yellow little head and that 's about it .  really thin for an imperial stout .

s -pretty skunky eurolageryness . besides the skunk it 's not too bad .  i 'm of the age where it 's a rather popular drink , it seems to be the philly hipster beer of choice , in my short life on living in the city i 've watched in double in price and have remained baffled . pbr does n't taste awful , atleast as long as i 'm not paying 6 dollars for 22oz of it at a bar . the main flavour i 've noticed in pbr is water , thats always the first thing that hits my pallet , water , then some slight grain flavor that mixes with the alchohal . the appeal to pbr is that it is n't the university beer bong beer , so cheers to you pbr for being the beer of an overpaying counter culture .  m - thin , watery , overly carbonated .

wheat smell , with a sickly sweet remainder , not exactly pleasant .  the beer was so black my laser pointer would not shine through it ! the beer poured a poor head that was gone soon as i finished pouring .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : the carbonation isnt stinging and seems appropriate . the body of the beer seems far too thin .

animal urine and feces . very sweet with pine overtones .  pours a light yellow with minimal head and lacing .  feels very watery , not overly carbonated , but bubbles hard in your stomach , not letting you drink too many of these .

s-hint of skunky beer with weak caramel malt aroma . i hate green bottles-all brewers should stop using them . o-not my favorite marzen but respectable-would love to get some before the skunk sneaks in the bottle .  still feel this is easily the best us macro-brewed light beer . this is my go to beer if i 'm out tailgating or watching sports and need something cold , refreshing and in a quantity that wo n't have me draining the wallet . i will take this over bud or coors , everytime .  no attempt whatsoever to hide the alcohol and the addition of the heavy acidic espresso taste and a watery mouthfeel make this hard to down .

there was almost no smell initially after some warming i started to notice some malty essences , some molasses . pretty light taste wise .  pours a slightly hazed pale straw with a fizzy one-finger head . poor retention and minimal lacing .  a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher

not much in the nose , really . some faint pale malts and not much else .  pours an unexciting see-through straw colour with minimal fizzy head despite my vigorous pouring efforts .  m - light and fizzy , thin bodied .

the nose was the lightest grain and hop presence , and from there it blew my mind . the mouth feel was that of a proper cask bitter , but other than that and the faint aroma ... nothing ! ! !  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  ( btw the mouthfeel matches ) .

the smell is odd . i could have been picking up any of these , the smell was just odd .  if you cant drink beer out of a mug its not a beer ! appearance- pale clear yellow smell - not much more than a hint of beer odor taste- clean . very light and clean . drinkability- easy to drink .  mouthfeel feels thin and weak ; this is my only real complaint with this beer .

smell is faint with light adjunct , malt and hop . fairly light for the style acting and tasting more like a lager , the bottle does say ale , but ba style says dark lager which i would agree more with .  poured into a pint glass it looks about the same as coors light , except slightly cloudy ( and i mean ever so slightly ) . the head is almost non-existant and fades leaving zero lacing in my glass .  flavor is of arange , and body is highly carbonated . prickly mouthfeel , and a bit boring overall

the nose is a bit unpleasant .  pours a clear straw color with a small diappointing head , also there are some unidentifiable objects floating around .  mouthfeel : medium to light treading dangerously close to watery .

citrus/orange aroma ; really need to get the nose in there to detect much of the hops .  thos brew pours out as a clear yellow color with a fizzy whit sheaf that last only a few seconds .  m- spritzy , carbonation fills your mouth swelling your cheeks slightly . rough , bubbly and thin .

clear straw color with a full white head , active carbonation and slow bubbles with a nice constant carbonation throughout . serious adjunct aromas and flavors with a strong biting corn taste . per label : stroh brewery co. - milwaukee , wi ** which got bought by pabst brewing co. ** per pabst website : silver - 2004 gabf - american style specialty lager gold - 2002 gabf - american style specialty lager ( $ 1.69 / 40 oz .  pours a noisy amber with a finger of cream colored head . no head retention or lacing s : rich pumpkin & spice aroma t : follows the nose , more pice forward than pumpkin up front .  i picked up a carton of this pretty cheap the only downfall its in cans anyways it pours a golden amber see thru colour with nice carbonation that leaves a bubbly two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is pretty macro with grains and a feint bubblegum aroma , it has a thin mouthfeel with a rather grainy taste and isnt nothing to write home about , its definately better than the macroswill that sells for much more and easier to down but its not a beer that i would drink if i wanted a nice beer with character .

it produced a two-finger white head that lasted a few minutes and left some decent lacing on the glass . there is no smell to this beer - neither good nor bad . very mild flavors here - a faint amount of malt to balance out a faint amount of hop bitterness .  appearance : brown and translucent . the fizzy head dissipates almost immediately leaving no noticeable lacing .  i will admit that i did not like the mouthfeel very much . too bubbly .

carbonation is hard to gague , and the nose is just a bit of light barley malt . the flavor is better than the nose lets on- a bit of sweetish molasses up front with a ghost of hop in the finish .  this looks very strange when poured : it looks like small ice crystals in the liquid floating around for a short while ( the beer is chilled to round 6 c/42 f ) .  the body was very thin and the beer lacked substance .

certainly does n't smell bright and fresh .  to be honest , i only got this beer to try a beer made from denmark . really , really boring beer .  thin , harsh , and astringent- the mouthfeel is where the beer suffers the most .

it had a bitter smell like that of fermented raisins .  chang pours an light gold .  a : it 's still carbonated , that 's something at least . too fizzy .

not too impressed , as others in 6-pack had poor smells but also tasted fine . t : sweet , malty , biscuity m : carbonation , good lingering mouthfeel for golden o : a decent , very drinkable golden .  the classic , quintessential american adjunct lager pours an unimpressive , pale golden , with a sweet and malty grain ( corn ) scent . pbr scores points for remaining independent ( of the big beer monopolies ) and fully american-owned . when i 'm on a tight budget , and a good craft brew is n't in the cards , this is my go-to cheap beer .  it actually smells more like a belgian dubbel . it does n't have much complexity and it drinks very watery . this is by far the thinnest quad i 've ever come across .
