behind that , you get a decent blend of malt sweetness , graininess and saaz hops . to bad the fools had to out this in a green bottle .  poured chilled in ale glass a : no head ; cloudy pale yellow ; ok carb action s : very strong sweet aroma , reminiscent of pears ; suggests a belgian-style beer is ahead t : starts off as a sweet , belgian-inspired farmhouse ale , and segues after a few seconds into a diet-sprite-like wheat ale .  the body is thin and watery ; one hardly notices the beer until it is gone .

probably more of the latter , but still ... this is my go-to beer when i 'm reaching for an ice-cold 40 ... they 're cheap at the local bodega ( about $ 2.50 for a 40 or a dollar or two for the smaller cans ) and pleasantly skunky enough to please your average `` ale '' lover 's palate , especially if you 're just looking for something tasty , cold , cheap and readily available on a hot summer day .  pours golden yellow with one finger white head when poured aggressively that subsides to none almost instantly .  mouthfeel is thin for the style .

i smell a light clove-ish scent and bready yeast . smells almost like a dubbel that sat too long . not awful , but really odd per style .  the color is plae yellow and not overly exciting .  mouthfeel is almost cloying from the sweetness and really is the only category this beer suffers .

unfortunately , the aroma was a mixture of stale hoppiness and mildewed dishrag .  this beer has the typical huber metallic , sulfury , antiseptic taste . a high amount of carbonation that quickly fades and no head develops when poured .  m- not a lot of carbonation , kind of syrupy actually . i feel if it would have been carbonated more it would have helped a lot .

smell was very mild and nothing i noticed about it stands out .  pours out of the green bottle an extremely pale straw , lighter than most pale lagers .  m : flat . way too sweet for the ( non-existant ) level of carbonation .
very light smell of rice and malt .  bottle , a : pale yellow , with little head after the first five minutes .  carbonation is way too high .

i am not impressed with the smell , as it reminds me of a wet morning in a cornfield .  a na beer with almost ... almost an actual beer taste . hell , it 's got more taste than many to most true light beers .  mouthfeel : a bit on the fizzy side - really scrubs the tongue .

this is i would say an good hot day beer . a wheat beer would be more preferable but i havent one . either way it has no hop characteristics at all . deffinately sessionable  comes out of the tap a clear pale yellow with a typical white head - not inspiring .  skimpy in body , vapidly dextrinous and approaching watery in mouthfeel .

the smell is nothing special . had this one after the jupiler , and this beer is so much better for the style .  pours a clear , and very light golden color with barely any head .  it does n't taste bad or good , kind of like water . it tastes like bubble water with a hint of sweetness . it 's for getting your swill on , and nothing else . too bad this is what most americans think of , when they think of australian beer .

s- very disappointing . no hops , almost feels like i 'm smelling the glass .  2002 this is one ugly beer . its a decent color , dark red brownish hue , but so freakin ' murky and flat . it looks like it could be the dregs from my garbage disposal .  starts with fruit taste , looses interest with a thin mouthfeel and water middle although helped by a supporting co2 texture and some tartness ( carbondated water ) ending with lactic acid and dry pucker on the back of the tongue and esophagus .

pours clear yellow with a 2 inch cloudy white head ; smells of malt and yeast , with the malt odor dominating , but still very faint overall .  well , it gets really hot down here , so i figured a caribbean beer would be good yard beer for the summer . anyway , this was a decent one , definitely a good one for the heat , maybe one to take fishing with me . maybe it 'll show up here this summer .  m : dammit , i hate porters like this . light , watery body , slightly oily , and slick on the palate . this would have been so much better with more body to it .

o : well , this one was all over the place ; the smell reminded of euro pale lager , the taste was more like german pilsener but way to mild .  decent for a macro . kinda dark for a fizzy yellow american lager . taste is clean with noticable corn adjunct .  2.5 m very light , i am not impressed . it is very close to water in feel .
the smell lacks any character . it 's hard to distinguish anything from the nose .  a : pours brown , with no head and no lacing . looks like it might be flat .  too thin .

the smell does n't have a lot of character , mostly roasted malts and wheat ... pretty faint all around .  drank this one straight out of the can so the appearance score does n't hold much weight .  thin mouthfeel .

the nose is grainy and grassy . it tastes sweet and grainy with hints of apples and euro pale lager-esque yeastiness . there is very little of interest here . it 's weak , subdued , but in the end very drinkable .  a : opaque faded-straw colored body with a thin white head with little lacing .  very pale straw yellow color , hazy but filtered look no aroma noted water like very light bodied taste and looks like water ... . however better than most would give credit to seeing how its bud .

smell - like cherry cough syrup ( i 'm scared ) taste - actually surprisingly ok for a style beer i usually do n't like much .  no head with no retention and no lace . pretty bland looking .  mouthfeel was pretty watery and went down quickly .

stoudt 's fat dog passes muster as a rock solid oatmeal stout on 4 of the 5 senses : looks good , tastes good , feels good , suppose i give it the benefit of that it sounds good . fat dog had a hard to place , rotting cheese aroma that accompanied the brew . quite off putting , even interfered with the taste ( with clothespin applied to nose i 'm confident the taste score could be a full point higher .  a - straw yellow , clear with no head .  above average taste for an adunct lager , but not great by any measure . this is definately better than budweiser , coors or miller , but not exactly to die for . foster 's price point is right about miller/bud level , but always slightly higher . it 's worth the extra coins if you 're on a budget . much more enjoyable than the run-of-the-mill macros .

the nose was a little musty and , frankly , off putting .  served in a nonic pint glass , the beer pours a hazy gold color with about a 1/4 inch white head that went away pretty quickly . no lacing whatsoever .  mouthfeel is overly carbonated .

smells very weakly of yeast and not much else .  i good beer for a good price , and with the exception of a few flaws , a fine example of a dopple bock . poured into a pilsner glass the beer produces no head , no carbonation to speak of , and no lacing .  better than expected , but as someone who despises ab products + light beer i was n't expecting much trouble is , within the same can it tasted like lemonade in some sips , water in others . giving it a 4 on drinkability because it 's light , so one could drink a lot of these if they chose to .

light straw golden color with an airy white head . light and sweet nose , with a bit of corn/cereal grains .  small head that is very short lived . light yellow gold in color .  mouthfeel - one of the most water beers i 've had .

aroma is weak for an imperial ipa , with a tangy , earthy aroma ( not in a good way ) that is not usually found in this style . that earthy aroma was apparent in the flavor , for lack of a better term , this aroma/flavor is manure .  it pours a milky white , slightly straw colored liquid . not much of a head . this is a boat drink , not a beer .  mouthfeel is thin and weak .

it 's not that good of a pale ale -- in fact , i think it 's barely an ale at all -- with just a slight hint of ale-like fruitiness and diacetyl . the aroma is certainly nothing to write home about with a little whiff of canned corn and just a hint of hop spice .  bud light is my favorite beer to start when starting a session . the color is light and relatively generic .  mouthfeel is very thin and overly carbonated .

by the way , is a beer to drunk fast because the taste when it 's in a high temperature is very bad . the merchandise is greater than the taste but is better than other brazilian pilsen style beers .  almost looks green in its pint glass on my computer desk . fairly aggressive pour that would have 99 % of all other hefes spilling over the sides of the glass , leaves me with only a mediocre head . body is lemon yellow when held to a lamp , and in lieu of the usual cloudiness , this is clear with 1000 's of individually recognisable particulates floating around .  fizzy ... gross . m- watery , thin , minimal carbonation , and nothing lingering .

the nose , however , brings in a harsh metallic scent which is rather unpleasent , though it 's the sort of thing that 's possibly more indicative of a bad batch . luckily , the metallic scent does n't carry over too much into the flavor , which is actually quite enjoyable . the brew 's a bit more weighty than the light red hue might have you think , and malty to the core .  pours an amber color with reddish hues , looks more like a red ale than anything else , not much of a head and what there is fades fast , no lacing on the glass .  very light in body with a slick mouthfeel at first that becomes almost slimy .

smell is mainly light corn .  soft white to off white head begins at two and three quarters inches falling to one quarter of an inch within five minutes leaving no lace on the glass . hazy dirty gold in color . large quantity of sediment entered glass despite careful pouring efforts .  the mouthfeel leans toward the thin and watery side .
virtually no nose .  clear gold and looks a bit like a bog standard pale larger .  my big complaint is the mouthfeel . this stuff had some serious astringency to it leaving my mouth prickly and dry .

smell & gt ; alcohol , metal . just average drinkability & gt ; the smell was a bit off-putting for me , but my parents , who were with me , have found a new favorite beer , so i 'm going with `` just above average ''  poured crystal clear and light yellow . had a snow white head that didnt last long . not a lot of lacing but a little .  body is very thin , drinkability is ok , but there 's not very much to this beer .

s : not much here . some light chocolate maybe . t : sweet malt and fruits .  a : pours a half finger head of okay thickness , no cream , and poor retention .  mouthfeel is very thin with low carbonation , almost watery , drinkability is poor , huge bitterness and watery mouthfeel is a disappointment .

very clear brassy color s - smells like two skunks fighting in an old oil drum .  live review a- clear straw yellow . very cabonated , foams up big but dissaptes fast to have no head whatsoever s- strong scent , sweet , malty t- clean taste , sweet malts , grassy , surpisingly a yeasty afternote m- watery and very light d- not the tastest of beers , but one that can lead to very adventrous nights  flavor : then , i drank some & everything went downhill . it was watery & disappointing .

no apparent lacing s - nothing much , a little sweetness , no hop aroma detected t - very sweet . it tastes kind of like malt extract used in homebrewing .  pours a cloudy , maize color . poor retention and poor lacing .  m = thin . thats it .

i was surprised by this beer . it is likely the best chinese beer i have had . it does not have a lot of flavor , but what there is is not offensive.the flavour is very mild , a bit of hops and perhaps grain . i wish water tasted this good , as what this beer reminds me most of is a good mineral water .  pours a dark brown with almost no head .  m : thin body with not much carbonation .

pours a hazy yellow smelled too much of wheat , even for a hefeweizen , with not enough citrus or lemony notes . recommend skipping this hefe and going to harpoon 's own raspberry hefeweizen that improves on the blandness of the regular .  very small head , particularly for a wheat . it dies to literally no bubbles and therefore no lace . the finish is milky and short lived .  the body is a bit thin and feels too bubbly .
smell was intense and unpleasant .  semi-cloudy caramel , forming a small white head with no retention or lacing .  mouthfeel - very light and dry .

yeasty aroma with the funk of rotten fruit and full kitchen garbage can.. nasal accents of strong commonly-belgian hops work their way in as well .  weal yellowy macro-ish pour with white fluff head that disappears in a blink leaving little to no lace . this would be fine at a show with cheap taps or as a cheap can of hipster irony .  tragically the mouthfeel is watery and the carbonation ( which others had noted ) , distracts from the overall experience .

smell isvery light hops , light malt and bugger-all else , zip , nada , zilch .  a - a dark brown color , it looks like a flat coke . pours with a little tan head , absolutely no lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and very watery .

cans . ugh , off-putting smell . extra high abv high gravities , like 9.0 % and above , have the grape tinge to them . this smells like it is going to have the grapey alcohol overpowering taste thing going on . ides . ) barely any sweetness at all .  a : the beer is clear pale yellow in color and has no visible signs of carbonation .  very thin , and watery . lower carbonation .

s : clover , grassy . cooked rice .  a little out of season to have this one now , but better now than before it goes bad . basically no head , only a ring of white . this is a wheat beer , it should have some head to it ... blah ... wheat and yeast aromas .  has a bit of a sweet maltiness and maple flavor does come out more as it warms m : very thin feel for a porter and leaves an odd buttery coating d : nothing really appauling , and nothing overpowering so it is drinkable , but i probably wo n't get another

s- smells grainy , little bit of corn , little metallic , almost white wine smelling .  a cloudy light amber with enough suspended particles in it to make it look like there is sand floating in my beer when held up to the light .  the body is too full and filling .

a - copper color with thin off white head s - light smell.. sweet malt.. little alcohol.. sort of a slight pukey smell too.. lol t - not very good , not all that bad .  pours to a pale yellow color , with thin white heaed that dissipates quickly , and leaves little lacing .  mouthfeel - pretty astringent . almost watery except for the stickiness of the body .

nose is super bland and tame .  this was always my emergency beer ; the cheapest sixer at the one place that stayed open latest . tastes pretty cheap and watery and best served ice-cold-as-possible .  very thin , and barely any head .

it smells like slightly rotten apples and butter ; if only french hookers smelled like bass !  it 's yellow and fizzy . the only real distinction between this and other malt liquors is that it tastes even more like old boiled corn than most and has a slightly higher alcohol content .  m - watery and sticky . its almost a thin beer .

pours like strong coffee except it has virtually no aroma . as mentioned earlier , there is no nose with this beer .  good thing they told me this was a hefeweizen on the label , because otherwise i would n't have been able to tell . golden yellow color with an awful lot of clarity for a hefe . do n't think i 've ever seen a hefeweizen that 'd been filtered this much .  mouthfeel : not much carbonation and the body is kind of watery .

ok malt scent , not an aromatic beer really . starts out mildly sweet with a decent herbal hop assault .  a- hazey pale orange . if i ignored the small foamy cap i 'd swear it was some sort of orange soda made with juice . i would n't buy a 6-pack , and if i had a choice of this macro and blue moon i 'd choose blue moon .  one thing about this beer is it feels extremely watery .

smell is pretty strange and unpleasant , an odd mix of fruits and spices with what i want to say is tomato coming out strong in front .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  mouthfeel was much too thin to be of any merit .

there lacked a adequate smell here . there was a malty smell , but very slight .  it was watery and thin , but no off flavors - just a little adjunct flavor on top of the water , and lo and behold - i actually percieved a mild gummy hop bitterness and aroma ! i 'm used to seeing empty cans of these piled all over my brother 's sleeping body when i peak in on him most saturday mornings .  i am dissapionted in the carbination as it is nearly flat with a medium/light feel .

had this one on tap at whistle binkies pub in rochester . the aroma did n't have any obvious notes that i could detect . mouthfeel was about what i expect in an ipa .  pours a medium off colored copper , with very thin head and lacing . very low carbonation level .  feels watery with a sweet burn on the way down . soapy .

aromas are weak , with really only grassy hops and corn discernible . not impressive yet .  if what you 're looking for is a cheap beer to keep your fridge full , this is my first suggestion . it 's not much different from others in this category , ie . macro brew adjunct lager , yet the one thing that sets it apart is hops .  it feels more watery than i 'd like my porter , however .

smell : diluted malts , anyone ?  the head is initially one finger before settling down to a thin cap and a fatter collar . no real lace or anything . sort of bland looking .  mouthfeel : seltzer drinkability : would be good but the mouthfeel sucks .

smells very faintly sweet , but not much . tastes pretty good , sweet malt upfront , faint hops but some skunk thrown in for good measure ( damn green bottles ) but the skunk is not as bad as , heinikin for example . overall it is quite drinkable and think it would be a lot better if it was in brown bottles , get rid of the skunk and it may be almost as good as pilsner urquell .  pours a hazy brown/black with a very quickly disappearing head .  mouthfeel is very thin , again very soda like .

the label on the bottle i 'm drinking has a coat of arms , 2 cherries and says the abv is 6.8 % . the smell was the first thing that weirded me out ; maybe i was expecting more of a lambic-ness , but the smell had a funk that i found hard to place . what the hell was that smell ? dirty underwear ? the taste started okay with a tart , bitter cherry flavor but followed by a metallic nastiness that almost pressed down on the back of my tongue .  pours a bright , clear yellow/light gold , with moderate white head about an inch thick . retains for a few minutes , then quickly vanishes , leaving no lacing . typical weak lager appearance .  alcohol is very well masked for a 6.5 % way too much carbonation for my liking .

it was light and added character to the blonde ale , but it 's a little much in here and it make the aroma offensive . the flavor and aroma come off extra bready with a little rubber in the aroma .  review based on notes : pours an effervescent auburn with a pinky of tan head . zero head retention & lacing s : slight toasty malt & nothing else t : slight breadyness , herbal & metallic hops , plus dryness up front .  mouthfeel is very flat .

aroma : coffee and , unfortunately , cigarettes .  bottle , a : pours almost an amber , a shade or 2 darker than an average pils , fizzy head with fair retention , no lacing .  body was light and feel was watery .

smells : slightly sulfurous on opening , but not as bad as my last sample of pbr . maybe the pabst plant has a little sulfur in the water ? i 'd really like to compare this side-by-side with pbr since they 're both pabst beers .  i poured the beer and it gave me about a one inch head . some what less cloudy than what i enjoy in a weiss beir my expectations were low .  overall , feels unbalanced , too much carbonation and a little too dull .

i could n't smell anything . but i could taste a lot .  had a bomber of this with my indian dinner tonight pours golden/straw with 1 '' of white head . zero lacing or head retention s : sweet malt & perfumy hops t : sweet malt & hint of herbal hops up front .  it 's watery on the palate , surprisingly so - i 've had beers of 3 to 4 % alcohol that had more body . the finish is lightly astringent and bitter .

s-the smell was absent i sniffed as hard as i could and nothing . t-the taste was definitely better than the smell and the look but not astonishing .  a - very pale in color . overall , bud light like many similiar mega-produced american beers , lacks any original flavor .  immediately upon entering the mouth it felt very watery and light for an 80/- .

the smell is slightly skunky and also pours an oft-red color .  a : lovely raspberry colour . when held up to light looks a thick cherry colour .  the flavor was spicy and malty and the mouthfeel was tingly along with a burning sensation as it is swallowed .

o : the aroma was just unpleasant . flavor was n't too bad , though .  dark golden look . head was about an inch and a half that left a quarter-inch ( or more ) film . reminded me of that candy that fizzes in your mouth .  really fizzy ( like coca-cola fizzy ) on the tongue , with a metallic finish , not really what i was hoping for , dissapointing .
not much in the way of smell except a little sweetness .  ca n't really knock this beer for it 's appearance , it looks pretty good .  m : watery , very light-bodied , body of a light lager .

i 've somehow not yet tried this pale from victory . the nose comprises dark greens , egg yolk , caramel , flowers , and light leek . not sure where that egg-y smell 's coming from , but it 's not helping things at all .  appearance : black which shows a clear ruby when backlit . had a creamy tan head that left a little bit of lacing .  it tasted mostly like water with a very light toffee/sweet taste in the back of the tongue . that 's it . it was very drinkable in the same way water is drinkable . when a brewer wants you to chill his beer , there must be a issue with the flavor at cellar temps . i ca n't believe some people consider this to be the flagship for the style .
nose : very slight nose .  it looks good in the glass a hazing orange with a nice white head .  the mouthfeel is pretty thin and watery .
smell - what you might expect form a rice lager . smells of grass , hay , and wheat .  a : a nice clear bright yellow .  mouthfeel is thin .

this is a very average , no frills stout . i pick up no smell what-so-ever . acceptable , some chocolate hints in the flavoring but nothing stellar yet nothing really bad either .  pours a dark brown with hints of amber and ruby , a good two fingers builds up on the pour and leaves light lacing down the glass .  2.5 m thin , with only the grain tastes and the slightest stickiness keeping it from being water itself .

not my cup of tea , but for a bud product it is made very well , can it be considered a true belgian wit now that inbev owns ab ? beer was granished with an orange adding to the orange falvor i could smell and taste .  pours pale yellow and settles light amber in the glass . impressive , frothy head .  the mouthfeel is very watered down like an american pale ale but i thought the pumpkin taste was enjoyable .

has that barnyard scent with some citrus fruit as well , but it also has a funky medicinal/green olive scent that is really turning me off . taste- spices galore here .  it 's appearance is fine with a nice amber color and decent head .  i must say this beer is best on tap as everywhere i 've tried it otherwise all of its carbonation seems to be non-existant .

lemon scent with a hint of canned corn smell .  black with brown highlights and an enormous soapy light tan head that leaves scattered patches of lacing .  pretty easy to drink with a light , watery mouthfeel .

smell : very little . nothing really sticking out here .  i really enjoy most st offerings a -- nice amber/copper color s -- very surprising nutty aroma .  mouthfeel is watery . this style needs more body - the maltiness is there , but there is very little roasted character & not enough creaminess .

weak in every sence of the word , the wheat is to light , i can berly taste the blackberrys , i am not enteirly convinced that i am not drinking water , i loved this beer in the past , maby this is a bad batch . i do detect sour at the end , at least their is somthing i can detect . i could down this like water or funnel this beer if i wanted to get trashed in a hury , not a top sheilf beer  it shows a bone-white head with heavy lace , and a sassy , vivid yellow color with low co2 .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's weakest point . also , it feels a bit heavy on the palate and is almost syrupy .
s : not a lot to it . maybe very faint wheat smell .  pours a nice light gold colour with light fluffy head .  the mouthfeel was flat and very dissapointing .

schlafley 's ipa is a case in point . however , this is supposed to be an ipa , but there was no hop aroma to speak of . just a faintly sweet malt and that was it .  dark dark brown in color similar to almost all stouts .  taste is weak , almost watery , has to be drank ice cold or has a taste like vomit . bottom line is compared to other cheap beers pbr excels in taste , quality , and conveniently the price , 7 bucks a 12 pack .

laced well . maybe i have a sinus infection or something ( or had the beer too cold ) but i could hardly smell anything . the faint aromas i got were plesant , but i did n't really smell much . again ... what taste ? choice between this and `` lite '' or bud light , this wins , but i prolly wont buy it again unless i really do have no smell due to sinus .  pours a jet black colour with no difference whatsoever when held to the light .  pretty nice . the body is as thin as water . that leads to a very drinkable beer , actually , since it goes down ... well , like water .

ok , so i bit on the $ 2 can at a local burger bar . i wo n't work through the five-tier rating system here , and will just say , for what you are paying , this is an honest beer . beats the hell out of bud , miller , coors any day .  appearance : this pours a maple brown , nearly mahogany , with an eggshell colored head that retains nicely . strangely light appearance for a double cda , though .  good for a lager , but way too much carbonation really throwing this beer off .

the aroma was nonexistant . i was at a cajun restaurant so the smoke from the bar and the spices from the kitchen may have wiped out what little aroma there was in the beer .  appears a dark amber/red color . with a small white head .  the mouthfeel was watery , the body medium/light and the carbonation average .

not a whole lot of smell , there 's a little malt , and i do n't really smell pumpkin .  a - hazy ( for a pale lager ) yellow with a big frothy head that lingers .  mouthfeel was very watery and not smooth in the slightest .

had this on tap at the aranyhomok in keskemet , hungary a - pours a light golden color that produced a foamy white head that disappears and leaves no lacing around the glass s - no real scents , i guess because i had on tap in europe there was no skunk , but i guess sutle malts was all t - not a complex beer , but then again was n't supposed to be .  pours a deep ruddy brown with a thin layer of head that leaves a massive amount of lacing .  i 'm going to have to go against the gimmick and with the style here , the mouthfeel just is n't there . i 'm not impressed at all , it 's like a half flat beer that you 've left on your desk whilst reviewing a beer and forgotten about it only to come back to it 30 mins later . the shining point of this beer is it 's drinkability .

black pour that left lots of lace as i drank it , but very little aroma . maybe the pub itself was too smoky to smell anything , but i basically caught some malty scents , and that 's it .  served in a stone vertical epic glass that can be described as stemless martini-like . pours a dark golden-copper color with a good white head and some lacing .  the mouthfeel on this one fluctuates but it has one of the worst finishes i can recall in a beer . the thin body and soda-like carbonation ( and some wheaty texture ) save this some , but the finish is just harsh . artificial flavor , sticks to the teeth , chewing on cardboard , something is wrong here finish to the mouthfeel .

unfortunately , the aroma does n't really stand up to the look . there is hardly any malt presence . the taste and texture are ok . it does not hold up to the style well , but if you 're a monty python fan it 's definitely a must .  looks kinda cool .  i 'm gon na have to say the mouthfeel is what keeps this from being very drinkable . it felt almost like flat soda .

smell is extremely poor , not showing any orange .  reviewed 2/7/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a golden yellow colored body , with a huge creamy white head , lasting , with okay lacing .  water with a little spice and alcohol . the smell is the best part with mainly cinnamon . the taste is one dimensional cinnamon with a super light water taste on the back . no malt or pumpkin to be found . not a good beer nor a good pumpkin ale but if someone handed me one i would have no problem finishing it . also you could down 3 or 4 no problem and being $ 6 a 6 pack you ca n't beat that .

doesnt smell the best , but its small size ( 7oz ) makes drinking them easy .  stroh 's in a can , why not let 's do this ... appears a golden clear bubbly quote , unquote beer look to it with large heavily carbonated bright white head floating above body dwindling at a moderate pace leaves some nice patches of sporadic lacing around my duvel chalice ... sorry duvel .  the mouthfeel is way to under carbonated and watery for the style .

weak aroma , not much of anything except for a tiny bit of earth and oxidation . plae malt with no depth at all . floral hop flavor with a hint of bitterness . overall , not enough malt flavor to make this one worth it .  it pours a golden color with a bodacious foamy head . the white foam across the top almost has the consistency of pudding .  thin to medium mouthfeel with zero carbonation -- lifeless .
aroma is a big put off of alcohol and sweat .  looks pretty good in a pint glass .  mouthfeel very thin , almost light-bodied , and lacking in bitterness .

it is an odd aroma , there is n't much there , but it smells a bit sour .  pours out to a slightly hazy light amber with orange accents , forming a large light beige head after a vigorous pour . head is sea-foam in consistency and has ok retention with sparse lacing .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and watery .

scent - almost also non-existent . a faint carmel aroma .  once the cheap gold foil is removed and the cap pried off , it pours a very clear deep purpley ruby with a slightly pink head that laces nicely . looks really neat .  not so much the taste as it had a good belgian style wheatiness to it but the body was extremely thin and almost watery . i was looking for more in the way of the mouthfeel .

the smell is that of boston lager , rather skunky with hints of hops and malts .  the pour into 180 ml chimay chalice delivers a garnet reddish-brown body overlain by light tan head that slowly sets to a bubbly island encircled by an elevated peripheral ring .  the mouthfeel is disappointing with absolutely no carbonation and mild flavors lingering around . overall , i could have possibly gotten a flat beer but this beer had potential ( when carbonated ) but it didnt come through in my bottle .

light hay aroma is typical for the style , but not my thing and it does n't even come off that well in comparison to other macro lagers imho .  looks can be deceiving . this beer looked fine , sporting a rich copper hue .  very watery . the mouthfeel was thin and watery as well .
it smells of corn syrup and stale hops ( or some other foul off smell ) .  black pour with a two tone mocha head that is several fingers thick .  mouthfeel is thin , macro thin .

not much of a scent , a little skunky , some grain .  nice to see this on tap in boston , it is n't available everwhere . nice thick head that lasted throughout the pint , decorated my glass all the way down . medium copper in color , with a clean slightly soapy smell .  m : bitter , almost no carbonation , light to medium body .

smelled on the road to skunking however . yes it had some hints of spice and citrus but to be honest with you it was so mild that this could have passed for any meak american beer if in a blind taste test or straight from a can .  a : this beer pours a nice deep , translucent , bronze color with a khaki colored sudsy head .  this is very much like corona . not as good as miller light .

s - it smells like a sour old beer .  i poured the beer into my favorite laser etched pint . the head is a little more bubbly than the stout , but other than that it looked like a pint of the draught .  mouthfeel is also watery with not much body and no carbonation but essentially pretty drinkable due to the fact that is just resembles colored water .

s : faint smells of oranges and honey and quite a bit of booze . smell reminds me a bit of apple cider vinegar and copper . not a real great combo . t : tastes are of orange peel , honey , and a fair amount of booze .  served in a bruery tulip . pour yields a garnet-colored brew that is almost bordering on purple . good tan head and a bit of lacing as it goes down .  the lack of body really disappointed me . while surprisingly drinkable , this beer needs to be heavier to match the taste , so more body and more alcohol are needed .

s- not very appealing , some weak malts and an odd metallic smell . t- thin sweet caramel malt with a little bit of bready character to it . overall i guess for $ 5.99 i should n't really be complaining that this beer is just mediocre .  it pours a very active pale gold , with a thick , three-finger head that imparts nice lacing - looks kinda like a hefe or wit .  m - weak and thin . lifeless .

it pours a gold colour , very ligth , like anouncing a poor body , as it gets on th mouth , then the hops would be barely noticed ... hey , i could n't smell them ... the flavour last good on the mouth , like 10 seconds , and thats good . i dont think so , as the 1500 cc bottle i bougth for my dad tasted the very same and no skunk at all ... i dunno ... .  bomber , a : pours black with a medium mocha coloured head . good retention , light lace .  a nice chocolatey finish that lingers for a while on the palate is the best part about this beer . m : poor .

slightly murky ( as i would expect of an unfiltered wheat ) s : kind of like bud light . not impressed or excited upon smelling it .  after having and really liking the belgium red i figured that i would find this one out of this world , as i like raspberries far more than cherries . it is thick too . the pour has a pinkish head as well . i guess it just tastes too real -- well with the addition of far too much sugar .  mouthfeel is rather thin for a scotch ale .

it looks great but there is absolutely no smell .  it looks pretty nice .  it was ice cold thanks to the cooler and that made it tasty . watery but that 's alright because your not expecting anything but that from bud ice .

smells metallic , not pleasant .  pours a large white head with fair retention and some lace .  appearance : dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' off white head ... unfortunately this reminded me of a pop on the pour smell : pine , hops , citrus taste : kinda watery , slight citrus ( maybe cascade hops ) mouthfeel : thin drinkability : could do two in a night , but i 'd rather drink something that tastes better

i could hardly get any smell from this beer , so not much to be impressed with . the taste starts out with some corn and sweet malts and later get some hops that nicely balance the malts out . a good beer to drink when low on money and in need of one .  pours a deep black color with a thick brown colored head and a little lacing all around .  for the level of alcohol , there is hardly any hotness at all and a bizarrely watery and light body for a barleywine . could also stand some more hops , as i could hardly detect any at all .
s : nothing . uh oh ! t : pilsner like . m : light and mellow , yet some bitterness .  the beer has an overall nice appearance .  mouthfeel is weak and watery .

the smell is about half and half lager flavor does no tliv eup to the malt smell at all .  a- nice deep-amber body with a good head and great retention .  m : light carbonation with a very light watery body .

smell is barely detectable . some very faint light wheat , a bit of grassy hops , and yeast . but not much there at all , and what is there is n't impressive .  pours from the bottle into an imperial pint with an amber color and a decent head .  aside from that , the taste , like the smell , is unremarkable mouthfeel is borderline watery .

i have not had an american lager in a lonnnggg time so i gave bud a try . the aroma was as i remembered - absent .  pours a brown , yellow , orange color with a good white head .  no finish , the faintest body , texture is nil , nothing to recommend it at all .

the aroma is a let down , though , as there is barely anything perceptible ( although that also means there is nothing unpleasant in the aroma either ) . as a result , this beer is an improvement over many of the other options available at most mexican eateries , but it still did a fine job cutting through the savory spice of the food .  decent retention but great lacey webbing even on a sultry summer evening .  body is way too thick , sweet , and syrupy .
s - little bit of a corn smell in the nose .  the beer came in a handsomely labeled bottle , and poured out dark red , with a decent sized foamy off white head .  watery and flat in my mouth .

s : pale malt and yeast , practically no detectable hop aroma .  a : rbb is mahagony and crystal clear , with a white head that holds up , but is rather thin .  the mouthfeel is poor . it seems to lack enough carbonation .

there seems to be no aromatic hops whatsoever , leaving the smell very dull .  the beige compact , firm foam is two finger thick .  head falls into the liquid way too quickly and seems to look more like bubble bath suds that the typical beautiful belgian head . certainly is the high point of the beer . alcohol comes a little too strong on the palate and seems to take over the other flavors . flat on the tonque . outrageously overpriced and overrated .

i had never had a real irish red ale so when i found out this was contract brewed in holland i was little disappointed . the smell was odd at first , not inviting at all .  a - orange type of color with a nice head .  the mouthfeel is a lowlight , though , with a very thin , watery body being punctuated by small , prickly bubbles .

poured into a shaker glass ... virtually no aroma ( at least to my smeller ) . lemon is very faint .  on-tap at bruery provisions the pour is bright orange in color with a finger of white head .  here we go : a - opaque reddish-brown , small head with minimal lacing s - malts , hint of hops , not much else t - much like the aroma , mildly sweet malts , faint hop bitterness with weak coffee m - thin , a bit too thin for a brown ale d - no problem putting down a few if i chose to , but i do n't think i would unless it was my only alternative to bmc lagers .

i am not a beer connoisseur . this is a cheap beer that is good enough to drink . it is extremely poundable . no need to rinse the glass for refills , the beer does not foam switched to this from miller high life good taste , does n't change when warming up can drink forever or until you fall down if i have money , i like wheat beers  i love all things kirkland and am also a big fan of costco , but this beer was a genuine let-down . it pours an attractive brassy color , with a pretty nice amount of head .  m - the body is vanishingly thin and i feel the carbonation is too high for an english porter .

smells of nothing . very light floral nose as it warms .  a-cloudy gold , nice white head s-fairly gross smelling , like a very tangy orange with wheat t-orange and wheat upfront that quickly fades in to a tanginess . sam adams , thank you for changing the spring seasonal to the noble pils , you still should 've left this out of the winter package and never made this again .  taste is rich and sweet , slightly nutty , but this beer really sufferes from it 's thin and watery mouthfeel .

s : adjuncts t : adjunts . corn sugar , rice etc .  the color was very appealing , but that was all . when i gathered the nerve to take a drink and really sink my teeth into this beer , it felt like i was drinking a beef jerky smoothie .  mouthfeel is disappointing ; thin and watery , with too much carbonation for my taste .

no aroma .  it sits golden in the glass , partially obscured by haze , and stacked high with sticky , lingering white suds .  mouthfeel is where the beer suffers . it just feels wrong . a very tasty and aromatic beer , and if you can get past or prefer the super-low carbonation level .

the smell is epl , it is almost like it is pre-skunked .  alex keeps feeding the beast ... a sexy can served in my darkness glass ... pours a super clear medium gold with about three fingers of head . the head just looks weak , watery and whispy but it actually hangs for a bit and has surprisingly full lacing ... a medium skunk aroma , rice , alcohol .  i feel like i have now experienced the true port/lost abbey experience , this is the first one i 've had that is flat ... a : pours dark brown with caramel highlights , zero head even after stiff pour , some clarity s : nose is predominantly oak and vanilla , some char quality in there , stout base takes a back seat t : vanilla and bourbon again dominate , some ashy character in there along with light notes of leather and tobacco , a bit of of boozieness on the finish mf : low carbonation is an understatement , medium body o : good flavors here , the lack of carbonation takes away from the quality a bit , for the premium price tag , i would expect carbonation .

smells like very like wheat grain . almost nothing there . tastes the same as it smells . very , very light wheat .  appalachian trail blaze brown is a clear red ale with a thin beige head that fades and leaves nice lacing .  getting some sweetness from the milk sugar too , but not a lot m- thin . flat .

for a macro lager made for mass consumption it has more flavor than one should expect . typical appearance for a lager and a distinct pretzel flavor . i 'm not arguing that its a great beer , just good for what it is .  greatful red pours a amber color with strong red and light brown hues . good head and lacing .  over carbonated , watery .

really lacking in the aroma department .  it poured a dark brown-copper color with a nice off-white head and good lacing .  the first thing i notice with this beer is the watery mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is terrible .
no aroma at all from this pint glass .  pours black with a very light tan head . nice retention and dotted lacing covers my glass .  m/d - weak and thin mouthfeel .

anyhow , it 's yet another rare euro pale that is apparently only sold in russia and iowa . smells light and weedy . nothing much going on here , though absolutely nothing is off .  appearance is very good . a nice dark red brown but not black like so many american porters . clean and transparent . dirty socks maybe ? a cheap macro would do this for you .  crisp to the point of being overdone , loads and loads of soda like carbonation . notes : ho hum , average , run of the mill , mediocre ... etc .

skunky and sulphur-like aroma . grainy , with some corn notes as well . not very good in this department .  appearance : this was a very dark , ruby-brown lager with a light tan head . a thin layer of foam was left capping the beer , leaving a decent amount of lace behind .  body is a nip thin . a bit too still , but more carbonation would have blasted through the empty body of the beer , making it even less desirable .

s : was more aromatic once it warmed up to drinking temp .  pours a rather attractive light orange hue .  the beer was thin bodied and very easy to drink . for a faint tasting , macro lager it was n't too bad .

the drink was described as light and long with a sweet taste that stays in your mouth but no `` haze '' more like the reminder of something like perfume sprayed in the air .  the beer poured a clear medium gold color with a four finger fluffy white head that lasted awhile and left lots of lacing .  medium bodied , but watery .

s : shocker ! it 's got that bland , undesirable `` rogue '' nose . you know what i 'm talking about - that grassy , earthiness which might appeal to a hamster . t : barley , bready , with hints of muted chinook hops .  this nearly opaque brown pint arrived with a huge , cloudy head .  mostly smells and tastes like a lager pretending to be an ale . that hint of lager ( as in yuengling lager ) sits there in the background , but then there 's a nice hit of hops in there too . it 's odd , but not necessarily bad ( although certainly not a good american pale in any sense of the word ... it 's a cheap beer masquerading as an american pale ) . not great , but one to try if you 're tired of lager as your cheap beer for the minute .

aroma : sour dough bread with emphasis on sour , as in old stale rags .  the pour was highly carbonated , with thick tan , lingering head .  mouthfeel this one was clumsy and , worst of all , lacked the fluffy character of a good hefe weizen .

a : pale straw , fizzy , some head retention s : stale cereal grains , corn , a hint of sweetness t : starts with a tinge of sweetness , big grainy bread profile , considerable amount of flavor for an adjunct lager , decent balance mf : light body , high carb o : better than most of what bmc offers , but only by a slim margin  not sure of the age of the bottle , freshness dating might be a good idea . looked good .  feel : very thin bodied and a bit too light in body for an ipa or even an apa .

s : the grain and metal come through far too much here . this smell automatically makes me think of watching sec football in a fraternity basement ( and being unable to feel my face ) , and that 's not as fun as it used to be .  got about an inch of head with average retention . somewhat impressed with the lacing on this one .  the body was water and medium light .

smells like a skunky heineken . then corn ?  the santa fe pale ale poured a copper-orange with an thick and creamy off-white head that laced the glass .  mouthfeel : body is thin and water and a little flat ; finsih is wet and is like drinking malt flavored water . the flavors are mild and meek , the body is super watery and does n't offer much , so i do n't feel i will be drinking this again .

smell is quite weak but fruity and clean . slightly boozy and yeasty ; some fermented fruit smells ( apple ? subdued , but inoffensive flavours and aroma , light body , all work together for a decently drinkable beer .  appearance : hazy but clear blond with a big billowing white head . very bubbly stuff .  i was again surprised to find a very thin mouth feel dominated by carbonation which seemed to accent the minimal hops to make them more pronounced .

smell is extremely faint ; all i can detect are pale malts and maybe a bit of citrus .  beer emerged from the bottle a rich golden color and offered a decent white head that then went on to leave some lacing on my glass .  mouthfeel is overly fizzy , making an already light beer even fluffier . overall , this is an interesting beer that could be very refreshing if less carbonated .

nothing spectacular on the nose but for the typical belgian `` funk '' which was fine but i could distinguish nothing else . overall , a keeper , i just expected some more hop character to poke through but , then again , perhaps belgian darks are n't where we go for hop nirvana ?  appearance : it pours a rich brown colour with 1 1/2 finger white foam head .  m - syrupy , mouth coating body with an obnoxious amount of carbonation . carbonation is prickly and really too much as i feel like i ca n't taste everything because of it . it does get better the more you let it warm and let the carbonation die down .

pours a straw yellow with a one finger head . no lacing on the glass aroma is light hops , yeast , sweet taste is good dose of hops , citrusy lemon , the bitterness is sour . pretty bland , not enough hop bitterness for me to really wash down some spicey indian food .  my wife picked this up for me last week in nyc , i assume its fresh . poured from a bomber into an oversized snifter . produceing a 1 '' tan head . the beer is black with no light penetration . scattered thin lace left on the glass .  very light bodied , an ok mouthfeel.. just way too watery and thin , not much for taste , just some lemon zest on the after taste .

the smell is barely perceptible ; i do n't pick up much other than a bit of dry dark malt . i guess it could be worse . add to that a creamy oiliness in the mouthfeel and you 've got a better-than-average mexican beer , but nothing stunning . still , it 's better than corona , better than bud , better than labatt 's blue .  orange color , looks like it might be hoppy , excited .  appearance : golden with extremely high head with low head retention smell : sublte hop aroma , taste : light and refreshing , herbal with some decent hop flavor mouthfeel : light bodied , way too much carbonation , jeez ... drinkability : great flavor belgian pale but its overcarbonated .

smells sort of like wet hay or grassy . body is fairly light with a thicker coating on the mouth feel than i was expecting . otherwise leaves little aftertaste , and not as watery as many similar brews .  appearance : i must say by taking a look at it , its a very pretty orange/ honey color with minimal head ... so far so good .  m - way too much carbonation for my taste .

slightly smokey malt aroma that is quit bland reall with faint hints of oak , toast , bbq , charcoal and bacon .  nice color for the style .  t : cheap carbonated corn . m : if it werent for the bottle this beer would have sunk years ago .

smell is weak , faint caramel malt and slight sugary adjunct aroma .  looks nice . very dark brown with clear , ruby-brown edges and a thin tan cap of fine bubbles . good head retention , a bit of lacing .  mouthfeel is very flat and is not impressing at all .

pale , sweetish lager . very light golden color in the pint glass . essentially flavorless but manages to project a pleasant beeriness . certainly nothing to excite even the lager lover , but in a mexican restaurant faced with the full range of lites , this is not a bad option .  the pour on the beer was very nice , proper stout black with a thick tan head on top .  m - very thin and watery with flat carbonation .

mariestad porter looks like a glass of coke and does n't really smell much except a little roasted malts and fish ( ! ) .  a : wow ... i must say i 'm quite amazed at the formation of the head on this thing . after it settles it leaves a 1/2in white creamy head . looks kind of like ice cream the body of the beer is black with some ruby highlights . the only thing keeping me from giving this a five is the fact that it really dos n't look like beer , more like a milkshake or something .  the body is light and really lacking .

however , i had to work to find much aroma , and what i did get was just a hint of wheat .  drank from a bottle . i first had to rid myself of the expectations of guiness extra stout in a bottle ( what i 'm used to ) . chocolately and coffee-ish , appropriately bitter , no noticeable hops .  mouthfeel : absolutely no carbonation .

after hearing such good reviews about this malt i decided to give it a shot . and after finding a 24-pack of 16 ounce cans for under $ 12 at my favorite local distributor , i couldnt resist . i must say that this is by far the best malt liquor i have ever tried . it is much lighter in the mouth , without the repulsive taste of familiar malts ; it is also smoother in the throat , as well as being lighter in the stomach than any other malt liquor i have tried .  the brown 33cl bottle ( best before 11/2011 ) was poured into a 'paderborner pilsner ' badged stemmed flute . regular lager look , clean , clear , light golden body , crowned with a snowy white head of bubbles , the head left some good lacing on the flute .  mouthfeel is very , very light -- it goes down like nothing at all .

smell of hops and maybe a hint of skunking . if there were such a thing as `` beerness '' i 'd say this sample has a lot of it , because it 's like any of the mainstream bmcs just magnified in the color , taste , and smell . and i understand this was sort of a gateway beer which bridged the old bmc style to the more modern hoppy ipas , so i respect that , but instead of coming across as fresh strong hops it comes off almost more like a skunked bmc .  it looks nice enough , in fact it looks pretty great . it pours very dark with nice ruby highlights on the edges when held up to light .  m - thin , a little harsh and a bit drying .

it smelled of cheap beer , like grain and alcohol , with a bit of sourness .  pours a brassy yellow with a solid foamy head that laces the glass nicely .  the mouthfeel is flat , but predictable as there are virtually no bubbles in the glass after the first minute or so . as far as drinkability goes , i 'd save it for the hot summer days , the ballpark and the cheap 30 pack for the party .

aroma-light grainy malts blend with moderately low notes of hops , but are overtaken by notes of butter ( diacetyl ) and corn ( dms ) . light fruity esters present as well.there are some redeeming notes , but on the whole , the buttered corn aroma really is n't doing it for me . up front the buttery diacetyl rears its ugly head again , but its blunted a bit by a sort of mineral quality and some moderately low hop flavor/bitterness .  tommyknockers imp nut brown a 4-4.5 somewhat aggressive pour yields a one-finger tan head above a cocoa body with orange highlights . the ring holds well and leaves spotty lace .  nose was fruity apples , peaches , apricots , but the mouthfeel was watery and very sour ... not like the lead-in on a flemish sour ... just tartly sour .

s - smells like a bud light . the smell is disappointing . very hard to pick out anything in the smell . t - in spite of the smell , the taste works out to be pretty good .  gee , i hate to write a bumming report on my favorite brewery but ... this beer taste like it got scorched at some point . big scorched coffeee tatse , and hints of molasses . very dark and again the recipe has changed from last year ( last years was very piney ) .  smells and tastes bland and grain like . almost stale . it is a good beer to party with if all your doin is playin beer pong or circle .

the nose is ... strange . i 'm bad with identifying odors , but suffice to say , whatever it is it does n't smell good .  poured a thick foamy head on a solid red body .  m- strange , slick mouthfeel with a semi dry finish .

the smell is raisins , plums , maybe some dark chocolate and caramel , followed by a sweet syrupy alcohol . there is an unpleasant metallic component to the sweetness , and there is not much complexity .  appearance-dark golden color , nice white head that dissapears slowly .  very sweet flavour , largely the same elements as in the aroma , but far too sugary and overwhelmingly sweet for me .

overall its tough to accurately rate this beer as there is no aroma but no aroma is expected given the hops .  the peak one pours a dark black with mahongany highlights . it has a light brown head that quickly dissipated to a thin film and collar that laced the glass a little .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with almost no carbonation .
smell is weak , slight roasted barley and a little dark malt character but not much else .  pours an attractive deep copper with a small head .  the mouhfeel is weak , watery , thin .

when i want a cheap , drinkable single serving can of beer , this is what i drink . in all seriousness this beer is macro style with a bit more flavor than the others . one of the positives of this brew is that it does leave a very nice lacing on my glass ; which , i was surprised at . flavor , well , is sour with a mish mash of corn , grains , hops .  a nice carbonated tangerine orange . a thin soap-like head that laces to the glass nicely . this is a very average amber ale .  m : despite its creamy appearance , the head feels thin on the palate . the brew itself is thin and watery , especially as it warms . the carbonation barely registers .

great head retention & super lacing s : an almost dirt like smell , maybe mushroom ? then vegtal notes , t : nutty malt & dryness up front with a hint of brown sugar . finishes with a hint of choclate , brown sugar & more breadyness mf : chewy for the abv with low carbonation drinks fine if you can past the funky smell , maybe the perfect session when you have a cold or sinus infection ? been a long time since i had abeer that smelled this bad & still tasted good .  poured dark amber , clear , with a good head .  palate scraping astringency . the lack of carbonation particularly makes me wonder if i should have given this more time in the cellar to condition .
i ca n't smell much of anything in this . at least it is n't skunky .  it has good color , but beyond that that this ipa is not a pleasant one to drink .  mouthfeel was slightly thick and flat .

pretty weak smell .  the only thing i liked about this brew was in its presentation . it forms a tight white creamy head , which sticks around quite well . the body is golden with a slight haze .  thin watery and light in body o - did not even reach moderate expectations of being a porter and tasting barrel aged , just not very good in my opinion .

the aroma is very light but that was expected . there is a hint of hops and adjunct malt but it 's mostly metallic and floral . it 's an average light lager .  the pour is promising .  a - light , clear , yellow color with a thick head that dissipated quickly s - beer , cheap beer t - beer from a can , cheap beer from a can m - thin , flat , not much d - went down smooth , probably because i 'd wisely iced it down with some ice and rock salt so it would get really cold .

appearance : light brown/gold , good clarity , not much head formation aroma : lightly skunky , malty caramel , feint strawberries , honey flavor : light initial malt sweetness before a somewhat acidic backwash riding a wave of herbally hops , green olives ( ? ) , finishes dryish with a lingering hop bitterness mouthfeel : light body , crisp texture , low carbonation other comments : an ok beer , but a bit timid and unexciting .  appearance : clear coppery color with a rich thick white foam . plenty of persistent lacing on the glass as i drank it down , but the foam on top does eventually go to just a thin film . shame that a beer which looks so nice at first turns out to be a let down in all other categories .  mouth is thin and watery . too simple and too one dimensional and thin .

its about what you would be expecting from a mexican lager .  a : pours a dark golden yellow with a couple fingers worth of fairly oily looking bright white head that took its time fading into a thin film that left a pretty good layer of sticky lace down the glass .  where this beer falls off is the mouthfeel ; it was like coca-cola without the carbonation . drinkability would be pretty good i guess , if you can get pas the average flavors and thin mouthfeel .

i have tried this beer two ways ... ..with and without lime in it . my advice is to definatly drink this with a lime . a lime improves the taste significantly . thats why i rated the taste and drinkability higher than i would have if i would have reviewed this without adding anything . this beer appears pale with a small head that dissapears in the blink of an eye .  the beer is beautiful golden and looks damn good but yuck w the taste ... .  mouthfeel is entirely too thin and watery .

nothing special in the smells department . kind of reminds me of smelling miller high life .  i wasnt sure i would get the $ 6.50 that i wanted so i could buy the local growler i had my eye on , and i didnt . ) the beer itself ( seen easily through the clear glass 40 bottle , ) seems darker than many other 40s like st ides and steel reserve , which boast the same 8.2 abv .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and just way too thin and watery for an oatmeal stout .

aroma is hard to detect , very mild malt/hops and paper .  a : this sour brown ale , true to its name , pours deep ruby-tinted brown , with a quickly-vanishing two-finger head that is also a rich burnt-straw-brown mahogany . maybe i 'm just not a sour beer drinker , as this is perhaps a well-crafted beer for its style , but not what i like to experience when tasting a fourteen-dollar bottle of beer .  good lacing down the glass s : coffee , sweet bready malts t : coffee , slight harsh maltiness also slight hint of chocolate m : light very thin bodied beer .

poured from a bottle into tulip glass- a- poured a nice orange/gold with a head on fine white lacing s- there was n't much going on at all in the aroma department . i was a bit disappointed . t- spices definitely stand out here and are backed by some fusel alcohol notes and a slight burn m- had a very bubbly mouthfeel d- average drinkability , but i really was n't too impressed by this one .  pours amber with a large , white head .  m - kind of flat on the palate with very little carbonation . hop profile caught me off guard and the mouthfeel is pretty weak .

aroma - barely a scent at all here . standard grain , nothing more .  i really want to like this local brewery but something about every beer i try ends up being below average . this beer , for a stout , is great looking but the taste is something very strange .  m : thin body and light carbonation .

serving type : bottle appearance : a straw like yellow that started w/ a 2 finger head that quickly dissipated to nothing smell : grains and some sort of skunky smell .  nice chestnut hue to it . some head with a decent carbonation level .  thin and watery .
the fruity and yeasty aroma is spoiled from a acidic and sour smell .  a- has a nice amber color to it . nice and clear .  the mouthfeel is pretty sad on this one . very watery and thin .

smell is not very strong , and to me with a cold developing it is non existent . taste is dominated by banana and wheat . overall a half decent beer , though i would not drink it regularly , and to be honest not a very good representative of the style .  poured into a snifter it forms a tan head that falls to islands . picturesque ruby red body with slow rolling carbonation .  the mouthfeel is unbalanced as if the carbonation and the liquid will not merge . for as much noise the carbonation made on opening the bottle , it seems quite on the palate .

the nose was really light in its sweetness , hardly discernible at all .  this brew suffered from major oxidation ... we had two sixers of this and they both tasted the same ... such a shame , i had heard such good things about this dark berry brew ... i literally couldnt drink an entire bottle of the product we had due to the horrible funk taste i came across ... oh well it looked great being poured into the saskatchewan tundra ... cheers !  s. nonexistent . m. also nonexistent . just plain and unoffensive . light beer on amber side ? nothing to brag about but goes down like water . above average in it 's class .

aroma of dirty socks and dank , overwhelming .  a- actually looked nice after the pour . red in appearance , nice head retension s- smell is where it really falls out .  mouthfeel is too thin for me .

overall pretty unpleasant/non-existent .  330ml bottle poured into a pilsner glass appearance- light and golden , bright and transparent . good 2 fingers of head , which dissipates very slowly .  not much depth at all m- lacking for a stout -- - no creaminess and it 's pretty thin overall d- wo n't seek this out again and i hope the rest of the breweries selections are better -- - really loses you in the mouthfeel

nose is grainy - pretty faint .  a - pours a deep gold with about two inches of foam .  the finish is lightly sweet rather than crisp , and the mouthfeel , which started out thin , ends on a watery , undercarbonated note . zywiec is an average epl , making it a below average beer in general .
the aroma is sweet roasted grains and cola .  25cl into a tulip . unexceptional head , nice lacing .  mouthfeel is overyly fizzy and thin .
smells ... bad ! yuck .  it pours nicely and the nitro tap gives it that cool lava lamp effect .  watery mouthfeel in terms of a stout .

trying to get some more scents , but the smell really is quite weak .  either a nitrous pour , a crazy looking on-tap carbonation . looks decent , dark brownish black with a very creamy off white head .  it drinks as a light beer ; it is very thin and weak , much unlike guinness .

i faintly smelled a `` beer '' smell , but only when i held my nose darn near in the glass .  the beer poured very dark brown with a nice tannish head .  high gravity beer , this one is king . drink alot of water when drinking or a major headache occurs . so drink with caution .
it smells like a basic macro .  hazy orange with a nice head .  very carbonated ... .too much .

pours a strong yellow ; thankfully tastes better than it smells ( was n't too impressed here ... ) .  the beer pours a clear amber with a full fluffy red tinted head .  ( m ) thin mouthfeel with some bitterness loosely gripping at the tongue , barely holding on .
aroma is faint malts with a mild and vague hoppy character and some alcohol .  from the bottle , it pours dark amber and clean .  horrible macro version of the style .

... smell needs major improvement ... heads abit low for my liking ... golden copper in colour ... hides the abv quite well ... lacing is very nice ... smooth and drinkable but lacks that special something to make it stand out ... 'jiminy jilikers ' ''  one moment i think i really like bocks and then i have a bock like this , and then am not so sure .  empty , chalky mouthfeel , not much going on here .

it just smells like beer .  this beer has a pinkish hue , a nice color and good head formation upon pouring into a pint glass .  a thin mouthfeel and not a lot of carbonation .

no noticable odor of any kind . this aromatic absence was confirmed by others at our table.tasted like someone burnt the malt .  poured a black color with good carbonatio and a tannish head .  mouthfeel is thin .

hops are subdued , in fact , the entire aroma is . tastes fine .  it poured a dark burnt , stained woodlike amber with a quickly dissipating off white head .  the mouthfeel is light and watery , not much substance . a very watered down dunkel , i would skip this in the future .

ca n't find one , really . t : roasted , hints of smoke and coffee . a bit too dry , too odorless and with too little after taste .  pours a orange almost amber color with a less than finger head .  m - medium-thin mouthfeel with low carbonation . a bit watery , the consistency of this beer is not what i wanted . too thin , not creamy enough for me .

some malt , corn maybe . nothing offensive - nothing different - nothing outragious . have moosehead pale ale .  the color of this beer is quite good . light yellow with a small white head .  the mouthfeel was flat leaving a watery feel in the mouth .

the aroma is straight buttered popcorn .  pours a nice `` pale-golden '' yellow , nice head , that last fairly long .  that being said i want to keep track of beers i have tried and will start to try reviewing beers i drink ) from a sampler pack found at specs liquor . tastes flat to me . no alcohol taste that i can tell of and not a whole lot of flavor . goes down easy and not much of an aftertaste .

it smells of corn sugar and a hint of malt .  bottle : poured a light pastel color beer with a big foamy head with great retention .  it 's piercing , almost . the nose lands itself squarely on the tongue , unadulterated . what you are left with is a diminished , pale , watery finish . this , fortunately , leads to high quaffability .

the aroma is grainy with a bit of hops .  i must admit i was suprised to see this new offering from coopers as i have never heard of it , it pours a pale golden see thru champagne colour with a nice frothy one finger head , sparkling carbonation and bubbly clingy lacing , it has a green , grassy hop aroma with a malty background , it has a thin mouthfeel even thinner for the style for my liking and the taste isnt as pleasant as it looks it has tastes of watery hops with a feint grainish aftertaste not as great as i was hoping for but definately better than the other macro swill out there .  feels thin and watery on the tongue with a low level of carbonation . bitterness is harsh and detracts from drinkability , mouthfeel is unsatisfying , and the flavors are n't interesting and complex enough to yield repeated enjoyment .

at first blush , it smells like rotten fruit and maple syrup .  poured from a bottle into a pilsner glass , beer is what you might expect from a `` black '' beer , very dark in color although not quite black and a root beer colored head .  very little mouthfeel , this beer is meant to be drank ice cold as implied with the cold indicator on the can unlike most beers that i drink .

12 ounce green bottle appearance : clear pale yellow color with a thick head that diminished fairly quick but left alright lacing smell : slight skunky smell with very little malt smells taste : slight bready taste and less flavor then some pilsners , but similar with very little bitterness but the bitterness that is there stays as an aftertaste for a while comment : it seems that the less taste the more refreshing , and this is the same .  poured a dark reddsih-brown . creamy looking head 1 '' high . slightly cloudy .  m : this feels fairly thin ; the flavors fall quickly off the tongue , resulting in a watery finish .

there is little smell , but what i can catch is sweet with a tiny bit of spice . something in there reminds me of budweiser .  this beer pours a cloudy amber hue with a thick head that slowly settles .  mouthfeel : lacking . too light for the style .

suprising considering the spiced nature of this beer . it smells lagery to me ... .a bit musty . there is not very much of the pumpkin and spice aromas that i was expecting . smells slightly sweet ... maybe some caramel . the taste is somewhat more powerfull than the weak smell . it does n't really taste like pumpkins , spices , or ale for that matter .  the appearance is pretty good . it is mostly foam but the head is thick and cloudy and rocky and dense .  very thin feel , little oily .

smell is bitter and a bit like citrus sitting on top of the malt .  the beer pours a nice clear amber color with a small fluffy oatmeal colored head foaming up and fading gradually .  m - slick and watery .

s- have some citrus notes , but you could hardly smell anything . hops also in nose . t/m-medium bitterness , some wheat aroma , carbonation is present highly .  solid black body , trails of bubbles run up the sides of the glass , so decent carbonation in this stout . head is khaki and creamy .  very watery .

i smelled it . it smelled sour . not too strong , but the scent was there . i tipped back my glass and got a very weak malt taste .  ap- this beer actually looks pretty damn good sititing in the glass .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

very odd aroma ... sulphuric , vegetal ... lemon dish soap maybe ? whatever it is , it 's not pleasing .  pours pale orange amber with hazed clarity . holds a one finger head well after the nitro ceases .  it was flat on the tongue and mouthfeel was very weak .

very faint hops ... .  bottle : poured a golden color lager with a big foamy head with good retention and some minimal lacing .  the sweetness died out in the taste , however , which was flat and slightly watered-down . a weird bitterness gave an unpleasant mouthfeel but still not difficult to drink .

the nose is almost non existant .  barnyard in a bottle . but uniquely so . if for no other reason than to go back to a differing style .  m - too thin , light body , fizzy carbonation . the mouthfeel on this beer is no good .

not much happening here . clean and dry but not particularly flavoursome . faint traces of lemon both in aroma and palate , and some bitterness / aniseed in the latter . but , ultimately just doesnt offer much at all , like most local examples of the genre .  poured a entirely opaque dark brown color that yielded nothing when held up to light . big , creamy tan head that required two pours . lots of lace on the sides of the glass .  m - the downfall of this beer . carbonation is way to high , almost makes the beer feel fuzzy .

s : very mild citrus , not much else detected . unimpressive smell . t : much better than expected .  had at watch city 9/2 reviewed from notes served in a pint glass a : this beer pours a straw yellow with a two finger of creamy head .  mf : thin bodied and only moderate carbonation makes this beer a bit too watery .

there is almost no smell , except a very faint malt roastyness .  a careful pour got me a couple fingers of stiff foam over a clear honey colored brew .  palate is watery with that adjuncty grain flavor , but not too offensive . easy drinking .

tallboy can @ 4.9 % and $ 1.85 . we can all agree this is n't fancy stuff , but it 's special none the less . it does n't smell good . heck , it does n't really smell at all .  a : a strange deep red color with both pink and brownish hues .  i thought that the mouthfeel was kind of watered down ... it needed more `` oommff '' .

the nose is ale yeast and disapointing .  looks nice . has a dark , almost gingerbread like color .  carbonation is minimal , almost flat . again understanding its aged but this beer is pretty sweet and without some degree of carbonation to clear out the palette at the end it becomes cloying .

aroma is of some husky , corny , grainy , malts . aroma is not sweet in least , almost a budweiser-type aroma . taste is much more pleasant than the aroma . surprisingly sweet in the taste , which i was n't expecting from the smell , with hints of rice ( budweiser-like again ) , but nothing much in the way of some decent malt flavor .  pours a dark copper colour ... . damn good lacing under right conditions ... .smell is of some kind of raspberry extract/cough syrup ( no real fruit aromas ) ... .taste is refreshing .  medium body , almost non existent carbonation , sweet sticky syrupy mouthfeel . i think the lack of carbonation ruins the mouthfeel and makes this taste and smell overly sweet .

smell : i ca n't really smell anything here . taste : follows the nose . not a whole lot going on in this one .  as the blonde approached my table , i noticed the white lace that collared her neck . as as blondes go , she definately deserved a second look , and i obliged . the lavender was so thick i could almost taste it . i needed relief from what looked to be a good encounter but had turned poorly so quickly .  this is a drinkable brew that definatly packs a punch , but it 's kind of one dimensional and thin .
weak aroma of some malt , hops ... typical miller beer scent .  served on tap , this pours a pleasing clear amber color .  carbonation is too high .

very little aroma , mouthfeel 's watery .  beer is yellow and completely hazy with a two finger white head of small and medium bubbles that leaves some lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is way thin , but drinkability is ok .

not much for aroma , just a little grainy malt .  appearance : frothy , mostly diminished head , clear body , brown .  m - watery . too thin , especially for a beer so strong , and meant to be malt-forward .

very distinct wet paint smell with a hint of mold . good smell other than the wet paint off-smell that ca n't be unsmelled .  i was excited by the color and look .  it 's drinkable , but the body and carbonation are really lacking .

aroma is really pretty light with as much hops as malt .  a - pours a nice clear amber colour with a white large bubbled head that dies quickly to a film .  slightly watery body and bland carbonation .

the smell issue and alcohol after taste put it off my future list .  nice retention and incredibly solid lace adorns the glass .  carbonation is ridiculously high .

by pabst . you wo n't believe me but it kind of smells like a bar of soap . damn it . it tastes like nothing at first , then really sweet , then like boiled corn .  appearance : pours a super large 3+ finger thinner off-white head . actually poured relatively clear for a dunkelweizen , then quickly turned cloudy after a few seconds .  thin and tingly mouthfeel .

not much on the nose , a little jammy with hints of dried tree fruits . maybe it was possible , i could n't smell anything in this !  bottle : poured a slightly hazy blonde color ale with a huge foamy head with better then average retention .  biting carbonation , was that a hint of roastiness ?
