pours bright clear gold with a 1 finger fizzy white head that faded to nothing in no time fast and left no lacing smell - not much here faint banana and macro adjunts taste - where 's the wheat ?  has a pretty nice look actually .  m - maybe i 've had too many rises recently , but this is thin , very very thin .

no alcohol notes , good for 6.7 % abv and warmer serving temp . drinkability : decent , i could drink a few in one sitting overall : smell is pretty disappointing , way too faint for a west coast ipa and `` the bursting hops '' it claims on the label .  appearance - a murky , dirty orange wth a certain luminescence to it . a nice cap builds up to about a finger 's depth , off white , creamy with pocky dimples . the head hangs around a bit , displaying some lace as it yields .  mouthfeel is thin and a bit watery .

smell is not much , sort of bland with a bit of skunk to it , small hints of malt and grains here and there .  12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner - fridge - 2009 appearance : pours a transparent golden color with lots of flowing carbonation . the head is white and rises 1 '' tall , showing a good amount of foaminess and retention . a coating of lace remains behind . nice !  mouthfeel : this is where the beer went south for me . the carbonation was almost non-existent , which was in stark contrast to the initial appearance .

s - unfortunately it does not smell like hefeweizen , or at least not like the ones i like . there 's an off-putting sweat and sulfur aroma mingling with phenolic yeast , and some standard hefe flavors well in the background . t - taste is thankfully better , without as much of the off flavors . d - one of revolution 's rare misses . with so many superior offerings at revolution , i ca n't really recommend this one at all .  appearance this one had a nicely carbonated orange body with some cool-looking sediment and a promising head .  nose : it 's aroma is a little bit malty , a little bit citrusy flavor : the taste has some lemon/citrus notes w/ some hints of maltiness , but the big thing that you notice is how fizzy this beer is . it 's far too fizzy for me .
a very faint , very vague fruity aroma . a nice lead malt caramel taste .  a-tan and spongy head with a black body .  mouthfeel is way watery and i feel like it is slightly udnercarbonated .

typical-smelling adjunct lager- grainy , corny and sweet . crisp , vegetable flavor but more than the average adjunct lager . nice body and pleasant aftertaste as well .  appearance - golden yellow , very carbonated , very pretty -- looks appetizing .  mouthfeel : way too carbonated .

it was n't yellow and it was n't pale . it had a unique smell that was hard to place . a slight sweetness that was maybe vaguely fruity , like a pear ? something else was present that i could n't quite place , sort earthy .  i know there are tons of people who rave about guinness ... but for what reason , i do n't know ... a : bartender did not perfect pour this one for sure , but it still looked good s : smells like burnt coffee t : tastes like it smells , burnt coffee m : like cold burnt thick coffee .  almost watery .

a good hot weather outdoors session beer , can only get in a bottle , not available in a keg for my kegerator , a shame , need to add a lime and lots of salt , that way i can not taste the actual beer . this is a light beer but not as watery tasting as american light beers and the lime and salt make it something a little special .  bad sign , but i ordered it anyway a - looked fine , medium golden , mildly hazy s - mild citric hop smell quickly hidden behind malty/bisquity sweet smell . can still smell the yeast on it as well , which makes me wonder if they filter at all .  thin and watery for a dark beer . little carbonation . needless to say , i was disapointed in this beer .

sleeman porter 68 is a very dark and dim red ale with a huge , frothy , waxy and dimpled off-white head that leaves great lacing . there is a sharp metallic tone in the aroma ; a whiff of freshly-dug earth and grain that resembles ... wheat ?  a - foggy tea-color , with an ample tan head .  m : watery , high carbonation .

purchased a 4-pack of nitro cans - a treat every stout lover must indulge in every once in a while . the cascading in the glass was also pretty impressive - got ta love that widget . personally i thought the smell was a mix between chalk dust and flat budweiser .  poured a nice garnet hue with a slight off white head that barely lingers with minamal lacing going on .  it does bring vanilla to mind . the sweetness almost removes it from the style of beer . far to thin for a brown ale .

had this one on tap at a bar just down the street from the brewery , smell of biscuity malts , color a classic amber , tastes of german malts little to no hop presence , abv quite high for the drinkability , and as such it makes a good session beer , if you do n't mind partying a little hard .  a : the pour is dark amber/red-brown with a thin tan head forming .  the mouthfeel is the downfall , it is watery with a dry finish , it just does n't convey the flavors to the tongue well enough .

slighlty sweet malt aroma without much character . very plain and weak aroma .  almost opaque black with deep ruby highlights . nice creamy tan head looks like nitro to me .  the herbal hops will become medicinal with traces of alluminum and will become a bit less appealing as it goes from a zippy feel to rather stagnent . a flat and bitter hop flavor is the finish .

there was very little scent from the pint , a faint smell of hops and nothing else , very bland .  a pretty golden orange color in the glass but the fragrance was musty to me and actually unpleasant .  far too thin and light for a bock . carbonation was assertive , but the body just felt thin and watery .

grassy smell with some and i say some yeasty type smells coming through . too pricy to be lawnmower beer .  famous november 2003 750ml : nice orange-brown color . thin off-white head .  however , extremely thin for a beer , and not very carbonated either .
very unimpressive .  appearance : looks pretty good .  mouthfeel is extremely thin- it felt like a porter rather than an ris .

aroma of sweet malt plus a slight off aroma , kinda sour and metallic .  appearance : pours a brilliant copper in color , extremely clear with a ton of carbonation bubbles ( not necessarily a good thing ) .  mouthfeel is flat and thin . medium bodied and watery in texture , this brew falls short of anything special on the palate .
smell : a slightly sour smell that i seem to associate with wheat brews . fairly clen aroma .  pours a blackish brown with maybe three fingers of puffy tan head .  tingly , thin watery feel .

the aroma set the tone for me . maybe a little hop aroma would have pushed it higher for me .  bottle into a pint glass pours black in color with a bit of red highlighting along the edges of the glass .  mouthfeel was poor .

sweet and fruity aroma with some odd notes . actually smells kind of like tomato sauce ( ?  thanks to kegatron for the extras ! a-golden kissed copper with a fluffy white head that hung on , slowly reduced and left decent lace .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is very high , way too high , for a milk stout . the body is thin . drinkability : just an ok beer , the mouthfeel also hurts the drinkability .

almost no discernible odor , what i can pick up is grassy or vegetable-like .  big , black , thick and sludgy looking . nice looking half a finger of leather head . some visual spotty lacing .  mouthfeel is very thin and weak .

very little aroma , has a slight grassy smell i thought it was a drinkable beer that has a much different taste than it american counterparts .  looks great on a bar top . amber red with a decent enough head but little retention , surprised to see some good lacings .  the weak malt presence and light flavor really hasnt enough oomph to fire up the taste buds . this one lacks that definitive crisp and bitter roastiness of the traditional dry stout . or watering their beers down ? actually , this wasnt that bad - light , thin and watered down , but not terrible .

smells moderately skunked and i 'd suppose the green glass bottle despite looking cool contributed to that .  nice head and appearance .  mouthfeel is all wrong . way too much carbonation and way too thin of a body .

n : not much of anything . minimal fruitiness and spices climbing to mostly lemon as it warmed . t : definitely shined more when it was crisp and cold than when it warmed .  pours a color similiar to my girlfriends hair color . good head and retention though .  the mouthfeel was a bit thin and watery .

very little to smell here . faint hops and not much else .  pours out to a clear ( i.e-filtered ) pale golden , forming a tall , poofy white head with excellent retention and nice lacing .  m : mild , almost weak or watery . does not have stout presence at all ; feels like flat cola , if anything .

smell is sticky beer residue , compost , margarine , & some straw .  pours a clear bright copper with a tall white frothy head .  mouthfeel - super watery overall - the only thing this beer has going for it is the aroma which is misleading .

smell : quite sweet , hints of fruit and a bit metallic with a hint of tomato . not a lot of hops here .  appearance : rich amber color , with about one finger 's worth of head .  as many others have said , i 'm not liking the extra carbonation .

not much sweetness . some grassiness in there or maybe a barnyard smell . t - way different than the smell . other than that this was a basic , satisfying porter .  pours a dark , fairly thick , muddy brown with a thin beige head . good head retention . given my memory of the pale , winter , and scandia , this is definitely one of their weaker offerings .  taste : decidedly like its nose , only more so ; large notes of bittersweet chocolate and espresso rule the roost , here ; not nearly as sweet as you might imagine ; total lack of carbonation left the impression of a somewhat light , thin mouthfeel .

nose is non existent . really nothing there at all .  nitro like creamy in texture and tan like color head in appearance . some good lacing while drinking also . bouquet is dead for an oatmeal stout , not much going here .  it is very thin like any us macro , making it very drinkable like water .

smell- what smell ? maybe a little hops and malt but barely anything .  nice auburn with yellow highlights .  `` simple '' is the best word i can use to describe the taste , but it does deliver with scorched malts with a touch of lactose . my biggest complaint with this beer is the mouthfeel- it 's way too watery .

no real discernible nose , slight slight hops .  poured slightly heady with a very cloudly light brown color .  slightly watery body with adequate carbonation . mouthfeel is slick and thin with a metallic and astringent finish as it dries .

aroma is very hard to detect ... very faint cola notes is all i pick up . i get the fruit cake notes mentioned in the commercial descrip .  it poured a deep , cherry red with minimal head which foamed a bit when swirled .  heard great things about this , found it in buffalo bought a 96 vintage.started promising i liked the color and the nice head , after that all downhill.had little to no smell , the taste was peppery ( overpoweringly so ) and way to sour ! the beer was way to thin and watery to go along with that taste.didnt finish the bottle just to peppery and thin for me , waiste of six bucks .

it had almost no aroma at all though , which was a bit disappointing . the flavor had very light malt aroma with no hop aroma with a bit of lemon in the background .  pours a nutty brown ( not a golden brown ! ) with a big , soapy light beige head with good retention and generous lacing . a lagerish wimp that masks as a dunkel - if you compare it to kstritzer schwarzbier , or even krusovice , it comes across as half-baked and undernourished .  the flavor echoes the aroma , but the mouthfeel is n't quite up to scratch - weirdly thin and watery , which does no favors to the toasty , nutty , tea-like , and hoppy notes that are all individually assertive but harmonious and balanced in tandem , like a good jazz band .

aroma is mildly skunky , stale hops and light malts .  poured from bottle into a pint glass a : dark brown coloring , fairly subtle tan-colored head .  thin mouthfeel with average macro carbonation . touch of caustic mouthfeel in the middle with the bitterness and petrol notes .

smell : grainy with a cut grass smell when cold - and almost no smell at all when warm .  appearance- black with little tan head .  the mouthfeel needs work . it is n't creamy at all , it is just really watery and lacking carbonation .

the smell is pretty unimpressive - a bit hoppy , some alcohol .  this filled the pint glass with a densely black color with a little red at the edges .  mouthfeel : thin and watery body , medium carbonation overall : highly overrated .
the smell had a hint of bread and fruit , but just a hint .  deep cherrywood or chestnut body with white fluffy head .  fizzy carbonation and no body .
it smells pretty bad too .  pours a golden color with a big head .  mouthfeel is very watery w/ average crabonation .
